      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:1-7 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\n\n> ἐσχίσθη δὲ τὸ πλῆθος τῆς πόλεως, καὶ οἱ μὲν ἦσαν σὺν τοῖς Ἰουδαίοις, οἱ δὲ σὺν τοῖς ἀποστόλοις.\n\n**Interlinear Table**\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 13 rows = 91 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | ἐσχίσθη | eschisthē | G4977 | σχίζω | V-API-3S | was split / was divided |\n| 2 | δὲ | de | G1161 | δέ | Conj | but / and |\n| 3 | τὸ | to | G3588 | ὁ | T-NSN | the |\n| 4 | πλῆθος | plēthos | G4128 | πλῆθος | N-NSN | multitude / people |\n| 5 | τῆς | tēs | G3588 | ὁ | T-GSF | of the |\n| 6 | πόλεως | poleōs | G4172 | πόλις | N-GSF | city |\n| 7 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 8 | οἱ | hoi | G3588 | ὁ | T-NPM | the (ones) |\n| 9 | μὲν | men | G3303 | μέν | Part | on the one hand |\n| 10 | ἦσαν | ēsan | G2258 | εἰμί | V-IAI-3P | were |\n| 11 | σὺν | syn | G4862 | σύν | Prep | with (+dat) |\n| 12 | τοῖς | tois | G3588 | ὁ | T-DPM | the |\n| 13 | Ἰουδαίοις | Ioudaiois | G2453 | Ἰουδαῖος | A-DPM | Jews |\n| 14 | οἱ | hoi | G3588 | ὁ | T-NPM | the (ones) |\n| 15 | δὲ | de | G1161 | δέ | Conj | on the other hand |\n| 16 | σὺν | syn | G4862 | σύν | Prep | with (+dat) |\n| 17 | τοῖς | tois | G3588 | ὁ | T-DPM | the |\n| 18 | ἀποστόλοις | apostolois | G652 | ἀπόστολος | N-DPM | apostles |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation**\n\n> But the multitude of the city was split, and some on the one hand were with the Jews, but some on the other hand were with the apostles.\n\n**Standalone English Translation**\n\n> But the people of the city were divided; some sided with the Jews, and others with the apostles.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation**\n\n> But the population of the city was violently torn into two factions [a deep social schism was created], and on the one hand, some aligned themselves with the unbelieving Jews, while on the other hand, the rest aligned themselves with the apostles [sent ones].\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:1-7 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Script (NA28)</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>ἐσχίσθη δὲ τὸ πλῆθος τῆς πόλεως, καὶ οἱ μὲν ἦσαν σὺν τοῖς Ἰουδαίοις, οἱ δὲ σὺν τοῖς ἀποστόλοις.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Interlinear Table</strong></p>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 13 rows = 91 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>ἐσχίσθη</td>\n<td>eschisthē</td>\n<td>G4977</td>\n<td>σχίζω</td>\n<td>V-API-3S</td>\n<td>was split / was divided</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>δὲ</td>\n<td>de</td>\n<td>G1161</td>\n<td>δέ</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>but / and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>τὸ</td>\n<td>to</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-NSN</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>πλῆθος</td>\n<td>plēthos</td>\n<td>G4128</td>\n<td>πλῆθος</td>\n<td>N-NSN</td>\n<td>multitude / people</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>τῆς</td>\n<td>tēs</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-GSF</td>\n<td>of the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>πόλεως</td>\n<td>poleōs</td>\n<td>G4172</td>\n<td>πόλις</td>\n<td>N-GSF</td>\n<td>city</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>οἱ</td>\n<td>hoi</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-NPM</td>\n<td>the (ones)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>μὲν</td>\n<td>men</td>\n<td>G3303</td>\n<td>μέν</td>\n<td>Part</td>\n<td>on the one hand</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>ἦσαν</td>\n<td>ēsan</td>\n<td>G2258</td>\n<td>εἰμί</td>\n<td>V-IAI-3P</td>\n<td>were</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>σὺν</td>\n<td>syn</td>\n<td>G4862</td>\n<td>σύν</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>with (+dat)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>τοῖς</td>\n<td>tois</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-DPM</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>Ἰουδαίοις</td>\n<td>Ioudaiois</td>\n<td>G2453</td>\n<td>Ἰουδαῖος</td>\n<td>A-DPM</td>\n<td>Jews</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>14</td>\n<td>οἱ</td>\n<td>hoi</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-NPM</td>\n<td>the (ones)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15</td>\n<td>δὲ</td>\n<td>de</td>\n<td>G1161</td>\n<td>δέ</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>on the other hand</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>16</td>\n<td>σὺν</td>\n<td>syn</td>\n<td>G4862</td>\n<td>σύν</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>with (+dat)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>17</td>\n<td>τοῖς</td>\n<td>tois</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-DPM</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>18</td>\n<td>ἀποστόλοις</td>\n<td>apostolois</td>\n<td>G652</td>\n<td>ἀπόστολος</td>\n<td>N-DPM</td>\n<td>apostles</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>But the multitude of the city was split, and some on the one hand were with the Jews, but some on the other hand were with the apostles.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>But the people of the city were divided; some sided with the Jews, and others with the apostles.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>But the population of the city was violently torn into two factions [a deep social schism was created], and on the one hand, some aligned themselves with the unbelieving Jews, while on the other hand, the rest aligned themselves with the apostles [sent ones].</p>\n</blockquote>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** The authoritative proclamation of the gospel is never neutral; it is a divine power that forces a choice, creating a division between those who align with Christ and those who oppose Him.\n*   **Fallen Condition Focus (FCF):** The broken human condition this passage addresses is the desire for a comfortable, universally acceptable, non-offensive \"gospel\" that avoids conflict. It confronts our fear of being on the wrong side of popular opinion and our tendency to soften the sharp edges of Christ's claims to keep the peace.\n*   **Shared Particulars:** Like the people of Iconium, we live in a pluralistic society. We are presented daily with the choice to align ourselves with the clear, apostolic message or with the prevailing cultural opposition to it.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** Before we are called to stand in the division, we must know that Christ stood for us. At the cross, Jesus absorbed the ultimate division—separation from the Father—so that we could be united with God. He is the one who \"makes peace by the blood of his cross\" (Col 1:20) for all who come to Him, even as that cross divides the world.\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* When you share your faith, do not be surprised or discouraged by rejection or division. Expect it as a sign that the gospel is doing its work.\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Cultivate a holy courage that fears God more than social disapproval. Find your identity and security in being \"with the apostles,\" not with the crowd.\n    *   *Relational:* Love and support fellow believers who are facing opposition for their faith. The division created by the gospel should forge a stronger unity within the church.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* In your workplace or community, be prepared for your allegiance to Christ to create awkwardness or even hostility. Stand firm with grace and truth, knowing you represent the ultimate King.\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** The passage reveals God's sovereignty over the proclamation of His Word. We adore a God whose truth is so powerful it cannot be ignored, a King whose claims are so absolute they demand a choice. \"To You, O Lord, whose Word is a sword and a fire, we give praise. You are the great King who rightly divides, and we thank you for calling us to Your side.\"\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> The authoritative proclamation of the gospel is never neutral; it is a divine power that forces a choice, creating a division between those who align with Christ and those who oppose Him.</li>\n<li><strong>Fallen Condition Focus (FCF):</strong> The broken human condition this passage addresses is the desire for a comfortable, universally acceptable, non-offensive \"gospel\" that avoids conflict. It confronts our fear of being on the wrong side of popular opinion and our tendency to soften the sharp edges of Christ's claims to keep the peace.</li>\n<li><strong>Shared Particulars:</strong> Like the people of Iconium, we live in a pluralistic society. We are presented daily with the choice to align ourselves with the clear, apostolic message or with the prevailing cultural opposition to it.</li>\n<li><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> Before we are called to stand in the division, we must know that Christ stood for us. At the cross, Jesus absorbed the ultimate division—separation from the Father—so that we could be united with God. He is the one who \"makes peace by the blood of his cross\" (Col 1:20) for all who come to Him, even as that cross divides the world.</li>\n<li><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\":</em> When you share your faith, do not be surprised or discouraged by rejection or division. Expect it as a sign that the gospel is doing its work.</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\":</em> Cultivate a holy courage that fears God more than social disapproval. Find your identity and security in being \"with the apostles,\" not with the crowd.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> Love and support fellow believers who are facing opposition for their faith. The division created by the gospel should forge a stronger unity within the church.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> In your workplace or community, be prepared for your allegiance to Christ to create awkwardness or even hostility. Stand firm with grace and truth, knowing you represent the ultimate King.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong> The passage reveals God's sovereignty over the proclamation of His Word. We adore a God whose truth is so powerful it cannot be ignored, a King whose claims are so absolute they demand a choice. \"To You, O Lord, whose Word is a sword and a fire, we give praise. You are the great King who rightly divides, and we thank you for calling us to Your side.\"</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:4 — \"the people of the city were divided\"\nKEY TERM:     ἐσχίσθη (*eschisthē*, \"was split/torn\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: The gospel's proclamation → forces a division, demanding allegiance.\nIMAGE:        A city street torn in two.\nAPPLICATION:  For the sake of the gospel, I will stand firm when my faith causes division.\nDOXOLOGY:     Praise to You, O God, whose truth is a sword that rightly divides.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:4 — &quot;the people of the city were divided&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>ἐσχίσθη (*eschisthē*, &quot;was split/torn&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>The gospel&#x27;s proclamation → forces a division, demanding allegiance.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>A city street torn in two.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>For the sake of the gospel, I will stand firm when my faith causes division.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Praise to You, O God, whose truth is a sword that rightly divides.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\n\nHave you ever wished for a faith that didn't create friction? A way to follow Jesus that everyone would find agreeable? The Bible is honest about this desire, and the story of Paul and Barnabas in Iconium gives us a bracing dose of reality. After they preached the \"word of His grace,\" a message confirmed by miracles, the city didn't unite in celebration. Instead, Acts 14:4 tells us the city \"was divided.\" The Greek word is ἐσχίσθη (*eschisthē*), meaning it was violently \"torn\" apart, like a piece of cloth.\n\nThe gospel is not a gentle suggestion; it's the announcement of a new King, and that announcement forces a choice. There is no neutral ground. In Iconium, people had to align either \"with the Jews\" who opposed the message or \"with the apostles\" who brought it. This same dividing line runs through history and right through our own communities today. Jesus Himself said He came to bring \"not peace, but a sword\" (Matthew 10:34). This isn't because the gospel is hateful, but because it is so true and so total in its claims that it exposes all our lesser loyalties. The good news is that the same Christ who divides the world unites all who come to Him into a new family. So when you feel the tension your faith creates, don't be discouraged. It's a sign that the Word is doing its powerful, clarifying work. This week, you can choose to stand firm on the apostles' side of that line, trusting the King who is worth any division.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever wished for a faith that didn't create friction? A way to follow Jesus that everyone would find agreeable? The Bible is honest about this desire, and the story of Paul and Barnabas in Iconium gives us a bracing dose of reality. After they preached the \"word of His grace,\" a message confirmed by miracles, the city didn't unite in celebration. Instead, Acts 14:4 tells us the city \"was divided.\" The Greek word is ἐσχίσθη (<em>eschisthē</em>), meaning it was violently \"torn\" apart, like a piece of cloth.</p>\n<p>The gospel is not a gentle suggestion; it's the announcement of a new King, and that announcement forces a choice. There is no neutral ground. In Iconium, people had to align either \"with the Jews\" who opposed the message or \"with the apostles\" who brought it. This same dividing line runs through history and right through our own communities today. Jesus Himself said He came to bring \"not peace, but a sword\" (Matthew 10:34). This isn't because the gospel is hateful, but because it is so true and so total in its claims that it exposes all our lesser loyalties. The good news is that the same Christ who divides the world unites all who come to Him into a new family. So when you feel the tension your faith creates, don't be discouraged. It's a sign that the Word is doing its powerful, clarifying work. This week, you can choose to stand firm on the apostles' side of that line, trusting the King who is worth any division.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n\n1.  What was the key Greek verb used in Acts 14:4 to describe what happened to the city?\n    A: ἐσχίσθη (*eschisthē*), meaning \"was split\" or \"was torn.\"\n\n2.  What were the two groups the people of Iconium were divided between?\n    A: They were divided between siding \"with the Jews\" (the opponents) and siding \"with the apostles\" (the messengers).\n\n3.  What does this verse teach us about the nature of the gospel message?\n    A: It teaches that the gospel is not neutral. It is a powerful truth that demands a response and inevitably creates a division between those who accept it and those who reject it.\n\n4.  How can a believer respond when their faith causes division in their relationships or community?\n    A: They can stand firm with courage and grace, not being surprised by the opposition, and finding their security and solidarity with Christ and His church.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>What was the key Greek verb used in Acts 14:4 to describe what happened to the city?\n    A: ἐσχίσθη (<em>eschisthē</em>), meaning \"was split\" or \"was torn.\"</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>What were the two groups the people of Iconium were divided between?\n    A: They were divided between siding \"with the Jews\" (the opponents) and siding \"with the apostles\" (the messengers).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>What does this verse teach us about the nature of the gospel message?\n    A: It teaches that the gospel is not neutral. It is a powerful truth that demands a response and inevitably creates a division between those who accept it and those who reject it.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>How can a believer respond when their faith causes division in their relationships or community?\n    A: They can stand firm with courage and grace, not being surprised by the opposition, and finding their security and solidarity with Christ and His church.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>",
