 it is a sword\").\nGate 21: PASS — AABB rhyme scheme is consistent and rhymes are exact.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is in a single ` ```text ` fenced block.\nGate 23: PASS — Syllable counts verified per line: all are 6-8, within the 5-9 rule.\nGate 24: PASS — Title \"The Torn City\" is a concrete image, memorable, and from the text's core metaphor.\n\n```text\nTitle: The Torn City\nStyle: Folk rock, driving acoustic guitar, insistent kick drum, raw male vocal, Hammond organ swells, harmonica, large room acoustics, live room bleed, thick mid-range, wooden resonance, environmental air, no noise reduction, raw analog capture, tape saturation\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nThe word of grace was preached (A)\nWith signs for all to see (A)\nBut jealous hearts were breached (B)\nBy bitter enmity (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nThe city it was torn (A)\nA line drawn in the sand (A)\nA loyal camp was born (B)\nTo join the Savior's band (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nThere is no middle ground (A)\nNo place to stand aside (A)\nWhen trumpet truth resounds (B)\nIt forces men to hide (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nThe city it was torn (A)\nA line drawn in the sand (A)\nA loyal camp was born (B)\nTo join the Savior's band (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nYou did not come for peace (A)\nYour truth, it is a sword (A)\nO Lord, grant me release (B)\nTo stand and speak Your word (B)\n\n[Outro]\nThe city it was torn (A)\nAnd I will choose my side (A)\nThe city it was torn (B)\nAnd I will choose my side (B)\n\n[End]\n```\n",
