e gospel is often hostility and rejection (John 3:19-20).</li>\n<li>☐ <strong>Missiology (sub-locus of Ecclesiology):</strong> This verse establishes a realistic theology of missions. Missionaries should expect opposition and division as a normal part of their work.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Theological Tension / Paradox:</strong> The gospel is simultaneously a message of ultimate reconciliation (2 Cor 5:18-20; Eph 2:14-16) and the cause of immediate division (Luke 12:51). The tension is resolved in this: it reconciles man to God and creates a new, unified humanity (the Church), but in doing so, it necessarily divides that new humanity from the world that remains in rebellion.</li>\n<li><strong>Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification:</strong> This passage points to Christ as the great dividing line of human history. One's relationship to Him, as proclaimed by His apostles, determines one's ultimate allegiance and destiny. He is the rock on which people are either established or broken (Matt 21:44).</li>\n</ul>",
