      "h1_title_html": "<p>Acts 14:7 — Gospel Persistence Amidst Persecution</p>",
      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:1-7 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Greek (NA28)**\nκακεῖ ἦσαν εὐαγγελιζόμενοι.\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 3 rows = 21 cells.*\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | κακεῖ | kakei | G2546 | κἀκεῖ | Adv | and there |\n| 2 | ἦσαν | ēsan | G2258 | εἰμί | V-IAI-3P | they were |\n| 3 | εὐαγγελιζόμενοι | euangelizomenoi | G2097 | εὐαγγελίζω | V-PMP-NPM | preaching the good news |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (Formal Equivalence)**\nand there they were preaching the gospel.\n\n**Standalone English Translation (Optimal Equivalence)**\nand there they continued to preach the good news.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (Meaning-Based Expansion)**\nAnd so there [in that new region, without delay], they were continuously and habitually engaged in the work of proclaiming the good news [as their primary mission and unwavering response to persecution].\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:1-7 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Greek (NA28)</strong>\nκακεῖ ἦσαν εὐαγγελιζόμενοι.</p>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 3 rows = 21 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>κακεῖ</td>\n<td>kakei</td>\n<td>G2546</td>\n<td>κἀκεῖ</td>\n<td>Adv</td>\n<td>and there</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>ἦσαν</td>\n<td>ēsan</td>\n<td>G2258</td>\n<td>εἰμί</td>\n<td>V-IAI-3P</td>\n<td>they were</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>εὐαγγελιζόμενοι</td>\n<td>euangelizomenoi</td>\n<td>G2097</td>\n<td>εὐαγγελίζω</td>\n<td>V-PMP-NPM</td>\n<td>preaching the good news</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation (Formal Equivalence)</strong>\nand there they were preaching the gospel.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation (Optimal Equivalence)</strong>\nand there they continued to preach the good news.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation (Meaning-Based Expansion)</strong>\nAnd so there [in that new region, without delay], they were continuously and habitually engaged in the work of proclaiming the good news [as their primary mission and unwavering response to persecution].</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\")**: The authenticating mark of God's mission is its irrepressible continuation; opposition serves not to end it, but to extend its reach according to God's sovereign design.\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\")**: The individual and corporate human tendency is to respond to pressure, opposition, or failure with fear, silence, and retreat. We instinctively prioritize self-preservation over mission continuation.\n*   **Shared Particulars**: Like the apostles, believers today face opposition—whether overt persecution, social marginalization, professional setbacks, or relational conflict—that tempts them to stop being witnesses for Christ. We too are often \"driven out\" of comfortable situations.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding)**: Because Jesus Christ, our forerunner, was the perfect Faithful Witness who did not shrink back from the cross, and because He was raised in victory and has given us His own Spirit, we are freed from the fear that leads to silence. His power is made perfect in our weakness (2 Cor 12:9), and His gospel cannot be chained (2 Tim 2:9).\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace)**:\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\" & \"Being\"*: When you face a setback or are forced out of a comfortable situation, consciously reject the impulse to retreat. Instead, ask, \"Lord, what is the new 'Lystra and Derbe' you have brought me to, and how can I begin to be a witness for you here?\" Your identity is \"witness,\" not \"victim.\"\n    *   *Relational*: In your church, actively encourage those who are facing hardship or opposition for their faith. Remind them of this biblical pattern: God is not abandoning them; He may be repositioning them for a new phase of fruitful ministry.\n    *   *Public / Vocational*: View your workplace, neighborhood, or social circle—especially after a change or a difficulty—as a divinely appointed mission field. Your consistent, faithful presence and readiness to speak of the hope within you is the modern equivalent of \"continuously preaching the good news.\"\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\")**: The passage reveals God's sovereign faithfulness to His own mission. We worship Him as the Unstoppable God, whose purposes cannot be thwarted by human opposition. \"Lord, we praise You that not even the threat of death can silence Your gospel. You turn the enemy's weapons into plows that break new ground for Your kingdom. Your Word runs swiftly, and we adore You for Your unconquerable power.\"\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\")</strong>: The authenticating mark of God's mission is its irrepressible continuation; opposition serves not to end it, but to extend its reach according to God's sovereign design.</li>\n<li><strong>FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\")</strong>: The individual and corporate human tendency is to respond to pressure, opposition, or failure with fear, silence, and retreat. We instinctively prioritize self-preservation over mission continuation.</li>\n<li><strong>Shared Particulars</strong>: Like the apostles, believers today face opposition—whether overt persecution, social marginalization, professional setbacks, or relational conflict—that tempts them to stop being witnesses for Christ. We too are often \"driven out\" of comfortable situations.</li>\n<li><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding)</strong>: Because Jesus Christ, our forerunner, was the perfect Faithful Witness who did not shrink back from the cross, and because He was raised in victory and has given us His own Spirit, we are freed from the fear that leads to silence. His power is made perfect in our weakness (2 Cor 12:9), and His gospel cannot be chained (2 Tim 2:9).</li>\n<li><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace)</strong>:<ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\" &amp; \"Being\"</em>: When you face a setback or are forced out of a comfortable situation, consciously reject the impulse to retreat. Instead, ask, \"Lord, what is the new 'Lystra and Derbe' you have brought me to, and how can I begin to be a witness for you here?\" Your identity is \"witness,\" not \"victim.\"</li>\n<li><em>Relational</em>: In your church, actively encourage those who are facing hardship or opposition for their faith. Remind them of this biblical pattern: God is not abandoning them; He may be repositioning them for a new phase of fruitful ministry.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational</em>: View your workplace, neighborhood, or social circle—especially after a change or a difficulty—as a divinely appointed mission field. Your consistent, faithful presence and readiness to speak of the hope within you is the modern equivalent of \"continuously preaching the good news.\"</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\")</strong>: The passage reveals God's sovereign faithfulness to His own mission. We worship Him as the Unstoppable God, whose purposes cannot be thwarted by human opposition. \"Lord, we praise You that not even the threat of death can silence Your gospel. You turn the enemy's weapons into plows that break new ground for Your kingdom. Your Word runs swiftly, and we adore You for Your unconquerable power.\"</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:7 \"...and there they continued to preach the gospel.\"\nKEY TERM:     εὐαγγελιζόμενοι (*euangelizomenoi*, \"were preaching good news\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: Apostolic persistence → Persecution relocates, not stops, the gospel.\nIMAGE:        A seed carried by a harsh wind to new soil.\nAPPLICATION:  For the church: see opposition as a divine redirect, not a dead end.\nDOXOLOGY:     Praise to the God whose gospel cannot be chained.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:7 &quot;...and there they continued to preach the gospel.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>εὐαγγελιζόμενοι (*euangelizomenoi*, &quot;were preaching good news&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>Apostolic persistence → Persecution relocates, not stops, the gospel.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>A seed carried by a harsh wind to new soil.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>For the church: see opposition as a divine redirect, not a dead end.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Praise to the God whose gospel cannot be chained.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nWhat do you do when you get shut down? When a plan fails, a door closes, or you face real opposition, the natural response is to pull back, regroup, and maybe even quit. In the book of Acts, we see a completely different pattern. Paul and Barnabas had just been run out of the city of Iconium, with a mob preparing to stone them. They fled for their lives. But the moment they arrived in the new towns of Lystra and Derbe, the Bible says simply, \"and there they continued to preach the good news\" (Acts 14:7).\n\nThe key is in the grammar: ἦσαν εὐαγγελιζόμενοι (*ēsan euangelizomenoi*, \"they were preaching the good news\"). It describes a continuous, ongoing state of being. Proclaiming Jesus wasn't just an event on their calendar; it was the very fabric of their lives. This shows us that the power for God's mission isn't located in our safety or comfort, but in the gospel message itself, empowered by the Holy Spirit. Because Christ was the ultimate faithful witness who endured the cross for us, we are freed from the fear that silences. So, when you face your next setback, ask God to show you the new \"Lystra\" He's brought you to. It's not a dead end; it's a new field, ready for the good news.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>What do you do when you get shut down? When a plan fails, a door closes, or you face real opposition, the natural response is to pull back, regroup, and maybe even quit. In the book of Acts, we see a completely different pattern. Paul and Barnabas had just been run out of the city of Iconium, with a mob preparing to stone them. They fled for their lives. But the moment they arrived in the new towns of Lystra and Derbe, the Bible says simply, \"and there they continued to preach the good news\" (Acts 14:7).</p>\n<p>The key is in the grammar: ἦσαν εὐαγγελιζόμενοι (<em>ēsan euangelizomenoi</em>, \"they were preaching the good news\"). It describes a continuous, ongoing state of being. Proclaiming Jesus wasn't just an event on their calendar; it was the very fabric of their lives. This shows us that the power for God's mission isn't located in our safety or comfort, but in the gospel message itself, empowered by the Holy Spirit. Because Christ was the ultimate faithful witness who endured the cross for us, we are freed from the fear that silences. So, when you face your next setback, ask God to show you the new \"Lystra\" He's brought you to. It's not a dead end; it's a new field, ready for the good news.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  What grammatical feature in Acts 14:7 emphasizes the *ongoing* nature of the apostles' preaching?\n    A: The periphrastic imperfect construction (ἦσαν εὐαγγελιζόμενοι), which means \"they were continuously preaching\" as a habitual activity.\n2.  What event immediately caused Paul and Barnabas to go to Lystra and Derbe?\n    A: They fled a plot in the city of Iconium to mistreat them and stone them to death.\n3.  What does this verse teach about God's sovereign control over His mission?\n    A: It teaches that God sovereignly uses opposition and persecution not to stop His mission, but to strategically spread the gospel to new places and peoples.\n4.  How can a believer apply this verse when facing a personal or professional setback?\n    A: The believer can see the new circumstance not as a defeat, but as a new, God-given assignment and place to continue being a faithful witness for Christ.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What grammatical feature in Acts 14:7 emphasizes the <em>ongoing</em> nature of the apostles' preaching?\n    A: The periphrastic imperfect construction (ἦσαν εὐαγγελιζόμενοι), which means \"they were continuously preaching\" as a habitual activity.</li>\n<li>What event immediately caused Paul and Barnabas to go to Lystra and Derbe?\n    A: They fled a plot in the city of Iconium to mistreat them and stone them to death.</li>\n<li>What does this verse teach about God's sovereign control over His mission?\n    A: It teaches that God sovereignly uses opposition and persecution not to stop His mission, but to strategically spread the gospel to new places and peoples.</li>\n<li>How can a believer apply this verse when facing a personal or professional setback?\n    A: The believer can see the new circumstance not as a defeat, but as a new, God-given assignment and place to continue being a faithful witness for Christ.</li>\n</ol>",
