ed throughout; rhymes are exact.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is a single fenced <code>text</code> code block.\nGate 23: PASS — All lines counted and confirmed to be 6-8 syllables.\nGate 24: PASS — Title \"The Unchained Word\" is a memorable, concrete image.</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-text\">Title: The Unchained Word\nStyle: Folk rock, male vocals, driving acoustic guitar, subtle upright bass, minimalist drums with brushes, Large room acoustics, live room bleed, thick mid-range, wooden resonance, environmental air, no noise reduction, raw analog capture, tape saturation\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nThe plot was made with stones (A)\nDown to their very bones (A)\nThey fled the city gate (B)\nA grim and hurried fate (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nAnd there they were preaching (A)\nThe good news unceasing (A)\nThe Word cannot be bound (B)\nOn new and foreign ground (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nMy comfort zone is gone (A)\nA hard and painful dawn (A)\nThis place I did not choose (B)\nI feel I only lose (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nBut you, O Lord, were sent (A)\nTo shame and punishment (A)\nOn you the true stones fell (B)\nTo rescue us from hell (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nAnd here we are preaching (A)\nThe good news unceasing (A)\nThe Word cannot be bound (B)\nOn new and foreign ground (B)\n\n[Outro]\nOn new and foreign ground (A)\nA firm and joyful sound (A)\nThe good news unceasing (B)\nThe blessing is increasing (B)\n\n[End]\n</code></pre>",
      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\")**: The apostolic activity of Paul and Barnabas immediately after fleeing persecution in Iconium and arriving in the region of Lystra and Derbe.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\")**: Their response to being driven out was not to retreat or hide, but to immediately resume their primary mission with continuous, ongoing intensity.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\")**: Persecution does not stop the gospel; it sovereignly relocates and fuels the continuous work of proclamation.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\")</strong>: The apostolic activity of Paul and Barnabas immediately after fleeing persecution in Iconium and arriving in the region of Lystra and Derbe.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\")</strong>: Their response to being driven out was not to retreat or hide, but to immediately resume their primary mission with continuous, ongoing intensity.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\")</strong>: Persecution does not stop the gospel; it sovereignly relocates and fuels the continuous work of proclamation.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role**: The book of Acts chronicles the Holy Spirit-empowered advance of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, in fulfillment of Christ's commission (Acts 1:8). This short verse is a perfect miniature of that thesis: faced with violent opposition, the mission does not stop but simply moves to a new frontier and continues unabated.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc**: This verse serves as the conclusion to the events at Iconium (Acts 14:1-6) and the introduction to the ministry in Lystra and Derbe (14:8-21). It is the hinge that connects the cause (persecution and flight) to the effect (renewed proclamation in a new area). This is a recurring pattern in Paul's First Missionary Journey.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic**: The genre is historical narrative. The governing **hermeneutic** (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this as a factual account that is descriptive of a prescriptive pattern for the Church. The relentless, mobile, proclamation-centered nature of the apostolic mission is a model for the Church in every age.\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational)**: The passage is set firmly in the Church Age (the dispensation of Grace), under the New Covenant. The gospel is breaking new ground among the Gentiles in Lycaonia, a direct fulfillment of the Abrahamic promise that in his seed all the nations of the earth would be blessed (Gen 12:3; Gal 3:8).\n*   **Author & Attribution**: The author is Luke, the physician and traveling companion of Paul, writing to Theophilus (Luke 1:1-4; Acts 1:1). The work is dated pre-A.D. 70, likely in the early 60s.\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors**: The verse is propelled by the immediate context. In Iconium, a plot was formed \"to mistreat them and to stone them\" (Acts 14:5). Their flight (v. 6) is not cowardice but obedience to Christ's command (Matt 10:23). This verse (v. 7) is their immediate response, which sets the stage for the healing of the lame man at Lystra (v. 8ff).\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels**: This verse exemplifies a key theme in Acts where persecution directly fuels gospel expansion (Acts 8:1-4 [Pericope: Acts 8:1-4 · source: NA28]; Acts 11:19-21 [Pericope: Acts 11:19-26 · source: NA28]). It is a practical outworking of Jesus's instruction to his disciples: \"When they persecute you in one town, flee to the next\" (Matt 10:23 [Pericope: Matt 10:16-23 · source: NA28]).\n",
      "phase_c_big_picture_html": "<h3>Big Picture: Where this passage fits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Whole-Book Thesis &amp; Passage's Role</strong>: The book of Acts chronicles the Holy Spirit-empowered advance of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, in fulfillment of Christ's commission (Acts 1:8). This short verse is a perfect miniature of that thesis: faced with violent opposition, the mission does not stop but simply moves to a new frontier and continues unabated.</li>\n<li><strong>Discourse / Section Arc</strong>: This verse serves as the conclusion to the events at Iconium (Acts 14:1-6) and the introduction to the ministry in Lystra and Derbe (14:8-21). It is the hinge that connects the cause (persecution and flight) to the effect (renewed proclamation in a new area). This is a recurring pattern in Paul's First Missionary Journey.</li>\n<li><strong>Genre &amp; Hermeneutic</strong>: The genre is historical narrative. The governing <strong>hermeneutic</strong> (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this as a factual account that is descriptive of a prescriptive pattern for the Church. The relentless, mobile, proclamation-centered nature of the apostolic mission is a model for the Church in every age.</li>\n<li><strong>Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational)</strong>: The passage is set firmly in the Church Age (the dispensation of Grace), under the New Covenant. The gospel is breaking new ground among the Gentiles in Lycaonia, a direct fulfillment of the Abrahamic promise that in his seed all the nations of the earth would be blessed (Gen 12:3; Gal 3:8).</li>\n<li><strong>Author &amp; Attribution</strong>: The author is Luke, the physician and traveling companion of Paul, writing to Theophilus (Luke 1:1-4; Acts 1:1). The work is dated pre-A.D. 70, likely in the early 60s.</li>\n<li><strong>Gravitational Neighbors</strong>: The verse is propelled by the immediate context. In Iconium, a plot was formed \"to mistreat them and to stone them\" (Acts 14:5). Their flight (v. 6) is not cowardice but obedience to Christ's command (Matt 10:23). This verse (v. 7) is their immediate response, which sets the stage for the healing of the lame man at Lystra (v. 8ff).</li>\n<li><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels</strong>: This verse exemplifies a key theme in Acts where persecution directly fuels gospel expansion (Acts 8:1-4 [Pericope: Acts 8:1-4 · source: NA28]; Acts 11:19-21 [Pericope: Acts 11:19-26 · source: NA28]). It is a practical outworking of Jesus's instruction to his disciples: \"When they persecute you in one town, flee to the next\" (Matt 10:23 [Pericope: Matt 10:16-23 · source: NA28]).</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology**: The event occurs during Paul's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars like Harold Hoehner to c. A.D. 47-48.\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography**: Paul and Barnabas fled from Iconium south to \"the cities of Lycaonia, Lystra and Derbe, and the surrounding region\" (Acts 14:6). This was a district within the Roman province of Galatia (modern-day Turkey). Lystra was a Roman colony, located about 30 km (18 miles) south of Iconium. The region was more rural and less Hellenized than Pisidian Antioch or Iconium, and the native Lycaonian language was still spoken (Acts 14:11).\n*   **Original Audience Identification**: The original audience of the book was Theophilus and, by extension, the wider early church, composed of both Jewish and Gentile believers. The audience *in the narrative* at Lystra and Derbe was a mix of local pagans and likely a small Jewish population.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text)**: Luke is carefully documenting the unstoppable, Spirit-directed advance of the Christian mission. His purpose is to assure his readers of the certainty of the things they have been taught (Luke 1:4), demonstrating that the gospel's spread is not a human accident but the deliberate plan of God, which even the most violent opposition cannot thwart.\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology</strong>: The event occurs during Paul's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars like Harold Hoehner to c. A.D. 47-48.</li>\n<li><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography</strong>: Paul and Barnabas fled from Iconium south to \"the cities of Lycaonia, Lystra and Derbe, and the surrounding region\" (Acts 14:6). This was a district within the Roman province of Galatia (modern-day Turkey). Lystra was a Roman colony, located about 30 km (18 miles) south of Iconium. The region was more rural and less Hellenized than Pisidian Antioch or Iconium, and the native Lycaonian language was still spoken (Acts 14:11).</li>\n<li><strong>Original Audience Identification</strong>: The original audience of the book was Theophilus and, by extension, the wider early church, composed of both Jewish and Gentile believers. The audience <em>in the narrative</em> at Lystra and Derbe was a mix of local pagans and likely a small Jewish population.</li>\n<li><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text)</strong>: Luke is carefully documenting the unstoppable, Spirit-directed advance of the Christian mission. His purpose is to assure his readers of the certainty of the things they have been taught (Luke 1:4), demonstrating that the gospel's spread is not a human accident but the deliberate plan of God, which even the most violent opposition cannot thwart.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\n*   **Literal-Primary Filter**: The verse makes a simple historical statement: in the new location, they preached. The theological weight is found in the grammar and the context.\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax**: The most significant feature is the periphrastic imperfect construction: ἦσαν εὐαγγελιζόμενοι (*ēsan euangelizomenoi*, \"they were preaching the good news\"). This is formed with the imperfect of the verb \"to be\" plus a present participle. Unlike a simple aorist tense (\"they preached\"), this construction emphasizes the *continuous, habitual, and ongoing nature* of the action in past time. Luke is not just saying they held an event; he is describing their constant state of activity. Preaching the gospel was what they were *doing*, their defining work in that new place.\n*   **Names**: The verb εὐαγγελίζω (*euangelizō*) is derived from εὖ (*eu*, \"good\") and ἄγγελος (*angelos*, \"messenger\"). It means \"to announce good news.\" The content of this news is the person and work of Jesus Christ: His death, burial, and resurrection for the forgiveness of sins (1 Cor 15:1-4).\n*   **Imagery & Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?)**: The implicit image is of a resilient, life-giving river. When dammed or diverted in one place (Iconium), it does not stop but simply cuts a new channel (to Lystra and Derbe) and continues to flow with the same force. The gospel is the water, and the apostles are the channel directed by God.\n    *   **Two-Books Confirmation (\"Scripture (special revelation) and Nature (general revelation) bear witness to the same Creator — operational-science confirmation only; no deep time, no origins claims\")**: In hydrology, a river that meets an obstacle builds up pressure (potential energy) until it either overtops the barrier or finds a new, weaker path, carving a new channel. This natural process of diversion and continued flow mirrors the spiritual reality of the gospel's advance through opposition.\n*   **Common Misreadings Flag**:\n    *   *Misreading:* This is merely a transitional, \"filler\" verse connecting two more important stories.\n    *   *Why wrong:* The specific grammatical choice of the periphrastic imperfect elevates this from a simple transition to a thematic statement about the relentless nature of the apostolic mission. It is the theological summary of their response to persecution.\n    *   *Cross-references:* 2 Tim 4:2; Acts 5:42\n    *   *Correct reading:* This verse is a concise, powerful declaration that the core identity and activity of the church is the continuous proclamation of the gospel, an activity that persecution may relocate but cannot stop.\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Literal-Primary Filter</strong>: The verse makes a simple historical statement: in the new location, they preached. The theological weight is found in the grammar and the context.</li>\n<li><strong>Linguistic Mechanics &amp; Syntax</strong>: The most significant feature is the periphrastic imperfect construction: ἦσαν εὐαγγελιζόμενοι (<em>ēsan euangelizomenoi</em>, \"they were preaching the good news\"). This is formed with the imperfect of the verb \"to be\" plus a present participle. Unlike a simple aorist tense (\"they preached\"), this construction emphasizes the <em>continuous, habitual, and ongoing nature</em> of the action in past time. Luke is not just saying they held an event; he is describing their constant state of activity. Preaching the gospel was what they were <em>doing</em>, their defining work in that new place.</li>\n<li><strong>Names</strong>: The verb εὐαγγελίζω (<em>euangelizō</em>) is derived from εὖ (<em>eu</em>, \"good\") and ἄγγελος (<em>angelos</em>, \"messenger\"). It means \"to announce good news.\" The content of this news is the person and work of Jesus Christ: His death, burial, and resurrection for the forgiveness of sins (1 Cor 15:1-4).</li>\n<li><strong>Imagery &amp; Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?)</strong>: The implicit image is of a resilient, life-giving river. When dammed or diverted in one place (Iconium), it does not stop but simply cuts a new channel (to Lystra and Derbe) and continues to flow with the same force. The gospel is the water, and the apostles are the channel directed by God.<ul>\n<li><strong>Two-Books Confirmation (\"Scripture (special revelation) and Nature (general revelation) bear witness to the same Creator — operational-science confirmation only; no deep time, no origins claims\")</strong>: In hydrology, a river that meets an obstacle builds up pressure (potential energy) until it either overtops the barrier or finds a new, weaker path, carving a new channel. This natural process of diversion and continued flow mirrors the spiritual reality of the gospel's advance through opposition.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Common Misreadings Flag</strong>:<ul>\n<li><em>Misreading:</em> This is merely a transitional, \"filler\" verse connecting two more important stories.</li>\n<li><em>Why wrong:</em> The specific grammatical choice of the periphrastic imperfect elevates this from a simple transition to a thematic statement about the relentless nature of the apostolic mission. It is the theological summary of their response to persecution.</li>\n<li><em>Cross-references:</em> 2 Tim 4:2; Acts 5:42</li>\n<li><em>Correct reading:</em> This verse is a concise, powerful declaration that the core identity and activity of the church is the continuous proclamation of the gospel, an activity that persecution may relocate but cannot stop.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment**: This verse is a direct fulfillment of Christ's words in the Olivet Discourse, \"And this gospel of the kingdom will be proclaimed throughout the whole world as a testimony to all nations, and then the end will come\" (Matt 24:14 [Pericope: Matt 24:1-35 · source: NA28]). Each time the apostles are scattered and continue preaching, this great prophetic program advances. This is a [TYPE] of the Church's mission throughout history.\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic)**: This verse is a key point in the biblical motif of the \"Suffering Witness.\" This trajectory begins with figures like Joseph and Jeremiah, finds its ultimate expression in the Suffering Servant of Isaiah, and is perfectly embodied in Jesus Christ. The apostles are now walking in their Master's footsteps, participating in His sufferings for the sake of the gospel (Col 1:24). The **Christo-telic terminus** (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the final victory of the saints, who conquer not by avoiding suffering but through their faithful testimony, grounded in Christ's victory. The *terminus verse* is Revelation 12:11: \"And they have conquered him by the blood of the Lamb and by the word of their testimony.\"\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag**:\n    *   Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"): This verse is a primary text for missiology, defining the church's mission as persistent, mobile, gospel-centered proclamation.\n    *   Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\"): Though the Spirit is not explicitly named, He is the implied power behind their persistence, fulfilling the promise of Acts 1:8.\n    *   Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"): The content of their preaching is εὐαγγέλιον (*euangelion*, \"the gospel\"), the message of salvation.\n*   **Theological Tension / Paradox**: The passage displays the paradox of divine sovereignty and human responsibility. God sovereignly uses the evil intentions of persecutors to advance His kingdom to new regions. Simultaneously, Paul and Barnabas make the responsible, faithful choice to continue their work rather than succumb to fear. God's plan is worked out through their courageous obedience (cf. Acts 2:23).\n*   **Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification**: The apostles are not preaching a generic message of hope; they are preaching the εὐαγγέλιον (*euangelion*, \"good news\") *of Jesus Christ*. Their persistence in the face of death threats is a reflection of Christ's own steadfast resolve to go to Jerusalem to accomplish our redemption (Luke 9:51). They are living extensions of His mission, empowered by His Spirit.\n",
      "phase_f_canonical_html": "<h3>Canonical Connection</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Foreshadowing &amp; Fulfillment</strong>: This verse is a direct fulfillment of Christ's words in the Olivet Discourse, \"And this gospel of the kingdom will be proclaimed throughout the whole world as a testimony to all nations, and then the end will come\" (Matt 24:14 [Pericope: Matt 24:1-35 · source: NA28]). Each time the apostles are scattered and continue preaching, this great prophetic program advances. This is a [TYPE] of the Church's mission throughout history.</li>\n<li><strong>Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic)</strong>: This verse is a key point in the biblical motif of the \"Suffering Witness.\" This trajectory begins with figures like Joseph and Jeremiah, finds its ultimate expression in the Suffering Servant of Isaiah, and is perfectly embodied in Jesus Christ. The apostles are now walking in their Master's footsteps, participating in His sufferings for the sake of the gospel (Col 1:24). The <strong>Christo-telic terminus</strong> (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the final victory of the saints, who conquer not by avoiding suffering but through their faithful testimony, grounded in Christ's victory. The <em>terminus verse</em> is Revelation 12:11: \"And they have conquered him by the blood of the Lamb and by the word of their testimony.\"</li>\n<li><strong>Systematic-Theology Loci Tag</strong>:<ul>\n<li>Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"): This verse is a primary text for missiology, defining the church's mission as persistent, mobile, gospel-centered proclamation.</li>\n<li>Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\"): Though the Spirit is not explicitly named, He is the implied power behind their persistence, fulfilling the promise of Acts 1:8.</li>\n<li>Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"): The content of their preaching is εὐαγγέλιον (<em>euangelion</em>, \"the gospel\"), the message of salvation.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Theological Tension / Paradox</strong>: The passage displays the paradox of divine sovereignty and human responsibility. God sovereignly uses the evil intentions of persecutors to advance His kingdom to new regions. Simultaneously, Paul and Barnabas make the responsible, faithful choice to continue their work rather than succumb to fear. God's plan is worked out through their courageous obedience (cf. Acts 2:23).</li>\n<li><strong>Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification</strong>: The apostles are not preaching a generic message of hope; they are preaching the εὐαγγέλιον (<em>euangelion</em>, \"good news\") <em>of Jesus Christ</em>. Their persistence in the face of death threats is a reflection of Christ's own steadfast resolve to go to Jerusalem to accomplish our redemption (Luke 9:51). They are living extensions of His mission, empowered by His Spirit.</li>\n</ul>",
