      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:8–20 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\n\nΚαί τις ἀνὴρ ἐν Λύστροις ἀδύνατος τοῖς ποσὶν ἐκάθητο, χωλὸς ἐκ κοιλίας μητρὸς αὐτοῦ ὑπάρχων, ὃς οὐδέποτε περιεπεπατήκει.\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 13 rows = 91 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Καί | Kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | And / Now |\n| 2 | τις | tis | G5100 | τις | A-NSM | a certain |\n| 3 | ἀνὴρ | anēr | G435 | ἀνήρ | N-NSM | man |\n| 4 | ἐν | en | G1722 | ἐν | Prep | in / at |\n| 5 | Λύστροις | Lystrois | G3082 | Λύστρα | N-DPN | Lystra |\n| 6 | ἀδύνατος | adynatos | G102 | ἀδύνατος | A-NSM | powerless / unable |\n| 7 | τοῖς | tois | G3588 | ὁ | T-DPM | in the |\n| 8 | ποσὶν | posin | G4228 | πούς | N-DPM | feet |\n| 9 | ἐκάθητο | ekathēto | G2521 | κάθημαι | V-IMI-3S | was sitting |\n| 10 | χωλὸς | chōlos | G5560 | χωλός | A-NSM | lame / crippled |\n| 11 | ἐκ | ek | G1537 | ἐκ | Prep | from |\n| 12 | κοιλίας | koilias | G2836 | κοιλία | N-GSF | womb |\n| 13 | μητρὸς | mētros | G3384 | μήτηρ | N-GSF | of his mother |\n\n*(Note: The NA28 text includes ὑπάρχων, ὃς οὐδέποτε περιεπεπατήκει, which are analyzed in the Verse-Level Craft section for completeness.)*\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation**\n\nAnd a certain man in Lystra, powerless in the feet, was sitting, being lame from the womb of his mother, who had never walked.\n\n**Standalone English Translation**\n\nNow at Lystra there was a man sitting who was powerless in his feet, lame from his mother’s womb, and he had never walked.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation**\n\nAnd in the city of Lystra, a particular man was sitting there, utterly powerless [ἀδύνατος, *adynatos*] in his feet. He was, by his very nature [ὑπάρχων, *hyparchōn*], crippled right from his mother’s womb [ἐκ κοιλίας μητρός, *ek koilias mētros*], a man who had never, not once in his entire life, walked.\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:8–20 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Script (NA28)</strong></p>\n<p>Καί τις ἀνὴρ ἐν Λύστροις ἀδύνατος τοῖς ποσὶν ἐκάθητο, χωλὸς ἐκ κοιλίας μητρὸς αὐτοῦ ὑπάρχων, ὃς οὐδέποτε περιεπεπατήκει.</p>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 13 rows = 91 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>Καί</td>\n<td>Kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>And / Now</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>τις</td>\n<td>tis</td>\n<td>G5100</td>\n<td>τις</td>\n<td>A-NSM</td>\n<td>a certain</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>ἀνὴρ</td>\n<td>anēr</td>\n<td>G435</td>\n<td>ἀνήρ</td>\n<td>N-NSM</td>\n<td>man</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>ἐν</td>\n<td>en</td>\n<td>G1722</td>\n<td>ἐν</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>in / at</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>Λύστροις</td>\n<td>Lystrois</td>\n<td>G3082</td>\n<td>Λύστρα</td>\n<td>N-DPN</td>\n<td>Lystra</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>ἀδύνατος</td>\n<td>adynatos</td>\n<td>G102</td>\n<td>ἀδύνατος</td>\n<td>A-NSM</td>\n<td>powerless / unable</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>τοῖς</td>\n<td>tois</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-DPM</td>\n<td>in the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>ποσὶν</td>\n<td>posin</td>\n<td>G4228</td>\n<td>πούς</td>\n<td>N-DPM</td>\n<td>feet</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>ἐκάθητο</td>\n<td>ekathēto</td>\n<td>G2521</td>\n<td>κάθημαι</td>\n<td>V-IMI-3S</td>\n<td>was sitting</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>χωλὸς</td>\n<td>chōlos</td>\n<td>G5560</td>\n<td>χωλός</td>\n<td>A-NSM</td>\n<td>lame / crippled</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>ἐκ</td>\n<td>ek</td>\n<td>G1537</td>\n<td>ἐκ</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>from</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>κοιλίας</td>\n<td>koilias</td>\n<td>G2836</td>\n<td>κοιλία</td>\n<td>N-GSF</td>\n<td>womb</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>μητρὸς</td>\n<td>mētros</td>\n<td>G3384</td>\n<td>μήτηρ</td>\n<td>N-GSF</td>\n<td>of his mother</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><em>(Note: The NA28 text includes ὑπάρχων, ὃς οὐδέποτε περιεπεπατήκει, which are analyzed in the Verse-Level Craft section for completeness.)</em></p>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation</strong></p>\n<p>And a certain man in Lystra, powerless in the feet, was sitting, being lame from the womb of his mother, who had never walked.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation</strong></p>\n<p>Now at Lystra there was a man sitting who was powerless in his feet, lame from his mother’s womb, and he had never walked.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation</strong></p>\n<p>And in the city of Lystra, a particular man was sitting there, utterly powerless [ἀδύνατος, <em>adynatos</em>] in his feet. He was, by his very nature [ὑπάρχων, <em>hyparchōn</em>], crippled right from his mother’s womb [ἐκ κοιλίας μητρός, <em>ek koilias mētros</em>], a man who had never, not once in his entire life, walked.</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** God delights in demonstrating His supernatural power in situations of absolute human hopelessness to show that restoration comes from Him alone.\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):** The FCF is the deep-seated human condition of being \"born this way\"—powerless to change our most fundamental spiritual brokenness. We are, from the womb, unable to walk in God's ways or heal ourselves.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** While we were powerless (ἀδύνατος, *adynatos*), just like this man, Christ died for the ungodly (Rom 5:6). The same power that raised Jesus from the dead is at work to give new life to those who are spiritually dead and lame, enabling them to \"walk in newness of life\" (Rom 6:4; Eph 2:1-5).\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Recognize and confess your own congenital inability apart from Christ. Abandon all self-reliance and find your strength and ability to \"walk\" in Him alone.\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* Look for the \"lame men\" in your own Lystra—those whom society has written off as hopeless cases. See them not as problems to be managed, but as canvases for God's grace.\n    *   *Relational:* When you share the gospel, do not downplay the severity of sin. Present the human condition as it is—hopeless apart from God—so that the power of the gospel can be seen as the radical, miraculous rescue it truly is.\n    *   *Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):* Adore the God who does not look for our ability but specializes in our inability. Praise Him that His power is made perfect in weakness (2 Cor 12:9).\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> God delights in demonstrating His supernatural power in situations of absolute human hopelessness to show that restoration comes from Him alone.</li>\n<li><strong>FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):</strong> The FCF is the deep-seated human condition of being \"born this way\"—powerless to change our most fundamental spiritual brokenness. We are, from the womb, unable to walk in God's ways or heal ourselves.</li>\n<li><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> While we were powerless (ἀδύνατος, <em>adynatos</em>), just like this man, Christ died for the ungodly (Rom 5:6). The same power that raised Jesus from the dead is at work to give new life to those who are spiritually dead and lame, enabling them to \"walk in newness of life\" (Rom 6:4; Eph 2:1-5).</li>\n<li><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\":</em> Recognize and confess your own congenital inability apart from Christ. Abandon all self-reliance and find your strength and ability to \"walk\" in Him alone.</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\":</em> Look for the \"lame men\" in your own Lystra—those whom society has written off as hopeless cases. See them not as problems to be managed, but as canvases for God's grace.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> When you share the gospel, do not downplay the severity of sin. Present the human condition as it is—hopeless apart from God—so that the power of the gospel can be seen as the radical, miraculous rescue it truly is.</li>\n<li><em>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</em> Adore the God who does not look for our ability but specializes in our inability. Praise Him that His power is made perfect in weakness (2 Cor 12:9).</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:8 — \"crippled from birth and had never walked.\"\nKEY TERM:     ἀδύνατος (*adynatos*, \"powerless, unable\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: A man's total inability becomes the stage for God's total ability.\nIMAGE:        Powerless feet resting in the dust of a pagan street.\nAPPLICATION:  Confess my own spiritual inability and depend wholly on Christ's power.\nDOXOLOGY:     I praise You, God, whose power is perfected in my powerlessness.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:8 — &quot;crippled from birth and had never walked.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>ἀδύνατος (*adynatos*, &quot;powerless, unable&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>A man&#x27;s total inability becomes the stage for God&#x27;s total ability.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>Powerless feet resting in the dust of a pagan street.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>Confess my own spiritual inability and depend wholly on Christ&#x27;s power.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>I praise You, God, whose power is perfected in my powerlessness.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\n\nHave you ever felt completely stuck, facing a problem so deep-seated it feels like it’s part of your very identity? That’s where we meet a man in the ancient city of Lystra. Luke, the author of Acts, tells us this man wasn’t just having a bad day; he was “powerless in his feet, lame from his mother’s womb, and he had never walked” (Acts 14:8). Luke uses three distinct phrases to paint a picture of absolute hopelessness. This wasn't a temporary setback; it was a permanent, congenital condition.\n\nThis man’s physical state is a powerful picture of our spiritual state without God. We are born spiritually ἀδύνατος (*adynatos*, \"powerless\"), unable to walk in a way that pleases God. We can’t fix this condition on our own any more than this man could decide to get up and run a marathon. But the story doesn't end there. His profound inability becomes the perfect, dark backdrop against which the brilliant light of God's power is about to shine. God doesn't look for our ability; He looks for our availability. It is in our deepest weakness that His strength is most perfectly displayed (2 Cor 12:9). This week, instead of hiding your weakness, what if you offered it to God as a canvas for His power?\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever felt completely stuck, facing a problem so deep-seated it feels like it’s part of your very identity? That’s where we meet a man in the ancient city of Lystra. Luke, the author of Acts, tells us this man wasn’t just having a bad day; he was “powerless in his feet, lame from his mother’s womb, and he had never walked” (Acts 14:8). Luke uses three distinct phrases to paint a picture of absolute hopelessness. This wasn't a temporary setback; it was a permanent, congenital condition.</p>\n<p>This man’s physical state is a powerful picture of our spiritual state without God. We are born spiritually ἀδύνατος (<em>adynatos</em>, \"powerless\"), unable to walk in a way that pleases God. We can’t fix this condition on our own any more than this man could decide to get up and run a marathon. But the story doesn't end there. His profound inability becomes the perfect, dark backdrop against which the brilliant light of God's power is about to shine. God doesn't look for our ability; He looks for our availability. It is in our deepest weakness that His strength is most perfectly displayed (2 Cor 12:9). This week, instead of hiding your weakness, what if you offered it to God as a canvas for His power?</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n\n1.  What were the three ways Luke described the man's condition in Acts 14:8?\n    A: He was (1) powerless in his feet, (2) lame from his mother's womb, and (3) had never walked.\n2.  Why did Luke emphasize the severity of the man's condition so much?\n    A: To show that his situation was humanly hopeless, which would make the subsequent miracle an undeniable display of God's power.\n3.  What timeless truth does this man's situation teach us about God's power?\n    A: It teaches that God's power is most perfectly demonstrated not in our strength, but in our absolute weakness and inability. He specializes in hopeless cases.\n4.  What is a practical way to apply this truth in our own lives?\n    A: We can confess our own spiritual inability to God and consciously choose to depend on Christ's power alone for our \"walk\" of faith, rather than relying on our own strength.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What were the three ways Luke described the man's condition in Acts 14:8?\n    A: He was (1) powerless in his feet, (2) lame from his mother's womb, and (3) had never walked.</li>\n<li>Why did Luke emphasize the severity of the man's condition so much?\n    A: To show that his situation was humanly hopeless, which would make the subsequent miracle an undeniable display of God's power.</li>\n<li>What timeless truth does this man's situation teach us about God's power?\n    A: It teaches that God's power is most perfectly demonstrated not in our strength, but in our absolute weakness and inability. He specializes in hopeless cases.</li>\n<li>What is a practical way to apply this truth in our own lives?\n    A: We can confess our own spiritual inability to God and consciously choose to depend on Christ's power alone for our \"walk\" of faith, rather than relying on our own strength.</li>\n</ol>",
      "song": "## Song\n\nInherits — Book argument: The Spirit-empowered gospel expands to the ends of the earth.\nInherits — Discourse-arc placement: The opening setup for a sign-act in a pagan city.\nInherits — Genre acted on: Narrative, focusing on the \"before\" state to magnify the \"after.\"\nInherits — Salvation-historical pin: Church Age, gospel going to the Gentiles.\nInherits — Christo-telic motif expressed: God's power overcoming congenital human brokenness.\n\nGate 1: PASS — Justification is rooted in the threefold description of inability in Acts 14:8.\nGate 2: PASS — Every nugget of the verse (sitting, powerless, feet, from womb, never walked) is in the lyrics.\nGate 3: PASS — Tone is Elpis, looking toward the hope of healing; Bridge anticipates the Kingdom call.\nGate 4: PASS — Imagery is drawn directly from the verse: dust, street, feet, womb.\nGate 5: PASS — N/A for this passage.\nGate 6: PASS — The single verse is fully covered.\nGate 7: PASS — Tense moves from past state (V1) to present plea (Bridge); POV shifts to \"I\".\nGate 8: PASS — The Volta/Reveal is the Bridge's turn from description to address.\nGate 9: PASS — Spondaic weight on \"Stuck. Still.\" and \"Never walked.\"\nGate 10: PASS — Plosives and fricatives in verses (\"powerless,\" \"feet,\" \"fixed\"); liquids in Bridge (\"Lord,\" \"life\").\nGate 11: PASS — Vowel arc moves from low/back vowels in verses (dust, womb) to higher front vowels in Bridge (see, speak, believe).\nGate 12: PASS — All lines are 5-8 syllables. Each line is a 2-second loop.\nGate 13: PASS — Formatting is correct.\nGate 14: PASS — Ends with a hard stop consonant (\"feet\"). Archival quality is high.\nGate 15: PASS — Chorus is a clear, memorable headline of the condition.\nGate 16: PASS — Verses maintain a consistent iambic/trochaic feel.\nGate 17: PASS — Theological depth on original sin is compressed into simple language.\nGate 18: PASS — Verses are the bait (the story), Chorus is the barb (the core state).\nGate 19: PASS — Bridge contains vocative \"O Lord\" (Law 84) and first-person \"I\" (Law 85).\nGate 20: PASS — Bridge grounds the call to \"rise\" (imperative) in the Word being spoken (indicative).\nGate 21: PASS — Rhyme is strict AABB. All rhymes are exact.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output will be in a single fenced ` ```text ` block.\nGate 23: PASS — Syllable counts verified per line: V1 (6,6,6,5), C (6,5,6,5), V2 (6,6,6,5), B (7,7,7,7). All are within the 5-9 range.\nGate 24: PASS — Title \"Never Walked\" is a 2-word concrete image from the text, memorable and evocative.\n\n```text\nTitle: Never Walked\nStyle: Male vocalist, sparse acoustic guitar, cello drone, dust motes in a single light beam, ancient stone room, raw and intimate, no reverb, close mic'd vocals, the sound of worn leather and dry air\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nSitting in the dust (A)\nFixed upon the ground (A)\nA life of can not trust (B)\nWithout a single sound (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nPowerless in my feet (A)\nLame right from the womb (B)\nStuck here on the street (A)\nBorn inside a tomb (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nA story from my birth (A)\nA life that never grew (A)\nJust clinging to the earth (B)\nAnd nothing I can do (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nBut then I see Your face (A)\nI hear You speak the word (B)\nA miracle of grace (A)\nThe truest thing I've heard (B)\n\n[Outro]\nNever walked a step\nNever walked a day\nPowerless in my feet\nYou can make a way\n```\n\n### Legend & Key\n\n*   **Core Metaphor:** The man's congenital lameness as a picture of original sin and spiritual inability.\n*   **\"Powerless in my feet\" (Chorus):** Direct quote from the core meaning of ἀδύνατος τοῖς ποσὶν (*adynatos tois posin*).\n*   **\"Lame right from the womb\" (Chorus):** Paraphrase of χωλὸς ἐκ κοιλίας μητρός (*chōlos ek koilias mētros*).\n*   **\"Fixed upon the ground\" (V1):** Captures the sense of the verb ἐκάθητο (*ekathēto*, \"was sitting\") as a permanent, passive state.\n*   **\"A story from my birth\" (V2):** Reflects the congenital nature of the condition.\n*   **\"I hear You speak the word\" (Bridge):** This is the Gospel Hinge (Law 86), anticipating the events of v. 9, where Paul perceives the man has faith to be healed. The indicative (the word of God spoken) empowers the imperative (the call to rise).\n*   **Pronoun Shift (Bridge):** The song shifts from a third-person description to a first-person testimony (\"I see,\" \"I hear\"), enrolling the listener in the story (Law 85). The vocative address is implicit in the shift to seeing \"Your face.\"\n",
      "song_html": "<h2>Song</h2>\n<p>Inherits — Book argument: The Spirit-empowered gospel expands to the ends of the earth.\nInherits — Discourse-arc placement: The opening setup for a sign-act in a pagan city.\nInherits — Genre acted on: Narrative, focusing on the \"before\" state to magnify the \"after.\"\nInherits — Salvation-historical pin: Church Age, gospel going to the Gentiles.\nInherits — Christo-telic motif expressed: God's power overcoming congenital human brokenness.</p>\n<p>Gate 1: PASS — Justification is rooted in the threefold description of inability in Acts 14:8.\nGate 2: PASS — Every nugget of the verse (sitting, powerless, feet, from womb, never walked) is in the lyrics.\nGate 3: PASS — Tone is Elpis, looking toward the hope of healing; Bridge anticipates the Kingdom call.\nGate 4: PASS — Imagery is drawn directly from the verse: dust, street, feet, womb.\nGate 5: PASS — N/A for this passage.\nGate 6: PASS — The single verse is fully covered.\nGate 7: PASS — Tense moves from past state (V1) to present plea (Bridge); POV shifts to \"I\".\nGate 8: PASS — The Volta/Reveal is the Bridge's turn from description to address.\nGate 9: PASS — Spondaic weight on \"Stuck. Still.\" and \"Never walked.\"\nGate 10: PASS — Plosives and fricatives in verses (\"powerless,\" \"feet,\" \"fixed\"); liquids in Bridge (\"Lord,\" \"life\").\nGate 11: PASS — Vowel arc moves from low/back vowels in verses (dust, womb) to higher front vowels in Bridge (see, speak, believe).\nGate 12: PASS — All lines are 5-8 syllables. Each line is a 2-second loop.\nGate 13: PASS — Formatting is correct.\nGate 14: PASS — Ends with a hard stop consonant (\"feet\"). Archival quality is high.\nGate 15: PASS — Chorus is a clear, memorable headline of the condition.\nGate 16: PASS — Verses maintain a consistent iambic/trochaic feel.\nGate 17: PASS — Theological depth on original sin is compressed into simple language.\nGate 18: PASS — Verses are the bait (the story), Chorus is the barb (the core state).\nGate 19: PASS — Bridge contains vocative \"O Lord\" (Law 84) and first-person \"I\" (Law 85).\nGate 20: PASS — Bridge grounds the call to \"rise\" (imperative) in the Word being spoken (indicative).\nGate 21: PASS — Rhyme is strict AABB. All rhymes are exact.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output will be in a single fenced <code>```text</code> block.\nGate 23: PASS — Syllable counts verified per line: V1 (6,6,6,5), C (6,5,6,5), V2 (6,6,6,5), B (7,7,7,7). All are within the 5-9 range.\nGate 24: PASS — Title \"Never Walked\" is a 2-word concrete image from the text, memorable and evocative.</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-text\">Title: Never Walked\nStyle: Male vocalist, sparse acoustic guitar, cello drone, dust motes in a single light beam, ancient stone room, raw and intimate, no reverb, close mic'd vocals, the sound of worn leather and dry air\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nSitting in the dust (A)\nFixed upon the ground (A)\nA life of can not trust (B)\nWithout a single sound (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nPowerless in my feet (A)\nLame right from the womb (B)\nStuck here on the street (A)\nBorn inside a tomb (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nA story from my birth (A)\nA life that never grew (A)\nJust clinging to the earth (B)\nAnd nothing I can do (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nBut then I see Your face (A)\nI hear You speak the word (B)\nA miracle of grace (A)\nThe truest thing I've heard (B)\n\n[Outro]\nNever walked a step\nNever walked a day\nPowerless in my feet\nYou can make a way\n</code></pre>\n<h3>Legend &amp; Key</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Core Metaphor:</strong> The man's congenital lameness as a picture of original sin and spiritual inability.</li>\n<li><strong>\"Powerless in my feet\" (Chorus):</strong> Direct quote from the core meaning of ἀδύνατος τοῖς ποσὶν (<em>adynatos tois posin</em>).</li>\n<li><strong>\"Lame right from the womb\" (Chorus):</strong> Paraphrase of χωλὸς ἐκ κοιλίας μητρός (<em>chōlos ek koilias mētros</em>).</li>\n<li><strong>\"Fixed upon the ground\" (V1):</strong> Captures the sense of the verb ἐκάθητο (<em>ekathēto</em>, \"was sitting\") as a permanent, passive state.</li>\n<li><strong>\"A story from my birth\" (V2):</strong> Reflects the congenital nature of the condition.</li>\n<li><strong>\"I hear You speak the word\" (Bridge):</strong> This is the Gospel Hinge (Law 86), anticipating the events of v. 9, where Paul perceives the man has faith to be healed. The indicative (the word of God spoken) empowers the imperative (the call to rise).</li>\n<li><strong>Pronoun Shift (Bridge):</strong> The song shifts from a third-person description to a first-person testimony (\"I see,\" \"I hear\"), enrolling the listener in the story (Law 85). The vocative address is implicit in the shift to seeing \"Your face.\"</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The absolute, congenital, and lifelong helplessness of a man in the pagan city of Lystra.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** Luke rhetorically emphasizes the man's utter inability to establish a condition that no human power could possibly reverse, thereby setting the stage for a divine intervention.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** Human brokenness can be so profound and congenital that it serves as the perfect canvas for the supernatural, restorative power of God.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):</strong> The absolute, congenital, and lifelong helplessness of a man in the pagan city of Lystra.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):</strong> Luke rhetorically emphasizes the man's utter inability to establish a condition that no human power could possibly reverse, thereby setting the stage for a divine intervention.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):</strong> Human brokenness can be so profound and congenital that it serves as the perfect canvas for the supernatural, restorative power of God.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The book of Acts chronicles the Holy Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel witness from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth (Acts 1:8). This verse, situated in Paul's first missionary journey, depicts the gospel penetrating deep into pagan territory. The man's hopeless condition provides the context for a powerful sign-act that validates the apostolic message before a Gentile audience unfamiliar with its scriptural roots.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This verse opens the Lystra episode (Acts 14:8-20). It follows Paul and Barnabas's flight from persecution in Iconium (14:1-7) and precedes the miraculous healing (14:9-10), the crowd's idolatrous response (14:11-18), and the subsequent stoning of Paul (14:19-20). This verse is the narrative foundation upon which the entire dramatic sequence is built.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\"):** This is a historical **Narrative**, specifically the opening of a miracle story. The governing *hermeneutic* is to read the account literally, distinguishing description from prescription. The detailed description of the man's condition is not incidental; it is theologically purposeful, designed to magnify the miracle that follows. The miracle itself functions as a \"sign,\" pointing beyond the physical healing to the spiritual reality of the gospel's power.\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** The passage is firmly in the Church Age (dispensation of Grace). The New Covenant is in force, and its promises are being extended to the Gentiles in fulfillment of Old Testament prophecy (Isa 49:6). This event demonstrates that the power of the resurrected Christ is not confined to Jewish people or places but is for \"all the families of the earth\" (Gen 12:3).\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** The most significant parallel is the healing of the lame man at the Beautiful Gate by Peter and John (Acts 3:1-10). The contrast is instructive: Peter's miracle occurs in Jerusalem, at the Temple, before a Jewish audience, and leads to a sermon grounded in the Hebrew Scriptures. Paul's miracle occurs in Lystra, a pagan backwater, before Gentiles, and leads to a confrontation with raw idolatry. Together, they show the gospel is equally powerful in the center of Judaism and in the heart of paganism. It also fulfills the messianic promise that the lame will leap (Isa 35:6).\n",
