for \"all the families of the earth\" (Gen 12:3).</li>\n<li><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels:</strong> The most significant parallel is the healing of the lame man at the Beautiful Gate by Peter and John (Acts 3:1-10). The contrast is instructive: Peter's miracle occurs in Jerusalem, at the Temple, before a Jewish audience, and leads to a sermon grounded in the Hebrew Scriptures. Paul's miracle occurs in Lystra, a pagan backwater, before Gentiles, and leads to a confrontation with raw idolatry. Together, they show the gospel is equally powerful in the center of Judaism and in the heart of paganism. It also fulfills the messianic promise that the lame will leap (Isa 35:6).</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** This event takes place during Paul’s first missionary journey, dated by conservative scholars like Hoehner to approximately AD 47-48.\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:** Lystra was a city in the Roman province of Galatia, in the district of Lycaonia (modern-day south-central Turkey). It was a Roman colony, founded by Augustus to help pacify the region. Its status as a colony meant it had a significant Roman presence, but the local population was Lycaonian, speaking their own dialect (Acts 14:11). It was not a major trade hub and likely had a very small Jewish population, if any (evidenced by the lack of a synagogue, Paul's usual starting point).\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** The immediate audience in the narrative are the pagan citizens of Lystra. Luke's intended reader for the book of Acts is Theophilus (Acts 1:1) and the broader early church, demonstrating the unstoppable advance of the gospel into Gentile territory.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke, the physician and traveling companion of Paul, is the author, writing as a careful historian (Luke 1:1-4). He selects this event to illustrate a key theme: the gospel's power is demonstrated through signs and wonders, but it is constantly misunderstood by the pagan world, which defaults to its own idolatrous framework (interpreting Paul and Barnabas as Hermes and Zeus).\n*   **Socio-Political Background:** As a Roman colony, Lystra was a pocket of Roman law and culture in a non-Roman region. Local religion, however, was syncretistic. Tier 1 source Ovid (*Metamorphoses* 8.626-724) records a local legend of Zeus and Hermes visiting the region in human form and being received only by the elderly couple Philemon and Baucis. This pre-existing myth provides the crucial background for understanding the crowd's explosive reaction in verse 11, where they identify Barnabas and Paul with these very gods.\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology:</strong> This event takes place during Paul’s first missionary journey, dated by conservative scholars like Hoehner to approximately AD 47-48.</li>\n<li><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography:</strong> Lystra was a city in the Roman province of Galatia, in the district of Lycaonia (modern-day south-central Turkey). It was a Roman colony, founded by Augustus to help pacify the region. Its status as a colony meant it had a significant Roman presence, but the local population was Lycaonian, speaking their own dialect (Acts 14:11). It was not a major trade hub and likely had a very small Jewish population, if any (evidenced by the lack of a synagogue, Paul's usual starting point).</li>\n<li><strong>Original Audience Identification:</strong> The immediate audience in the narrative are the pagan citizens of Lystra. Luke's intended reader for the book of Acts is Theophilus (Acts 1:1) and the broader early church, demonstrating the unstoppable advance of the gospel into Gentile territory.</li>\n<li><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):</strong> Luke, the physician and traveling companion of Paul, is the author, writing as a careful historian (Luke 1:1-4). He selects this event to illustrate a key theme: the gospel's power is demonstrated through signs and wonders, but it is constantly misunderstood by the pagan world, which defaults to its own idolatrous framework (interpreting Paul and Barnabas as Hermes and Zeus).</li>\n<li><strong>Socio-Political Background:</strong> As a Roman colony, Lystra was a pocket of Roman law and culture in a non-Roman region. Local religion, however, was syncretistic. Tier 1 source Ovid (<em>Metamorphoses</em> 8.626-724) records a local legend of Zeus and Hermes visiting the region in human form and being received only by the elderly couple Philemon and Baucis. This pre-existing myth provides the crucial background for understanding the crowd's explosive reaction in verse 11, where they identify Barnabas and Paul with these very gods.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\n\n*   **Literal-Primary Filter:** The verse is a straightforward description of a man's physical state. Luke, the physician, provides a threefold diagnosis to establish the severity and hopelessness of the case beyond any doubt.\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax:** Luke stacks three descriptions to create a powerful rhetorical effect of totality:\n    1.  **ἀδύνατος τοῖς ποσὶν** (*adynatos tois posin*, \"powerless in the feet\"): This is the functional diagnosis. The word ἀδύνατος (*adynatos*) is a compound of *a-* (a negative prefix) and *dynatos* (\"powerful, able\"). He is literally \"not-able,\" completely without power in his feet. The dative case τοῖς ποσὶν (*tois posin*) specifies the location of his inability.\n    2.  **χωλὸς ἐκ κοιλίας μητρὸς αὐτοῦ** (*chōlos ek koilias mētros autou*, \"lame from his mother's womb\"): This is the etiological diagnosis. His condition is congenital. χωλὸς (*chōlos*, \"lame/crippled\") is the specific term for this disability. The phrase ἐκ κοιλίας μητρός (*ek koilias mētros*, \"from a mother's womb\") is a standard Semitic idiom for a congenital condition (cf. John 9:1), emphasizing it was not caused by accident or disease later in life.\n    3.  **ὃς οὐδέποτε περιεπεπατήκει** (*hos oudepote periepepatēkei*, \"who had never walked\"): This is the historical diagnosis, confirming the previous two. The emphatic negative οὐδέποτε (*oudepote*) means \"never at any time.\" The verb περιεπεπατήκει (*periepepatēkei*) is in the pluperfect tense, which describes a state completed in the past. It portrays his non-walking status as a settled, permanent feature of his life up to that point.\n*   **Imagery & Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):** The image of the man \"sitting\" (ἐκάθητο, *ekathēto*) is one of passivity and permanence. He is not just resting; he is fixed, grounded by his disability. He becomes a living symbol of the Gentile world's condition from a spiritual perspective: born into a state of separation from God (Eph 2:1-3), powerless to approach Him, and having \"never walked\" in His ways. His physical healing will therefore serve as a powerful metaphor for the spiritual life and freedom the gospel offers.\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Literal-Primary Filter:</strong> The verse is a straightforward description of a man's physical state. Luke, the physician, provides a threefold diagnosis to establish the severity and hopelessness of the case beyond any doubt.</li>\n<li><strong>Linguistic Mechanics &amp; Syntax:</strong> Luke stacks three descriptions to create a powerful rhetorical effect of totality:<ol>\n<li><strong>ἀδύνατος τοῖς ποσὶν</strong> (<em>adynatos tois posin</em>, \"powerless in the feet\"): This is the functional diagnosis. The word ἀδύνατος (<em>adynatos</em>) is a compound of <em>a-</em> (a negative prefix) and <em>dynatos</em> (\"powerful, able\"). He is literally \"not-able,\" completely without power in his feet. The dative case τοῖς ποσὶν (<em>tois posin</em>) specifies the location of his inability.</li>\n<li><strong>χωλὸς ἐκ κοιλίας μητρὸς αὐτοῦ</strong> (<em>chōlos ek koilias mētros autou</em>, \"lame from his mother's womb\"): This is the etiological diagnosis. His condition is congenital. χωλὸς (<em>chōlos</em>, \"lame/crippled\") is the specific term for this disability. The phrase ἐκ κοιλίας μητρός (<em>ek koilias mētros</em>, \"from a mother's womb\") is a standard Semitic idiom for a congenital condition (cf. John 9:1), emphasizing it was not caused by accident or disease later in life.</li>\n<li><strong>ὃς οὐδέποτε περιεπεπατήκει</strong> (<em>hos oudepote periepepatēkei</em>, \"who had never walked\"): This is the historical diagnosis, confirming the previous two. The emphatic negative οὐδέποτε (<em>oudepote</em>) means \"never at any time.\" The verb περιεπεπατήκει (<em>periepepatēkei</em>) is in the pluperfect tense, which describes a state completed in the past. It portrays his non-walking status as a settled, permanent feature of his life up to that point.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Imagery &amp; Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):</strong> The image of the man \"sitting\" (ἐκάθητο, <em>ekathēto</em>) is one of passivity and permanence. He is not just resting; he is fixed, grounded by his disability. He becomes a living symbol of the Gentile world's condition from a spiritual perspective: born into a state of separation from God (Eph 2:1-3), powerless to approach Him, and having \"never walked\" in His ways. His physical healing will therefore serve as a powerful metaphor for the spiritual life and freedom the gospel offers.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment (Whole-Passage):** The healing of this man is a fulfillment of messianic prophecy. Isaiah prophesied that in the age of salvation, \"the lame man [shall] leap like a deer\" (Isa 35:6). [PROPHECY] Jesus's ministry was marked by such healings, which He cited as evidence of His messianic identity (Luke 7:22). Now, the apostles, as witnesses of the resurrected Messiah, continue to perform the same signs by His power and in His name, demonstrating that the age of salvation has dawned and its power is active through the church.\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** The motif is **God's power overcoming congenital human brokenness.**\n    *   *Genesis:* Humanity is born in a fallen state, spiritually crippled from the \"womb\" of Adam's sin (Gen 3; Rom 5:12).\n    *   *Law:* The Law reveals this crippled state but cannot heal it (Rom 3:20; 7:7-11).\n    *   *Prophets:* Isaiah foresees a day of miraculous restoration when the lame will leap (Isa 35:6).\n    *   *Gospels:* Christ, the Messiah, repeatedly heals the lame, demonstrating His authority to restore what was broken from birth (John 5:1-9; John 9:1-7). This is the *hinge-of-hinges*.\n    *   *Acts:* The apostolic church, empowered by the Spirit, continues Christ's restorative work, demonstrating that His power is present with them (Acts 3:1-10; 14:8-10).\n    *   *Epistles:* Paul explains the spiritual reality: believers are raised from spiritual death to \"walk in newness of life\" (Rom 6:4).\n    *   *Revelation:* The trajectory finds its *Christo-telic terminus* (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") in the New Jerusalem, where there will be no more pain or crying, and the curse of brokenness is undone forever (Rev 21:4). The terminus verse is Rev 21:4.\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:**\n    *   ☐ Anthropology (\"the doctrine of humanity as God made us\") & ☐ Hamartiology (\"the doctrine of sin and the Fall\"): The man's congenital condition is a powerful illustration of the doctrine of original sin—a state of inability we are born into, not one we acquire.\n    *   ☐ Christology (\"the doctrine of the person and work of Christ\"): The subsequent healing demonstrates Christ's ongoing power and authority, exercised through His apostles, to reverse the effects of the Fall.\n    *   ☐ Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"): The physical healing is a sign of the greater spiritual salvation offered in the gospel, which gives spiritual \"feet\" to those who could never walk in righteousness on their own.\n",
      "phase_f_canonical_html": "<h3>Canonical Connection</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Foreshadowing &amp; Fulfillment (Whole-Passage):</strong> The healing of this man is a fulfillment of messianic prophecy. Isaiah prophesied that in the age of salvation, \"the lame man [shall] leap like a deer\" (Isa 35:6). [PROPHECY] Jesus's ministry was marked by such healings, which He cited as evidence of His messianic identity (Luke 7:22). Now, the apostles, as witnesses of the resurrected Messiah, continue to perform the same signs by His power and in His name, demonstrating that the age of salvation has dawned and its power is active through the church.</li>\n<li><strong>Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):</strong> The motif is <strong>God's power overcoming congenital human brokenness.</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Genesis:</em> Humanity is born in a fallen state, spiritually crippled from the \"womb\" of Adam's sin (Gen 3; Rom 5:12).</li>\n<li><em>Law:</em> The Law reveals this crippled state but cannot heal it (Rom 3:20; 7:7-11).</li>\n<li><em>Prophets:</em> Isaiah foresees a day of miraculous restoration when the lame will leap (Isa 35:6).</li>\n<li><em>Gospels:</em> Christ, the Messiah, repeatedly heals the lame, demonstrating His authority to restore what was broken from birth (John 5:1-9; John 9:1-7). This is the <em>hinge-of-hinges</em>.</li>\n<li><em>Acts:</em> The apostolic church, empowered by the Spirit, continues Christ's restorative work, demonstrating that His power is present with them (Acts 3:1-10; 14:8-10).</li>\n<li><em>Epistles:</em> Paul explains the spiritual reality: believers are raised from spiritual death to \"walk in newness of life\" (Rom 6:4).</li>\n<li><em>Revelation:</em> The trajectory finds its <em>Christo-telic terminus</em> (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") in the New Jerusalem, where there will be no more pain or crying, and the curse of brokenness is undone forever (Rev 21:4). The terminus verse is Rev 21:4.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:</strong><ul>\n<li>☐ Anthropology (\"the doctrine of humanity as God made us\") &amp; ☐ Hamartiology (\"the doctrine of sin and the Fall\"): The man's congenital condition is a powerful illustration of the doctrine of original sin—a state of inability we are born into, not one we acquire.</li>\n<li>☐ Christology (\"the doctrine of the person and work of Christ\"): The subsequent healing demonstrates Christ's ongoing power and authority, exercised through His apostles, to reverse the effects of the Fall.</li>\n<li>☐ Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"): The physical healing is a sign of the greater spiritual salvation offered in the gospel, which gives spiritual \"feet\" to those who could never walk in righteousness on their own.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
