 You see the faith\" is a clear gospel hinge.\nGate 21: PASS — AABB rhyme scheme is declared and strictly followed with exact rhymes.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is in a single, copy-friendly <code>```text</code> fenced block.\nGate 23: PASS — Syllable counts verified per line (all are 6-8).\nGate 24: PASS — Title \"The Faith to Be Healed\" is concrete, memorable, and from the Chorus.</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-text\">Title: The Faith to Be Healed\nStyle: Southern Gospel, Male quartet, Upright piano, Hammond B3 organ, Simple drum beat, Large room acoustics, live room bleed, thick mid-range, wooden resonance, environmental air, no noise reduction, raw analog capture, tape saturation\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nBound and broken from his birth (A)\nNever walked upon the earth (A)\nHeard the Word that Paul proclaimed (B)\nA hope he'd never dared to name (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nAnd Paul looked down and saw it then (A)\nA new life waiting to begin (A)\nHe saw he had the faith to be healed (B)\nThe power of God was now revealed (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nWe sit and listen to the sound (A)\nOn our own helpless ground (A)\nThe gospel story, strong and true (B)\nCreates a faith inside of you (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nO Lord, Your Spirit can perceive (A)\nThe trust Your own dear Word can weave (A)\nIt's not a strength that we possess (B)\nOur brokenness is our address (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nAnd You look down and see it then (A)\nA new life waiting to begin (A)\nYou see we have the faith to be healed (B)\nYour power, O Lord, is now revealed (B)\n\n[Outro]\nThe Word was heard, the faith was seen (A)\nA soul restored, a body clean (A)\nHe leaped and walked and stood up tall (B)\nBy faith that answered to the call (B)\n\n[End]\n</code></pre>",
      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\")**: The Apostle Paul's focused, spiritual perception of a lame man's internal state as he listened to the gospel.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\")**: Paul discerned that the man possessed a genuine, God-given faith sufficient to receive divine healing, which then served as the basis for the subsequent miracle.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\")**: The power of the proclaimed gospel creates discernible, saving faith in the hearer, which is the channel for God's miraculous intervention.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\")</strong>: The Apostle Paul's focused, spiritual perception of a lame man's internal state as he listened to the gospel.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\")</strong>: Paul discerned that the man possessed a genuine, God-given faith sufficient to receive divine healing, which then served as the basis for the subsequent miracle.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\")</strong>: The power of the proclaimed gospel creates discernible, saving faith in the hearer, which is the channel for God's miraculous intervention.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role**: The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the church from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth (Acts 1:8). This verse is a microcosm of that thesis, showing the gospel penetrating a pagan Gentile city (Lystra) on the First Missionary Journey, with apostolic ministry authenticated by a sign-miracle that hinges on the faith of a local recipient.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc**: This verse sits within the narrative of Paul's First Missionary Journey (Acts 13–14). It is the pivot point in the Lystra episode (14:8-20), connecting the preaching of the gospel (v. 7) to the performance of the miracle (v. 10). The sequence is crucial: Word proclaimed → Faith created → Faith discerned → Power demonstrated.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic**: The genre is **Historical Narrative**. The governing hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this descriptively, not necessarily prescriptively for all believers. Luke records what happened, highlighting the unique authority and spiritual gifting of an apostle to discern an internal state. The event demonstrates the nature of faith as a response to the Word (Rom 10:17).\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational)**: This event occurs firmly within the **Church Age** (Dispensation of Grace), under the New Covenant. It exemplifies the \"to the Jew first, and also to the Greek\" pattern breaking out into purely Gentile territory, fulfilling Christ's commission and demonstrating that the blessings of the kingdom are available to all through faith, apart from the Mosaic Law.\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels**:\n    *   **Peter at the Beautiful Gate (Acts 3:1-10)**: A direct parallel in Acts. An apostle encounters a man lame from birth, healing occurs through faith in Jesus' name, and it becomes a public spectacle and preaching opportunity.\n    *   **Jesus and the Paralytic (Mark 2:5)**: Jesus \"saw their faith\" and healed the man, explicitly linking faith and physical restoration.\n    *   **The Woman with the Issue of Blood (Mark 5:34)**: Jesus tells her, \"your faith has made you well (literally, *saved you*).\" The same Greek root, σῴζω (*sōzō*), is used.\n    *   **Faith Comes by Hearing (Rom 10:17)**: This verse is a narrative illustration of Paul's later theological statement: ἄρα ἡ πίστις ἐξ ἀκοῆς (*ara hē pistis ex akoēs*, \"so then, faith comes by hearing\"). The man \"was listening\" before he had faith.\n",
      "phase_c_big_picture_html": "<h3>Big Picture: Where this passage fits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Whole-Book Thesis &amp; Passage's Role</strong>: The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the church from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth (Acts 1:8). This verse is a microcosm of that thesis, showing the gospel penetrating a pagan Gentile city (Lystra) on the First Missionary Journey, with apostolic ministry authenticated by a sign-miracle that hinges on the faith of a local recipient.</li>\n<li><strong>Discourse / Section Arc</strong>: This verse sits within the narrative of Paul's First Missionary Journey (Acts 13–14). It is the pivot point in the Lystra episode (14:8-20), connecting the preaching of the gospel (v. 7) to the performance of the miracle (v. 10). The sequence is crucial: Word proclaimed → Faith created → Faith discerned → Power demonstrated.</li>\n<li><strong>Genre &amp; Hermeneutic</strong>: The genre is <strong>Historical Narrative</strong>. The governing hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this descriptively, not necessarily prescriptively for all believers. Luke records what happened, highlighting the unique authority and spiritual gifting of an apostle to discern an internal state. The event demonstrates the nature of faith as a response to the Word (Rom 10:17).</li>\n<li><strong>Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational)</strong>: This event occurs firmly within the <strong>Church Age</strong> (Dispensation of Grace), under the New Covenant. It exemplifies the \"to the Jew first, and also to the Greek\" pattern breaking out into purely Gentile territory, fulfilling Christ's commission and demonstrating that the blessings of the kingdom are available to all through faith, apart from the Mosaic Law.</li>\n<li><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels</strong>:<ul>\n<li><strong>Peter at the Beautiful Gate (Acts 3:1-10)</strong>: A direct parallel in Acts. An apostle encounters a man lame from birth, healing occurs through faith in Jesus' name, and it becomes a public spectacle and preaching opportunity.</li>\n<li><strong>Jesus and the Paralytic (Mark 2:5)</strong>: Jesus \"saw their faith\" and healed the man, explicitly linking faith and physical restoration.</li>\n<li><strong>The Woman with the Issue of Blood (Mark 5:34)</strong>: Jesus tells her, \"your faith has made you well (literally, <em>saved you</em>).\" The same Greek root, σῴζω (<em>sōzō</em>), is used.</li>\n<li><strong>Faith Comes by Hearing (Rom 10:17)</strong>: This verse is a narrative illustration of Paul's later theological statement: ἄρα ἡ πίστις ἐξ ἀκοῆς (<em>ara hē pistis ex akoēs</em>, \"so then, faith comes by hearing\"). The man \"was listening\" before he had faith.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology**: The event takes place during Paul and Barnabas's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars (Hoehner) to approximately **AD 47-48**.\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography**: **Lystra** was a city in the district of Lycaonia, part of the Roman province of Galatia (modern-day south-central Turkey, near Hatunsaray). It was a Roman colony, which gave it certain civic privileges. Its remote, somewhat rustic location, compared to a metropolis like Ephesus, helps explain the locals' pagan superstition in the subsequent verses (14:11-13).\n*   **Original Audience Identification**: The audience of the book of Acts was Theophilus (Acts 1:1) and the wider early church, composed of both Jewish and Gentile believers. The audience *in Lystra* was predominantly pagan Gentiles, who practiced a local form of Greco-Roman polytheism, as evidenced by their immediate identification of Barnabas with Zeus and Paul with Hermes (Acts 14:12).\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text)**: Luke, the physician and historian, is the author, writing an orderly account to confirm the certainty of the gospel's historical reality and Spirit-powered advance. His focus here is on the legitimate transfer of gospel authority to Paul and the power that accompanies his apostolic ministry.\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology</strong>: The event takes place during Paul and Barnabas's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars (Hoehner) to approximately <strong>AD 47-48</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography</strong>: <strong>Lystra</strong> was a city in the district of Lycaonia, part of the Roman province of Galatia (modern-day south-central Turkey, near Hatunsaray). It was a Roman colony, which gave it certain civic privileges. Its remote, somewhat rustic location, compared to a metropolis like Ephesus, helps explain the locals' pagan superstition in the subsequent verses (14:11-13).</li>\n<li><strong>Original Audience Identification</strong>: The audience of the book of Acts was Theophilus (Acts 1:1) and the wider early church, composed of both Jewish and Gentile believers. The audience <em>in Lystra</em> was predominantly pagan Gentiles, who practiced a local form of Greco-Roman polytheism, as evidenced by their immediate identification of Barnabas with Zeus and Paul with Hermes (Acts 14:12).</li>\n<li><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text)</strong>: Luke, the physician and historian, is the author, writing an orderly account to confirm the certainty of the gospel's historical reality and Spirit-powered advance. His focus here is on the legitimate transfer of gospel authority to Paul and the power that accompanies his apostolic ministry.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\nThis verse is a chain of three key actions leading to the miracle: the man's hearing, Paul's looking, and Paul's seeing.\n\nThe man's posture is captured by the verb ἤκουεν (*ēkouen*, \"he was listening\"). The imperfect tense is significant; it denotes continuous, ongoing action in the past. He wasn't a passive bystander; he was actively and persistently absorbing the message Paul was preaching. This is the soil in which faith grows, per Romans 10:17.\n\nPaul's action is described with two participles. First, ἀτενίσας (*atenisas*, \"having stared intently\"). This is more than a casual glance. The word implies a fixed, penetrating gaze, a common feature in Luke-Acts for moments of spiritual intensity (Acts 1:10, 3:4, 7:55). It signals that Paul is looking beyond the surface.\n\nSecond, ἰδὼν (*idōn*, \"having seen / perceiving\"). This seeing is the result of the staring. It is not physical sight but spiritual discernment, a perception of the man's inner state. What did Paul see? ὅτι ἔχει πίστιν (*hoti echei pistin*, \"that he has faith\"). Faith is described as a possession, something the man \"has.\" This wasn't a vague hope but a concrete, present reality in the man, created by the hearing of the Word.\n\nThe nature of this faith is defined by the articular infinitive of purpose: τοῦ σωθῆναι (*tou sōthēnai*, \"of the (thing) to be saved / healed\"). The verb σῴζω (*sōzō*) has a wide semantic range in the New Testament, encompassing physical healing, deliverance from danger, and spiritual salvation. In this context, it brilliantly holds both meanings in tension. The man heard a gospel about spiritual salvation, and his faith was for *that*. Paul discerned this spiritual reality and saw that it was the sufficient condition for the man to also receive physical salvation (healing). The physical miracle would serve as a powerful sign and seal of the greater spiritual reality of the gospel message he had just believed. This was not the \"faith\" of prosperity theology, which seeks to manipulate God for physical blessing, but a genuine, gospel-wrought trust in the person and work of Christ, which made him a candidate for a sign of that gospel's power.\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<p>This verse is a chain of three key actions leading to the miracle: the man's hearing, Paul's looking, and Paul's seeing.</p>\n<p>The man's posture is captured by the verb ἤκουεν (<em>ēkouen</em>, \"he was listening\"). The imperfect tense is significant; it denotes continuous, ongoing action in the past. He wasn't a passive bystander; he was actively and persistently absorbing the message Paul was preaching. This is the soil in which faith grows, per Romans 10:17.</p>\n<p>Paul's action is described with two participles. First, ἀτενίσας (<em>atenisas</em>, \"having stared intently\"). This is more than a casual glance. The word implies a fixed, penetrating gaze, a common feature in Luke-Acts for moments of spiritual intensity (Acts 1:10, 3:4, 7:55). It signals that Paul is looking beyond the surface.</p>\n<p>Second, ἰδὼν (<em>idōn</em>, \"having seen / perceiving\"). This seeing is the result of the staring. It is not physical sight but spiritual discernment, a perception of the man's inner state. What did Paul see? ὅτι ἔχει πίστιν (<em>hoti echei pistin</em>, \"that he has faith\"). Faith is described as a possession, something the man \"has.\" This wasn't a vague hope but a concrete, present reality in the man, created by the hearing of the Word.</p>\n<p>The nature of this faith is defined by the articular infinitive of purpose: τοῦ σωθῆναι (<em>tou sōthēnai</em>, \"of the (thing) to be saved / healed\"). The verb σῴζω (<em>sōzō</em>) has a wide semantic range in the New Testament, encompassing physical healing, deliverance from danger, and spiritual salvation. In this context, it brilliantly holds both meanings in tension. The man heard a gospel about spiritual salvation, and his faith was for <em>that</em>. Paul discerned this spiritual reality and saw that it was the sufficient condition for the man to also receive physical salvation (healing). The physical miracle would serve as a powerful sign and seal of the greater spiritual reality of the gospel message he had just believed. This was not the \"faith\" of prosperity theology, which seeks to manipulate God for physical blessing, but a genuine, gospel-wrought trust in the person and work of Christ, which made him a candidate for a sign of that gospel's power.</p>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment**:\n    *   **[PROPHECY]** This healing is a direct fulfillment of Messianic prophecy, where the restoration of the lame is a sign of the kingdom's arrival (Isa 35:6, \"then shall the lame man leap like a deer\"). The apostles, as Christ's agents, continue this ministry, demonstrating that the age of salvation has dawned.\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic)**: The motif is **faith as the receptive channel for God's power**.\n    *   It begins with Abraham, whose belief was credited as righteousness (Gen 15:6).\n    *   It is exemplified throughout Christ's ministry, where He repeatedly responds to the faith of individuals (Mark 2:5; 5:34; 10:52).\n    *   It is articulated here in Acts as the basis for an apostolic miracle.\n    *   It is doctrinally expounded by Paul as the sole instrument of justification (Rom 3:28; Gal 2:16; Eph 2:8).\n    *   The **Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\")** is the believer's final glorification, the ultimate \"being saved\" that this physical healing foreshadows, secured by faith in the resurrected Christ. The **terminus verse** is Philippians 3:21, which speaks of the transformation of our lowly bodies to be like His glorious body.\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag**:\n    *   **Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\")**: Demonstrates that faith, created by the Word, is the instrument for receiving God's saving grace (Eph 2:8-9).\n    *   **Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\")**: The discernment Paul exercises is a gift of the Holy Spirit, enabling him to see a spiritual reality not visible to the natural eye (1 Cor 12:10, perhaps \"discerning of spirits\").\n    *   **Christology (\"the doctrine of the person and work of Christ\")**: The healing, though not explicitly stated here, is done in the name and by the power of Jesus Christ, whose authority the apostles wield (Acts 3:6, 16).\n    *   **Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\")**: Highlights the foundational role of the apostles, whose ministry was uniquely authenticated by \"signs and wonders\" (2 Cor 12:12).\n",
      "phase_f_canonical_html": "<h3>Canonical Connection</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Foreshadowing &amp; Fulfillment</strong>:<ul>\n<li><strong>[PROPHECY]</strong> This healing is a direct fulfillment of Messianic prophecy, where the restoration of the lame is a sign of the kingdom's arrival (Isa 35:6, \"then shall the lame man leap like a deer\"). The apostles, as Christ's agents, continue this ministry, demonstrating that the age of salvation has dawned.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic)</strong>: The motif is <strong>faith as the receptive channel for God's power</strong>.<ul>\n<li>It begins with Abraham, whose belief was credited as righteousness (Gen 15:6).</li>\n<li>It is exemplified throughout Christ's ministry, where He repeatedly responds to the faith of individuals (Mark 2:5; 5:34; 10:52).</li>\n<li>It is articulated here in Acts as the basis for an apostolic miracle.</li>\n<li>It is doctrinally expounded by Paul as the sole instrument of justification (Rom 3:28; Gal 2:16; Eph 2:8).</li>\n<li>The <strong>Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\")</strong> is the believer's final glorification, the ultimate \"being saved\" that this physical healing foreshadows, secured by faith in the resurrected Christ. The <strong>terminus verse</strong> is Philippians 3:21, which speaks of the transformation of our lowly bodies to be like His glorious body.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Systematic-Theology Loci Tag</strong>:<ul>\n<li><strong>Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\")</strong>: Demonstrates that faith, created by the Word, is the instrument for receiving God's saving grace (Eph 2:8-9).</li>\n<li><strong>Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\")</strong>: The discernment Paul exercises is a gift of the Holy Spirit, enabling him to see a spiritual reality not visible to the natural eye (1 Cor 12:10, perhaps \"discerning of spirits\").</li>\n<li><strong>Christology (\"the doctrine of the person and work of Christ\")</strong>: The healing, though not explicitly stated here, is done in the name and by the power of Jesus Christ, whose authority the apostles wield (Acts 3:6, 16).</li>\n<li><strong>Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\")</strong>: Highlights the foundational role of the apostles, whose ministry was uniquely authenticated by \"signs and wonders\" (2 Cor 12:12).</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
