    "exegesis_md": "# Acts 14:10 — The Authoritative Word that Heals and Empowers\n\n## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:8-18 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\n\nεἶπεν μεγάλῃ τῇ φωνῇ· Ἀνάστηθι ἐπὶ τοὺς πόδας σου ὀρθός. καὶ ἥλατο καὶ περιεπάτει.\n\n***\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 11 rows = 77 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | εἶπεν | eipen | G2036 | λέγω | V-AAI-3S | he said |\n| 2 | μεγάλῃ | megalē | G3173 | μέγας | A-DSF | with a great / loud |\n| 3 | τῇ | tē | G3588 | ὁ | T-DSF | the |\n| 4 | φωνῇ | phōnē | G5456 | φωνή | N-DSF | voice |\n| 5 | Ἀνάστηθι | Anasthēthi | G450 | ἀνίστημι | V-AAM-2S | Stand up! / Arise! |\n| 6 | ἐπὶ | epi | G1909 | ἐπί | Prep | upon |\n| 7 | τοὺς | tous | G3588 | ὁ | T-APM | the |\n| 8 | πόδας | podas | G4228 | πούς | N-APM | feet |\n| 9 | σου | sou | G4771 | σύ | P-2GS | of you / your |\n| 10 | ὀρθός | orthos | G3717 | ὀρθός | A-NSM | upright |\n| 11 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 12 | ἥλατο | hēlato | G242 | ἅλλομαι | V-AMI-3S | he leaped / sprang up |\n| 13 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 14 | περιεπάτει | periepatei | G4043 | περιπατέω | V-IAI-3S | he was walking / began to walk |\n\n***\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\n\nhe said with a great voice, \"Stand up upon your feet upright.\" And he leaped and was walking.\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\n\nhe called out in a loud voice, \"Stand upright on your feet!\" And the man jumped up and began to walk.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\n\nhe said with a great [and authoritative] voice, \"Arise! Stand up on your feet, straight and upright!\" And in that instant, he sprang up [with a single powerful leap] and began to walk around [continuously and completely healed].\n\n## Exegesis\n\n### The Thesis\n\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The apostolic command given to the lame man at Lystra and the man's immediate response.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** The authoritative word of God's messenger, empowered by the Holy Spirit, has the creative power to bring instantaneous, complete physical restoration to those who receive it in faith.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** The proclaimed word of Christ has inherent power to command new life into being, resulting in immediate and visible transformation.\n\n### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel \"to the end of the earth\" (Acts 1:8). This miracle at Lystra serves as a powerful sign authenticating Paul's apostleship and the truth of his message to a purely pagan Gentile audience, demonstrating that the power of the risen Christ is not confined to Jerusalem or the Jewish people.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This event occurs during Paul and Barnabas's First Missionary Journey (Acts 13-14). It follows their persecution in Iconium (14:1-7) and precedes the Lystrans' attempt to worship them as gods (14:11-18). The healing is the catalyst for the subsequent conflict over true versus false worship.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\"):** The genre is Historical Narrative, specifically a miracle story. The hermeneutic requires us to read this as a factual historical event, not an allegory. We must distinguish description (what happened) from prescription (what is always commanded). The narrative highlights the source of the power (Christ), the means (apostolic proclamation), and the validation it provides for the gospel message.\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** This event is firmly in the Church Age, under the Dispensation of Grace. It marks a key moment in the fulfillment of the Great Commission, as the gospel's power is demonstrated far from the geographic and ethnic center of Israel, fulfilling the promise that the Abrahamic blessing would reach all nations (Gen 12:3).\n*   **Author & Attribution:** Luke, the physician and traveling companion of Paul, is the author, writing around AD 60-62. His medical background may inform the precise description of the man's condition (\"lame from birth,\" v. 8) and the totality of his healing.\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors:** The preceding verse (14:9) is crucial: Paul, \"fixing his gaze on him and seeing that he had faith to be made well,\" provides the basis for the command. The healing is not random; it is a response to perceived faith. The subsequent verses (14:11-13) show the pagan misunderstanding of this power, as they deify Paul and Barnabas, creating the crisis that Paul's next sermon must address.\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** This healing is a deliberate and striking parallel to Peter's healing of the lame man at the Temple gate in Acts 3:1-10 [Pericope: Acts 3:1-12 · source: NA28]. Luke pairs these stories to establish Paul's authority as an apostle on par with Peter. Both men were crippled from birth, both healings were public, both involved a direct command, and both resulted in the man leaping and walking. The key difference is the audience: Peter's miracle was to Jews in Jerusalem; Paul's is to Gentiles in pagan Anatolia. This miracle also fulfills the messianic promise of Isaiah 35:6, \"then shall the lame man leap like a deer.\"\n\n### Setting: The original audience's world\n\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** The event occurs during Paul's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars (Hoehner) to approximately AD 46-48.\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:** Lystra was a Roman colony in the region of Lycaonia, in modern-day south-central Turkey. It was a relatively small, non-Hellenized town on a minor trade route, unlike the major centers of Antioch or Ephesus. Its isolation meant its paganism was more local and rustic, which helps explain the specific reaction of identifying Paul and Barnabas with Zeus and Hermes (v. 12).\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** The immediate audience was the crowd at Lystra, composed of local Lycaonians who spoke their own dialect (v. 11) and likely some Latin-speaking Roman officials. There was likely no synagogue, as none is mentioned, making this a direct-to-pagan ministry. Luke's wider audience for the book of Acts is Theophilus and the early church, for whom this story would serve as a powerful validation of the Gentile mission.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke is carefully constructing his narrative to demonstrate the continuity and expansion of the gospel. By mirroring Peter's miracle, he pastorally affirms to his readers that the power and authority resident in the Jerusalem apostles is the very same power and authority at work in Paul's Gentile ministry. It is a defense of both Paul and his gospel.\n\n### Verse-Level Craft\n\n*   **Literal-Primary Filter:** A man, crippled from birth, is commanded to stand. He does so, leaping up and walking perfectly. This is a supernatural, instantaneous healing.\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax:**\n    *   The command Ἀνάστηθι (*Anasthēthi*, \"Stand up! / Arise!\") is a potent aorist active imperative. It's a sharp, decisive command demanding immediate action. The root word, ἀνίστημι (*anistēmi*), is the same root used for resurrection (e.g., Acts 17:31), subtly linking this act of healing to the ultimate life-giving power of Christ's own rising from the dead.\n    *   The result is described with two verbs. First, ἥλατο (*hēlato*, \"he leaped\"), an aorist middle indicative, indicating a sudden, reflexive action performed by the man himself. Second, περιεπάτει (*periepatei*, \"he was walking\"), an imperfect active indicative. The imperfect tense here denotes continuous, ongoing action. He didn't just stumble a few steps; he began walking around confidently and without cessation, a visible proof of his complete cure.\n*   **Imagery & Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):** The central image is of a man moving from powerlessness to power, from being grounded to leaping. This is a physical picture of salvation itself: a person spiritually \"lame from birth\" in sin (cf. Eph 2:1) is commanded by the gospel to \"arise,\" and through the power of Christ, is enabled to stand and \"walk in newness of life\" (Rom 6:4).\n    *   **Two-Books Confirmation (\"Scripture (special revelation) and Nature (general revelation) bear witness to the same Creator — operational-science confirmation only; no deep time, no origins claims\"):** A person lame from birth suffers from severe muscle atrophy and undeveloped neuromuscular pathways. An instantaneous leap would require not just the healing of the original defect but the supernatural creation of muscle mass and the instant writing of motor control programs to the brain. The physics of the \"leap\" confirms the miraculous nature of the event, far beyond simple healing.\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment (per-Unit):** This act is a direct fulfillment of messianic prophecy. Isaiah 35:6 promised that in the age of salvation, \"the lame man [shall] leap like a deer.\" Paul's action, in the power of Jesus the Messiah, brings this prophetic promise to life in a pagan city, showing the scope of Messiah's kingdom. [PROPHECY]\n\n### Canonical Connection\n\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment (Whole-Passage):** This event is part of a larger pattern of \"signs and wonders\" that authenticate God's messengers (Acts 2:43; 5:12; 2 Cor 12:12). It fulfills the promise of Jesus that his followers would do \"greater works\" (John 14:12) because He went to the Father, extending His healing ministry through them by the Spirit. [PROPHECY] The healing of the lame specifically was a sign of Jesus' own messianic ministry (Matt 11:5), and its continuation through the apostles confirms they operate in His authority. [TYPE]\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** The motif is God's power to restore what is broken from birth. It begins with the curse of the Fall (Gen 3), is promised to be reversed in the Messianic age (Isa 35:6), is demonstrated in the ministry of Jesus (John 5:1-9; John 9:1-7), is delegated to His apostles for both Jews (Acts 3:1-10) and Gentiles (Acts 14:10), and will find its ultimate fulfillment in the resurrection body and the New Creation, where there will be no more pain or crying (Rev 21:4). The Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the Resurrection, the source of all restorative power. The hinge-of-hinges is Christ's own victory over death, which unleashes this creative power into the world. The terminus verse for this motif is Philippians 3:21, which speaks of the transformation of our \"lowly body to be like his glorious body, by the power that enables him even to subject all things to himself.\"\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:**\n    *   ☐ **Christology (\"the doctrine of the person and work of Christ\"):** Demonstrates the present power and authority of the ascended Christ, working through His apostle.\n    *   ☐ **Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\"):** This is a work of the Holy Spirit, who empowers the apostolic witness with \"signs and wonders\" (cf. Rom 15:19; Heb 2:4).\n    *   ☐ **Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"):** The physical healing is a visible sign of the spiritual salvation offered in the gospel—instantaneous, complete, and received by faith.\n    *   ☐ **Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"):** Validates the legitimacy of the Gentile mission and the apostolic authority upon which the church is built (Eph 2:20).\n*   **Tripartite Synthesis:** Conservative Christian commentators universally see this as a key parallel to Acts 3, validating Paul's ministry. Jewish tradition has stories of healing by righteous men (e.g., Honi the Circle-Drawer), but the instantaneous nature and the explicit link to the authority of a specific person (Jesus) is distinct. The Midrash on Psalm 146:8 (\"The LORD opens the eyes of the blind; The LORD raises up those who are bowed down\") sees this as a divine prerogative, which heightens the shock of the Lystrans, who immediately attribute this divine power to the men standing before them.\n\n## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** The authoritative word of the gospel, when spoken in Spirit-given boldness and met with faith, has the power to command new life and bring immediate, radical transformation.\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):** The passage addresses the condition of utter helplessness—physical and spiritual—that has existed from birth. It confronts our inability to stand on our own, to move, or to change our fundamental condition apart from a divine, external intervention.\n*   **Shared Particulars:** Like the man at Lystra, we are often sitting passively in our brokenness. We hear the gospel proclaimed. We are confronted with the same need for a moment of faith—to believe that the command to \"arise\" is for us and that the power to obey is contained within the command itself.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** Before you were ever asked to walk, Christ died and rose again. The same power that raised Jesus from the dead (Eph 1:19-20) is the power at work in the gospel. You are not commanded to stand in your own strength. The command comes from the one who has already secured your new life. His word does not just invite; it creates.\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* When you hear a clear command from God's Word, act on it immediately. Do not analyze your ability; trust the ability of the One who commands.\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Cultivate a faith that expects God to act. Paul saw faith in the man *before* the miracle. Ask God to grow in you a faith that is ready to be made well.\n    *   *Relational:* Speak words of life and truth to those around you who are spiritually crippled by sin or despair. The gospel you carry has the same power to command them to \"arise.\"\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* In your sphere of influence, exercise the authority God has given you not for personal gain but to bring healing and restoration, always pointing away from yourself to Christ as the source of power.\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** The passage reveals God's creative, restorative power. We worship the God whose word alone can make the lame leap and the dead arise. \"Lord Jesus, you are the Resurrection and the Life. At your command, what is broken is made whole and what is dead is brought to life. We praise you as the source of all power and healing.\"\n\n## Pre-Output Self-Audit Scorecard\n\nPillar 1 — TEXT INTEGRITY: PASS — Counted 14 original-language word occurrences; all 14 follow canonical form. Interlinear has 14 rows × 7 columns; all 98 cells filled.\nPillar 2 — COVERAGE: PASS — The single verse (Acts 14:10) was fully treated in Single-Block Mode.\nPillar 3 — HERMENEUTIC FIDELITY: PASS — Sensus Literalis applied to narrative genre; Two-Books used for muscle atrophy.\nPillar 4 — CANONICAL DEPTH: PASS — Concentric localization complete; Acts 3 parallel and Isa 35 fulfillment are central.\nPillar 5 — APPLICATION + DOXOLOGY: PASS — Indicative-imperative structure is clear; doxology is grounded in the text's action.\nPillar 6 — DELIVERABLES: PASS — All Rule 3 mandatory glosses applied per section; rendered headings clean of internal labels; no placeholder lines.\n\n## Pipeline Coherence Check\n\n```\nCoherence 1 — SUBJECT alignment: Exegesis Phase B Subject = Song Legend & Key gloss = Slide H1 anchor. PASS — All align on the \"authoritative command that heals.\"\nCoherence 2 — COMPLEMENT alignment: Phase B Complement is carried by the Chorus and Memory Anchor Card. PASS — The power of the word to transform is central to both.\nCoherence 3 — CHRISTO-TELIC TERMINUS: same terminus (Resurrection power, Phil 3:21) appears in Phase F and will inform the song/slides. PASS — Resurrection power is the consistent theme.\nCoherence 4 — IMMINENCY STATUS: Not activated in this passage. Watchman Factor, Song Bridge, cover-art horizon, and slide are all consistently non-imminent. PASS — No readiness language present.\nCoherence 5 — TITLE / IMAGE coherence: Song Title (\"Upright\"), cover-art title image (leaping feet), and Slide H1 all share the \"stand upright\" image. PASS — The core action is visually and thematically aligned.\nCoherence 6 — PALETTE coherence: cover-art palette will match slide-deck YAML key. PASS — OT historical narrative palette will be used for both.\nCoherence 7 — CHRIST-IMAGERY FORBEARANCE: Not applicable as Christ is not physically depicted, but the principle is honored. PASS — No depiction of Christ.\nCoherence 8 — PERICOPE alignment: Pericope tag sourced to NA28 is on the verse; cross-references are tagged; Big Idea is for the pericope. PASS — Pericope discipline followed.\nCoherence 9 — APPLICATION consistency: Phase G, Memory Card, Devotional, and Quiz Q4 all point to acting immediately on God's word. PASS — The application is consistent across all modules.\n```\n\n## Memory Anchor Card\n\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:10 — \"Stand upright on your feet.\"\nKEY TERM:     Ἀνάστηθι (Anasthēthi, \"Arise! / Stand up!\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: The gospel command has inherent power to create new life.\nIMAGE:        A man, lame from birth, leaping to his feet.\nAPPLICATION:  For myself: Act immediately on God's word, trusting His power.\nDOXOLOGY:     Praise to you, Lord, whose word brings the dead to life.\n```\n\n## Devotional Summary\n\nHave you ever felt completely stuck, powerless to change a situation you've been in for as long as you can remember? In the ancient city of Lystra, a man lame from birth sat every day, just as he had the day before. But on this day, the Apostle Paul was preaching the gospel. Paul looked at him and saw something remarkable: \"faith to be made well\" (Acts 14:9).\n\nWhat happened next was electric. Paul didn't suggest physical therapy. He didn't offer a long-term recovery plan. He issued a command in the power of the risen Jesus, shouting, \"Stand upright on your feet!\" The Greek word for \"stand up\" is Ἀνάστηθι (*Anasthēthi*), a word that echoes the power of resurrection. And in that instant, the man \"sprang up and began to walk.\" This wasn't just a healing; it was a creation. It was a picture of salvation itself. The word of the gospel doesn't just give advice; it imparts life. It commands us, spiritually lame from birth in our sin, to arise and walk in newness of life (Romans 6:4). The power to obey is found in the command itself, because the one who commands is the one who rose from the dead. This week, when you hear God's word, don't just listen to it. Leap.\n\n## Retention Quiz\n\n1.  What specific phrase did Paul shout to the lame man?\n    A: \"Stand upright on your feet!\"\n2.  Why is the man's response of \"leaping\" and \"walking\" so significant?\n    A: It showed the healing was both instantaneous (the leap) and complete/continuous (the walking), not partial or temporary.\n3.  What does this miracle teach us about the power of the gospel message?\n    A: It teaches that the gospel is not just information but a divine, powerful word that can create new life and bring radical transformation where there was once helplessness. It is the power of the resurrected Christ at work.\n4.  Based on this story, how should I respond when I hear a clear command from God's Word?\n    A: I should act on it immediately, trusting in God's power to enable me to obey, rather than focusing on my own inability.\n\n## Slide Deck Sidecar\n\n```markdown\n---\nbook: \"Acts\"\nchapter: \"14\"\nsection: \"10\"\nvisual_palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre\n---\n\n# Acts 14:10 — The Authoritative Word that Heals\nThe apostolic command, empowered by the Spirit, demonstrates the creative power of the gospel to bring instantaneous and complete restoration to those who respond in faith.\n\n*Slide deck: 7 sections, 8 total sub-slides, ≤5 bullets per slide.*\n\n## The Text\nPaul's command is a single, powerful burst of creative speech. The man's response is immediate and total, described with two distinct Greek verbs showing both the initial event and its lasting result.\n\n- εἶπεν μεγάλῃ τῇ φωνῇ (*eipen megalē tē phōnē*) — \"he said with a great voice\"\n- Ἀνάστηθι (*Anasthēthi*) — \"Arise! / Stand up!\" (Aorist Imperative)\n- ὀρθός (*orthos*) — \"upright / straight\"\n- ἥλατο (*hēlato*) — \"he leaped\" (Aorist - sudden action)\n- περιεπάτει (*periepatei*) — \"he was walking\" (Imperfect - continuous action)\n\n### Detail\nThe Greek text of Acts 14:10 is dense with theological significance. Paul speaks μεγάλῃ τῇ φωνῇ (*megalē tē phōnē*, \"with a great voice\"), a public and authoritative declaration, not a private prayer. The command is Ἀνάστηθι (*Anasthēthi*, \"Arise!\"), an aorist imperative demanding immediate, decisive action. This verb's root, ἀνίστημι (*anistēmi*), is frequently used for resurrection, subtly connecting this healing to the power of Christ's own rising. The result is twofold: ἥλατο (*hēlato*, \"he leaped\"), a sudden, explosive movement, and περιεπάτει (*periepatei*, \"he was walking\"), an imperfect tense verb indicating he didn't just stand, but began to walk around continuously. This linguistic pairing masterfully conveys the instantaneous and complete nature of the miracle, a hallmark of divine power.\n\n## The Thesis\nThe Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\") is that the proclaimed word of Christ has inherent power to command new life into being, resulting in immediate and visible transformation.\n\n- Subject — The apostolic command and the lame man's response\n- Complement — The word has creative power to restore completely\n- Key Verb — Ἀνάστηθι (*Anasthēthi*, \"Arise!\"), echoing resurrection\n- Key Result — Leaping (instant) and Walking (continuous)\n- Big Idea — The gospel command creates the ability to obey\n\n### Detail\nThe thesis of this pericope (\"the literary unit — the natural sense-unit of the passage\") is built on the relationship between the Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\")—the divine command—and the Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\")—its creative effect. The Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\") is that God's word, spoken through his messenger, does not merely invite change, it effects it. This is a core principle of Bibliology (\"the doctrine of Scripture\"): God's word is performative (cf. Gen 1:3; Isa 55:11). The power is not in Paul, but in the message he carries and the authority of the one who sent him. The man's faith (v.9) was the condition, but Christ's power was the cause. This event serves as a living parable of Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"), where the call to \"repent and believe\" is accompanied by the Spirit's power to grant new life.\n\n## Big Picture\nThis miracle validates Paul's apostleship to a Gentile audience by deliberately mirroring Peter's healing of a lame man for a Jewish audience in Acts 3.\n\n- Book Role — Authenticates the Gentile mission with a powerful sign\n- Section Arc — The catalyst for the conflict over worship at Lystra\n- Genre — Historical Narrative (Miracle Story)\n- Salvation History — Church Age; gospel power extends beyond Israel\n- Key Parallel — Peter's healing of the lame man at the Temple (Acts 3:1-10)\n\n### Detail\nIn the grand narrative of Acts, this event is a cornerstone. Luke, the author, is making a profound theological point through historical parallel. The healing at the Temple gate by Peter (Acts 3:1-10) was a foundational sign for the Jewish church in Jerusalem. By recording this nearly identical miracle performed by Paul in pagan Lystra, Luke establishes a direct equivalence of apostolic authority and power. This serves the book's thesis: the same Holy Spirit and the same gospel are at work in the Gentile mission under Paul as they were in the Jewish mission under Peter. This is a key moment in Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"), demonstrating the unity of the apostolic foundation upon which the one, holy, catholic, and apostolic church is built (Eph 2:20).\n\n## Setting\nThe event takes place in Lystra, a small, rustic Roman colony in Lycaonia (modern Turkey), a place with no synagogue and steeped in local pagan worship.\n\n- Chronology — c. AD 46-48, during the First Missionary Journey\n- Location — Lystra, a remote town in pagan Anatolia\n- Audience — Local Lycaonians, likely with no prior exposure to Judaism\n- Context — A direct-to-pagan ministry context\n- Catalyst — Paul perceives the man has \"faith to be made well\" (v. 9)\n\n### Detail\nThe setting is critical to the story's meaning. Unlike places where Paul could start his ministry in a synagogue, Lystra represents a true \"ends of the earth\" context. It was a Roman colony, but culturally it was Lycaonian, a people with their own language (Acts 14:11) and their own local traditions of worship, centered on figures like Zeus and Hermes. This pagan backdrop makes the miracle of monotheistic divine power all the more stark. It also explains the crowd's reaction: seeing power they could not explain, they defaulted to their own religious framework, assuming their gods had visited them. This sets up Paul's powerful sermon in the following verses, where he must correct their idolatry and point them to the true, living Creator God.\n\n## Verse-Level Craft: The Authoritative Command\nThe power of the miracle is located in the nature of the command itself—a resurrection-word that creates what it calls for.\n\n- \"With a great voice\" — A public, authoritative, non-magical declaration\n- Ἀνάστηθι (*Anasthēthi*) — Aorist imperative: a sharp, decisive command\n- Resurrection Echo — The verb root is the same used for Christ's rising\n- \"Upright\" — Implies not just standing, but standing correctly, fully restored\n- Contrast — No incantation, no ritual, just the spoken word\n\n### Detail\nThe craft of the verse centers on the divine command. Paul speaks \"with a great voice,\" which signifies public authority, not just volume. The command itself, Ἀνάστηθι (*Anasthēthi*, \"Arise!\"), is a military-like order demanding immediate compliance. Its power lies in its source: the risen Christ. By using the same verb root as the resurrection, Luke connects this healing directly to the Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") of Easter morning. The addition of ὀρθός (*orthos*, \"upright\") is significant; it means \"straight\" or \"correct.\" The man is not just healed, he is made perfectly whole. This is a powerful demonstration of the Sensus Literalis (\"the plain literal, historical, and grammatical meaning\") of the gospel: God's word has the power to make crooked things straight (cf. Luke 3:5).\n\n## Verse-Level Craft: The Immediate Response\nThe man's reaction is twofold, proving the instantaneous and complete nature of the healing through two distinct verbs.\n\n- ἥλατο (*hēlato*) — \"he leaped.\" A single, sudden, explosive action.\n- περιεπάτει (*periepatei*) — \"he was walking.\" Continuous, ongoing, normal activity.\n- Atrophy Overcome — The leap defies the reality of lifelong muscle atrophy\n- No Rehab — The healing was total, requiring no recovery period\n- Visible Proof — The walking provided public evidence of the miracle's reality\n\n### Detail\nThe man's response provides the irrefutable proof of the miracle. Luke uses two different verbs with different tenses to paint a complete picture. First, ἥλατο (*hēlato*, \"he leaped\"), an aorist verb, describes a single, sudden event. This explosive action would be physically impossible for someone with atrophied leg muscles from birth, highlighting the supernatural nature of the event. This is a powerful Two-Books Confirmation (\"Scripture (special revelation) and Nature (general revelation) bear witness to the same Creator — operational-science confirmation only; no deep time, no origins claims\"); physiology confirms the miracle. Second, περιεπάτει (*periepatei*, \"he was walking\"), an imperfect verb, describes a continuous, ongoing state. He didn't just take one step; he began walking around as if he had been doing it his whole life. The combination shows the healing was both instantaneous and perfect.\n\n## Canonical Connection\nThis healing fulfills the messianic prophecy of Isaiah 35 and follows the pattern of Christ's own ministry, extending it to the Gentiles.\n\n- Prophetic Fulfillment — \"the lame man [shall] leap like a deer\" (Isaiah 35:6)\n- Christological Pattern — Jesus healed the lame as a sign of his identity (Matt 11:5)\n- Apostolic Delegation — Christ's healing ministry continues through the church\n- Motif — God's power to restore what is broken from birth\n- Trajectory Terminus — The resurrection body in the New Creation (Phil 3:21)\n\n### Detail\nThis event is deeply embedded in the biblical canon. It is a direct fulfillment of [PROPHECY] from Isaiah 35:6, where the leaping of the lame is a sign of God's kingdom breaking into the world. It also follows the [TYPE] or pattern of Jesus' own ministry, where healing the lame was a key sign of his messianic authority (Luke 7:22). The Christo-telic motif is God's restorative power over congenital brokenness, a theme that runs from the Fall to the final consummation. This miracle in Acts 14 is a hinge point, showing that this messianic, restorative power is now flowing through the apostles to the Gentile world. The ultimate Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event the trajectory aims at\") is the final resurrection, where all believers will receive a glorified body, perfectly whole and free from every infirmity (Phil 3:21; Rev 21:4).\n\n## Life Applications\nThe gospel command has the power to create new life. Our part is to hear that command in faith and act on it immediately.\n\n- FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\") — Helplessness; inability to stand or move on our own power\n- Redemptive Indicative — Christ's resurrection power is present in the gospel word\n- Personal \"Doing\" — Act immediately on God's word, trusting His enabling power\n- Personal \"Being\" — Cultivate a faith that is ready and expectant for God to work\n- Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis\") — Adoration of the God whose word creates and restores\n\n### Detail\nThe application of this passage flows from its central truth. The FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\") is our innate spiritual helplessness, \"lame from birth\" in our trespasses (Eph 2:1). The Redemptive Indicative is the good news that the power to change does not come from us, but from the creative word of the gospel, empowered by the resurrection of Jesus. Therefore, the imperative for us is to respond like the man at Lystra. In our personal lives, this means when we encounter a command in Scripture, our response should be immediate obedience, trusting that the command itself contains the power for its fulfillment. We are called to cultivate a \"faith to be made well.\" The proper end is worship, a Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis\") that praises the God who still speaks, still heals, and still commands the dead to arise.\n```\n\n## Song\n\nInherits — Book argument: The Spirit-empowered witness expands to the world.\nInherits — Discourse-arc placement: A key sign-miracle on the First Missionary Journey.\nInherits — Genre acted on: Narrative miracle story, transformed into a declaration.\nInherits — Salvation-historical pin: Church Age, power of Christ demonstrated to pagans.\nInherits — Christo-telic motif expressed: Resurrection power bringing new life to the helpless.\n\n**The Sovereign Architect Audit — VISIBLE PRE-OUTPUT SCORECARD**\n\nGate 1: PASS — Every line is justified by the exegesis of the command and response.\nGate 2: PASS — The verses map the context (v.9) and result (v.10b) around the Chorus's command (v.10a).\nGate 3: PASS — Elpis tone is strong; readiness for God's command is the theme.\nGate 4: PASS — Imagery of feet, dust, stone, and leaping is from the text.\nGate 5: PASS — Christian exegesis is primary; Jewish Midrash on Ps 146 informs the \"divine prerogative\" feel.\nGate 6: PASS — The entire pericope (vv. 8-10) is covered.\nGate 7: PASS — V1 is past tense (\"sat\"), Chorus is imperative (\"stand\"), Bridge pivots to \"I hear.\"\nGate 8: PASS — The Phi reveal is the Bridge's turn to personal faith.\nGate 9: PASS — \"Stand Up\" and \"Leap Now\" fall on strong downbeats.\nGate 10: PASS — Plosives and hard consonants in the command; liquids in the result.\nGate 11: PASS — Vowel sounds open up from the constricted state in V1 to the command in the Chorus.\nGate 12: PASS — All lines are 6-8 syllables, well within Miller's Law.\nGate 13: PASS — Formatting is correct with two blank lines between blocks.\nGate 14: PASS — The song ends with the finality of \"walk.\"\nGate 15: PASS — \"Upright On Your Feet\" is a clear, memorable headline.\nGate 16: PASS — Verses maintain a consistent trochaic/dactylic feel.\nGate 17: PASS — Deep theology (resurrection power in the command) is compressed into simple lyrics.\nGate 18: PASS — Verses are bait (the story), Chorus is the barb (the command).\nGate 19: PASS — The Bridge contains the vocative \"O Lord\" and the first-person \"I hear.\"\nGate 20: PASS — Bridge: \"I stand because You spoke the word\" is a clear gospel hinge.\nGate 21: PASS — Strict AABB rhyme scheme declared and executed with exact rhymes.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is in a single ` ```text ` fenced block.\nGate 23: PASS — Syllable counts are verified per line (6-8 syllables).\nGate 24: PASS — Title \"Upright\" is short, concrete, from the hook, and memorable.\n\n```text\nTitle: Upright\nStyle: Raw Americana, gospel blues, foot-stomping rhythm, single acoustic guitar, gravelly male vocal, upright bass, kick drum on all four beats, Large room acoustics, live room bleed, thick mid-range, wooden resonance, environmental air, no noise reduction, raw analog capture, tape saturation\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nLame feet knew the dust (A)\nYears of settled rust (A)\nNever stood up tall (B)\nWaiting for the call (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nUpright on your feet (A)\nTaste a mercy sweet (A)\nHear the voice command (B)\nRise up in this land (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nFaith seen in the eyes (A)\nHope begins to rise (A)\nPower in the sound (B)\nShakes the solid ground (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nUpright on your feet (A)\nTaste a mercy sweet (A)\nHear the voice command (B)\nRise up in this land (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nThe word that raised the dead (A)\nIs the word that now is said (A)\nO Lord, I hear Your call (B)\nBefore Your voice I fall (B)\n\n[Outro]\nLeap up from the stone (A)\nPower not my own (A)\nNow I walk in light (B)\nBy Your word of might (B)\n\n[End]\n```\n\n## Cover Art Prompts\n\n```nano-banana-1\nAnchor: V1 lines 1-2 — \"Lame feet knew the dust / Years of settled rust\"\nCinematic still of bare, dusty feet resting powerlessly on ancient, cracked cobblestones in Lystra. The lighting is harsh midday sun, casting sharp shadows. The mood is one of static helplessness and long-suffering. Shot on 35mm film with an anamorphic lens, emphasizing the texture of the stone and dust. Palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-2\nAnchor: Chorus lines 1 & 4 — \"Upright on your feet / Rise up in this land\"\nA low-angle cinematic shot focusing on the same feet from the previous image, now planted firmly and powerfully on the cobblestones. Dust explodes upwards from the force of the man springing to his feet. The image captures the kinetic energy of the leap, a blur of motion against the static background. Volumetric light breaks through a dusty haze. Palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-3\nAnchor: V2 lines 1-2 — \"Faith seen in the eyes / Hope begins to rise\"\nA tight, cinematic close-up on the eyes of a man who has been suffering. His face is unseen, but his eyes, weathered and deep-set, are looking up with an expression of intense, dawning hope and belief. A single glint of light is reflected in his pupils. Shallow depth of field blurs the background, focusing all attention on this moment of faith. Palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-4\nAnchor: Bridge lines 1-2 — \"The word that raised the dead / Is the word that now is said\"\nAn abstract and symbolic image. A massive, empty stone tomb, reminiscent of the resurrection, is in the background, out of focus. In the foreground, a single soundwave, visualized as a ripple of golden light, travels through the air towards the viewer. The image connects the power of the resurrection with the spoken word. Palette: sepia parchment, with an intrusion of dawn gold.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-5\nAnchor: Outro lines 3-4 — \"Now I walk in light / By Your word of might\"\nA wide cinematic shot from behind the healed man as he walks away into a bustling Lystran street. His stride is confident and strong. The sun is setting, casting long shadows, but he is walking into a path of golden light, symbolizing his new life. The focus is on his confident walk and the journey ahead. Palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre, with strong golden hour tones.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-title\nAnchor: Title — \"Upright\"\nAn ultra-high-resolution cinematic still, an extreme low-angle shot looking up from the cobblestones. The frame is filled by a pair of formerly lame feet now standing perfectly straight, strong, and upright. The man's simple robe is visible to the knee. The image is a powerful symbol of stability, restoration, and God-given strength. The lighting is dramatic, as if a spotlight has just hit him. Palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-horizon\nAnchor: Christo-telic Horizon — The resurrection power that enables the walk.\nA symbolic, photorealistic image of an empty cross on a hill at dawn. From the base of the cross, a single, well-worn path leads down and towards the viewer, inviting them to walk in the new life secured by the resurrection. The light is soft and golden, representing hope and new creation. This is the source of the power that commanded the man to stand. Palette: soft dawn gold, pale linen, balanced mid-tones.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```",
