      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:8-20 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\n\n> 11 οἵ τε ὄχλοι ἰδόντες ὃ ἐποίησεν Παῦλος ἐπῆραν τὴν φωνὴν αὐτῶν Λυκαονιστὶ λέγοντες· Οἱ θεοὶ ὁμοιωθέντες ἀνθρώποις κατέβησαν πρὸς ἡμᾶς.\n\n***\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 13 rows = 91 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | οἵ | hoi | G3588 | ὁ | Art-NPM | the |\n| 2 | τε | te | G5037 | τέ | Conj | and / both |\n| 3 | ὄχλοι | ochloi | G3793 | ὄχλος | N-NPM | crowds |\n| 4 | ἰδόντες | idontes | G1492 | ὁράω | V-AAP-NPM | having seen |\n| 5 | ὃ | ho | G3739 | ὅς | Pro-AN-S | what |\n| 6 | ἐποίησεν | epoiēsen | G4160 | ποιέω | V-AAI-3S | he did |\n| 7 | Παῦλος | Paulos | G3972 | Παῦλος | N-NSM | Paul |\n| 8 | ἐπῆραν | epēran | G1869 | ἐπαίρω | V-AAI-3P | they lifted up |\n| 9 | φωνὴν | phōnēn | G5456 | φωνή | N-ASF | voice |\n| 10 | Λυκαονιστὶ | Lykaonisti | G3072 | Λυκαονιστί | Adv | in the Lycaonian language |\n| 11 | λέγοντες | legontes | G3004 | λέγω | V-PAP-NPM | saying |\n| 12 | θεοὶ | theoi | G2316 | θεός | N-NPM | gods |\n| 13 | κατέβησαν | katebēsan | G2597 | καταβαίνω | V-AAI-3P | they came down |\n\n***\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation**\n\n> 11 And the crowds, having seen what Paul did, lifted up their voice in Lycaonian, saying, \"The gods, having become like men, came down to us.\"\n\n**Standalone English Translation**\n\n> 11 When the crowds saw what Paul had done, they raised their voices, shouting in the Lycaonian language, \"The gods have come down to us in human form!\"\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation**\n\n> 11 And when the crowds witnessed what Paul had done [instantly healing a man lame from birth], they instinctively lifted up their collective voice, shouting not in the common Greek but in their native Lycaonian tongue, saying, \"The gods themselves, having taken on the likeness of mortal men, have descended to visit us!\"\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:8-20 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Script (NA28)</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>11 οἵ τε ὄχλοι ἰδόντες ὃ ἐποίησεν Παῦλος ἐπῆραν τὴν φωνὴν αὐτῶν Λυκαονιστὶ λέγοντες· Οἱ θεοὶ ὁμοιωθέντες ἀνθρώποις κατέβησαν πρὸς ἡμᾶς.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 13 rows = 91 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>οἵ</td>\n<td>hoi</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>Art-NPM</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>τε</td>\n<td>te</td>\n<td>G5037</td>\n<td>τέ</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and / both</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>ὄχλοι</td>\n<td>ochloi</td>\n<td>G3793</td>\n<td>ὄχλος</td>\n<td>N-NPM</td>\n<td>crowds</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>ἰδόντες</td>\n<td>idontes</td>\n<td>G1492</td>\n<td>ὁράω</td>\n<td>V-AAP-NPM</td>\n<td>having seen</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>ὃ</td>\n<td>ho</td>\n<td>G3739</td>\n<td>ὅς</td>\n<td>Pro-AN-S</td>\n<td>what</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>ἐποίησεν</td>\n<td>epoiēsen</td>\n<td>G4160</td>\n<td>ποιέω</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3S</td>\n<td>he did</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>Παῦλος</td>\n<td>Paulos</td>\n<td>G3972</td>\n<td>Παῦλος</td>\n<td>N-NSM</td>\n<td>Paul</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>ἐπῆραν</td>\n<td>epēran</td>\n<td>G1869</td>\n<td>ἐπαίρω</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3P</td>\n<td>they lifted up</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>φωνὴν</td>\n<td>phōnēn</td>\n<td>G5456</td>\n<td>φωνή</td>\n<td>N-ASF</td>\n<td>voice</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>Λυκαονιστὶ</td>\n<td>Lykaonisti</td>\n<td>G3072</td>\n<td>Λυκαονιστί</td>\n<td>Adv</td>\n<td>in the Lycaonian language</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>λέγοντες</td>\n<td>legontes</td>\n<td>G3004</td>\n<td>λέγω</td>\n<td>V-PAP-NPM</td>\n<td>saying</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>θεοὶ</td>\n<td>theoi</td>\n<td>G2316</td>\n<td>θεός</td>\n<td>N-NPM</td>\n<td>gods</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>κατέβησαν</td>\n<td>katebēsan</td>\n<td>G2597</td>\n<td>καταβαίνω</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3P</td>\n<td>they came down</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>11 And the crowds, having seen what Paul did, lifted up their voice in Lycaonian, saying, \"The gods, having become like men, came down to us.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>11 When the crowds saw what Paul had done, they raised their voices, shouting in the Lycaonian language, \"The gods have come down to us in human form!\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>11 And when the crowds witnessed what Paul had done [instantly healing a man lame from birth], they instinctively lifted up their collective voice, shouting not in the common Greek but in their native Lycaonian tongue, saying, \"The gods themselves, having taken on the likeness of mortal men, have descended to visit us!\"</p>\n</blockquote>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\")**: Without the clarifying truth of God's Word, even genuine encounters with divine power will be misinterpreted through the idolatrous lens of the fallen human heart.\n\n*   **Fallen Condition Focus (FCF)**: The passage diagnoses the universal human tendency to worship the messenger instead of the Message-Giver, to deify human beings or experiences, and to fit God into our pre-existing cultural or personal boxes rather than allowing His Word to shatter them.\n    *   *Individual*: The reflex to elevate and idolize charismatic leaders, powerful figures, or even spiritual gifts, rather than Christ Himself.\n    *   *Corporate*: The danger for a church or movement to become centered on a dynamic personality, a particular style of worship, or a pattern of miraculous signs, rather than on the gospel of Jesus Christ.\n\n*   **Shared Particulars**: We, like the Lystrans, live in a world saturated with \"spirituality\" and stories of power. We are constantly tempted to interpret God's work through the lens of pop psychology, political ideologies, or consumerist self-help, rather than through the grid of Scripture.\n\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding)**: The good news is that the true God *did* come down in the likeness of men. Jesus Christ did not come as a mythical figure but as a historical person. He did not come for a brief visit but to live, die for our idolatry, and rise again to give us new minds to understand and worship Him correctly (1 Cor 2:16; Rom 12:2). Because of Christ, we are freed from having to invent our own gods and can know the one true God personally.\n\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace)**:\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\"*: When you witness God's power at work (an answered prayer, a changed life), immediately give verbal and explicit glory to Jesus Christ. Refuse to let the focus settle on the person or the method.\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\"*: Cultivate a heart of humility that, like Paul and Barnabas, is horrified by any praise that belongs to God alone. See yourself as a pointer to Christ, not the destination.\n    *   *Relational*: In your church, gently but firmly correct any conversation that drifts toward idolizing a pastor, worship leader, or any other human being. Continually re-center the community's focus on Christ (Col 1:18).\n    *   *Public / Vocational*: In your witness to unbelievers, be prepared for them to misunderstand. Do not just share stories of God's power; share the gospel that interprets that power correctly. Power attracts, but only truth saves.\n\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\")**:\n    *   **Attribute(s) of God surfaced**: God's exclusive right to worship; His transcendent otherness from all created things.\n    *   **One-sentence doxology**: To You alone, O Lord, who are not like the gods of myth but are the Creator of heaven and earth, be all glory for every good and powerful work.\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\")</strong>: Without the clarifying truth of God's Word, even genuine encounters with divine power will be misinterpreted through the idolatrous lens of the fallen human heart.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Fallen Condition Focus (FCF)</strong>: The passage diagnoses the universal human tendency to worship the messenger instead of the Message-Giver, to deify human beings or experiences, and to fit God into our pre-existing cultural or personal boxes rather than allowing His Word to shatter them.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Individual</em>: The reflex to elevate and idolize charismatic leaders, powerful figures, or even spiritual gifts, rather than Christ Himself.</li>\n<li><em>Corporate</em>: The danger for a church or movement to become centered on a dynamic personality, a particular style of worship, or a pattern of miraculous signs, rather than on the gospel of Jesus Christ.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Shared Particulars</strong>: We, like the Lystrans, live in a world saturated with \"spirituality\" and stories of power. We are constantly tempted to interpret God's work through the lens of pop psychology, political ideologies, or consumerist self-help, rather than through the grid of Scripture.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding)</strong>: The good news is that the true God <em>did</em> come down in the likeness of men. Jesus Christ did not come as a mythical figure but as a historical person. He did not come for a brief visit but to live, die for our idolatry, and rise again to give us new minds to understand and worship Him correctly (1 Cor 2:16; Rom 12:2). Because of Christ, we are freed from having to invent our own gods and can know the one true God personally.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace)</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\"</em>: When you witness God's power at work (an answered prayer, a changed life), immediately give verbal and explicit glory to Jesus Christ. Refuse to let the focus settle on the person or the method.</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\"</em>: Cultivate a heart of humility that, like Paul and Barnabas, is horrified by any praise that belongs to God alone. See yourself as a pointer to Christ, not the destination.</li>\n<li><em>Relational</em>: In your church, gently but firmly correct any conversation that drifts toward idolizing a pastor, worship leader, or any other human being. Continually re-center the community's focus on Christ (Col 1:18).</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational</em>: In your witness to unbelievers, be prepared for them to misunderstand. Do not just share stories of God's power; share the gospel that interprets that power correctly. Power attracts, but only truth saves.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\")</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Attribute(s) of God surfaced</strong>: God's exclusive right to worship; His transcendent otherness from all created things.</li>\n<li><strong>One-sentence doxology</strong>: To You alone, O Lord, who are not like the gods of myth but are the Creator of heaven and earth, be all glory for every good and powerful work.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:11 — \"The gods have come down to us in the likeness of men!\"\nKEY TERM:     θεοὶ (*theoi*, \"gods\") — the crowd's plural, pagan error.\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: A divine miracle, misinterpreted by a pagan heart, leads to idolatry.\nIMAGE:        A shouting crowd pointing at two dusty missionaries.\nAPPLICATION:  When God works, I will give all glory to Christ alone, not to the human instrument.\nDOXOLOGY:     You alone are God; there is no other who deserves our praise.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:11 — &quot;The gods have come down to us in the likeness of men!&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>θεοὶ (*theoi*, &quot;gods&quot;) — the crowd&#x27;s plural, pagan error.</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>A divine miracle, misinterpreted by a pagan heart, leads to idolatry.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>A shouting crowd pointing at two dusty missionaries.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>When God works, I will give all glory to Christ alone, not to the human instrument.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>You alone are God; there is no other who deserves our praise.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever seen something amazing—a dramatic answer to prayer or a life suddenly turned around—and been tempted to focus on the person God used? In the ancient city of Lystra, Paul and Barnabas encountered this in the extreme. After Paul healed a man who had been lame his entire life, the local crowd exploded. But they didn't praise God. Instead, reverting to their native language and local myths, they began shouting, \"The gods have come down to us in human form!\" (Acts 14:11). They saw God's power but filtered it through their own pagan beliefs, ready to worship the messengers instead of the one who sent them.\n\nThis raw, historical moment reveals a tendency deep in our own hearts: to misinterpret God's work and create idols. We can idolize pastors, ministries, or even our own spiritual experiences. The story is a powerful reminder that God's power must always be paired with God's truth. The good news is that God really *did* come down in the likeness of men—not as a myth, but in the person of Jesus Christ (John 1:14). He came not just to show power, but to die for our idolatrous hearts and give us new minds to worship Him rightly. This week, when you see God move, make a conscious choice to give all the glory to Christ alone.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever seen something amazing—a dramatic answer to prayer or a life suddenly turned around—and been tempted to focus on the person God used? In the ancient city of Lystra, Paul and Barnabas encountered this in the extreme. After Paul healed a man who had been lame his entire life, the local crowd exploded. But they didn't praise God. Instead, reverting to their native language and local myths, they began shouting, \"The gods have come down to us in human form!\" (Acts 14:11). They saw God's power but filtered it through their own pagan beliefs, ready to worship the messengers instead of the one who sent them.</p>\n<p>This raw, historical moment reveals a tendency deep in our own hearts: to misinterpret God's work and create idols. We can idolize pastors, ministries, or even our own spiritual experiences. The story is a powerful reminder that God's power must always be paired with God's truth. The good news is that God really <em>did</em> come down in the likeness of men—not as a myth, but in the person of Jesus Christ (John 1:14). He came not just to show power, but to die for our idolatrous hearts and give us new minds to worship Him rightly. This week, when you see God move, make a conscious choice to give all the glory to Christ alone.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  In what language did the people of Lystra shout their praise to Paul and Barnabas?\n    A: They shouted in Lycaonian, their local, native tongue.\n2.  Why did the crowd's reaction show a fundamental misunderstanding of the miracle?\n    A: They attributed the divine healing to their own pagan gods (Zeus and Hermes), deifying the apostles instead of giving glory to the one true God.\n3.  How does this passage point to the uniqueness of Jesus Christ?\n    A: The crowd's mistaken cry that \"gods have come down\" is a pagan parody of the glorious, unique, and true Incarnation, where God the Son truly became a man, Jesus Christ, to save us.\n4.  What is one specific way you can apply this passage's lesson this week?\n    A: When I see God work through someone, I will consciously thank God for His power and pray for the person He used, refusing to put them on a pedestal.\n",
