      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\")**: The spontaneous reaction of the pagan crowd in Lystra to the miraculous healing performed by Paul.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\")**: They immediately interpreted the supernatural event through their polytheistic worldview, deifying the apostles by shouting in their native tongue that gods had visited them in human form.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\")**: The fallen human heart, when confronted with divine power apart from divine revelation, defaults to idolatry, mapping the miracle onto its own pagan categories rather than seeking the one true God.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\")</strong>: The spontaneous reaction of the pagan crowd in Lystra to the miraculous healing performed by Paul.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\")</strong>: They immediately interpreted the supernatural event through their polytheistic worldview, deifying the apostles by shouting in their native tongue that gods had visited them in human form.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\")</strong>: The fallen human heart, when confronted with divine power apart from divine revelation, defaults to idolatry, mapping the miracle onto its own pagan categories rather than seeking the one true God.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role**: The book of Acts, anchored in its purpose statement at Acts 1:8, chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth. This verse marks a key moment in that expansion, as Paul's first missionary journey confronts raw, un-Hellenized paganism in the heart of Anatolia. The incident demonstrates the profound worldview clash between the gospel and polytheism, showing that even an undeniable miracle is not self-interpreting but is filtered through the audience's existing religious framework.\n\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc**: This event occurs within the narrative of Paul's First Missionary Journey (Acts 13:1–14:28). It is the climactic event in Lystra, situated between the healing of the lame man (14:8-10) and the apostles' horrified rejection of the crowd's attempt to offer sacrifices to them (14:12-18). This verse is the pivot, capturing the moment of catastrophic misunderstanding that triggers the subsequent confrontation.\n\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic**: The genre is Historical Narrative. The governing *hermeneutic* (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to distinguish description from prescription. Luke records what the Lystrans said and did, but this is not a model to be emulated. In fact, the apostles' subsequent actions (tearing their robes, 14:14) show this reaction to be a blasphemous error that must be corrected immediately and vehemently.\n\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational)**: The passage is firmly set in the Church Age (the dispensation of Grace). The New Covenant is being proclaimed to Gentiles who have no background in the Old Testament Scriptures or the covenants of promise (Eph 2:12). This is a \"cold call\" to a purely pagan audience, testing the gospel's power to penetrate a worldview utterly alien to its biblical presuppositions.\n\n*   **Author & Attribution**: The author is Luke the physician, a companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), writing a historical account to Theophilus (Luke 1:1-4; Acts 1:1). The work is dated conservatively to the early AD 60s, likely composed in Rome during Paul's first imprisonment.\n\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors**: The verse is triggered by the preceding miracle: Paul, seeing the faith of a man \"lame from his mother's womb,\" commands him to stand, and he is healed instantly (Acts 14:8-10). It immediately causes the subsequent action: the priest of Zeus brings oxen and garlands to offer sacrifice to Barnabas (identified as Zeus) and Paul (identified as Hermes) (Acts 14:12-13).\n\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels**:\n    *   **Apostolic Deflection of Worship**: In Acts 3:12, after healing another lame man, Peter immediately corrects the crowd: \"Men of Israel, why do you wonder at this, or why do you stare at us, as though by our own power or piety we have made him walk?\" [Pericope: Acts 3:11-26 · source: NA28].\n    *   **Confronting Pagan Idolatry**: Paul's sermon at the Areopagus in Athens directly confronts their worship of \"an unknown god\" (Acts 17:22-31) [Pericope: Acts 17:16-34 · source: NA28].\n    *   **Creature Worship Condemned**: The theological root of the Lystrans' error is diagnosed in Romans 1:25, where fallen humanity \"exchanged the truth about God for a lie and worshiped and served the creature rather than the Creator\" [Pericope: Rom 1:18-32 · source: NA28].\n    *   **The True Incarnation (Contrast)**: The crowd's cry is a pagan parody of the central truth of the gospel: God truly did come down in the likeness of men in the person of Jesus Christ (John 1:14; Phil 2:6-7) [Pericope: John 1:1-18 · source: NA28].\n",
