      "h1_title_html": "<p>Acts 14:13 — The Clash of Worship at Lystra's Gates</p>",
      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:8-20 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\nὅ τε ἱερεὺς τοῦ Διὸς τοῦ ὄντος πρὸ τῆς πόλεως ταύρους καὶ στέμματα ἐπὶ τοὺς πυλῶνας ἐνέγκας σὺν τοῖς ὄχλοις ἤθελεν θύειν.\n\n***\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 15 rows = 105 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | ὅ | ho | G3588 | ὁ | Art-NMS | the |\n| 2 | τε | te | G5037 | τέ | Part | and (connecting particle) |\n| 3 | ἱερεὺς | hiereus | G2409 | ἱερεύς | N-NMS | priest |\n| 4 | τοῦ | tou | G3588 | ὁ | Art-GMS | of the |\n| 5 | Διὸς | Dios | G2203 | Ζεύς | N-GMS | Zeus |\n| 6 | τοῦ | tou | G3588 | ὁ | Art-GMS | the one |\n| 7 | ὄντος | ontos | G1510 | εἰμί | V-PAP-GMS | being |\n| 8 | πρὸ | pro | G4253 | πρό | Prep | before / in front of |\n| 9 | τῆς | tēs | G3588 | ὁ | Art-GSF | the |\n| 10 | πόλεως | poleōs | G4172 | πόλις | N-GSF | city |\n| 11 | ταύρους | taurous | G5022 | ταῦρος | N-AMP | bulls / oxen |\n| 12 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 13 | στέμματα | stemmata | G4725 | στέμμα | N-ANP | garlands / wreaths |\n| 14 | ἐνέγκας | enenkas | G5342 | φέρω | V-AAP-NMS | having brought |\n| 15 | ἤθελεν θύειν | ēthelen thyein | G2309/G2380 | θέλω/θύω | V-IAI-3S / V-PAN | he was wanting to sacrifice |\n\n***\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\nAnd the priest of the Zeus, the one being before the city, having brought bulls and garlands to the gates, with the crowds was wanting to sacrifice.\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\nThe priest of Zeus, whose temple was just outside the city, brought bulls and garlands to the city gates and, along with the crowds, wanted to offer a sacrifice.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\nAnd the priest of Zeus—[whose temple and statue were prominently situated] at the entrance to the city—brought sacrificial bulls and festive garlands to the main gates, and together with the masses, he intended [and began the preparations] to offer a sacrifice [to Paul and Barnabas, whom they believed to be gods].\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:8-20 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Script (NA28)</strong>\nὅ τε ἱερεὺς τοῦ Διὸς τοῦ ὄντος πρὸ τῆς πόλεως ταύρους καὶ στέμματα ἐπὶ τοὺς πυλῶνας ἐνέγκας σὺν τοῖς ὄχλοις ἤθελεν θύειν.</p>\n<hr>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 15 rows = 105 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>ὅ</td>\n<td>ho</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>Art-NMS</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>τε</td>\n<td>te</td>\n<td>G5037</td>\n<td>τέ</td>\n<td>Part</td>\n<td>and (connecting particle)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>ἱερεὺς</td>\n<td>hiereus</td>\n<td>G2409</td>\n<td>ἱερεύς</td>\n<td>N-NMS</td>\n<td>priest</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>τοῦ</td>\n<td>tou</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>Art-GMS</td>\n<td>of the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>Διὸς</td>\n<td>Dios</td>\n<td>G2203</td>\n<td>Ζεύς</td>\n<td>N-GMS</td>\n<td>Zeus</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>τοῦ</td>\n<td>tou</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>Art-GMS</td>\n<td>the one</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>ὄντος</td>\n<td>ontos</td>\n<td>G1510</td>\n<td>εἰμί</td>\n<td>V-PAP-GMS</td>\n<td>being</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>πρὸ</td>\n<td>pro</td>\n<td>G4253</td>\n<td>πρό</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>before / in front of</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>τῆς</td>\n<td>tēs</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>Art-GSF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>πόλεως</td>\n<td>poleōs</td>\n<td>G4172</td>\n<td>πόλις</td>\n<td>N-GSF</td>\n<td>city</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>ταύρους</td>\n<td>taurous</td>\n<td>G5022</td>\n<td>ταῦρος</td>\n<td>N-AMP</td>\n<td>bulls / oxen</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>στέμματα</td>\n<td>stemmata</td>\n<td>G4725</td>\n<td>στέμμα</td>\n<td>N-ANP</td>\n<td>garlands / wreaths</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>14</td>\n<td>ἐνέγκας</td>\n<td>enenkas</td>\n<td>G5342</td>\n<td>φέρω</td>\n<td>V-AAP-NMS</td>\n<td>having brought</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15</td>\n<td>ἤθελεν θύειν</td>\n<td>ēthelen thyein</td>\n<td>G2309/G2380</td>\n<td>θέλω/θύω</td>\n<td>V-IAI-3S / V-PAN</td>\n<td>he was wanting to sacrifice</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)</strong>\nAnd the priest of the Zeus, the one being before the city, having brought bulls and garlands to the gates, with the crowds was wanting to sacrifice.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)</strong>\nThe priest of Zeus, whose temple was just outside the city, brought bulls and garlands to the city gates and, along with the crowds, wanted to offer a sacrifice.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)</strong>\nAnd the priest of Zeus—[whose temple and statue were prominently situated] at the entrance to the city—brought sacrificial bulls and festive garlands to the main gates, and together with the masses, he intended [and began the preparations] to offer a sacrifice [to Paul and Barnabas, whom they believed to be gods].</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** The human heart is a natural idol factory, and unless the power of God is explained by the Word of God, people will always worship the gift or the messenger instead of the Giver.\n*   **Fallen Condition Focus (FCF):** The passage diagnoses the universal human tendency to domesticate God by creating him in our own image or elevating human leaders, talents, or experiences to a place of worship.\n    *   *Individual:* The temptation to hero-worship pastors, leaders, or anyone who seems to be a channel of God's power.\n    *   *Corporate:* The danger of a church becoming centered on a charismatic personality, a particular style of worship, or miraculous signs, rather than on the Creator God Himself.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** The gospel smashes this idolatrous impulse. While we were trying to make men into gods, the true God became man in Jesus Christ. He did not come to receive sacrifices of bulls, but to become the one final sacrifice for sin Himself (Heb 10:11-12). Our worship is no longer a fearful attempt to appease fickle deities, but a joyful response to the one living God who has revealed Himself and redeemed us in His Son.\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* Actively deflect praise directed at you for any gift or service, and consciously redirect it to God (1 Pet 4:11). When you see God work, make sure your first words are about Him, not the person He worked through.\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Cultivate a heart of humility that is horrified, like Paul and Barnabas, at any hint of self-deification. See yourself rightly as a servant and messenger, nothing more.\n    *   *Relational:* In your church, gently correct conversations that drift into exalting a pastor or worship leader. Encourage one another to fix your eyes on Jesus, the author and perfecter of our faith (Heb 12:2).\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* In a world that deifies celebrities, athletes, and politicians, be a voice that points beyond human achievement to the God who gives \"rain from heaven and fruitful seasons\" (Acts 14:17).\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** The passage reveals God as the jealous, living Creator, utterly distinct from and superior to all idols.\n    *   *Attribute(s) of God surfaced:* The Living God; The Creator of all things.\n    *   *One-sentence doxology:* To You alone, the living God who made heaven and earth and the sea and all that is in them, be all glory and sacrifice, not to us, your servants.\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> The human heart is a natural idol factory, and unless the power of God is explained by the Word of God, people will always worship the gift or the messenger instead of the Giver.</li>\n<li><strong>Fallen Condition Focus (FCF):</strong> The passage diagnoses the universal human tendency to domesticate God by creating him in our own image or elevating human leaders, talents, or experiences to a place of worship.<ul>\n<li><em>Individual:</em> The temptation to hero-worship pastors, leaders, or anyone who seems to be a channel of God's power.</li>\n<li><em>Corporate:</em> The danger of a church becoming centered on a charismatic personality, a particular style of worship, or miraculous signs, rather than on the Creator God Himself.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> The gospel smashes this idolatrous impulse. While we were trying to make men into gods, the true God became man in Jesus Christ. He did not come to receive sacrifices of bulls, but to become the one final sacrifice for sin Himself (Heb 10:11-12). Our worship is no longer a fearful attempt to appease fickle deities, but a joyful response to the one living God who has revealed Himself and redeemed us in His Son.</li>\n<li><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\":</em> Actively deflect praise directed at you for any gift or service, and consciously redirect it to God (1 Pet 4:11). When you see God work, make sure your first words are about Him, not the person He worked through.</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\":</em> Cultivate a heart of humility that is horrified, like Paul and Barnabas, at any hint of self-deification. See yourself rightly as a servant and messenger, nothing more.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> In your church, gently correct conversations that drift into exalting a pastor or worship leader. Encourage one another to fix your eyes on Jesus, the author and perfecter of our faith (Heb 12:2).</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> In a world that deifies celebrities, athletes, and politicians, be a voice that points beyond human achievement to the God who gives \"rain from heaven and fruitful seasons\" (Acts 14:17).</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong> The passage reveals God as the jealous, living Creator, utterly distinct from and superior to all idols.<ul>\n<li><em>Attribute(s) of God surfaced:</em> The Living God; The Creator of all things.</li>\n<li><em>One-sentence doxology:</em> To You alone, the living God who made heaven and earth and the sea and all that is in them, be all glory and sacrifice, not to us, your servants.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:13 — \"...brought bulls and garlands to the gates and wanted to offer sacrifice.\"\nKEY TERM:     θύειν (*thyein*, \"to sacrifice\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: Pagan impulse misdirects worship from the Creator to the creature.\nIMAGE:        A priest leading garlanded bulls to the city gates.\nAPPLICATION:  When praised, I will deflect the glory and point people to God.\nDOXOLOGY:     To You alone, the Living God, be all honor and sacrifice.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:13 — &quot;...brought bulls and garlands to the gates and wanted to offer sacrifice.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>θύειν (*thyein*, &quot;to sacrifice&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>Pagan impulse misdirects worship from the Creator to the creature.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>A priest leading garlanded bulls to the city gates.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>When praised, I will deflect the glory and point people to God.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>To You alone, the Living God, be all honor and sacrifice.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever been tempted to put a pastor, a speaker, or even a friend on a pedestal? In the ancient city of Lystra, Paul and Barnabas encountered this impulse in its rawest form. After God used them to heal a man who had been lame from birth, the pagan crowds went wild. Convinced that the gods Zeus and Hermes were visiting them, they prepared a full-blown worship service. Acts 14:13 paints the scene: \"the priest of Zeus... brought bulls and garlands to the city gates and... wanted to offer a sacrifice.\"\n\nThis verse shows us the default setting of the human heart: to worship anything and everything except the one true God. When we see power or goodness, our instinct is to idolize the messenger, not the one who sent them. But the gospel turns this upside down. Paul and Barnabas were horrified and rushed to stop them, pointing away from themselves to the \"living God, who made the heaven and the earth\" (Acts 14:15). While we were busy trying to make men into gods, God became a man in Jesus Christ, not to receive our sacrifices, but to become the one true sacrifice for us. This week, when you're tempted to praise a person, use it as a prompt to give all the glory to God, the source of every good gift.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever been tempted to put a pastor, a speaker, or even a friend on a pedestal? In the ancient city of Lystra, Paul and Barnabas encountered this impulse in its rawest form. After God used them to heal a man who had been lame from birth, the pagan crowds went wild. Convinced that the gods Zeus and Hermes were visiting them, they prepared a full-blown worship service. Acts 14:13 paints the scene: \"the priest of Zeus... brought bulls and garlands to the city gates and... wanted to offer a sacrifice.\"</p>\n<p>This verse shows us the default setting of the human heart: to worship anything and everything except the one true God. When we see power or goodness, our instinct is to idolize the messenger, not the one who sent them. But the gospel turns this upside down. Paul and Barnabas were horrified and rushed to stop them, pointing away from themselves to the \"living God, who made the heaven and the earth\" (Acts 14:15). While we were busy trying to make men into gods, God became a man in Jesus Christ, not to receive our sacrifices, but to become the one true sacrifice for us. This week, when you're tempted to praise a person, use it as a prompt to give all the glory to God, the source of every good gift.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  What two specific items did the priest of Zeus bring for the sacrifice?\n    A: Bulls (or oxen) and garlands (or wreaths).\n2.  Why did the priest and the crowd want to offer this sacrifice to Paul and Barnabas?\n    A: Because after the healing of the lame man, they mistakenly believed Paul and Barnabas were the gods Hermes and Zeus in human form.\n3.  What does this incident teach us about the human heart and the nature of true worship?\n    A: The human heart defaults to idolatry, worshipping created things rather than the Creator. True worship must be directed only to the one living God, who is revealed not in myths, but in Jesus Christ and the gospel.\n4.  What is one practical way you can apply the apostles' example this week?\n    A: When someone praises me for a skill or action, I can make a point of deflecting the praise and giving the credit to God.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What two specific items did the priest of Zeus bring for the sacrifice?\n    A: Bulls (or oxen) and garlands (or wreaths).</li>\n<li>Why did the priest and the crowd want to offer this sacrifice to Paul and Barnabas?\n    A: Because after the healing of the lame man, they mistakenly believed Paul and Barnabas were the gods Hermes and Zeus in human form.</li>\n<li>What does this incident teach us about the human heart and the nature of true worship?\n    A: The human heart defaults to idolatry, worshipping created things rather than the Creator. True worship must be directed only to the one living God, who is revealed not in myths, but in Jesus Christ and the gospel.</li>\n<li>What is one practical way you can apply the apostles' example this week?\n    A: When someone praises me for a skill or action, I can make a point of deflecting the praise and giving the credit to God.</li>\n</ol>",
      "song": "## Song\n\nInherits — Book argument: The gospel's unstoppable advance to the ends of the earth.\nInherits — Discourse-arc placement: The climax of the gospel's first collision with raw paganism.\nInherits — Genre acted on: Narrative, showing a dramatic confrontation of worldviews.\nInherits — Salvation-historical pin: Church Age, the blessing of Abraham reaching the nations.\nInherits — Christo-telic motif expressed: The rejection of all idols in favor of the one true God, who became man in Christ.\n\n***\n\n**The Sovereign Architect Audit — VISIBLE PRE-OUTPUT SCORECARD**\nGate 1: PASS — Nuance of pagan worship vs. apostolic response is justified by Acts 14:8-20.\nGate 2: PASS — Every key element of the scene is mapped to the verses.\nGate 3: PASS — Tone is confident in the living God, pointing to His ultimate reign.\nGate 4: PASS — Imagery of bulls, garlands, gates, and torn robes is from the text.\nGate 5: PASS — Christian reading of apostolic faithfulness is the core.\nGate 6: PASS — The entire pericope (vv. 8-20) informs the lyrics.\nGate 7: PASS — V1 (past myth), V2 (present choice), Bridge (first-person confession).\nGate 8: PASS — The Bridge is the volta, the turn from observation to participation.\nGate 9: PASS — Stresses fall on key words: \"Gates,\" \"Bulls,\" \"Man,\" \"God.\"\nGate 10: PASS — Plosives (\"priest,\" \"gates\") contrast with liquids (\"living,\" \"rain\").\nGate 11: PASS — Vowel sounds open up from the closed-off pagan rite to the open declaration.\nGate 12: PASS — All lines are 6-8 syllables, well within the 5-9 Miller's Law range.\nGate 13: PASS — Formatting is correct with two blank lines between sections.\nGate 14: PASS — The song has a timeless theme of true vs. false worship.\nGate 15: PASS — Chorus is a clear, repeatable headline: \"We are not gods.\"\nGate 16: PASS — Verses maintain a consistent trochaic/iambic feel.\nGate 17: PASS — Deep theological contrast (creature/Creator) is held in simple lines.\nGate 18: PASS — Verses tell the story (Bait); Chorus delivers the core truth (Barb).\nGate 19: PASS — Bridge contains vocative \"O Living God\" and first-person \"I turn.\"\nGate 20: PASS — Bridge grounds the turning in God's creative act (\"You made the sky\").\nGate 21: PASS — Rhyme is AABB, sonorous, and exact. (Gates/waits, down/crown; Men/again, see/Deity; sky/why, rain/grain; stand/hand, see/me).\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is in a single fenced code block with the `text` tag.\nGate 23: PASS — Syllable counts verified per line (all 6-8).\nGate 24: PASS — Title \"Not Gods But Men\" is a 4-word paradox from the Chorus hook, memorable and direct.\n\n```text\nTitle: Not Gods But Men\nStyle: Folk rock, raw analog capture, large room acoustics, upright bass, mandolin, stomping kick drum, passionate baritone vocals, tape saturation\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nThe priest of Zeus comes to the gates (A)\nA garlanded bull awaits (A)\nThe city brings its worship down (B)\nTo offer us a crown (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nBut we are not gods come as men (A)\nTo walk the dusty roads again (A)\nWe tear our robes for all to see (B)\nWe are not your deity (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nYou saw a man walk on his feet (A)\nAnd brought a sacrifice to meet (A)\nA power that you did not know (B)\nSo you put on a show (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nBut we are not gods come as men (A)\nTo walk the dusty roads again (A)\nWe tear our robes for all to see (B)\nWe are not your deity (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nO Living God, who made the sky (A)\nWe turn from myths and ask you why (A)\nYou send the sun and fruitful rain (B)\nTo give the world its life and grain (B)\n\n[Outro]\nWe are just men who take a stand (A)\nAnd point to your creative hand (A)\nSo turn from bulls and look and see (B)\nThe God who died upon a tree (B)\n\n[End]\n```\n",
