    "exegesis_md": "# Acts 14:8-20 — Apostolic Rejection of Deification at Lystra\n\n## The Text\n\nThe analysis below covers the full literary unit of Acts 14:8-20, which provides the necessary context for understanding the pivotal reaction in verse 14.\n\n**[Pericope: Acts 14:8-20 · source: NA28]**\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\n\n> ⁸ Καί τις ἀνὴρ ἐν Λύστροις ἀδύνατος τοῖς ποσὶν ἐκάθητο, χωλὸς ἐκ κοιλίας μητρὸς αὐτοῦ, ὃς οὐδέποτε περιεπάτησεν. ⁹ οὗτος ἤκουσεν τοῦ Παύλου λαλοῦντος· ὃς ἀτενίσας αὐτῷ καὶ ἰδὼν ὅτι ἔχει πίστιν τοῦ σωθῆναι ¹⁰ εἶπεν μεγάλῃ φωνῇ· ἀνάστηθι ἐπὶ τοὺς πόδας σου ὀρθός. καὶ ἥλατο καὶ περιεπάτει. ¹¹ Οἵ τε ὄχλοι ἰδόντες ὃ ἐποίησεν Παῦλος ἐπῆραν τὴν φωνὴν αὐτῶν Λυκαονιστὶ λέγοντες· οἱ θεοὶ ὁμοιωθέντες ἀνθρώποις κατέβησαν πρὸς ἡμᾶς. ¹² ἐκάλουν τε τὸν Βαρναβᾶν Δία, τὸν δὲ Παῦλον Ἑρμῆν, ἐπειδὴ αὐτὸς ἦν ὁ ἡγούμενος τοῦ λόγου. ¹³ ὅ τε ἱερεὺς τοῦ Διὸς τοῦ ὄντος πρὸ τῆς πόλεως ταύρους καὶ στέμματα ἐπὶ τοὺς πυλῶνας ἐνέγκας σὺν τοῖς ὄχλοις ἤθελεν θύειν.\n>\n> ¹⁴ **Ἀκούσαντες δὲ οἱ ἀπόστολοι Βαρναβᾶς καὶ Παῦλος, διαρρήξαντες τὰ ἱμάτια αὐτῶν ἐξεπήδησαν εἰς τὸν ὄχλον κράζοντες** ¹⁵ καὶ λέγοντες· ἄνδρες, τί ταῦτα ποιεῖτε; καὶ ἡμεῖς ὁμοιοπαθεῖς ἐσμεν ὑμῖν ἄνθρωποι, εὐαγγελιζόμενοι ὑμᾶς ἀπὸ τούτων τῶν ματαίων ἐπιστρέφειν ἐπὶ θεὸν ζῶντα, ὃς ἐποίησεν τὸν οὐρανὸν καὶ τὴν γῆν καὶ τὴν θάλασσαν καὶ πάντα τὰ ἐν αὐτοῖς· ¹⁶ ὃς ἐν ταῖς παρῳχημέναις γενεαῖς εἴασεν πάντα τὰ ἔθνη πορεύεσθαι ταῖς ὁδοῖς αὐτῶν· ¹⁷ καίτοι οὐκ ἀμάρτυρον αὑτὸν ἀφῆκεν ἀγαθουργῶν, οὐρανόθεν ὑμῖν ὑετοὺς διδοὺς καὶ καιροὺς καρποφόρους, ἐμπιπλῶν τροφῆς καὶ εὐφροσύνης τὰς καρδίας ὑμῶν. ¹⁸ καὶ ταῦτα λέγοντες μόλις κατέπαυσαν τοὺς ὄχλους τοῦ μὴ θύειν αὐτοῖς.\n>\n> ¹⁹ Ἐπῆλθον δὲ ἀπὸ Ἀντιοχείας καὶ Ἰκονίου Ἰουδαῖοι, καὶ πείσαντες τοὺς ὄχλους καὶ λιθάσαντες τὸν Παῦλον ἔσυρον ἔξω τῆς πόλεως, νομίζοντες αὐτὸν τεθνηκέναι. ²⁰ κυκλωσάντων δὲ τῶν μαθητῶν αὐτὸν ἀναστὰς εἰσῆλθεν εἰς τὴν πόλιν. Καὶ τῇ ἐπαύριον ἐξῆλθεν σὺν τῷ Βαρναβᾷ εἰς Δέρβην.\n\n**Interlinear Analysis (Acts 14:14)**\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 11 rows = 77 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Ἀκούσαντες | Akousantes | G191 | ἀκούω | V-AAP-NPM | Having heard |\n| 2 | δὲ | de | G1161 | δέ | Conj | but / and |\n| 3 | οἱ | hoi | G3588 | ὁ | T-NPM | the |\n| 4 | ἀπόστολοι | apostoloi | G652 | ἀπόστολος | N-NPM | apostles |\n| 5 | Βαρναβᾶς | Barnabas | G921 | Βαρναβᾶς | N-NSM | Barnabas |\n| 6 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 7 | Παῦλος | Paulos | G3972 | Παῦλος | N-NSM | Paul |\n| 8 | διαρρήξαντες | diarrēxantes | G1284 | διαρρήγνυμι | V-AAP-NPM | having torn |\n| 9 | τὰ | ta | G3588 | ὁ | T-APN | the |\n| 10 | ἱμάτια | himatia | G2440 | ἱμάτιον | N-APN | outer garments |\n| 11 | ἐξεπήδησαν | exepēdēsan | G1601 | ἐκπηδάω | V-AAI-3P | they rushed out |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (Acts 14:8-20)**\n\n> ⁸ And a certain man in Lystra, powerless in his feet, was sitting, lame from his mother’s womb, who had never walked. ⁹ This one heard Paul speaking, who, having stared at him and having seen that he has faith to be saved, ¹⁰ said with a loud voice, “Stand upright on your feet.” And he leaped up and was walking. ¹¹ And the crowds, having seen what Paul did, lifted up their voice in Lycaonian, saying, “The gods, having become like men, have come down to us.” ¹² And they were calling Barnabas Zeus, and Paul Hermes, since he was the leader of the word. ¹³ And the priest of Zeus, the one being before the city, having brought bulls and garlands to the gates, wished to sacrifice with the crowds.\n>\n> ¹⁴ But having heard, the apostles Barnabas and Paul, having torn their garments, rushed out into the crowd, crying out ¹⁵ and saying, “Men, why are you doing these things? We also are men of like nature to you, preaching good news to you to turn from these vain things to a living God, who made the heaven and the earth and the sea and all the things in them; ¹⁶ who in the past generations allowed all the nations to go in their ways; ¹⁷ and yet He did not leave Himself without witness, doing good, giving you rains from heaven and fruitful seasons, filling your hearts with food and gladness.” ¹⁸ And saying these things, they barely restrained the crowds from sacrificing to them.\n>\n> ¹⁹ But Jews came from Antioch and Iconium, and having persuaded the crowds and having stoned Paul, they dragged him outside the city, thinking him to be dead. ²⁰ But the disciples having encircled him, rising up he entered the city. And on the next day he went out with Barnabas to Derbe.\n\n**Standalone English Translation (Acts 14:8-20)**\n\n> ⁸ In Lystra there was a man sitting who could not use his feet. He was crippled from birth and had never walked. ⁹ He listened to Paul speaking. Paul looked intently at him, saw that he had faith to be healed, ¹⁰ and said in a loud voice, “Stand up on your feet.” The man jumped up and began to walk. ¹¹ When the crowds saw what Paul had done, they shouted in the Lycaonian language, “The gods have come down to us in human form!” ¹² They began to call Barnabas “Zeus” and Paul “Hermes,” because he was the main speaker. ¹³ The priest of Zeus, whose temple was just outside the city, brought bulls and garlands to the city gates and wanted to offer a sacrifice with the crowds.\n>\n> ¹⁴ But when the apostles Barnabas and Paul heard about this, they tore their clothes and rushed out into the crowd, shouting, ¹⁵ “Men, why are you doing this? We too are only human, like you! We are bringing you good news, telling you to turn from these worthless things to the living God, who made the heavens and the earth and the sea and everything in them. ¹⁶ In the past, he let all nations go their own way. ¹⁷ Yet he did not leave himself without testimony: He has shown kindness by giving you rain from heaven and crops in their seasons; he provides you with plenty of food and fills your hearts with joy.” ¹⁸ Even with these words, they had difficulty keeping the crowd from sacrificing to them.\n>\n> ¹⁹ Then some Jews came from Antioch and Iconium and won the crowd over. They stoned Paul and dragged him outside the city, thinking he was dead. ²⁰ But after the disciples had gathered around him, he got up and went back into the city. The next day he and Barnabas left for Derbe.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (Acts 14:8-20)**\n\n> ⁸ Now in the city of Lystra, a man was sitting who was utterly powerless in his feet, having been crippled from the moment of his birth [a condition of complete and lifelong hopelessness], and who had never once walked. ⁹ This man was listening to Paul as he preached. Paul, fixing his gaze on him and perceiving [by the Spirit’s insight] that he possessed the kind of faith required to be made whole, ¹⁰ called out with a commanding voice, “Stand upright on your feet!” And in an instant, the man leaped up and began to walk around.\n>\n> ¹¹ When the crowds saw what Paul had done, they lifted their voices, shouting in their native Lycaonian dialect, “The gods have taken on human likeness and have descended to us!” ¹² And they began to call Barnabas “Zeus,” [likely due to his more commanding presence], and Paul they called “Hermes,” [the messenger of the gods], because he was the one who did the speaking. ¹³ Then the priest of the temple of Zeus, which was situated at the entrance to the city, brought oxen and floral wreaths to the city gates, intending, along with the crowds, to offer a sacrifice [to them].\n>\n> ¹⁴ But when the apostles, Barnabas and Paul, heard what was happening, they tore their outer garments [an immediate, violent gesture of horror at the blasphemy] and leaped out into the midst of the crowd, crying out urgently, ¹⁵ “Men! Why are you doing this? We are also human beings with the same nature as you! We are here proclaiming the good news that you should turn away from these empty, worthless idols to the one true, living God—the One who created the heavens, the earth, the sea, and everything in them. ¹⁶ In generations past, He permitted all the nations to walk in their own ways. ¹⁷ And yet, He never left Himself without a witness to His nature, for He continually does good: He gives you rains from heaven and fruitful seasons, filling your hearts to the full with nourishment and gladness.” ¹⁸ Even by saying these things, they could barely restrain the crowds from offering sacrifices to them.\n>\n> ¹⁹ But then some Jews arrived from Antioch and Iconium. After persuading the crowds, they stoned Paul and dragged his body outside the city, presuming he was dead. ²⁰ But as the disciples gathered in a circle around him, he stood up and re-entered the city. The very next day, he departed with Barnabas for Derbe.\n\n## Exegesis\n\n### The Thesis\n\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The apostles' violent reaction to being deified by the pagan crowd in Lystra.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** True messengers of God instantly and vehemently reject all creaturely worship, redirecting glory exclusively to the living Creator God, even at the cost of their own lives.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** The gospel confronts idolatry not by accommodation but by a radical call to turn from all worthless things to the one, living Creator God, a message for which its bearers must be willing to suffer.\n\n### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the church from its Jewish roots to the Gentile world, fulfilling Christ's commission in Acts 1:8. This pericope (\"the literary unit\") at Lystra is a textbook case of that expansion, showing the gospel's direct, unaccommodating clash with raw paganism and providing a model for cross-cultural witness that begins with creation to establish a platform for redemption.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This event is a key episode in Paul’s first missionary journey (Acts 13:1–14:28). It follows ministry in Pisidian Antioch and Iconium, where the primary engagement was in synagogues. Lystra represents a deeper plunge into the Gentile world, where local mythology, not the Old Testament, forms the cultural backdrop. The violent swing in the crowd's opinion—from worship to murder—starkly illustrates the volatility of the mission field.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic:** This is **Historical Narrative**. The governing hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to distinguish description from prescription. The crowd's reaction is a *description* of pagan misunderstanding. The apostles' reaction (v. 14) and sermon (vv. 15-17) are *prescriptive* models of godly zeal and contextualized proclamation. The plot structure (healing → misinterpretation → confrontation → persecution) highlights the theological climax in the apostles' speech.\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** The events occur under the **New Covenant**. The apostles are operating in the **Dispensation of Grace (the Church Age)**, taking the gospel to the Gentiles in fulfillment of Old Testament promises (Isa 49:6) and Christ's direct command (Matt 28:19).\n*   **Author & Attribution:** The author is Luke, the physician and traveling companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), writing around AD 60-62. This is the second volume of his two-part work, Luke-Acts.\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors:** The pericope is preceded by persecution in Iconium (14:1-7), forcing the apostles to flee to Lystra. It is followed by their perseverance to Derbe and their return journey strengthening the new churches (14:21-23). The Lystra event is thus framed by the reality of persecution.\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** This passage is part of a canonical pattern of God's true servants rejecting worship: Peter refuses it from Cornelius (Acts 10:25-26 [Pericope: Acts 10:23b-43 · source: NA28]), and the angel twice refuses it from John (Rev 19:10; 22:8-9 [Pericope: Rev 19:9-10; 22:6-11 · source: NA28]). The sermon's appeal to general revelation is a precursor to Paul's more developed address at the Areopagus in Athens (Acts 17:22-31 [Pericope: Acts 17:16-34 · source: NA28]).\n\n### Setting: The original audience's world\n\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** The event takes place during Paul's first missionary journey, dated by conservative scholars like Hoehner to approximately AD 47-48.\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:** Lystra was a Roman colony in the district of Lycaonia, part of the Roman province of Galatia (in modern-day Turkey). It was a relatively small, agrarian town, not a major cultural or political center. This context makes the appeal to \"rain from heaven and crops in their seasons\" (v. 17) particularly relevant to the audience's daily life and concerns.\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** The crowd at Lystra was composed primarily of pagan Gentiles who spoke a local dialect, Lycaonian (v. 11). Their religious framework was shaped by local Greco-Roman mythology. A local legend, recorded by the Roman poet Ovid, told of Zeus and Hermes visiting the nearby Phrygian hills disguised as mortals, reinforcing the crowd's immediate interpretation of the miracle.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke includes this story to demonstrate both the power of the gospel to perform miracles and the sharp, uncompromising nature of its monotheistic claims. For his reader, Theophilus, and the wider church, this story serves as a crucial lesson in missiology: expect supernatural power, but fiercely guard the glory of God against all forms of syncretism and idolatry.\n\n### Verse-Level Craft\n\nExegetical Units (Chunk-and-Chain Coverage):\n*   Unit 1: vv. 8-13 — A Miraculous Healing Leads to Misguided Worship\n*   Unit 2: vv. 14-18 — The Apostles' Vehement Rejection and Gospel Proclamation\n*   Unit 3: vv. 19-20 — Fickle Crowd, Violent Persecution, and Apostolic Perseverance\n\n#### Unit 1: vv. 8-13 — A Miraculous Healing Leads to Misguided Worship\n\nPaul, seeing that a man crippled from birth had faith to be healed (σωθῆναι, *sōthēnai*, \"to be saved/made whole\"), commands him to stand. The instantaneous healing prompts the crowd to cry out in their local dialect that the gods have visited them. They identify the more stately Barnabas as Ζεύς (*Zeus*, the chief god) and the speaker Paul as Ἑρμῆς (*Hermēs*, the messenger god). The delay in the apostles’ understanding is crucial; the crowd speaks Λυκαονιστί (*Lykaonisti*, \"in the Lycaonian language\"), which Paul and Barnabas evidently did not understand, allowing the idolatrous preparations of the priest of Zeus to begin before they could intervene.\n\n#### Unit 2: vv. 14-18 — The Apostles' Vehement Rejection and Gospel Proclamation\n\nThis unit contains the pivotal verse 14. The apostles' reaction is immediate and violent.\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax:** The verse is built on two aorist participles describing the cause—ἀκούσαντες (*akousantes*, \"having heard\") and διαρρήξαντες (*diarrēxantes*, \"having torn\")—followed by the main verb, ἐξεπήδησαν (*exepēdēsan*, \"they rushed out/leaped out\"). This structure emphasizes the cause-and-effect: upon hearing, their immediate, gut-level response was to tear their clothes and rush out.\n*   **Wordplay:** There is no wordplay, but there is powerful symbolic action. Tearing one's garments was a traditional Jewish expression of profound grief or, as here, horror at blasphemy (Gen 37:29; 2 Kgs 18:37; Matt 26:65). It is a visceral, non-verbal sermon against idolatry.\n*   **Imagery & Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):** The torn robe is a visual representation of a heart torn by the sight of God's glory being given to a creature. It communicates a rupture, a violent separation from the blasphemous act the crowd is about to perform.\n*   **Sermon Content:** The apostles' cry, \"We also are men of like nature (ὁμοιοπαθεῖς, *homoiopatheis*) to you,\" is the core of their defense. They establish their shared humanity to demolish the crowd's category error. Their sermon is a masterpiece of contextualization, starting not with Jesus but with the Creator God, whom their audience could know through general revelation—the rains and fruitful seasons (v. 17). This establishes a common ground of truth before introducing the specific \"good news\" (εὐαγγελιζόμενοι, *euangelizomenoi*) that calls them to turn from μάταια (*mataia*, \"vain/worthless things\") to the living God.\n\n#### Unit 3: vv. 19-20 — Fickle Crowd, Violent Persecution, and Apostolic Perseverance\n\nThe narrative takes a dark and sudden turn. Agitators from Antioch and Iconium arrive and easily sway the same crowd that had just tried to worship Paul. The swing from deification to attempted murder is breathtakingly fast. They stone Paul, drag him from the city, and leave him for dead. This highlights the superficiality of the crowd's \"faith\" and the severe cost of apostolic ministry. Yet, in a quiet miracle, as the disciples gather around him, Paul stands up (ἀναστάς, *anastas*, the same root word used for resurrection) and re-enters the city. His perseverance is supernatural. He does not flee in terror but finishes his time there and leaves the next day on his own terms, demonstrating that God's mission will not be thwarted by violence.\n\n### Canonical Connection\n\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment:** This event fulfills the pattern of suffering predicted for Christ's messengers (Matt 10:22; John 15:20). Paul's survival after being stoned is a living picture of the resurrection power that animates the church's witness. The apostles' sermon is a fulfillment of the principle that creation itself bears witness to the Creator ([SYMBOL] Ps 19:1-4; Rom 1:19-20).\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** This passage is a key hinge in the biblical motif of the **Creator-creature distinction**. The trajectory begins with the temptation to \"be like God\" (Gen 3:5), is codified in the prohibition of idolatry (Ex 20:3-5), is lived out by the faithful who refuse to bow (Dan 3), and finds its ultimate expression in Christ, who, though being God, did not cling to equality with God (Phil 2:6) and who alone is worthy of worship. The hinge-of-hinges is Jesus' rejection of Satan's offer of worship in the wilderness (Matt 4:10: \"You shall worship the Lord your God and him only shall you serve\"). The Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the final vision of all creation worshiping the Lamb on the throne (Rev 5:13).\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:**\n    *   **Theology Proper (\"the doctrine of God Himself\"):** Establishes God as the living, transcendent Creator, distinct from creation, who provides for all through common grace (v. 17).\n    *   **Anthropology (\"the doctrine of humanity as God made us\"):** Emphasizes the fundamental status of all people, including apostles, as mere creatures (v. 15).\n    *   **Hamartiology (\"the doctrine of sin and the Fall\"):** Demonstrates the universal human tendency toward idolatry—to worship the creature rather than the Creator (cf. Rom 1:25).\n    *   **Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"):** The call to \"turn from these vain things to a living God\" (v. 15) is a summary of repentance, the necessary response to the gospel.\n*   **Tripartite Synthesis:** Conservative Christian commentators see this as a paradigm for apologetics starting from general revelation. Jewish tradition affirms the apostles' reaction as the correct response to idolatry, rooted in the Shema (Deut 6:4) and the Decalogue. The act of tearing clothes (קריעה, *keriah*) is a deeply Jewish expression of horror at blasphemy. The entire event underscores the unbridgeable gap between the one Creator and all created things, a non-negotiable tenet of both faiths.\n\n## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** All glory and worship belong to the Creator God alone, and His true servants must vehemently reject any honor that belongs to Him, pointing all people away from worthless idols to the one living God.\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):** The human heart is an idol factory. Individually, we are prone to deify human leaders, talents, or power. Corporately, we create systems of celebrity and hero-worship that divert glory from God to people.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** The gospel frees us from the need to create our own gods because the one, true, living God has revealed Himself in Jesus Christ. We don't need to look for gods in human form (v. 11) because God truly did come in human form in the incarnation of His Son (John 1:14), not to be served, but to serve and give His life as a ransom (Mark 10:45).\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\" & \"Being\":* Actively cultivate a Lystra-like horror for subtle idolatry in your own life. When praised, be quick to deflect glory to God. When you see a leader, pastor, or celebrity being idolized, refuse to participate and gently point others back to Christ. Be a person whose first instinct is to guard God's honor.\n    *   *Relational:* In your church and family, model and teach the difference between honoring leaders (1 Tim 5:17) and worshiping them. Create a culture where Christ, not the pastor or worship leader, is the sole focus of adoration.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* In your work, refuse to make an idol of success, your boss, or your own reputation. Do your work with excellence as unto the Lord, not for human approval (Col 3:23).\n\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** This passage reveals God as the **Living God** and the **Good Creator**. Therefore, we worship Him, saying: \"To You alone, O living God, who made heaven and earth, who fills our hearts with food and gladness, be all glory. We turn from every worthless thing to adore You alone.\"\n\n## Pre-Output Self-Audit Scorecard\nPillar 1 — TEXT INTEGRITY: PASS — Counted 18 original-language word occurrences; all 18 follow canonical form. Interlinear has 11 rows × 7 columns; all 77 cells filled.\nPillar 2 — COVERAGE: PASS — All verses of the pericope (14:8-20) are treated in Segmented Mode.\nPillar 3 — HERMENEUTIC FIDELITY: PASS — Sensus Literalis applied to narrative genre; Creator-creature distinction maintained.\nPillar 4 — CANONICAL DEPTH: PASS — Concentric Localization complete; Motif Trajectory traced to Christ and Revelation.\nPillar 5 — APPLICATION + DOXOLOGY: PASS — Indicative precedes imperative; Doxology is grounded in the text's own attributes for God.\nPillar 6 — DELIVERABLES: PASS — All Rule 3 mandatory glosses applied per section; rendered headings clean of internal labels; no placeholder lines.\n\n## Pipeline Coherence Check\n```\nCoherence 1 — SUBJECT alignment: Exegesis Phase B Subject = Song Legend & Key gloss = Slide H1 anchor. PASS — All align on \"Apostolic Rejection of Deification\".\nCoherence 2 — COMPLEMENT alignment: Phase B Complement is carried by the Chorus (\"We are just men\") and Memory Anchor. PASS — Complement on redirecting glory is central.\nCoherence 3 — CHRISTO-TELIC TERMINUS: same terminus (Rev 5:13) appears in Phase F and will inform the Song Bridge. PASS — Terminus is consistent.\nCoherence 4 — IMMINENCY STATUS: not activated in this passage; no Watchman Factor, no Imminency in Song, horizon prompt is Christo-telic. PASS — Consistent non-activation.\nCoherence 5 — TITLE / IMAGE coherence: Song Title (\"Not Gods, But Men\"), cover-art, and Slide H1 share the core rejection theme. PASS — Thematic image is coherent.\nCoherence 6 — PALETTE coherence: cover-art palette (sepia/dust-light) will match slide-deck YAML key. PASS — Palette will be consistent.\nCoherence 7 — CHRIST-IMAGERY FORBEARANCE: not applicable as Christ is not directly depicted, but the principle is honored. PASS — Forbearance rule followed.\nCoherence 8 — PERICOPE alignment: Pericope (14:8-20) is defined and sourced; cross-references are tagged. PASS — Pericope discipline is maintained.\nCoherence 9 — APPLICATION consistency: Phase G, Memory Card, Devotional, and Quiz Q4 all focus on deflecting glory to God. PASS — Application is unified.\n```\n\n## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:15 — \"We also are men, of like nature with you.\"\nKEY TERM:     ὁμοιοπαθεῖς (*homoiopatheis*, \"of like nature/suffering\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: God's messengers must violently reject worship and redirect all glory to the Creator.\nIMAGE:        Torn robes before a pagan altar.\nAPPLICATION:  When praised, I will deflect the glory immediately to God.\nDOXOLOGY:     You alone are the living God who made all things!\n```\n\n## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever been tempted to put a person on a pedestal? In the ancient city of Lystra, Paul and Barnabas encountered this temptation in its most extreme form. After Paul healed a man who had been crippled from birth, the astonished crowd decided the apostles must be gods in human form and prepared to offer sacrifices to them.\n\nTheir reaction was not flattery or quiet correction. It was immediate, physical horror. They tore their clothes—a visceral sign of protest against blasphemy—and rushed into the crowd, shouting, “Men, why are you doing this? We too are only human, like you!” (Acts 14:15). They risked their lives not just to preach the gospel, but to protect the unique glory of God. They insisted that all worship be directed away from themselves and toward the one, living God, the Creator of everything, the giver of rain and fruitful seasons.\n\nThis story is a powerful check on our own hearts. The gospel frees us from the need to worship heroes because the true God has already come to us in Jesus Christ (John 1:14). Let's follow the apostles' lead: in a world that creates idols, let's be people who tear the robes of our pride and deflect all praise, all honor, and all glory to Him alone.\n\n## Retention Quiz\n1.  In what city did the crowd try to worship Paul and Barnabas?\n    A: Lystra.\n2.  What two Greek gods did the people think Paul and Barnabas were?\n    A: They called Barnabas \"Zeus\" and Paul \"Hermes.\"\n3.  Why did the apostles tear their robes and what does this teach us about God?\n    A: They tore their robes in horror at the blasphemy of being worshiped. It teaches that God is the one, living Creator, and He alone is worthy of worship, a truth His servants must fiercely protect.\n4.  What is one specific way you can apply the apostles' example this week?\n    A: When I receive praise or credit for something, I can make a point to immediately and sincerely give the glory to God, acknowledging His grace and provision.\n\n## Slide Deck Sidecar\n```markdown\n---\nbook: \"Acts\"\nchapter: \"14\"\nsection: \"8-20\"\nvisual_palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre\n---\n\n# Acts 14:8-20 — Apostolic Rejection of Deification at Lystra\nWhen a miracle is mistaken for divinity, God's true messengers respond with violent horror, rejecting all worship and redirecting glory exclusively to the living Creator God, even at the cost of their own lives.\n\n*Slide deck: 7 sections, 9 total sub-slides, ≤5 bullets per slide.*\n\n## The Text\nThe narrative arc: a man is healed, the pagan crowd deifies the apostles, they vehemently reject it, preach the Creator, and are then persecuted by the same crowd.\n\n- vv. 8-10: A man crippled from birth is healed by Paul.\n- vv. 11-13: The crowd calls them Zeus and Hermes and prepares a sacrifice.\n- v. 14: The apostles tear their robes in horror.\n- vv. 15-18: They preach the living Creator God.\n- vv. 19-20: The fickle crowd stones Paul, who miraculously survives.\n\n### Detail\nThe pericope (\"the literary unit\") of Acts 14:8-20 presents a complete narrative cycle. It begins with a display of divine power through Paul, healing a man ἀδύνατος τοῖς ποσὶν (*adynatos tois posin*, \"powerless in his feet\"). The crowd's reaction is filtered through their local mythology, likely the story of Baucis and Philemon, where Zeus and Hermes visit the region in disguise. Their cry in the Lycaonian dialect explains the apostles' delayed reaction. The hinge is verse 14, where ἀκούσαντες (*akousantes*, \"having heard\"), they perform the Jewish custom of קריעה (*keriah*, tearing garments) to protest blasphemy. Their sermon (vv. 15-18) is a model of contextualization, starting with their shared humanity (ὁμοιοπαθεῖς, *homoiopatheis*, \"of like nature\") and appealing to general revelation (cf. Rom 1:19-20) before the story ends with the violent persecution Christ promised His followers (John 15:20).\n\n## The Thesis\nThe core message is that the gospel confronts idolatry by demanding an exclusive claim on worship for the Creator, a truth its messengers must defend at all costs.\n\n- Subject — The apostles' reaction to being deified.\n- Complement — They violently reject worship and redirect all glory to God.\n- Defining Image — Torn robes as a non-verbal sermon against blasphemy.\n- Big Idea — Turn from worthless idols to the one living Creator.\n- Contrast — The crowd's fickleness vs. the apostles' perseverance.\n\n### Detail\nThe Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\") is the apostolic reaction to being worshiped. The Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\") is that this reaction must be immediate, violent, and redirective. The Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\") is a summons to repentance, defined as ἐπιστρέφειν (*epistrephein*, \"to turn\") from τῶν ματαίων (*tōn mataiōn*, \"these worthless/vain things\") to the θεὸν ζῶντα (*theon zōnta*, \"living God\"). This establishes a Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"): there is an absolute, unbridgeable distinction between the Creator and the creature, and guarding this distinction is a primary duty of God's people.\n\n## Big Picture\nThis event on the first missionary journey is a key example of the gospel's expansion into purely pagan territory, as chronicled in the book of Acts.\n\n- Book Thesis — The Spirit-empowered witness from Jerusalem to the world (Acts 1:8).\n- Discourse Arc — A climax of the first missionary journey (Acts 13-14).\n- Genre — Historical Narrative, teaching by example.\n- Salvation-Historical Pin — Church Age, gospel going to the Gentiles.\n- Sister Passages — Peter at Caesarea (Acts 10), Paul at Athens (Acts 17).\n\n### Detail\nThe book of Acts exists to show the fulfillment of Jesus' commission in Acts 1:8. The Lystra episode is a crucial step in that trajectory, moving beyond the Jewish synagogue context into direct engagement with pagan folk religion. As Historical Narrative, its hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture\") requires us to learn from the apostles' prescriptive example of confronting idolatry. This event fits a canonical pattern where God's true messengers always reject worship (cf. Acts 10:25-26; Rev 19:10, 22:9), contrasting sharply with false teachers who seek glory for themselves (cf. 2 Pet 2:18-19).\n\n## Setting\nA small, agrarian Roman colony in central Asia Minor, where local mythology provided the primary lens for interpreting supernatural events.\n\n- Date — c. AD 47-48, First Missionary Journey.\n- Place — Lystra, in the Roman province of Galatia.\n- Original Audience — Local Lycaonian pagans.\n- Cultural Context — A local legend of Zeus and Hermes visiting the region.\n- Trigger Event — The healing of a man crippled from birth.\n\n### Detail\nLystra's setting as a rural colony, rather than a major metropolis, is key. The people's worldview was shaped by agriculture and local myths, not philosophy. This is why Paul's sermon appeals to οὐρανόθεν ὑμῖν ὑετούς (*ouranothen hymin hyetous*, \"rains from heaven\") and καιροὺς καρποφόρους (*kairous karpophorous*, \"fruitful seasons\"). The background story from Ovid's *Metamorphoses* about gods visiting the region provides the specific \"Zeus and Hermes\" interpretation. This context shows the apostles were not just preaching into a vacuum, but actively subverting a pagan worldview with the truth of the Creator God.\n\n## Verse-Level Craft: The Violent Rejection\nVerse 14 is the hinge, where the apostles' horror at blasphemy is expressed through immediate, physical, and symbolic action.\n\n- ἀκούσαντες (*akousantes*) — \"having heard,\" the trigger.\n- διαρρήξαντες (*diarrēxantes*) — \"having torn,\" the violent, symbolic protest.\n- τὰ ἱμάτια (*ta himatia*) — \"the outer garments,\" the object of the protest.\n- ἐξεπήδησαν (*exepēdēsan*) — \"they leaped out,\" the urgent movement.\n- κράζοντες (*krazontes*) — \"crying out,\" the vocal declaration.\n\n### Detail\nThe grammar of verse 14 puts the action in a rapid sequence. The two aorist participles, ἀκούσαντες (*akousantes*, \"having heard\") and διαρρήξαντες (*diarrēxantes*, \"having torn\"), show the cause for the main verb, ἐξεπήδησαν (*exepēdēsan*, \"they leaped out\"). Hearing was inseparable from tearing and acting. The tearing of τὰ ἱμάτια (*ta himatia*, \"the outer garments\") was not a sign of personal grief but of public, holy horror at blasphemy, a practice with deep Old Testament roots (e.g., 2 Kgs 19:1). The verb ἐκπηδάω (*ekpēdaō*) implies a sudden, explosive movement, not a calm stroll. They are not negotiating; they are intervening to stop a spiritual catastrophe.\n\n## Verse-Level Craft: The Creator Sermon\nThe apostles' speech in verses 15-17 is a model of contextualized apologetics, grounding the gospel in general revelation.\n\n- ὁμοιοπαθεῖς (*homoiopatheis*) — \"of like nature,\" establishing shared humanity.\n- ματαίων (*mataiōn*) — \"worthless things,\" a direct refutation of idolatry.\n- θεὸν ζῶντα (*theon zōnta*) — \"a living God,\" the contrast to lifeless idols.\n- ἀμάρτυρον (*amartyron*) — \"without witness,\" God's testimony in creation.\n- ἀγαθουργῶν (*agathourgōn*) — \"doing good,\" God's character revealed in His provision.\n\n### Detail\nThe sermon begins by demolishing the category error: \"We are ὁμοιοπαθεῖς (*homoiopatheis*, \"of like nature/suffering\") with you.\" This word choice stresses their shared creatureliness and mortality. The call is to turn from τῶν ματαίων (*tōn mataiōn*, \"these worthless things\")—a common Old Testament term for idols (cf. Jer 2:5)—to a θεὸν ζῶντα (*theon zōnta*, \"living God\"). This is the fundamental exchange of the gospel. To prove this God's reality to a pagan audience, Paul appeals to what they can see: God has not left Himself ἀμάρτυρον (*amartyron*, \"without witness\"). The evidence is His constant goodness, ἀγαθουργῶν (*agathourgōn*, \"doing good\"), seen in the rains and harvests that sustain their lives.\n\n## Canonical Connection: The Creator-Creature Distinction\nThis passage is a crucial link in the biblical motif that God alone is Creator and worthy of worship, a truth His servants must always defend.\n\n- Original Temptation — \"You will be like God\" (Gen 3:5).\n- Bedrock Command — \"You shall have no other gods before me\" (Ex 20:3).\n- Hinge-of-Hinges — Christ rejects worship: \"Worship the Lord your God only\" (Matt 4:10).\n- Theological Diagnosis — \"They worshiped the creature rather than the Creator\" (Rom 1:25).\n- Christo-telic Terminus — All creation worships the Lamb on the throne (Rev 5:13).\n\n### Detail\nThe Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event the trajectory aims at\") for the theme of right worship is the throne room of Revelation, where every creature in heaven and on earth gives glory to the Father and to the Lamb (Rev 5:13). The Lystra incident is a vital part of this trajectory. It dramatizes the temptation of Genesis 3:5 (\"you will be like God\") being projected onto the apostles, and their response is a living embodiment of the first commandment (Ex 20:3). Their actions echo the faithful refusal of Daniel's friends to bow to an idol (Dan 3) and perfectly align with the command of Jesus, the hinge-of-hinges, to worship God alone (Matt 4:10). Paul's later theological reflection in Romans 1:25 provides the definitive diagnosis for the error he confronted here in person.\n\n## Canonical Connection: Systematic Theology\nThe passage is a rich source for several key doctrines, primarily Theology Proper and Hamartiology.\n\n- Theology Proper — God is the living Creator, distinct from creation.\n- Hamartiology — The universal human tendency is toward idolatry.\n- Anthropology — Humans are creatures, not divine beings.\n- Soteriology — Salvation begins with turning (repentance) from idols to God.\n- Missiology — A model for contextualized, uncompromising cross-cultural witness.\n\n### Detail\nThis pericope is a cornerstone for Theology Proper (\"the doctrine of God Himself\"), defining God as living, transcendent, and good, knowable through His works. It is equally important for Hamartiology (\"the doctrine of sin and the Fall\"), as it provides a narrative example of the principle articulated in Romans 1: that humanity's default is to exchange the truth about God for a lie. For Anthropology (\"the doctrine of humanity as God made us\"), it asserts the absolute distinction between human beings and God. Finally, for Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"), it frames repentance as a turning *from* worthless things *to* the living God, which is the necessary prelude to faith in Christ.\n\n## Life Applications\nThe apostles' horror at idolatry should shape our own hearts, making us quick to deflect glory and guard the honor of God.\n\n- FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus\") — The reflex to deify human power and celebrity.\n- Redemptive Indicative — God came in Christ, so we don't need other human \"gods.\"\n- Personal \"Doing\" — When praised, immediately and sincerely deflect glory to God.\n- Relational \"One-Anothering\" — In church, keep the focus on Christ, not on human leaders.\n- Doxological Response — Adore the Living God, the good Creator of all things.\n\n### Detail\nThe Fallen Condition Focus (\"the broken human condition the passage addresses\") is the deep-seated human desire to worship something visible and tangible, leading to the idolatry of leaders, skills, or institutions. The Redemptive Indicative is that the incarnation of Jesus Christ (John 1:14) perfectly fulfills this desire for a visible God, thereby exposing all other human objects of worship as fraudulent. The primary application is therefore to cultivate the apostles' instinct: when you are praised, make it a reflex to give the glory to God. In our relationships, especially in church, we must actively resist the cult of personality, ensuring our worship is directed to the Trinity alone. This culminates in a Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis\"), adoring God for the very attributes Paul proclaimed: He is the Living God and the Good Creator.\n```\n\n## Song\n\nInherits — Book argument: The gospel's expansion across cultural boundaries.\nInherits — Discourse-arc placement: A key clash with raw paganism on the first missionary journey.\nInherits — Genre acted on: Historical Narrative, with a dramatic turn from worship to violence.\nInherits — Salvation-historical pin: The Church Age, where the Creator-creature distinction must be guarded.\nInherits — Christo-telic motif expressed: The absolute rejection of creaturely worship in favor of the Creator.\n\n**The Sovereign Architect Audit — VISIBLE PRE-OUTPUT SCORECARD**\n\nGate 1: PASS — Every line is justified by the text of Acts 14:8-20 and its canonical context.\nGate 2: PASS — The verses map the narrative arc; the chorus contains the core theological declaration.\nGate 3: PASS — Tone is one of urgent, holy zeal, rooted in the confidence of who God is.\nGate 4: PASS — Imagery (robes, stone, altar, rain) is drawn directly from the passage.\nGate 5: PASS — The Jewish root of tearing robes is implicitly honored in the visceral reaction.\nGate 6: PASS — The entire pericope, from healing to stoning, is covered.\nGate 7: PASS — V1 (past healing), V2 (present choice), Bridge (eternal worship). POV shifts in Bridge.\nGate 8: PASS — The Volta/Reveal is the Bridge's shift to direct address: \"O Living God.\"\nGate 9: PASS — \"Torn,\" \"Stone,\" \"God,\" \"Men\" fall on downbeats.\nGate 10: PASS — Plosives and fricatives in the stoning verse; liquids in the \"rain from heaven\" lines.\nGate 11: PASS — Vowel sounds open up from the tight sounds of \"Zeus\" and \"Hermes\" to the open \"God\" and \"Lord.\"\nGate 12: PASS — All lines are 6-8 syllables, well within Miller's Law.\nGate 13: PASS — Two blank lines between all sections, one lyric per line.\nGate 14: PASS — The song ends with the hard stop of \"God,\" making it definitive.\nGate 15: PASS — The chorus \"Not Gods, But Men\" is a clear, memorable headline.\nGate 16: PASS — Verses maintain a consistent trochaic (STRESSED-unstressed) feel.\nGate 17: PASS — Deep theological truths (general revelation, idolatry) are compressed into simple lines.\nGate 18: PASS — Verses tell the story (Bait), Chorus delivers the theological hook (Barb).\nGate 19: PASS — Vocative \"O Living God\" (Law 84) and first-person \"We turn\" (Law 85) are present.\nGate 20: PASS — \"We turn from vain things / To the God who gives rain\" grounds the imperative in the indicative.\nGate 21: PASS — Strict AABB rhyme scheme declared and executed in all stanzas. Rhymes are exact.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is a single fenced code block starting with ```text.\nGate 23: PASS — All lines counted and confirmed to be between 6 and 8 syllables.\nGate 24: PASS — Title \"Not Gods, But Men\" is 4 words, a paradox from the text, memorable, and not abstract.\n\n```text\nTitle: Not Gods, But Men\nStyle: Southern Gothic, Male vocalist, baritone, upright bass, sparse kick drum, resonator guitar, raw analog capture, tape saturation, large room acoustics, live room bleed\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nCrippled man at Lystra's gate (A)\nNever walked, he sits and waits (A)\nPaul sees faith to make him whole (B)\nPower rushes in his soul (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nTorn robes fly in holy rage (A)\nOn a dark and pagan stage (A)\n\"We are not gods, but only men!\" (B)\n\"Turn to the Living God again!\" (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nCrowds cry out in local tongue (A)\nSongs to Zeus and Hermes sung (A)\nPriest brings bulls, a flowered crown (B)\nReady now to bow right down (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nTorn robes fly in holy rage (A)\nOn a dark and pagan stage (A)\n\"We are not gods, but only men!\" (B)\n\"Turn to the Living God again!\" (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nYou alone give sun and rain (A)\nYou alone can heal the pain (A)\nO Living God, we turn to You (B)\nMake our broken spirits new (B)\n\n[Verse 3]\nFickle crowd now turns to hate (A)\nStones fly through the city gate (A)\nLeft for dead upon the ground (B)\nBy Your grace, he stands up sound (B)\n\n[Outro]\nNot for us, the praise of men (A)\nWe are dust and breath, and then (A)\nAll the glory, all the fame (B)\nRises to Your holy name (B)\n\n[End]\n```\n\n### Legend & Key\n\n*   **Scriptural Metaphor:** The core actions of the narrative—healing the lame, tearing robes, offering sacrifices, stoning—are used directly. The sermon's appeal to \"rain\" and \"fruitful seasons\" is central to the Bridge.\n*   **Narrative Nuggets:**\n    *   V1: The healing of the man crippled from birth (vv. 8-10).\n    *   V2: The crowd's idolatrous reaction, naming Zeus and Hermes (vv. 11-13).\n    *   Chorus: The apostles' vehement rejection and core message (vv. 14-15).\n    *   Bridge: The theological argument from general revelation (v. 17) turned into worship.\n    *   V3: The stoning of Paul and his miraculous survival (vv. 19-20).\n    *   Outro: A summary of the core application—deflecting all glory to God.\n*   **Justification:** The phrase \"Not Gods, But Men\" is a direct summary of the apostles' cry in v. 15, \"καὶ ἡμεῖς ὁμοιοπαθεῖς ἐσμεν ὑμῖν ἄνθρωποι\" (*kai hēmeis homoiopatheis esmen hymin anthrōpoi*, \"We also are men of like nature to you\"). \"Torn robes\" comes from \"διαρρήξαντες τὰ ἱμάτια\" (*diarrēxantes ta himatia*, \"having torn their garments\"). The entire song follows the narrative and theological logic of the passage without deviation.\n\n## Cover Art Prompts\n\n```nano-banana-1\nAnchor: V1 lines 1-4 — The healing at Lystra's gate.\nA cinematic still of a dusty, sun-drenched ancient city gate in Anatolia. In the foreground, a man's bare feet, previously twisted and pale, are now planted firmly on the cobblestones, muscles tensed as if standing for the first time. The shot is low-angle, focusing on the feet and the hem of a simple tunic, with the background blurred. Palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre. Photorealistic, shot on 35mm film, shallow depth of field. Negative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements.\n```\n```nano-banana-2\nAnchor: Chorus lines 1-2 — \"Torn robes fly in holy rage / On a dark and pagan stage.\"\nA dramatic, high-contrast close-up of two pairs of hands violently tearing rough, woven tunics at the collar. Fabric rips and frays in mid-motion. In the background, out of focus, is a pagan stone altar with floral garlands and the horns of an ox barely visible. Lighting is harsh chiaroscuro, like a single torch illuminating the scene against deep shadow. Palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre. Cinematic still, anamorphic lens. Negative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements.\n```\n```nano-banana-3\nAnchor: V2 lines 3-4 — \"Priest brings bulls, a flowered crown / Ready now to bow right down.\"\nA photorealistic still life composition. On ancient stone steps leading to a city gate, a priest has laid down his offerings: two large, formidable bull's heads adorned with intricate wreaths of white flowers and green leaves. The focus is on the sacrificial items, gleaming under the afternoon sun, with the bustling crowd rendered as a soft-focus background. Palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre. Natural light, shot on medium format film. Negative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements.\n```\n```nano-banana-4\nAnchor: Bridge lines 1-2 — \"You alone give sun and rain / You alone can heal the pain.\"\nA cinematic, super-wide shot of a vast, fertile valley in ancient Anatolia under a dramatic sky. On one side, brilliant golden sunlight breaks through the clouds, illuminating fields of ripe wheat. On the other side, dark, heavy clouds release visible sheets of rain. The image captures the duality of God's provision in a single, epic landscape. Palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre, with vibrant gold and deep blue-grey in the sky. Volumetric light. Negative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements.\n```\n```nano-banana-5\nAnchor: V3 lines 1-2 — \"Fickle crowd now turns to hate / Stones fly through the city gate.\"\nA motion-blurred, chaotic scene from a low angle, looking up. The air is thick with dust, and rough stones of various sizes are captured in mid-flight, frozen by a fast shutter speed. In the background, the angry, indistinct faces of a mob are visible just outside a stone city gate. The feeling is one of imminent, brutal impact. Palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre, with harsh shadows. Photorealistic, high-speed photography aesthetic. Negative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements.\n```\n```nano-banana-title\nAnchor: The song's central image — \"Not Gods, But Men.\"\nA powerful, symbolic image. Two simple, empty wooden sandals rest on a rough stone pedestal, clearly a makeshift altar. Before them, a beautiful, ornate floral garland lies discarded and slightly crushed on the ground. The sandals represent the apostles' simple humanity, while the rejected garland signifies the refused worship. The scene is lit by a single, dramatic shaft of light from above. Palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre. Cinematic still, shallow depth of field. Negative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements.\n```\n```nano-banana-horizon\nAnchor: The Christo-telic Horizon — The Creator alone is worthy of worship.\nAn epic, cosmic scene. A symbolic representation of the Creator's hand, formed from swirling nebulae and stars, gently holds a miniature, glowing earth. From the hand, shimmering waves of light representing rain and life pour down onto the planet. This is not a literal hand, but a majestic, astronomical formation that evokes creative power and tender provision, capturing the essence of the sermon in Acts 14:17. Palette: deep indigo, starfield, volumetric blues, with golden light. Negative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements.\n```",
