reature rather than the Creator (cf. Rom 1:25).</li>\n<li><strong>Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"):</strong> The call to \"turn from these vain things to a living God\" (v. 15) is a summary of repentance, the necessary response to the gospel.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Tripartite Synthesis:</strong> Conservative Christian commentators see this as a paradigm for apologetics starting from general revelation. Jewish tradition affirms the apostles' reaction as the correct response to idolatry, rooted in the Shema (Deut 6:4) and the Decalogue. The act of tearing clothes (קריעה, <em>keriah</em>) is a deeply Jewish expression of horror at blasphemy. The entire event underscores the unbridgeable gap between the one Creator and all created things, a non-negotiable tenet of both faiths.</li>\n</ul>",
