/li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> Engage with people of other faiths with both respect and urgency. Understand that their \"ways\" are not equally valid paths to God, but a state from which God now lovingly commands them to turn.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> Feel the weight of gospel urgency. This verse is a powerful motivator for global missions. Because God's period of \"allowing\" is over and His command to repent is \"now,\" the Church is compelled to carry this message to every nation that is still walking in its own ways.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong> We adore the God of history, whose patience is vast and whose timing is perfect. We praise You, O Lord, that You did not leave us to walk in our own dark ways forever, but in the fullness of time, You shattered our ignorance with the glorious light of the gospel of Your Son.</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:16 — \"He allowed all the nations to walk in their own ways.\"\nKEY TERM:     εἴασεν (*eiasen*, \"he allowed/permitted\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: God's past forbearance with the nations now ends with the gospel's call.\nIMAGE:        Divergent paths leading away from a single, unseen source of light.\nAPPLICATION:  Share the gospel with a neighbor, knowing God's time of \"allowing\" is over.\nDOXOLOGY:     I praise You, God of history, for ending my wandering with Your call.\n```\n",
