      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:15-18 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Greek (NA28)**\nκαίτοι οὐκ ἀμάρτυρον ἑαυτὸν ἀφῆκεν ἀγαθουργῶν, οὐρανόθεν ὑμῖν ὑετοὺς διδοὺς καὶ καιροὺς καρποφόρους, ἐμπιπλῶν τροφῆς καὶ εὐφροσύνης τὰς καρδίας ὑμῶν.\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 15 rows = 105 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | καίτοι | kaitoi | G2543 | καίτοι | Conj | and yet / although |\n| 2 | οὐκ | ouk | G3756 | οὐ | Adv | not |\n| 3 | ἀμάρτυρον | amartyron | G267 | ἀμάρτυρος | A-ASM | without witness |\n| 4 | ἑαυτὸν | heauton | G1438 | ἑαυτοῦ | F-3ASM | Himself |\n| 5 | ἀφῆκεν | aphēken | G863 | ἀφίημι | V-AAI-3S | He left / let go |\n| 6 | ἀγαθουργῶν | agathourgōn | G15 | ἀγαθουργέω | V-PAP-NSM | doing good |\n| 7 | οὐρανόθεν | ouranothen | G3771 | οὐρανόθεν | Adv | from heaven |\n| 8 | ὑμῖν | hymin | G5213 | σύ | P-2DP | to you (plural) |\n| 9 | ὑετοὺς | hyetous | G5205 | ὑετός | N-AMP | rains |\n| 10 | διδοὺς | didous | G1325 | δίδωμι | V-PAP-NSM | giving |\n| 11 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 12 | καιροὺς | kairous | G2540 | καιρός | N-AMP | seasons / appointed times |\n| 13 | καρποφόρους | karpophorous | G2593 | καρποφόρος | A-AMP | fruit-bearing |\n| 14 | ἐμπιπλῶν | empimplōn | G1705 | ἐμπίπλημι | V-PAP-NSM | filling / satisfying |\n| 15 | εὐφροσύνης | euphrosynēs | G2167 | εὐφροσύνη | N-GSF | gladness / joy |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation**\nAnd yet not without-witness Himself He left, doing-good, from-heaven to-you rains giving and seasons fruit-bearing, filling with-food and with-gladness the hearts of-you.\n\n**Standalone English Translation**\nYet He did not leave Himself without a witness, for He did good by giving you rains from heaven and fruitful seasons, satisfying your hearts with food and gladness.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation**\nAnd yet, He has never left Himself without a tangible testimony [to His own nature], because He has been continually doing good: giving you rains from heaven [as a direct gift] and seasons that bear fruit, lavishly filling your hearts to the brim with both physical food and deep gladness.\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:15-18 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Greek (NA28)</strong>\nκαίτοι οὐκ ἀμάρτυρον ἑαυτὸν ἀφῆκεν ἀγαθουργῶν, οὐρανόθεν ὑμῖν ὑετοὺς διδοὺς καὶ καιροὺς καρποφόρους, ἐμπιπλῶν τροφῆς καὶ εὐφροσύνης τὰς καρδίας ὑμῶν.</p>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 15 rows = 105 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>καίτοι</td>\n<td>kaitoi</td>\n<td>G2543</td>\n<td>καίτοι</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and yet / although</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>οὐκ</td>\n<td>ouk</td>\n<td>G3756</td>\n<td>οὐ</td>\n<td>Adv</td>\n<td>not</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>ἀμάρτυρον</td>\n<td>amartyron</td>\n<td>G267</td>\n<td>ἀμάρτυρος</td>\n<td>A-ASM</td>\n<td>without witness</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>ἑαυτὸν</td>\n<td>heauton</td>\n<td>G1438</td>\n<td>ἑαυτοῦ</td>\n<td>F-3ASM</td>\n<td>Himself</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>ἀφῆκεν</td>\n<td>aphēken</td>\n<td>G863</td>\n<td>ἀφίημι</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3S</td>\n<td>He left / let go</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>ἀγαθουργῶν</td>\n<td>agathourgōn</td>\n<td>G15</td>\n<td>ἀγαθουργέω</td>\n<td>V-PAP-NSM</td>\n<td>doing good</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>οὐρανόθεν</td>\n<td>ouranothen</td>\n<td>G3771</td>\n<td>οὐρανόθεν</td>\n<td>Adv</td>\n<td>from heaven</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>ὑμῖν</td>\n<td>hymin</td>\n<td>G5213</td>\n<td>σύ</td>\n<td>P-2DP</td>\n<td>to you (plural)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>ὑετοὺς</td>\n<td>hyetous</td>\n<td>G5205</td>\n<td>ὑετός</td>\n<td>N-AMP</td>\n<td>rains</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>διδοὺς</td>\n<td>didous</td>\n<td>G1325</td>\n<td>δίδωμι</td>\n<td>V-PAP-NSM</td>\n<td>giving</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>καιροὺς</td>\n<td>kairous</td>\n<td>G2540</td>\n<td>καιρός</td>\n<td>N-AMP</td>\n<td>seasons / appointed times</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>καρποφόρους</td>\n<td>karpophorous</td>\n<td>G2593</td>\n<td>καρποφόρος</td>\n<td>A-AMP</td>\n<td>fruit-bearing</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>14</td>\n<td>ἐμπιπλῶν</td>\n<td>empimplōn</td>\n<td>G1705</td>\n<td>ἐμπίπλημι</td>\n<td>V-PAP-NSM</td>\n<td>filling / satisfying</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15</td>\n<td>εὐφροσύνης</td>\n<td>euphrosynēs</td>\n<td>G2167</td>\n<td>εὐφροσύνη</td>\n<td>N-GSF</td>\n<td>gladness / joy</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation</strong>\nAnd yet not without-witness Himself He left, doing-good, from-heaven to-you rains giving and seasons fruit-bearing, filling with-food and with-gladness the hearts of-you.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation</strong>\nYet He did not leave Himself without a witness, for He did good by giving you rains from heaven and fruitful seasons, satisfying your hearts with food and gladness.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation</strong>\nAnd yet, He has never left Himself without a tangible testimony [to His own nature], because He has been continually doing good: giving you rains from heaven [as a direct gift] and seasons that bear fruit, lavishly filling your hearts to the brim with both physical food and deep gladness.</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** God's constant, benevolent provision in the natural world serves as a universal and undeniable witness to His goodness, inviting all people to seek Him.\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):** The universal human tendency to either take God's provision for granted (practical atheism) or to misattribute it to false gods, luck, or impersonal natural forces (idolatry), thereby robbing the true Giver of His rightful glory.\n*   **Shared Particulars:** Like the Lystrans, we are utterly dependent on forces beyond our control for our daily food and well-being. Like them, we are surrounded by a culture that offers a thousand false explanations for the goodness we experience.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** The same God who did not leave Himself without a witness in creation has now given His ultimate witness in His Son (Heb 1:1-2). The God who fills our hearts with food and gladness has offered the true Bread of Life (John 6:35) and Living Water (John 4:14) in Jesus, so that our deepest hunger might be satisfied and our joy might be made full (John 15:11).\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\" & \"Being\":* Cultivate a moment-by-moment gratitude for common graces. Before a meal, consciously thank God not just for the food, but for the entire chain of provision He ordained: the sun, the soil, the rain, and the farmers. Intentionally see a sunrise or a rainstorm as a personal message of His faithfulness.\n    *   *Relational:* Use the beauty and order of creation as a natural bridge to conversations about God with unbelieving friends and family. Ask simple questions: \"Have you ever wondered where all this beauty and order comes from?\" Use it as Paul did, to introduce the Creator.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* If you are a farmer, scientist, artist, or chef, view your vocation as a ministry of highlighting the goodness of God's provision. Your work can help others see the witness that is embedded in the material world.\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):**\n    1.  **Attribute(s) of God surfaced:** Benevolent Providence, Faithful Goodness.\n    2.  **One-sentence doxology:** O Living God, I praise You, for You are the one who sends the rain, orders the seasons, and fills my heart with food and gladness, leaving a constant witness to Your goodness.\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> God's constant, benevolent provision in the natural world serves as a universal and undeniable witness to His goodness, inviting all people to seek Him.</li>\n<li><strong>FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):</strong> The universal human tendency to either take God's provision for granted (practical atheism) or to misattribute it to false gods, luck, or impersonal natural forces (idolatry), thereby robbing the true Giver of His rightful glory.</li>\n<li><strong>Shared Particulars:</strong> Like the Lystrans, we are utterly dependent on forces beyond our control for our daily food and well-being. Like them, we are surrounded by a culture that offers a thousand false explanations for the goodness we experience.</li>\n<li><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> The same God who did not leave Himself without a witness in creation has now given His ultimate witness in His Son (Heb 1:1-2). The God who fills our hearts with food and gladness has offered the true Bread of Life (John 6:35) and Living Water (John 4:14) in Jesus, so that our deepest hunger might be satisfied and our joy might be made full (John 15:11).</li>\n<li><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\" &amp; \"Being\":</em> Cultivate a moment-by-moment gratitude for common graces. Before a meal, consciously thank God not just for the food, but for the entire chain of provision He ordained: the sun, the soil, the rain, and the farmers. Intentionally see a sunrise or a rainstorm as a personal message of His faithfulness.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> Use the beauty and order of creation as a natural bridge to conversations about God with unbelieving friends and family. Ask simple questions: \"Have you ever wondered where all this beauty and order comes from?\" Use it as Paul did, to introduce the Creator.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> If you are a farmer, scientist, artist, or chef, view your vocation as a ministry of highlighting the goodness of God's provision. Your work can help others see the witness that is embedded in the material world.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong><ol>\n<li><strong>Attribute(s) of God surfaced:</strong> Benevolent Providence, Faithful Goodness.</li>\n<li><strong>One-sentence doxology:</strong> O Living God, I praise You, for You are the one who sends the rain, orders the seasons, and fills my heart with food and gladness, leaving a constant witness to Your goodness.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:17 — \"He did not leave himself without witness...giving you rains...and fruitful seasons.\"\nKEY TERM:     ἀμάρτυρον (*amartyron*, \"without witness\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: God reveals His goodness through the constant, joyful provision of creation.\nIMAGE:        Rain falling on a field of ripe fruit under a sunlit sky.\nAPPLICATION:  For myself and my neighbour: see daily provision (food, weather) as God's witness and say \"thank you.\"\nDOXOLOGY:     Thank you, God, for filling my heart with food and gladness.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:17 — &quot;He did not leave himself without witness...giving you rains...and fruitful seasons.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>ἀμάρτυρον (*amartyron*, &quot;without witness&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>God reveals His goodness through the constant, joyful provision of creation.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>Rain falling on a field of ripe fruit under a sunlit sky.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>For myself and my neighbour: see daily provision (food, weather) as God&#x27;s witness and say &quot;thank you.&quot;</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Thank you, God, for filling my heart with food and gladness.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever stopped to truly consider a simple meal? Or felt the relief of a summer rain? In the ancient city of Lystra, the apostle Paul pointed to these very things as proof of a loving, living God. After a miraculous healing, the local people tried to worship Paul and his companion Barnabas as pagan gods. Paul stopped them, urging them to turn from \"worthless things to a living God\" (Acts 14:15). How did he prove this God was real? He didn't quote a scroll they'd never read. Instead, he pointed to their own lives.\n\nHe said that God \"did not leave himself without a witness, for he did good by giving you rains from heaven and fruitful seasons, satisfying your hearts with food and gladness.\" God's signature is written across the created world. Every harvest, every season, every meal that fills our stomachs, and every moment of simple joy is a testimony. It's a gift from a good Father, intended not just for our survival, but for our delight. This universal goodness is the bridge to the greatest good: His Son, Jesus, the true Bread of Life. Today, let every common grace—a cup of coffee, the sun on your face—remind you of the Giver and lead your heart to thank Him.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever stopped to truly consider a simple meal? Or felt the relief of a summer rain? In the ancient city of Lystra, the apostle Paul pointed to these very things as proof of a loving, living God. After a miraculous healing, the local people tried to worship Paul and his companion Barnabas as pagan gods. Paul stopped them, urging them to turn from \"worthless things to a living God\" (Acts 14:15). How did he prove this God was real? He didn't quote a scroll they'd never read. Instead, he pointed to their own lives.</p>\n<p>He said that God \"did not leave himself without a witness, for he did good by giving you rains from heaven and fruitful seasons, satisfying your hearts with food and gladness.\" God's signature is written across the created world. Every harvest, every season, every meal that fills our stomachs, and every moment of simple joy is a testimony. It's a gift from a good Father, intended not just for our survival, but for our delight. This universal goodness is the bridge to the greatest good: His Son, Jesus, the true Bread of Life. Today, let every common grace—a cup of coffee, the sun on your face—remind you of the Giver and lead your heart to thank Him.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  What four specific things does Paul say God gives as a \"witness\" in this verse?\n    A: Rains from heaven, fruitful seasons, food, and gladness in people's hearts.\n\n2.  Why was it significant for Paul to say the *living God* gives rain, to this specific audience?\n    A: The pagan audience believed a sky-god like Zeus controlled the weather. Paul was redirecting their worship from a local idol to the universal Creator.\n\n3.  What does this verse teach about God's character and how He relates to all people?\n    A: It shows God's universal goodness and common grace. He actively and benevolently provides for all people, not just His covenant people, revealing His kind nature to everyone.\n\n4.  Based on this passage, what is one concrete action you can take this week to apply its truth?\n    A: I can pause before a meal, look at the food, and consciously thank God for the entire chain of provision (rain, sun, soil) as His personal witness to me.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>What four specific things does Paul say God gives as a \"witness\" in this verse?\n    A: Rains from heaven, fruitful seasons, food, and gladness in people's hearts.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Why was it significant for Paul to say the <em>living God</em> gives rain, to this specific audience?\n    A: The pagan audience believed a sky-god like Zeus controlled the weather. Paul was redirecting their worship from a local idol to the universal Creator.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>What does this verse teach about God's character and how He relates to all people?\n    A: It shows God's universal goodness and common grace. He actively and benevolently provides for all people, not just His covenant people, revealing His kind nature to everyone.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Based on this passage, what is one concrete action you can take this week to apply its truth?\n    A: I can pause before a meal, look at the food, and consciously thank God for the entire chain of provision (rain, sun, soil) as His personal witness to me.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>",
