    "exegesis_md": "# Acts 14:18 — The Scarcely-Averted Idolatry at Lystra\n\n## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:8-20 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\n\n18 καὶ ταῦτα λέγοντες μόλις κατέπαυσαν τοὺς ὄχλους τοῦ μὴ θύειν αὐτοῖς.\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 8 rows = 56 cells.*\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and / even |\n| 2 | ταῦτα | tauta | G5023 | οὗτος | D-APN | these things |\n| 3 | λέγοντες | legontes | G3004 | λέγω | V-PAP-NPM | saying (present participle) |\n| 4 | μόλις | molis | G3433 | μόλις | Adv | with difficulty / scarcely |\n| 5 | κατέπαυσαν | katepausan | G2664 | καταπαύω | V-AAI-3P | they restrained / stopped |\n| 6 | τοὺς | tous | G3588 | ὁ | T-APM | the |\n| 7 | ὄχλους | ochlous | G3793 | ὄχλος | N-APM | crowds |\n| 8 | τοῦ μὴ θύειν αὐτοῖς | tou mē thyein autois | G3588/3361/2380/846 | ὁ/μή/θύω/αὐτός | T-GSN / Neg / V-PAN / P-DPM | from sacrificing to them |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\n\n18 And saying these things, with difficulty they restrained the crowds from sacrificing to them.\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\n\n18 Even with these words, they could barely stop the crowds from offering sacrifices to them.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\n\n18 Yet even after saying all this [in their impassioned sermon], it was only with great difficulty [so ingrained was the people's idolatry] that they managed to restrain the crowds from their intention of offering sacrifice to them.\n\n## Exegesis\n\n### The Thesis\n\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The apostles' urgent attempt to stop the Lystran crowd from offering them idolatrous sacrifice.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** Their words were barely sufficient to restrain the people, highlighting the deep-seated and persistent nature of the pagan worldview.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** The gospel's demand for exclusive worship of the Creator God is so foreign to the fallen human heart that even a direct apostolic sermon can scarcely prevent people from defaulting to idolatry.\n\n### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The book of Acts documents the Holy Spirit-empowered expansion of the church from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth (Acts 1:8). This verse highlights a primary obstacle in that mission: the profound spiritual blindness of paganism, which instinctively deifies human agents of divine power rather than worshipping the divine Source. It showcases the apostles' non-negotiable commitment to the first commandment, even at the risk of offending a receptive crowd.\n\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This verse is the tense climax of the Lystra episode (Acts 14:8-20) on Paul's first missionary journey. Following the miraculous healing of a lame man, the crowd deifies Barnabas as Zeus and Paul as Hermes. The apostles react with horror, tear their clothes, and preach a short sermon on the living Creator God (vv. 15-17). Verse 18 is the immediate, fragile result of that sermon—a barely successful attempt to halt blasphemy—which is immediately followed by a violent reversal where the same crowd is persuaded to stone Paul (v. 19).\n\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic:** The primary genre is historical narrative. The key *hermeneutic* (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") here is to distinguish description from prescription. The crowd's reaction is described to show their fallen state; the apostles' reaction is prescriptive, modeling the correct response to idolatry and the deification of ministers. The plot's sharp turn from adoration (v. 18) to attempted murder (v. 19) illustrates the fickleness of unregenerate humanity.\n\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** This event occurs in the Church Age (dispensation of Grace), as the New Covenant is being proclaimed to the Gentiles. It represents a direct fulfillment of the Abrahamic Covenant's promise that Abraham's seed would be a blessing to \"all the families of the earth\" (Gen 12:3) by bringing them the truth that turns them from idols to the living God (1 Thess 1:9).\n\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** This incident forms a thematic set with other \"refused worship\" scenes. It stands in direct parallel to Peter refusing Cornelius's worship (Acts 10:25-26, [Pericope: Acts 10:23b-28 · source: NA28]) and the angel refusing John's worship (Rev 19:10; 22:9, [Pericope: Rev 22:6-11 · source: NA28]). It is the direct antithesis of Herod Agrippa I accepting worship and being struck down by God for his pride (Acts 12:21-23, [Pericope: Acts 12:20-23 · source: NA28]).\n\n### Setting: The original audience's world\n\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** The event takes place around AD 47-48, during the first missionary journey of Paul and Barnabas. This chronology is established by conservative scholars like Hoehner and Bruce.\n\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:** Lystra was a Roman colony in the region of Lycaonia, in the Roman province of Galatia (modern-day south-central Turkey, near Hatunsaray). It was a relatively rural town, not a major cultural hub, situated on a trade route. The local culture was a mix of Roman administration and deeply rooted Anatolian folk religion.\n\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** The immediate audience was a crowd of Lycaonian pagans, whose worldview was polytheistic and syncretistic. They spoke the local Lycaonian language (Acts 14:11). Their reaction shows they were steeped in myths of gods visiting earth in human form (theophany), such as the local legend of Zeus and Hermes visiting Philemon and Baucis in the same region, as recorded by Ovid (*Metamorphoses* 8.626-724) [Source-Discipline Tiering: Tier 2, later synthesis but reflects local tradition].\n\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke, the author of Acts, is writing to Theophilus and a wider Christian audience. His purpose in recording this is to demonstrate the nature of authentic apostolic ministry: it performs signs and wonders by God's power but relentlessly deflects all glory and worship away from itself and toward the one true God. It also prepares the church for the reality that the mission field is volatile, where today's worshippers can be tomorrow's executioners.\n\n### Verse-Level Craft\n\n*   **Literal-Primary Filter:** The plain meaning is that Paul and Barnabas, through their speech, barely managed to stop a pagan sacrifice intended for them. The verse's power lies in its assessment of the difficulty of their success.\n\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax:** The key word is the adverb μόλις (*molis*, \"with difficulty, scarcely\"). This single word colors the entire event, transforming it from a triumphant sermon into a near-disaster. It reveals the immense inertia of the pagan mindset. The verb κατέπαυσαν (*katepausan*, \"they restrained\") is an aorist indicative, marking that they *did* succeed in stopping the action, but the preceding adverb tells us it was a close call. The construction τοῦ μὴ θύειν (*tou mē thyein*, \"from sacrificing\") is a genitive articular infinitive, a common Greek way to express the result or content of the restraining action.\n\n*   **Imagery & Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):** The central image is that of a pagan sacrifice: a priest, garlands, and oxen (v. 13). This was the highest form of worship and honor in the ancient world. Luke includes these details to show the seriousness of the crowd's idolatrous intent. The apostles' response—tearing their garments (v. 14)—is a powerful counter-image, a traditional Jewish expression of horror at blasphemy (cf. Matt 26:65). The clash of these two images—pagan worship versus Jewish horror—is the central drama of the pericope (\"the literary unit\").\n\n*   **Common Misreadings Flag:**\n    *   *Misreading:* The crowd's desire to worship Paul and Barnabas was a sign of their spiritual openness or readiness for the gospel.\n    *   *Why wrong:* The text presents their reaction not as readiness but as profound misunderstanding. They tried to fit a monotheistic miracle into a polytheistic framework, which the apostles identified as idolatry, not faith. True readiness for the gospel involves turning *from* idols (1 Thess 1:9).\n    *   *Cross-references:* Acts 17:29-30; 1 Corinthians 10:14; 1 John 5:21.\n    *   *Correct reading:* The crowd's reaction was a demonstration of the fallen human tendency to worship the creature rather than the Creator, a core theme of Romans 1:21-25.\n\n### Canonical Connection\n\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment:** This event is a fulfillment of the apostolic commission to be witnesses to a world lost in darkness (Acts 26:17-18). It serves as a real-world example of the spiritual battle described throughout Scripture. [TYPE]: The apostles' refusal to accept worship is a type of Christ's own refusal to take a shortcut to glory by worshipping Satan in the wilderness (Matt 4:8-10).\n\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** The motif is the exclusive worship of the one true God. This trajectory begins with the command in the Decalogue (\"You shall have no other gods before me,\" Ex 20:3), is defended by the prophets (Isa 44:6), embodied by the faithful remnant in exile (Dan 3:16-18), and definitively articulated by Christ Himself (\"You shall worship the Lord your God and him only shall you serve,\" Matt 4:10). Acts 14:18 shows the apostles carrying this non-negotiable principle into the Gentile world. The *Christo-telic terminus* (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the final, universal worship of the Lamb on the throne, where every creature gives Him glory and honor (Rev 5:13). The *hinge-of-hinges* is Christ's temptation, and the *terminus verse* is Revelation 22:9: \"Worship God.\"\n\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:**\n    *   ☐ **Theology Proper (\"the doctrine of God Himself\"):** Establishes God as the unique, living Creator, utterly distinct from and transcendent over His creation, and alone worthy of worship.\n    *   ☐ **Hamartiology (\"the doctrine of sin and the Fall\"):** Demonstrates that idolatry is the default state of the fallen human heart, quick to worship created things or even fellow humans.\n    *   ☐ **Anthropology (\"the doctrine of humanity as God made us\"):** Reinforces the sharp distinction between mortal man and the immortal God. The apostles declare themselves to be men \"of like nature\" (ὁμοιοπαθεῖς, *homoiopatheis*) with the crowd (v. 15).\n    *   ☐ **Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"):** Specifically missiology, it models the missionary's duty to confront idolatry directly and preach the Creator God as the entry point for the gospel in a pagan context.\n\n*   **Antithetical Doctrine Check:** This passage directly refutes any form of the \"prosperity gospel\" or \"man of God\" cult of personality that elevates a minister to a status where they are seen as the source of power, rather than a mere vessel. It is a powerful scriptural rebuke to any leader who cultivates or tolerates a following that borders on worship.\n\n## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** All worship, honor, and glory for any good work or miraculous power belong exclusively to God the Creator, and it is the Christian's duty to vehemently reject any misdirected praise and redirect it to Him.\n\n*   **Fallen Condition Focus (FCF):** The passage addresses the universal human tendency to idolize. In the individual, this is the reflex to worship the gift or the messenger instead of the Giver. Corporately, it's the church's temptation to create celebrity pastors or ministry leaders, attributing the power of God to a person's charisma, methods, or personality.\n\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** The gospel frees us from the need to create our own gods. Christ has revealed the one true God, and through His death and resurrection, He has made access to this God possible. We don't need to look for gods in human form because God has already come in human form in the person of Jesus Christ (John 1:14; Col 1:15), who alone is worthy of worship (Phil 2:9-11).\n\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* When you receive praise for a talent, success, or act of service, develop the habit of explicitly and immediately giving the credit to God. Say it out loud: \"Thank you, that's kind, but all glory goes to God.\"\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Cultivate a heart of genuine humility that, like Paul and Barnabas, is horrified by self-glorification. See yourself rightly as a steward and vessel, not the source, of any good thing.\n    *   *Relational:* In your church, actively resist the culture of celebrity. Honor your leaders (1 Tim 5:17) but worship only God. Gently correct fellow believers who speak of pastors or worship leaders in ways that border on idolatry.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* In a world that idolizes success, power, beauty, and talent, your refusal to deify human achievement and your consistent redirection of praise to the Creator is a powerful and counter-cultural witness.\n\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** This passage reveals God as the jealous, living Creator who alone is worthy of sacrifice and worship. Our response is to adore Him for His absolute uniqueness and to join the apostles in declaring that He, not we, is the source of all life, breath, and goodness. \"To You alone, O living God, who made the heaven and the earth and the sea and all that is in them, be all glory and honor.\"\n\n## Pre-Output Self-Audit Scorecard\nPillar 1 — TEXT INTEGRITY: PASS — Counted 8 original-language word occurrences; all 8 follow canonical form. Interlinear has 8 rows × 7 columns; all 56 cells filled.\nPillar 2 — COVERAGE: PASS — The single verse is fully treated in Single-Block Mode.\nPillar 3 — HERMENEUTIC FIDELITY: PASS — Sensus Literalis applied; narrative genre rules honored; idolatry firewall maintained.\nPillar 4 — CANONICAL DEPTH: PASS — Concentric localization complete; motif trajectory traced; loci tagged.\nPillar 5 — APPLICATION + DOXOLOGY: PASS — Indicative-imperative structure used; FCF and doxology are text-grounded.\nPillar 6 — DELIVERABLES: PASS — All Rule 3 mandatory glosses applied per section; rendered headings clean of internal labels; no placeholder lines.\n\n## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:18 — \"With difficulty they restrained the crowds from sacrificing to them.\"\nKEY TERM:     μόλις (*molis*, \"scarcely, with difficulty\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: The apostles barely stop the crowd's idolatry, showing how deep it runs.\nIMAGE:        A priest's hand being stopped just before sacrificing an ox.\nAPPLICATION:  When praised for any good, I will immediately deflect the glory to God alone.\nDOXOLOGY:     To You alone, the Living God, be all worship and sacrifice.\n```\n\n## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever seen someone get praised for a good work and felt a little uncomfortable, as if the person was being put on a pedestal? In Acts 14, Paul and Barnabas face an extreme version of this. After they heal a man in Lystra who had been lame from birth, the pagan crowd goes wild. Convinced that gods have visited them, they prepare to offer sacrifices to Barnabas and Paul. The apostles are horrified. They tear their clothes and rush into the crowd, shouting that they are just men and that worship belongs only to the living God who made everything.\n\nToday's verse tells us the result: \"Even with these words, they could barely stop the crowds\" (Acts 14:18). The word \"barely\" is key. It shows how deeply ingrained our human tendency is to worship the visible—the messenger, the miracle worker, the gifted person—instead of the invisible God who is the source of all goodness. The gospel frees us from this. Because God truly did come in the flesh in Jesus Christ, He is the only human form worthy of our worship. This story is a powerful reminder for us. When we do anything good, or when we see good in others, our first and final response must be to deflect all praise and glory to the only One who deserves it: God Himself.\n\n## Retention Quiz\n1.  What adverb in Acts 14:18 shows how difficult it was for the apostles to stop the crowd?\n    A: The word is μόλις (*molis*), meaning \"scarcely\" or \"with difficulty.\"\n\n2.  Why did the crowd in Lystra want to offer sacrifices to Paul and Barnabas?\n    A: Because they had miraculously healed a man lame from birth, and the crowd wrongly concluded they were the gods Zeus and Hermes in human form.\n\n3.  What does this passage teach us about God and worship?\n    A: It teaches that God is the one, living Creator, completely distinct from His creation. He alone is worthy of worship and sacrifice, and He is jealous for that glory. True worship turns *from* idols *to* Him.\n\n4.  What is a specific action you can take this week based on this passage?\n    A: When I receive any compliment or praise for my work, skills, or service, I will make a point to verbally thank God and give Him the credit.\n\n## Pipeline Coherence Check\n```\nCoherence 1 — SUBJECT alignment: Exegesis Phase B Subject = Song Legend & Key gloss = Slide H1 anchor. PASS — All align on the \"apostles stopping idolatry\" theme.\nCoherence 2 — COMPLEMENT alignment: Phase B Complement is audibly carried by the Chorus and named in the Memory Anchor Card. PASS — The \"scarcely/barely\" concept is central to both.\nCoherence 3 — CHRISTO-TELIC TERMINUS: same terminus verse appears in Phase F, the Song Bridge or Outro, and the Slide \"Canonical Connection\" H2. PASS — Rev 5:13 / 22:9 (Worship God/the Lamb) is the consistent terminus.\nCoherence 4 — IMMINENCY STATUS: activated-or-not is identical across Phase G Watchman Factor, Song Bridge, cover-art `nano-banana-horizon`, and Slide Watchman's Charge H2. PASS — Imminency Clause is not activated in this passage; all modules reflect this.\nCoherence 5 — TITLE / IMAGE coherence: Song Title, cover-art `nano-banana-title` image, and Slide H1 anchor share one defining image traceable to the exegesis. PASS — The \"Barely Stopped the Knife\" image is consistent.\nCoherence 6 — PALETTE coherence: cover-art palette directive equals slide-deck `visual_palette:` YAML key. PASS — \"Sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre\" is used for both.\nCoherence 7 — CHRIST-IMAGERY FORBEARANCE: substitution rule honored in cover art AND in slide-deck bullets. PASS — Not applicable as Christ is not directly depicted, but the principle is maintained.\nCoherence 8 — PERICOPE alignment: every Phase A verse carries a source-named Pericope Tag; Phase 0c Pericope-Source Statement matches; Big Idea is the pericope's. PASS — Pericope Acts 14:8-20 is consistently framed.\nCoherence 9 — APPLICATION consistency: Phase G Personal-Doing imperative, Memory Anchor Card APPLICATION line, Devotional Summary Take-away, and Retention Quiz Q4 all name the same actor and the same concrete act. PASS — All four point to the reader deflecting praise to God.\n```\n\n## Slide Deck Sidecar\n```markdown\n---\nbook: \"Acts\"\nchapter: \"14\"\nsection: \"18\"\nvisual_palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre\n---\n\n# Acts 14:18 — The Scarcely-Averted Idolatry at Lystra\nThe apostles' urgent sermon barely restrains the Lystran crowd from offering them pagan sacrifices, revealing the deep-seated human instinct for idolatry and the non-negotiable Christian duty to redirect all worship to God alone.\n\n*Slide deck: 7 sections, 7 total sub-slides, ≤5 bullets per slide.*\n\n## The Text\nThe verse's climax hangs on a single adverb: μόλις (*molis*, \"scarcely\"). Their success was not a triumph but a near-failure, underscoring the spiritual battle.\n\n- καὶ ταῦτα λέγοντες (*kai tauta legontes*) — \"and saying these things\"\n- μόλις (*molis*) — \"with difficulty, scarcely\"\n- κατέπαυσαν (*katepausan*) — \"they restrained, they stopped\"\n- τοὺς ὄχλους (*tous ochlous*) — \"the crowds\"\n- τοῦ μὴ θύειν αὐτοῖς (*tou mē thyein autois*) — \"from sacrificing to them\"\n\n### Detail\nThe Greek of Acts 14:18 reveals the tension of the moment. The phrase begins with a present participle, καὶ ταῦτα λέγοντες (*kai tauta legontes*, \"and saying these things\"), linking the verse directly to the sermon in vv. 15-17 as an ongoing action. The critical word is the adverb μόλις (*molis*, \"scarcely\"), which tells the reader that the apostles' impassioned plea was on the verge of failing. The main verb, κατέπαυσαν (*katepausan*, \"they restrained\"), is aorist, indicating they *did* achieve their goal, but only just. Luke's choice of words emphasizes the profound spiritual inertia of the pagan worldview. The crowd's desire to offer a θυσία (*thysia*, \"sacrifice\") was the highest expression of worship, and stopping it required a vehement, desperate intervention, highlighting the gulf between their worldview and the gospel.\n\n## The Thesis\nThe Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\") is that the gospel's demand for exclusive worship of the Creator is so alien to the fallen heart that even an apostolic sermon can barely stop people from defaulting to idolatry.\n\n- Subject — The apostles' attempt to stop idolatrous worship\n- Complement — Their words were barely sufficient for the task\n- Defining Image — A hand stopping a sacrifice mid-swing\n- Core Conflict — Monotheism vs. Polytheism\n- Narrative Verdict — A fragile, temporary success\n\n### Detail\nThe thesis of this verse is built from its Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\")—the apostles' intervention—and its Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\")—that the intervention was only barely successful. This yields the Big Idea: the default human spiritual condition is idolatry, and turning people from it is incredibly difficult. The Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\") is that all glory for any good work belongs to God alone, and His servants must actively refuse and redirect any worship aimed at them. This principle is grounded in the First Commandment (Ex 20:3) and modeled perfectly by Christ (Matt 4:10). The FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\") is the universal human reflex to worship the creature rather than the Creator (Rom 1:25).\n\n## Big Picture\nThis verse is the climax of the Lystra episode in Acts 14, a key event on Paul's first missionary journey that demonstrates the gospel's direct collision with raw paganism.\n\n- Book Role — Shows a key obstacle to the Acts 1:8 commission\n- Discourse Arc — The fragile resolution before a violent reversal (stoning)\n- Genre — Historical narrative with an embedded apostolic sermon\n- Salvation History — Church Age mission to the Gentiles\n- Thematic Parallels — Peter at Caesarea (Acts 10), Herod's death (Acts 12)\n\n### Detail\nWithin the book of Acts, this pericope (\"the literary unit\") serves to instruct the church on the challenges of Gentile mission. It sits within the larger arc of the first missionary journey (Acts 13-14). The immediate context is a miracle (healing the lame man), which is misinterpreted by the pagan crowd, leading to the apostles' corrective sermon. This verse (v. 18) concludes the sermon's effect, but the story immediately pivots in v. 19 when hostile Jews arrive and turn the fickle crowd from adoration to violence. This structure highlights the volatility of mission work. The *hermeneutic* (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture\") requires us to see the apostles' actions as a model for rejecting misplaced worship, a theme echoed when Peter refuses worship from Cornelius (Acts 10:25-26) and contrasted with Herod's fatal pride (Acts 12:21-23).\n\n## Setting\nThe event occurs in Lystra, a rural Roman colony in Galatia (modern Turkey) around AD 47-48, a place steeped in local polytheistic myths and traditions.\n\n- Place — Lystra, a rural town in Lycaonia\n- Time — c. AD 47-48, First Missionary Journey\n- Audience — Lycaonian pagans with little exposure to Judaism\n- Culture — A worldview shaped by myths of gods visiting earth\n- Author's Purpose — To model authentic ministry for Theophilus\n\n### Detail\nLystra was not a major city like Ephesus or Corinth. It was a Roman colony, but its local culture was deeply Anatolian. The crowd's immediate leap to identify Paul and Barnabas with Hermes and Zeus reflects a worldview where the line between divine and human was porous and where local legends, like Ovid's tale of Baucis and Philemon welcoming disguised gods, were part of the cultural air. The apostles were entering a spiritual world fundamentally different from the synagogue-centric contexts they often began in. Luke's inclusion of this detail is pastoral: he is preparing his readers for the reality that the gospel must confront and re-shape entire worldviews, not just offer a new philosophy.\n\n## Verse-Level Craft\nThe verse's meaning is carried by the adverb μόλις (*molis*, \"scarcely\"), which reveals the deep inertia of the crowd's idolatrous worldview.\n\n- Key Word — μόλις (*molis*, \"with difficulty\") shows a near-failure\n- Key Image — The pagan sacrifice (oxen, garlands) vs. torn robes\n- Rhetorical Effect — Creates suspense and highlights the spiritual battle\n- Apostolic Model — Vehement rejection of personal glory\n- Crowd's Condition — Spiritually blind, defaulting to idolatry\n\n### Detail\nLuke's literary craftsmanship is evident in his choice of words. μόλις (*molis*, \"scarcely\") is the pivot on which the verse's tone turns. Without it, the verse would read as a simple success. With it, it becomes a story of desperate, last-minute intervention against a tide of pagan devotion. The imagery is stark: the priest of Zeus is ready with oxen and garlands for a full pagan ritual (v. 13). The apostles counter with the Jewish gesture of torn robes (v. 14), a sign of horror at blasphemy. This visual and cultural conflict underscores the chasm between the two belief systems. The verse teaches that correcting a false worldview is not a simple matter of presenting facts; it is a difficult spiritual struggle against deeply ingrained error.\n\n## Canonical Connection\nThis event stands in a long biblical line of God's servants rejecting idolatry, from Abraham to the prophets to Christ Himself in the wilderness.\n\n- Motif — The exclusive worship of YHWH, the Creator\n- OT Command — \"You shall have no other gods before me\" (Ex 20:3)\n- Christ's Example — \"You shall worship the Lord your God only\" (Matt 4:10)\n- Apostolic Practice — Redirecting all worship from self to God\n- Eschatological Terminus — The final worship of the Lamb on the throne (Rev 5:13)\n\n### Detail\nThe *Christo-telic terminus* (\"the Christ-event...that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") for the theme of exclusive worship is the scene in Revelation 5, where the Lamb that was slain is declared alone worthy to receive power, wealth, wisdom, might, honor, glory, and blessing. The apostles' actions in Lystra are a small-scale enactment of this ultimate reality. They are preserving the unique glory of Christ. This connects to multiple systematic-theology loci: **Theology Proper (\"the doctrine of God Himself\")**, as it defines God as the sole object of worship; **Hamartiology (\"the doctrine of sin and the Fall\")**, as it shows idolatry as sin's default expression; and **Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\")**, as it defines a core function of mission.\n\n## Life Applications\nWe must actively cultivate humility that is horrified by self-glorification and intentionally redirects all praise for our gifts and works to God alone.\n\n- FCF — The human reflex to worship the creature over the Creator\n- Redemptive Indicative — Christ alone is God-in-flesh worthy of worship\n- Personal \"Doing\" — Verbally give God the glory when praised\n- Relational \"Being\" — Resist the celebrity culture within the church\n- Doxological Response — Adore the living God who made all things\n\n### Detail\nThe FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\") is our innate desire to idolize—to put a human face on divine power. This manifests today not with oxen and garlands, but in celebrity worship, even within the church. The gospel provides the Redemptive Indicative: we have the one true God-man, Jesus, so we need no other idols. Our application is therefore twofold. *Personal*: we must develop the discipline of deflecting praise. When someone says, \"You were amazing,\" we should respond, \"Thank you, I'm glad God could use me.\" *Corporate*: we must resist elevating leaders to a pedestal, honoring them for their work while reserving all worship for God. The Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis\") is to praise the living God who gives rain and fruitful seasons (v. 17) and who alone is worthy of our ultimate devotion.\n```",
