      "h1_title_html": "<p>Acts 14:18 — The Scarcely-Averted Idolatry at Lystra</p>",
      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:8-20 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\n\n18 καὶ ταῦτα λέγοντες μόλις κατέπαυσαν τοὺς ὄχλους τοῦ μὴ θύειν αὐτοῖς.\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 8 rows = 56 cells.*\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and / even |\n| 2 | ταῦτα | tauta | G5023 | οὗτος | D-APN | these things |\n| 3 | λέγοντες | legontes | G3004 | λέγω | V-PAP-NPM | saying (present participle) |\n| 4 | μόλις | molis | G3433 | μόλις | Adv | with difficulty / scarcely |\n| 5 | κατέπαυσαν | katepausan | G2664 | καταπαύω | V-AAI-3P | they restrained / stopped |\n| 6 | τοὺς | tous | G3588 | ὁ | T-APM | the |\n| 7 | ὄχλους | ochlous | G3793 | ὄχλος | N-APM | crowds |\n| 8 | τοῦ μὴ θύειν αὐτοῖς | tou mē thyein autois | G3588/3361/2380/846 | ὁ/μή/θύω/αὐτός | T-GSN / Neg / V-PAN / P-DPM | from sacrificing to them |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\n\n18 And saying these things, with difficulty they restrained the crowds from sacrificing to them.\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\n\n18 Even with these words, they could barely stop the crowds from offering sacrifices to them.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\n\n18 Yet even after saying all this [in their impassioned sermon], it was only with great difficulty [so ingrained was the people's idolatry] that they managed to restrain the crowds from their intention of offering sacrifice to them.\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:8-20 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Script (NA28)</strong></p>\n<p>18 καὶ ταῦτα λέγοντες μόλις κατέπαυσαν τοὺς ὄχλους τοῦ μὴ θύειν αὐτοῖς.</p>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 8 rows = 56 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and / even</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>ταῦτα</td>\n<td>tauta</td>\n<td>G5023</td>\n<td>οὗτος</td>\n<td>D-APN</td>\n<td>these things</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>λέγοντες</td>\n<td>legontes</td>\n<td>G3004</td>\n<td>λέγω</td>\n<td>V-PAP-NPM</td>\n<td>saying (present participle)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>μόλις</td>\n<td>molis</td>\n<td>G3433</td>\n<td>μόλις</td>\n<td>Adv</td>\n<td>with difficulty / scarcely</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>κατέπαυσαν</td>\n<td>katepausan</td>\n<td>G2664</td>\n<td>καταπαύω</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3P</td>\n<td>they restrained / stopped</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>τοὺς</td>\n<td>tous</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-APM</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>ὄχλους</td>\n<td>ochlous</td>\n<td>G3793</td>\n<td>ὄχλος</td>\n<td>N-APM</td>\n<td>crowds</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>τοῦ μὴ θύειν αὐτοῖς</td>\n<td>tou mē thyein autois</td>\n<td>G3588/3361/2380/846</td>\n<td>ὁ/μή/θύω/αὐτός</td>\n<td>T-GSN / Neg / V-PAN / P-DPM</td>\n<td>from sacrificing to them</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)</strong></p>\n<p>18 And saying these things, with difficulty they restrained the crowds from sacrificing to them.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)</strong></p>\n<p>18 Even with these words, they could barely stop the crowds from offering sacrifices to them.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)</strong></p>\n<p>18 Yet even after saying all this [in their impassioned sermon], it was only with great difficulty [so ingrained was the people's idolatry] that they managed to restrain the crowds from their intention of offering sacrifice to them.</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** All worship, honor, and glory for any good work or miraculous power belong exclusively to God the Creator, and it is the Christian's duty to vehemently reject any misdirected praise and redirect it to Him.\n\n*   **Fallen Condition Focus (FCF):** The passage addresses the universal human tendency to idolize. In the individual, this is the reflex to worship the gift or the messenger instead of the Giver. Corporately, it's the church's temptation to create celebrity pastors or ministry leaders, attributing the power of God to a person's charisma, methods, or personality.\n\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** The gospel frees us from the need to create our own gods. Christ has revealed the one true God, and through His death and resurrection, He has made access to this God possible. We don't need to look for gods in human form because God has already come in human form in the person of Jesus Christ (John 1:14; Col 1:15), who alone is worthy of worship (Phil 2:9-11).\n\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* When you receive praise for a talent, success, or act of service, develop the habit of explicitly and immediately giving the credit to God. Say it out loud: \"Thank you, that's kind, but all glory goes to God.\"\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Cultivate a heart of genuine humility that, like Paul and Barnabas, is horrified by self-glorification. See yourself rightly as a steward and vessel, not the source, of any good thing.\n    *   *Relational:* In your church, actively resist the culture of celebrity. Honor your leaders (1 Tim 5:17) but worship only God. Gently correct fellow believers who speak of pastors or worship leaders in ways that border on idolatry.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* In a world that idolizes success, power, beauty, and talent, your refusal to deify human achievement and your consistent redirection of praise to the Creator is a powerful and counter-cultural witness.\n\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** This passage reveals God as the jealous, living Creator who alone is worthy of sacrifice and worship. Our response is to adore Him for His absolute uniqueness and to join the apostles in declaring that He, not we, is the source of all life, breath, and goodness. \"To You alone, O living God, who made the heaven and the earth and the sea and all that is in them, be all glory and honor.\"\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> All worship, honor, and glory for any good work or miraculous power belong exclusively to God the Creator, and it is the Christian's duty to vehemently reject any misdirected praise and redirect it to Him.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Fallen Condition Focus (FCF):</strong> The passage addresses the universal human tendency to idolize. In the individual, this is the reflex to worship the gift or the messenger instead of the Giver. Corporately, it's the church's temptation to create celebrity pastors or ministry leaders, attributing the power of God to a person's charisma, methods, or personality.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> The gospel frees us from the need to create our own gods. Christ has revealed the one true God, and through His death and resurrection, He has made access to this God possible. We don't need to look for gods in human form because God has already come in human form in the person of Jesus Christ (John 1:14; Col 1:15), who alone is worthy of worship (Phil 2:9-11).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\":</em> When you receive praise for a talent, success, or act of service, develop the habit of explicitly and immediately giving the credit to God. Say it out loud: \"Thank you, that's kind, but all glory goes to God.\"</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\":</em> Cultivate a heart of genuine humility that, like Paul and Barnabas, is horrified by self-glorification. See yourself rightly as a steward and vessel, not the source, of any good thing.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> In your church, actively resist the culture of celebrity. Honor your leaders (1 Tim 5:17) but worship only God. Gently correct fellow believers who speak of pastors or worship leaders in ways that border on idolatry.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> In a world that idolizes success, power, beauty, and talent, your refusal to deify human achievement and your consistent redirection of praise to the Creator is a powerful and counter-cultural witness.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong> This passage reveals God as the jealous, living Creator who alone is worthy of sacrifice and worship. Our response is to adore Him for His absolute uniqueness and to join the apostles in declaring that He, not we, is the source of all life, breath, and goodness. \"To You alone, O living God, who made the heaven and the earth and the sea and all that is in them, be all glory and honor.\"</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:18 — \"With difficulty they restrained the crowds from sacrificing to them.\"\nKEY TERM:     μόλις (*molis*, \"scarcely, with difficulty\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: The apostles barely stop the crowd's idolatry, showing how deep it runs.\nIMAGE:        A priest's hand being stopped just before sacrificing an ox.\nAPPLICATION:  When praised for any good, I will immediately deflect the glory to God alone.\nDOXOLOGY:     To You alone, the Living God, be all worship and sacrifice.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:18 — &quot;With difficulty they restrained the crowds from sacrificing to them.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>μόλις (*molis*, &quot;scarcely, with difficulty&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>The apostles barely stop the crowd&#x27;s idolatry, showing how deep it runs.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>A priest&#x27;s hand being stopped just before sacrificing an ox.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>When praised for any good, I will immediately deflect the glory to God alone.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>To You alone, the Living God, be all worship and sacrifice.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever seen someone get praised for a good work and felt a little uncomfortable, as if the person was being put on a pedestal? In Acts 14, Paul and Barnabas face an extreme version of this. After they heal a man in Lystra who had been lame from birth, the pagan crowd goes wild. Convinced that gods have visited them, they prepare to offer sacrifices to Barnabas and Paul. The apostles are horrified. They tear their clothes and rush into the crowd, shouting that they are just men and that worship belongs only to the living God who made everything.\n\nToday's verse tells us the result: \"Even with these words, they could barely stop the crowds\" (Acts 14:18). The word \"barely\" is key. It shows how deeply ingrained our human tendency is to worship the visible—the messenger, the miracle worker, the gifted person—instead of the invisible God who is the source of all goodness. The gospel frees us from this. Because God truly did come in the flesh in Jesus Christ, He is the only human form worthy of our worship. This story is a powerful reminder for us. When we do anything good, or when we see good in others, our first and final response must be to deflect all praise and glory to the only One who deserves it: God Himself.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever seen someone get praised for a good work and felt a little uncomfortable, as if the person was being put on a pedestal? In Acts 14, Paul and Barnabas face an extreme version of this. After they heal a man in Lystra who had been lame from birth, the pagan crowd goes wild. Convinced that gods have visited them, they prepare to offer sacrifices to Barnabas and Paul. The apostles are horrified. They tear their clothes and rush into the crowd, shouting that they are just men and that worship belongs only to the living God who made everything.</p>\n<p>Today's verse tells us the result: \"Even with these words, they could barely stop the crowds\" (Acts 14:18). The word \"barely\" is key. It shows how deeply ingrained our human tendency is to worship the visible—the messenger, the miracle worker, the gifted person—instead of the invisible God who is the source of all goodness. The gospel frees us from this. Because God truly did come in the flesh in Jesus Christ, He is the only human form worthy of our worship. This story is a powerful reminder for us. When we do anything good, or when we see good in others, our first and final response must be to deflect all praise and glory to the only One who deserves it: God Himself.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  What adverb in Acts 14:18 shows how difficult it was for the apostles to stop the crowd?\n    A: The word is μόλις (*molis*), meaning \"scarcely\" or \"with difficulty.\"\n\n2.  Why did the crowd in Lystra want to offer sacrifices to Paul and Barnabas?\n    A: Because they had miraculously healed a man lame from birth, and the crowd wrongly concluded they were the gods Zeus and Hermes in human form.\n\n3.  What does this passage teach us about God and worship?\n    A: It teaches that God is the one, living Creator, completely distinct from His creation. He alone is worthy of worship and sacrifice, and He is jealous for that glory. True worship turns *from* idols *to* Him.\n\n4.  What is a specific action you can take this week based on this passage?\n    A: When I receive any compliment or praise for my work, skills, or service, I will make a point to verbally thank God and give Him the credit.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>What adverb in Acts 14:18 shows how difficult it was for the apostles to stop the crowd?\n    A: The word is μόλις (<em>molis</em>), meaning \"scarcely\" or \"with difficulty.\"</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Why did the crowd in Lystra want to offer sacrifices to Paul and Barnabas?\n    A: Because they had miraculously healed a man lame from birth, and the crowd wrongly concluded they were the gods Zeus and Hermes in human form.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>What does this passage teach us about God and worship?\n    A: It teaches that God is the one, living Creator, completely distinct from His creation. He alone is worthy of worship and sacrifice, and He is jealous for that glory. True worship turns <em>from</em> idols <em>to</em> Him.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>What is a specific action you can take this week based on this passage?\n    A: When I receive any compliment or praise for my work, skills, or service, I will make a point to verbally thank God and give Him the credit.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>",
