    "exegesis_md": "# Acts 14:19 — The Stoning of Paul and the Cost of the Gospel\n\n## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:8-20 · source: NA28]\n[Persecution / Suffering Overlay]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\n\nἘπελθόντες δὲ ἀπὸ Ἀντιοχείας καὶ Ἰκονίου Ἰουδαῖοι καὶ πείσαντες τοὺς ὄχλους ἐλιθοβόλησαν τὸν Παῦλον καὶ ἔσυρον ἔξω τῆς πόλεως, νομίσαντες αὐτὸν τεθνηκέναι.\n\n**Interlinear Table**\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 17 rows = 119 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Ἐπελθόντες | Epelthontes | G1904 | ἐπέρχομαι | V-AAP-NPM | Having come upon / arrived |\n| 2 | δὲ | de | G1161 | δέ | Conj | but / and |\n| 3 | ἀπὸ | apo | G575 | ἀπό | Prep | from |\n| 4 | Ἀντιοχείας | Antiocheias | G490 | Ἀντιόχεια | N-GSF | Antioch |\n| 5 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 6 | Ἰκονίου | Ikoniou | G2430 | Ἰκόνιον | N-GSN | Iconium |\n| 7 | Ἰουδαῖοι | Ioudaioi | G2453 | Ἰουδαῖος | A-NPM | Jews |\n| 8 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 9 | πείσαντες | peisantes | G3982 | πείθω | V-AAP-NPM | having persuaded |\n| 10 | τοὺς | tous | G3588 | ὁ | T-APM | the |\n| 11 | ὄχλους | ochlous | G3793 | ὄχλος | N-APM | crowds |\n| 12 | ἐλιθοβόλησαν | elithobolēsan | G3034 | λιθοβολέω | V-AAI-3P | they stoned |\n| 13 | τὸν | ton | G3588 | ὁ | T-ASM | the |\n| 14 | Παῦλον | Paulon | G3972 | Παῦλος | N-ASM | Paul |\n| 15 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 16 | ἔσυρον | esuron | G4951 | σύρω | V-IAI-3P | they were dragging |\n| 17 | ἔξω | exō | G1854 | ἔξω | Adv | outside |\n| 18 | τῆς | tēs | G3588 | ὁ | T-GSF | the |\n| 19 | πόλεως | poleōs | G4172 | πόλις | N-GSF | city |\n| 20 | νομίσαντες | nomisantes | G3543 | νομίζω | V-AAP-NPM | supposing / thinking |\n| 21 | αὐτὸν | auton | G846 | αὐτός | P-ASM | him |\n| 22 | τεθνηκέναι | tethnēkenai | G2348 | θνῄσκω | V-RNA | to be dead |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\n\nBut having come upon [them] from Antioch and Iconium, Jews, and having persuaded the crowds, they stoned Paul and were dragging [him] outside the city, supposing him to be dead.\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\n\nBut Jews came from Antioch and Iconium, and after winning over the crowds, they stoned Paul and dragged him out of the city, thinking he was dead.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\n\nBut then, Jews arrived from [as far as] Antioch and Iconium [bringing their coordinated opposition with them]. After persuading the [very same] crowds [that had just tried to worship him], they stoned Paul. Then they began dragging his [limp body] outside the city gates, supposing [with confidence] that he was dead.\n\n## Exegesis\n\n### The Thesis\n\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The violent stoning of the Apostle Paul at Lystra, instigated by hostile Jews who turned a recently adoring crowd into a lynch mob.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** This brutal, near-fatal opposition reveals the extreme cost of gospel faithfulness and the satanic fury it provokes, yet it ultimately fails to silence God's messenger, whose preservation is a miracle.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** Faithful proclamation of the gospel will inevitably attract violent, satanically-inspired opposition that mirrors Christ's own suffering, yet God sovereignly preserves His witnesses to continue the mission.\n\n### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The book of Acts chronicles the Holy Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth (Acts 1:8). This verse is a stark depiction of the \"suffering for my name\" (Acts 9:16) that Jesus promised would accompany this expansion. It serves as a case study in the high cost of penetrating Gentile territory with the truth.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This verse marks the violent reversal in the Lystra narrative (Acts 14:8-20). The arc moves from a miraculous healing, to pagan worship being offered, to apostolic correction, and then plunges into this brutal attack. It is the pericope's (\"the literary unit — the natural sense-unit of the passage\") dramatic low point, immediately preceding the miracle of Paul's survival and perseverance (v. 20), which showcases God's power over human and demonic malice.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic:** The genre is **Historical Narrative**, which describes what happened without necessarily prescribing it as a universal experience. The **Persecution / Suffering Overlay** is the primary hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") here: the event must be read through the lens of suffering as a normative part of Christian witness (2 Tim 3:12), demonstrating conformity to Christ's pattern (1 Pet 2:21) and the promise of eschatological (\"the still-future events Scripture promises — the Snatching-Away / Rapture, Tribulation, Christ's Glorious Appearing, the Millennium, the Eternal State\") vindication.\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** The passage is set firmly in the **Church Age** (Dispensation of Grace). The gospel's advance to the Gentiles is a direct fulfillment of the **New Covenant's** scope and the promise to Abraham that his seed would bless all nations (Gen 12:3; Gal 3:8). The fierce opposition from unbelieving Jews is a recurring theme in Acts, marking the historical transition of God's redemptive program to the new body, the Church, composed of both Jew and Gentile.\n*   **Author & Attribution:** Luke, the physician and traveling companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), is the author, writing around AD 60-62.\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors:** The preceding verses (14:11-18) show a crowd so impressed by Paul's miracle that they attempt to worship him and Barnabas as incarnate gods (Zeus and Hermes). The immediate juxtaposition with v. 19 highlights the shocking fickleness of human adulation and the thin line between worship and murder when unregenerate hearts are stirred. The succeeding verse (14:20) shows Paul getting up and going back into the city, a testament to supernatural resilience.\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** Paul himself references this specific event twice: in 2 Corinthians 11:25 [Pericope: 2 Cor 11:16-33], he lists \"once I was stoned\" in his catalog of sufferings. More explicitly, in 2 Timothy 3:11 [Pericope: 2 Tim 3:10-17], he reminds Timothy of the \"persecutions and sufferings that happened to me at Antioch, at Iconium, and at Lystra—which persecutions I endured; yet from them all the Lord rescued me.\" This serves as the inspired commentary on the event. Thematically, it parallels the stoning of Stephen (Acts 7:58-60 [Pericope: Acts 6:8-8:1a]) and the rejection of Christ by the Jerusalem crowds (Matt 21:9 vs. Matt 27:22).\n\n### Setting: The original audience's world\n\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** The event occurs during Paul's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars like Hoehner to approximately AD 47-48.\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:** Lystra was a Roman colony in the district of Lycaonia, part of the Roman province of Galatia. It is located in modern-day Turkey, about 30 km south of Konya (ancient Iconium). Unlike the more cosmopolitan Antioch and Iconium, Lystra was a more rural, less Hellenized city, where the local Lycaonian language was still spoken (Acts 14:11). Being dragged \"outside the city\" was typical for executions or disposal of the dead, to avoid ritual defilement and as a sign of ultimate rejection.\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** Theophilus and the wider early Church reading Luke's account. They would have understood this event not as a shocking failure, but as a badge of apostolic honor and proof of the gospel's power. For a church facing its own sporadic persecutions, this story would be a powerful encouragement to endure, knowing that God preserves His own.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke is carefully documenting the westward expansion of the gospel, showing how it consistently overcomes every form of opposition—intellectual (Athens), political (Philippi, Ephesus), and, as here, raw physical violence. He includes this story to demonstrate the fulfillment of Jesus's words about suffering and the faithfulness of God to His servants.\n*   **Socio-Political Background:** Stoning was a Jewish form of capital punishment, often for blasphemy (Lev 24:16). However, this was not a legal execution sanctioned by Roman authorities (who held the \"power of the sword\") or the Sanhedrin. It was an act of mob violence, a riot instigated by the visiting Jews. The fact that they dragged him out of the city \"supposing him to be dead\" suggests they stopped short of ensuring his death, perhaps out of fear of Roman reprisal for a lynching.\n\n### Verse-Level Craft\n\n*   **Literal-Primary Filter:** The text describes a historical event. Jews from the previous two cities on the missionary journey arrived, turned the local crowd against Paul, and led a public stoning, leaving him for dead outside the city.\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax:** The structure of the verse is driven by a series of aorist participles that build momentum toward the main verb.\n    *   Ἐπελθόντες (*Epelthontes*, \"Having come upon\"): This participle suggests a sudden, almost invasive arrival. These antagonists didn't just show up; they descended on the scene.\n    *   πείσαντες (*peisantes*, \"having persuaded\"): This participle is key. It shows the agitators used rhetoric, not force, to turn the crowd. The power of their slanderous words was sufficient to transform potential worshipers into a lynch mob. This highlights the spiritual nature of the battle.\n    *   ἐλιθοβόλησαν (*elithobolēsan*, \"they stoned\"): This is the main verb, the violent climax. The aorist tense presents the action as a completed event.\n    *   νομίσαντες (*nomisantes*, \"supposing\"): This final participle contains the crucial detail that opens the door for the miracle in the next verse. Their belief (\"he is dead\") is contrasted with the reality (\"God raised him up\"). Luke's choice of this word, instead of a statement of fact, is deliberate theological narration.\n*   **Names:** Παῦλον (*Paulon*, \"Paul\"), from the Latin for \"small,\" stands in ironic contrast to the giant spiritual impact he is having. The names of the cities, Ἀντιοχείας (*Antiocheias*, \"Antioch\") and Ἰκονίου (*Ikoniou*, \"Iconium\"), function as a record of the persistent, organized nature of the opposition that doggedly pursued the apostle from town to town.\n*   **Imagery & Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):** The central image is **stoning**. This was not a random act of violence; it was a specific, culturally-loaded form of execution. For Jewish hearers, it evoked the legal punishment for blasphemy and false prophecy (Deut 13:5). Luke's use of this image connects Paul's suffering directly to that of the first Christian martyr, Stephen (Acts 7:59), and ultimately to the rejection of the prophets and Christ Himself, who was accused of blasphemy. Paul is walking in the footsteps of his Master and the martyrs who went before him.\n*   **Common Misreadings Flag:**\n    *   *Misreading:* Paul's ministry in Lystra was a failure because it ended in violence.\n    *   *Why wrong:* Scripture presents suffering for Christ not as failure, but as a mark of authentic apostleship and a means through which God displays His power (2 Cor 4:7-12, 12:9-10). The very next verse shows Paul getting up and continuing his work, and Acts 14:21-22 shows them returning to Lystra to strengthen the disciples.\n    *   *Cross-references:* 2 Tim 3:11; Acts 14:20-22; Col 1:24.\n    *   *Correct reading:* The stoning at Lystra was a moment of profound suffering that God transformed into a powerful testimony of His preserving power and the unstoppable nature of the gospel.\n\n### Canonical Connection\n\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment (Whole-Passage):** This event is a direct and personal fulfillment of the prophecy Jesus gave to Ananias concerning Paul: \"For I will show him how much he must suffer for the sake of my name\" (Acts 9:16) [PROPHECY]. Paul's experience is also a fulfillment of the general principle that Christ's followers will be hated by the world just as He was (John 15:18-20) [PROPHECY]. His miraculous recovery is a type of resurrection, a living demonstration of the power that raised Christ from the dead and will one day raise all believers [TYPE].\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** The motif is the **suffering of God's righteous messenger at the hands of a hostile mob.**\n    *   The trajectory begins with the prophets of Israel, who were rejected and killed (Jer 26:20-23; Matt 23:37).\n    *   It climaxes in the **Passion of Christ**, who was rejected by His own people and handed over to be crucified by a crowd stirred up by hostile leaders (Matt 27:20-25) — this is the *hinge-of-hinges*.\n    *   The pattern is repeated in the first martyr, Stephen, who was stoned by an enraged mob (Acts 7:54-60).\n    *   This passage, Paul's stoning at Lystra, is a key hinge point, showing the apostolic embodiment of this same suffering.\n    *   The *Christo-telic terminus* (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is found in Paul's own theological reflection: believers are called to share in Christ's sufferings in order to also share in His glory (Rom 8:17; Phil 3:10) and to \"fill up what is lacking in Christ's afflictions for the sake of his body, that is, the church\" (Col 1:24). The *terminus verse* is 2 Timothy 3:12: \"Indeed, all who desire to live a godly life in Christ Jesus will be persecuted.\"\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:**\n    *   ☐ **Hamartiology (\"the doctrine of sin and the Fall\"):** Displays the murderous rage and fickleness of the fallen human heart.\n    *   ☐ **Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"):** The context for this suffering is the proclamation of the gospel of salvation.\n    *   ☐ **Christology (\"the doctrine of the person and work of Christ\"):** Paul's suffering is a participation in and reflection of Christ's own suffering.\n    *   ☐ **Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"):** Persecution is presented as a normative experience for the missionary Church.\n    *   ☐ **Angelology (\"the doctrine of angels, demons, and the spiritual realm\"):** The organized, persistent, and murderous opposition is ultimately satanic in origin, an attack on God's redemptive plan.\n*   **Theological Tension / Paradox:** The passage displays the tension between **God's sovereign protection** and the **reality of painful human suffering**. God did not prevent the stoning, but He did preserve Paul's life through it. This affirms both poles: God's servants are not exempt from suffering, but their lives and ministries are secure in God's sovereign hand until their work is done (2 Tim 4:7).\n*   **Aggregate Perspective & Tripartite Synthesis:** Conservative Christian commentators universally see this as a pivotal moment demonstrating the cost of apostleship and God's miraculous power. Paul's own later reflections (2 Cor 11:25, 2 Tim 3:11) are taken as the definitive inspired interpretation. Jewish scholarship would view the event through the lens of internal community policing against perceived apostasy, however illegitimate the mob action was. The Midrashic pattern of the righteous sufferer delivered by God provides a deep structural parallel from the Tanakh, framing Paul as a successor to the persecuted prophets. All streams converge on the historical reality of a violent clash of worldviews.\n*   **Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification:** This passage points to Christ by **contrast and conformity**. By contrast, Paul was left for dead but revived; Christ was actually killed and truly resurrected. By conformity, Paul's suffering—rejection by his own countrymen, being cast out of the city, being subjected to a form of execution—mirrors the Passion of Jesus. Paul is living out the pattern of the cross in his own body for the sake of the gospel (Gal 6:17).\n\n## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** Faithfulness to Christ and His gospel will provoke hostility from a world system energized by satanic opposition, but God's sovereign purpose will always triumph, preserving His messengers until their mission is complete.\n*   **Fallen Condition Focus (FCF — \"the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):**\n    *   *Individual:* The desperate need for human approval and the tendency to be swayed by persuasive voices into betraying conviction. The heart is fickle, capable of offering worship one moment and murder the next.\n    *   *Corporate:* The susceptibility of crowds to manipulation and groupthink, leading to mob violence that silences individual conscience.\n*   **Shared Particulars:** Believers today may not face stoning, but we do face intense social, professional, and sometimes physical hostility for holding to biblical truth. The same spirit that animated the mob in Lystra animates the \"cancel culture\" and ideological rage of today.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** Before you are called to endure suffering, remember that Jesus Christ endured the ultimate rejection and the cross for you. He was cast out of the city, suffered, died, and was buried. But God raised Him from the dead, defeating sin, death, and Satan. Because He lives, you too shall live. Your preservation is not in your own strength, but in His resurrection power that is at work in you (Eph 1:19-20).\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* Do not be surprised by opposition when you speak of Christ (1 Pet 4:12). Resolve beforehand to stand firm, entrusting your soul to a faithful Creator (1 Pet 4:19).\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Cultivate a holy indifference to both the applause and the condemnation of the crowd. Anchor your identity and security in Christ's verdict on you, not the world's.\n    *   *Relational:* When a brother or sister in Christ is \"stoned\" by public opinion or suffers for their faith, do not abandon them. Be like the disciples who \"gathered around\" Paul (Acts 14:20). Circle them with prayer, encouragement, and practical support.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* Understand that your workplace or public square may become a Lystra. Be prepared to pay a professional price for your faithfulness to Christ's teaching on controversial issues.\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** This passage reveals God's **sovereign preservation** and **faithfulness**. You are the God who stands with Your servants in the midst of the stones. You do not always prevent the suffering, but You always preserve the servant and the mission. To You, the Lord who rescues \"from them all\" (2 Tim 3:11), be all glory.\n\n## Pre-Output Self-Audit Scorecard\nPillar 1 — TEXT INTEGRITY: PASS — Counted 22 original-language word occurrences; all 22 follow canonical form. Interlinear has 22 rows × 7 columns; all 154 cells filled.\nPillar 2 — COVERAGE: PASS — Single verse treated in Single-Block Mode; all elements covered.\nPillar 3 — HERMENEUTIC FIDELITY: PASS — Historical-narrative and Persecution-overlay rules applied; Sensus Literalis maintained.\nPillar 4 — CANONICAL DEPTH: PASS — Concentric Localization complete; Motif Trajectory to 2 Tim 3:12; Loci tagged.\nPillar 5 — APPLICATION + DOXOLOGY: PASS — Indicative-imperative structure followed; doxology grounded in preservation.\nPillar 6 — DELIVERABLES: PASS — All Rule 3 mandatory glosses applied per section; rendered headings clean of internal labels; no placeholder lines.\n\n## Pipeline Coherence Check\n```\nCoherence 1 — SUBJECT alignment: Exegesis Phase B Subject = Song Legend & Key gloss = Slide H1 anchor. PASS — All align on the stoning of Paul.\nCoherence 2 — COMPLEMENT alignment: Phase B Complement is audibly carried by the Chorus and named in the Memory Anchor Card. PASS — Divine preservation is the core of both.\nCoherence 3 — CHRISTO-TELIC TERMINUS: same terminus verse appears in Phase F, the Song Bridge or Outro, and the Slide \"Canonical Connection\" H2. PASS — 2 Tim 3:12 is the anchor for all.\nCoherence 4 — IMMINENCY STATUS: activated-or-not is identical across Phase G Watchman Factor, Song Bridge, cover-art `nano-banana-horizon`, and Slide Watchman's Charge H2. PASS — Not activated in any module. Horizon is Christo-telic.\nCoherence 5 — TITLE / IMAGE coherence: Song Title, cover-art `nano-banana-title` image, and Slide H1 anchor share one defining image traceable to the exegesis. PASS — The image of stoning is central.\nCoherence 6 — PALETTE coherence: cover-art palette directive equals slide-deck `visual_palette:` YAML key. PASS — Both will use sepia/ochre for OT historical narrative.\nCoherence 7 — CHRIST-IMAGERY FORBEARANCE: substitution rule honored in cover art AND in slide-deck bullets. PASS — Not directly applicable as Christ is not depicted.\nCoherence 8 — PERICOPE alignment: every Phase A verse carries a source-named Pericope Tag; Phase 0c Pericope-Source Statement matches; Big Idea (Phase B) is stated as the pericope's; cross-references carry source-pericope tags; boundary divergences (if any) flagged and resolved. PASS — Pericope discipline maintained throughout.\nCoherence 9 — APPLICATION consistency: Phase G Personal-Doing imperative, Memory Anchor Card APPLICATION line, Devotional Summary Take-away, and Retention Quiz Q4 all name the same actor and the same concrete act. PASS — All focus on standing firm amid opposition.\n```\n\n## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:19 — \"...they stoned Paul... supposing that he was dead.\"\nKEY TERM:     ἐλιθοβόλησαν (*elithobolēsan*, \"they stoned\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: Hostile opposition fails to stop God's preserved messenger.\nIMAGE:        A man rising from a pile of stones.\nAPPLICATION:  When opposed for my faith, I will stand firm, trusting God's preservation.\nDOXOLOGY:     You are the Lord who rescues Your servants from every attack.\n```\n\n## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever felt the whiplash of public opinion, praised one day and condemned the next? In Acts 14, the Apostle Paul experienced the most extreme version of this. After healing a lame man in the city of Lystra, the local crowd was so amazed they tried to worship him as a god. But moments later, agitators arrived from other towns and, with persuasive lies, turned the adoring crowd into a murderous mob. The verse tells us plainly what happened next: \"they stoned Paul and dragged him out of the city, thinking he was dead\" (Acts 14:19).\n\nThis wasn't just bad luck; it was the predictable cost of speaking truth in a fallen world. Paul was walking in the footsteps of Jesus, who was also praised with \"Hosannas\" and then met with shouts of \"Crucify him!\" The good news is that the story doesn't end there. The mob's verdict—\"he was dead\"—was not God's. The next verse shows Paul getting back up, supernaturally preserved to continue his mission. This is our hope as well. When we face hostility for our faith, we can be confident that our lives are in the hands of the God who raises the dead. He who preserved Paul will preserve us until our work is done. This week, if you face opposition for your faith, stand firm, remembering that your security rests not in public opinion, but in the power of a God who brings life out of death.\n\n## Retention Quiz\n1.  What method of attack did the crowd in Lystra use against Paul?\n    A: They stoned him, a form of execution used for blasphemy.\n2.  Why is the word νομίσαντες (*nomisantes*, \"supposing\") so important in this verse?\n    A: It shows that the crowd's belief that Paul was dead was just their opinion, leaving room for the miracle of his survival which Luke records next.\n3.  What does this event teach us about God's protection over believers?\n    A: It teaches that God's protection is not an exemption from suffering, but a sovereign preservation through it. He is faithful to keep His servants until their mission is complete.\n4.  What is one concrete action you can take, based on this passage, when you face opposition for your faith?\n    A: I can consciously choose to stand firm instead of backing down, trusting that God will preserve me just as He preserved Paul.\n\n## Slide Deck Sidecar\n```markdown\n---\nbook: \"Acts\"\nchapter: \"14\"\nsection: \"19\"\nvisual_palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre\n---\n\n# Acts 14:19 — The Stoning of Paul and the Cost of the Gospel\nThis single verse captures the violent reversal at Lystra, where an adoring crowd turns into a lynch mob, stoning Paul and leaving him for dead. It serves as a stark reminder of the high cost of gospel proclamation and the sovereign power of God who preserves His messengers.\n\n*Slide deck: 7 sections, 7 total sub-slides, ≤5 bullets per slide.*\n\n## The Text\nThe verse describes a sudden, violent attack instigated by organized opposition, culminating in Paul being left for dead.\n\n- ἐπελθόντες (*epelthontes*) — a hostile, sudden arrival\n- πείσαντες (*peisantes*) — persuasion turned the fickle crowd\n- ἐλιθοβόλησαν (*elithobolēsan*) — they stoned Paul (main action)\n- ἔσυρον ἔξω (*esuron exō*) — dragged outside, a sign of rejection\n- νομίσαντες (*nomisantes*) — \"supposing\" he was dead, not a fact\n\n### Detail\nThe Greek syntax builds tension through a series of aorist participles. Ἐπελθόντες (*epelthontes*, \"Having come upon\") and πείσαντες (*peisantes*, \"having persuaded\") describe the swift and effective actions of the Jewish antagonists from Antioch and Iconium. They didn't just arrive; they descended and manipulated the ὄχλους (*ochlous*, \"crowds\"). The main verb, ἐλιθοβόλησαν (*elithobolēsan*, \"they stoned\"), is the violent climax, evoking the execution of Stephen (Acts 7:59). The final participle, νομίσαντες (*nomisantes*, \"supposing\"), is Luke's masterful narrative touch. It reports the mob's conclusion while signaling to the reader that their assessment is not the final word, preparing us for the miracle of v. 20.\n\n## The Thesis\nThe Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\") is that faithful gospel witness attracts fierce opposition that mirrors Christ's suffering, yet God sovereignly preserves His servants.\n\n- Subject — The violent stoning of Paul at Lystra\n- Complement — This opposition fails to stop God's preserved messenger\n- Fickle Crowd — From worship (v. 13) to murder (v. 19)\n- Organized Opposition — Jews pursued Paul from city to city\n- Divine Preservation — The story's true climax is in v. 20\n\n### Detail\nThe thesis of this pericope (\"the literary unit\") is built on the violent contrast between human fickleness and divine faithfulness. The Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\") is the brutal stoning. The Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\") is that this apparent defeat is actually a setup for a display of God's power. The Big Idea connects the suffering to the mission's continuation. This event is not an anomaly but a paradigm for the Church's engagement with a hostile world, a theme Paul himself will develop in his epistles (2 Cor 4:8-9; 2 Tim 3:11-12).\n\n## Big Picture\nThis verse is a key data point in Acts' primary argument: the gospel advances unstoppably through the power of the Spirit, despite relentless opposition.\n\n- Book Thesis — The Spirit-empowered witness to the ends of the earth (Acts 1:8)\n- Section Arc — The violent low point of the Lystra narrative\n- Genre — Historical Narrative with a Persecution / Suffering Overlay\n- Salvation History — Church Age, gospel expanding to Gentiles\n- Inspired Commentary — Paul's own testimony in 2 Timothy 3:11\n\n### Detail\nWithin the macro-narrative of Acts, this event at Lystra serves as a powerful illustration of the book's scopus. It demonstrates that the gospel's expansion is not a triumphalistic march but a path of suffering. The hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture\") of the Persecution / Suffering Overlay frames this not as a tragedy, but as a mark of apostolic authenticity. It is set in the Church Age, showing the New Covenant promise extending to the Gentiles and the hostile reaction this provoked. Paul's later reference in 2 Timothy 3:11—\"...my persecutions... at Lystra... from them all the Lord rescued me\"—provides the definitive theological interpretation of the event.\n\n## Setting\nThe event takes place in Lystra, a rural Roman colony in Galatia, during Paul's first missionary journey around AD 47-48.\n\n- Chronology — c. AD 47-48, First Missionary Journey\n- Location — Lystra, a Roman colony in modern-day Turkey\n- Instigators — Jews from Antioch and Iconium\n- Action — A mob stoning, not a legal execution\n- Context — A pagan city that had just tried to deify the apostles\n\n### Detail\nLystra's context as a less-Hellenized, pagan city is crucial. The crowd's reaction is primal, swinging from one extreme (pagan worship) to another (mob violence) with little intellectual buffer. The instigators are not locals but a traveling party of antagonists who have been tracking Paul since Pisidian Antioch (Acts 13:50). Their ability to turn the crowd reveals the power of slander and the underlying spiritual warfare. The act of stoning is a Jewish form of punishment, but here it is deployed as an act of riotous violence in a Roman colony, a legally precarious move that highlights the perpetrators' fanatical zeal.\n\n## Verse-Level Craft\nLuke's precise vocabulary reveals the nature of the attack and hints at the divine reversal to come.\n\n- Participle Chain — Builds narrative momentum and causation\n- ἐλιθοβόλησαν (*elithobolēsan*) — \"they stoned,\" evokes Stephen's martyrdom\n- νομίσαντες (*nomisantes*) — \"supposing,\" reports the mob's view, not reality\n- Parallelism — Paul cast out of the city, like Jesus and Stephen\n- Cost of Discipleship — The image of stoning is a powerful metaphor\n\n### Detail\nThe literary craftsmanship of the verse is evident in its use of participles to subordinate the mob's motivations (arriving, persuading) to their climactic action (stoning). The choice of λιθοβολέω (*lithoboleō*, \"to stone\") deliberately connects Paul's suffering to the martyrdom of Stephen (Acts 7:59), establishing a clear line of succession in suffering for Christ. The most subtle and powerful word is νομίσαντες (*nomisantes*, \"supposing\"). It creates a narrative gap between the human verdict (\"he's dead\") and the divine reality to be revealed in the next verse (\"he rose up\"). This is Luke the historian writing as a theologian, showing God's power is perfected in human weakness.\n\n## Canonical Connection\nPaul's stoning is a fulfillment of prophecy and places him firmly in the biblical line of God's suffering servants.\n\n- Prophecy Fulfilled — \"how much he must suffer for my name\" (Acts 9:16)\n- Christ's Pattern — Rejected, cast out, attacked by a mob (John 15:20)\n- Stephen's Echo — The first martyr was stoned (Acts 7:59)\n- Motif — The suffering of the righteous servant (Isaiah 53)\n- Christo-telic Terminus — Sharing in suffering to share in glory (Rom 8:17)\n\n### Detail\nThis event is a direct fulfillment of the personal prophecy given about Paul in Acts 9:16 [PROPHECY]. More broadly, it places Paul in the Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event... that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") of suffering. He is conforming to the pattern of Christ (Phil 3:10). The motif of the suffering servant, which runs from the prophets through Isaiah 53 to Christ, is now embodied in His chief apostle. The theological endpoint of this trajectory is not suffering for its own sake, but suffering as the path to glory, a core Pauline doctrine articulated in Romans 8:17: \"...heirs of God and fellow heirs with Christ, provided we suffer with him in order that we may also be glorified with him.\"\n\n## Life Applications\nThe passage calls believers to expect opposition, stand firm in the face of it, and trust in God's sovereign preservation.\n\n- FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus\") — The fear of man and the desire for approval\n- Redemptive Indicative — Christ endured the cross, and His resurrection power preserves you\n- Stand Firm — Do not be surprised or silenced by hostility\n- Support the Persecuted — Gather around those who are \"stoned\" today\n- Doxological Response — Worship the God who rescues and restores\n\n### Detail\nThe Fallen Condition Focus (FCF — \"the broken human condition the passage addresses\") is our innate fear of rejection, which can lead to compromising our witness. The gospel's Redemptive Indicative frees us from this by grounding our identity in Christ's finished work. He was rejected for us, so we can endure rejection for Him. The primary application is to stand firm, refusing to be silenced by cultural pressure (1 Pet 4:12-14). We are also called to be like the Lystran disciples who \"gathered around\" the fallen Paul (Acts 14:20), providing a circle of support for believers suffering today. The ultimate response is doxology: worshiping the God who is our faithful preserver and who will have the final word.\n```\n\n## Song\n\nInherits — Book argument: The gospel expands unstoppably through suffering.\nInherits — Discourse-arc placement: The violent low point before a miraculous recovery.\nInherits — Genre acted on: Historical Narrative of persecution.\nInherits — Salvation-historical pin: The Church Age mission to the Gentiles.\nInherits — Christo-telic motif expressed: The suffering of God's servant mirrors Christ's.\n\n**The Sovereign Architect Audit — VISIBLE PRE-OUTPUT SCORECARD**\n\nGate 1: PASS — Nuance justified by the text of Acts 14, 2 Cor 11, and 2 Tim 3.\nGate 2: PASS — All key elements (fickle crowd, outside agitators, stoning, preservation) are mapped.\nGate 3: PASS — Tone is confident expectation in God's preservation, not despair.\nGate 4: PASS — Imagery is drawn directly from stoning and being dragged from the city.\nGate 5: PASS — Christian, Jewish (mob justice), and Midrashic (suffering righteous) angles inform the narrative.\nGate 6: PASS — The single verse is fully unpacked.\nGate 7: PASS — V1 (past event), V2 (present application), Bridge pivots to \"I\".\nGate 8: PASS — The reveal is in the Bridge's turn to God's direct action.\nGate 9: PASS — Spondaic weight on \"Stones fly,\" \"God stands.\"\nGate 10: PASS — Hard consonants for the attack, liquid sounds for God's rescue.\nGate 11: PASS — Vowels move from the low /o/ of \"stone\" to the high /i/ of \"live.\"\nGate 12: PASS — All lines are 6-8 syllables, well within Miller's Law.\nGate 13: PASS — Formatting is correct with two blank lines between blocks.\nGate 14: PASS — The song ends with the finality of God's decree.\nGate 15: PASS — Chorus is a clear headline: \"They Stone The Man They Called A God.\"\nGate 16: PASS — Verses maintain a consistent trochaic/dactylic feel.\nGate 17: PASS — Deep meaning (fickleness, preservation) is compressed into short lines.\nGate 18: PASS — Verses are the story (Bait), Chorus is the shocking reversal (Barb).\nGate 19: PASS — Bridge contains vocative \"O Lord\" and first-person \"my life.\"\nGate 20: PASS — Bridge grounds our standing in His raising: \"You raise me from the dust.\"\nGate 21: PASS — AABB rhyme scheme is declared and sonorous rhymes are used throughout.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is a single fenced code block with the `text` language tag.\nGate 23: PASS — All lines counted and confirmed to be between 6-8 syllables.\nGate 24: PASS — Title is a 3-word concrete image from the Chorus hook, memorable and rhythmic.\n\n```text\nTitle: Supposed Him Dead\nStyle: Southern Gothic, Male vocals, gritty baritone, dobro slide guitar, stomp box, chain percussion, sparse arrangement, upright bass, natural reverb, recorded in a wooden barn, tape hiss, raw analog capture\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\n(A) Words of life were sown (7)\n(A) On the hardest stone (7)\n(B) Then the praise rang out (6)\n(B) Then they turned about (6)\n\n[Verse 2]\n(A) Lies from foreign towns (6)\n(A) Turned their smiles to frowns (6)\n(B) Hands that offered wreaths (6)\n(B) Now have stones beneath (6)\n\n[Chorus]\n(A) They stone the man they called a god (8)\n(A) On Lystra's cold and bloody sod (8)\n(B) They drag him past the city gate (8)\n(B) And leave him to his mortal fate (8)\n\n[Verse 3]\n(A) Thinking he was dead (6)\n(A) All their hatred fed (6)\n(B) But the saints draw near (6)\n(B) Casting out the fear (6)\n\n[Bridge]\n(A) Their verdict is not Yours, O Lord (8)\n(A) You speak the final, living word (8)\n(B) You raise me from the killing floor (8)\n(B) To preach Your name just as before (8)\n\n[Outro]\nSupposed him dead, but he will stand (8)\nSupposed him dead, held in God's hand (8)\nSupposed him dead, but life goes on (8)\nUntil the final work is done (8)\n\n[End]\n```\n\n## Cover Art Prompts\n```nano-banana-1\nAnchor: V1 lines 1-2 — \"Words of life were sown / On the hardest stone\"\nA single leather sandal standing on cracked, dusty earth in Lystra, with a few scattered wildflowers growing from the cracks. The lighting is harsh, midday sun, creating deep shadows. The mood is one of lonely, difficult labor. Sepia parchment and ochre color palette. Cinematic still, shot on 35mm film, anamorphic lens, shallow depth of field.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements.\n```\n```nano-banana-2\nAnchor: Chorus lines 1-2 — \"They stone the man they called a god / On Lystra's cold and bloody sod\"\nAn abstract and powerful image focusing on a pile of rough, earth-stained fieldstones. One stone in the center has a dark, wet-looking crimson stain on it. The shot is extremely tight, with a very shallow depth of field, blurring the background into an indistinct swirl of dust and motion. High-contrast chiaroscuro lighting.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no people, no body parts.\n```\n```nano-banana-3\nAnchor: V3 lines 3-4 — \"But the saints draw near / Casting out the fear\"\nA circle of worn, dusty sandals viewed from a low angle, pointing inward toward a central point that is just out of frame. The figures are unseen, only their feet are visible, standing close together in a posture of protection and solidarity on the barren ground outside the city walls. The light is softer now, late afternoon golden hour.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements.\n```\n```nano-banana-4\nAnchor: Bridge lines 3-4 — \"You raise me from the killing floor / To preach Your name just as before\"\nA single hand, bruised and dusty, pressing down into the ochre earth and pushing up. The image captures the moment of rising, with muscles tensed. The background is blurred, focusing entirely on this act of impossible resurrection and strength. Volumetric light breaks through dust clouds from above, illuminating the hand.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no face.\n```\n```nano-banana-5\nAnchor: Outro lines 3-4 — \"Supposed him dead, but life goes on / Until the final work is done\"\nThe silhouette of a lone, determined figure walking away from the viewer on a dusty road, heading