      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:8-20 · source: NA28]\n[Persecution / Suffering Overlay]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\n\nἘπελθόντες δὲ ἀπὸ Ἀντιοχείας καὶ Ἰκονίου Ἰουδαῖοι καὶ πείσαντες τοὺς ὄχλους ἐλιθοβόλησαν τὸν Παῦλον καὶ ἔσυρον ἔξω τῆς πόλεως, νομίσαντες αὐτὸν τεθνηκέναι.\n\n**Interlinear Table**\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 17 rows = 119 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Ἐπελθόντες | Epelthontes | G1904 | ἐπέρχομαι | V-AAP-NPM | Having come upon / arrived |\n| 2 | δὲ | de | G1161 | δέ | Conj | but / and |\n| 3 | ἀπὸ | apo | G575 | ἀπό | Prep | from |\n| 4 | Ἀντιοχείας | Antiocheias | G490 | Ἀντιόχεια | N-GSF | Antioch |\n| 5 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 6 | Ἰκονίου | Ikoniou | G2430 | Ἰκόνιον | N-GSN | Iconium |\n| 7 | Ἰουδαῖοι | Ioudaioi | G2453 | Ἰουδαῖος | A-NPM | Jews |\n| 8 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 9 | πείσαντες | peisantes | G3982 | πείθω | V-AAP-NPM | having persuaded |\n| 10 | τοὺς | tous | G3588 | ὁ | T-APM | the |\n| 11 | ὄχλους | ochlous | G3793 | ὄχλος | N-APM | crowds |\n| 12 | ἐλιθοβόλησαν | elithobolēsan | G3034 | λιθοβολέω | V-AAI-3P | they stoned |\n| 13 | τὸν | ton | G3588 | ὁ | T-ASM | the |\n| 14 | Παῦλον | Paulon | G3972 | Παῦλος | N-ASM | Paul |\n| 15 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 16 | ἔσυρον | esuron | G4951 | σύρω | V-IAI-3P | they were dragging |\n| 17 | ἔξω | exō | G1854 | ἔξω | Adv | outside |\n| 18 | τῆς | tēs | G3588 | ὁ | T-GSF | the |\n| 19 | πόλεως | poleōs | G4172 | πόλις | N-GSF | city |\n| 20 | νομίσαντες | nomisantes | G3543 | νομίζω | V-AAP-NPM | supposing / thinking |\n| 21 | αὐτὸν | auton | G846 | αὐτός | P-ASM | him |\n| 22 | τεθνηκέναι | tethnēkenai | G2348 | θνῄσκω | V-RNA | to be dead |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\n\nBut having come upon [them] from Antioch and Iconium, Jews, and having persuaded the crowds, they stoned Paul and were dragging [him] outside the city, supposing him to be dead.\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\n\nBut Jews came from Antioch and Iconium, and after winning over the crowds, they stoned Paul and dragged him out of the city, thinking he was dead.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\n\nBut then, Jews arrived from [as far as] Antioch and Iconium [bringing their coordinated opposition with them]. After persuading the [very same] crowds [that had just tried to worship him], they stoned Paul. Then they began dragging his [limp body] outside the city gates, supposing [with confidence] that he was dead.\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:8-20 · source: NA28]\n[Persecution / Suffering Overlay]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Script (NA28)</strong></p>\n<p>Ἐπελθόντες δὲ ἀπὸ Ἀντιοχείας καὶ Ἰκονίου Ἰουδαῖοι καὶ πείσαντες τοὺς ὄχλους ἐλιθοβόλησαν τὸν Παῦλον καὶ ἔσυρον ἔξω τῆς πόλεως, νομίσαντες αὐτὸν τεθνηκέναι.</p>\n<p><strong>Interlinear Table</strong></p>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 17 rows = 119 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>Ἐπελθόντες</td>\n<td>Epelthontes</td>\n<td>G1904</td>\n<td>ἐπέρχομαι</td>\n<td>V-AAP-NPM</td>\n<td>Having come upon / arrived</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>δὲ</td>\n<td>de</td>\n<td>G1161</td>\n<td>δέ</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>but / and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>ἀπὸ</td>\n<td>apo</td>\n<td>G575</td>\n<td>ἀπό</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>from</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Ἀντιοχείας</td>\n<td>Antiocheias</td>\n<td>G490</td>\n<td>Ἀντιόχεια</td>\n<td>N-GSF</td>\n<td>Antioch</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>Ἰκονίου</td>\n<td>Ikoniou</td>\n<td>G2430</td>\n<td>Ἰκόνιον</td>\n<td>N-GSN</td>\n<td>Iconium</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>Ἰουδαῖοι</td>\n<td>Ioudaioi</td>\n<td>G2453</td>\n<td>Ἰουδαῖος</td>\n<td>A-NPM</td>\n<td>Jews</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>πείσαντες</td>\n<td>peisantes</td>\n<td>G3982</td>\n<td>πείθω</td>\n<td>V-AAP-NPM</td>\n<td>having persuaded</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>τοὺς</td>\n<td>tous</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-APM</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>ὄχλους</td>\n<td>ochlous</td>\n<td>G3793</td>\n<td>ὄχλος</td>\n<td>N-APM</td>\n<td>crowds</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>ἐλιθοβόλησαν</td>\n<td>elithobolēsan</td>\n<td>G3034</td>\n<td>λιθοβολέω</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3P</td>\n<td>they stoned</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>τὸν</td>\n<td>ton</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-ASM</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>14</td>\n<td>Παῦλον</td>\n<td>Paulon</td>\n<td>G3972</td>\n<td>Παῦλος</td>\n<td>N-ASM</td>\n<td>Paul</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>16</td>\n<td>ἔσυρον</td>\n<td>esuron</td>\n<td>G4951</td>\n<td>σύρω</td>\n<td>V-IAI-3P</td>\n<td>they were dragging</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>17</td>\n<td>ἔξω</td>\n<td>exō</td>\n<td>G1854</td>\n<td>ἔξω</td>\n<td>Adv</td>\n<td>outside</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>18</td>\n<td>τῆς</td>\n<td>tēs</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-GSF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>19</td>\n<td>πόλεως</td>\n<td>poleōs</td>\n<td>G4172</td>\n<td>πόλις</td>\n<td>N-GSF</td>\n<td>city</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>20</td>\n<td>νομίσαντες</td>\n<td>nomisantes</td>\n<td>G3543</td>\n<td>νομίζω</td>\n<td>V-AAP-NPM</td>\n<td>supposing / thinking</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>21</td>\n<td>αὐτὸν</td>\n<td>auton</td>\n<td>G846</td>\n<td>αὐτός</td>\n<td>P-ASM</td>\n<td>him</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>22</td>\n<td>τεθνηκέναι</td>\n<td>tethnēkenai</td>\n<td>G2348</td>\n<td>θνῄσκω</td>\n<td>V-RNA</td>\n<td>to be dead</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)</strong></p>\n<p>But having come upon [them] from Antioch and Iconium, Jews, and having persuaded the crowds, they stoned Paul and were dragging [him] outside the city, supposing him to be dead.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)</strong></p>\n<p>But Jews came from Antioch and Iconium, and after winning over the crowds, they stoned Paul and dragged him out of the city, thinking he was dead.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)</strong></p>\n<p>But then, Jews arrived from [as far as] Antioch and Iconium [bringing their coordinated opposition with them]. After persuading the [very same] crowds [that had just tried to worship him], they stoned Paul. Then they began dragging his [limp body] outside the city gates, supposing [with confidence] that he was dead.</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** Faithfulness to Christ and His gospel will provoke hostility from a world system energized by satanic opposition, but God's sovereign purpose will always triumph, preserving His messengers until their mission is complete.\n*   **Fallen Condition Focus (FCF — \"the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):**\n    *   *Individual:* The desperate need for human approval and the tendency to be swayed by persuasive voices into betraying conviction. The heart is fickle, capable of offering worship one moment and murder the next.\n    *   *Corporate:* The susceptibility of crowds to manipulation and groupthink, leading to mob violence that silences individual conscience.\n*   **Shared Particulars:** Believers today may not face stoning, but we do face intense social, professional, and sometimes physical hostility for holding to biblical truth. The same spirit that animated the mob in Lystra animates the \"cancel culture\" and ideological rage of today.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** Before you are called to endure suffering, remember that Jesus Christ endured the ultimate rejection and the cross for you. He was cast out of the city, suffered, died, and was buried. But God raised Him from the dead, defeating sin, death, and Satan. Because He lives, you too shall live. Your preservation is not in your own strength, but in His resurrection power that is at work in you (Eph 1:19-20).\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* Do not be surprised by opposition when you speak of Christ (1 Pet 4:12). Resolve beforehand to stand firm, entrusting your soul to a faithful Creator (1 Pet 4:19).\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Cultivate a holy indifference to both the applause and the condemnation of the crowd. Anchor your identity and security in Christ's verdict on you, not the world's.\n    *   *Relational:* When a brother or sister in Christ is \"stoned\" by public opinion or suffers for their faith, do not abandon them. Be like the disciples who \"gathered around\" Paul (Acts 14:20). Circle them with prayer, encouragement, and practical support.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* Understand that your workplace or public square may become a Lystra. Be prepared to pay a professional price for your faithfulness to Christ's teaching on controversial issues.\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** This passage reveals God's **sovereign preservation** and **faithfulness**. You are the God who stands with Your servants in the midst of the stones. You do not always prevent the suffering, but You always preserve the servant and the mission. To You, the Lord who rescues \"from them all\" (2 Tim 3:11), be all glory.\n",
