l — \"Being\":</em> Cultivate a holy indifference to both the applause and the condemnation of the crowd. Anchor your identity and security in Christ's verdict on you, not the world's.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> When a brother or sister in Christ is \"stoned\" by public opinion or suffers for their faith, do not abandon them. Be like the disciples who \"gathered around\" Paul (Acts 14:20). Circle them with prayer, encouragement, and practical support.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> Understand that your workplace or public square may become a Lystra. Be prepared to pay a professional price for your faithfulness to Christ's teaching on controversial issues.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong> This passage reveals God's <strong>sovereign preservation</strong> and <strong>faithfulness</strong>. You are the God who stands with Your servants in the midst of the stones. You do not always prevent the suffering, but You always preserve the servant and the mission. To You, the Lord who rescues \"from them all\" (2 Tim 3:11), be all glory.</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:19 — \"...they stoned Paul... supposing that he was dead.\"\nKEY TERM:     ἐλιθοβόλησαν (*elithobolēsan*, \"they stoned\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: Hostile opposition fails to stop God's preserved messenger.\nIMAGE:        A man rising from a pile of stones.\nAPPLICATION:  When opposed for my faith, I will stand firm, trusting God's preservation.\nDOXOLOGY:     You are the Lord who rescues Your servants from every attack.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:19 — &quot;...they stoned Paul... supposing that he was dead.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>ἐλιθοβόλησαν (*elithobolēsan*, &quot;they stoned&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>Hostile opposition fails to stop God&#x27;s preserved messenger.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>A man rising from a pile of stones.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>When opposed for my faith, I will stand firm, trusting God&#x27;s preservation.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>You are the Lord who rescues Your servants from every attack.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever felt the whiplash of public opinion, praised one day and condemned the next? In Acts 14, the Apostle Paul experienced the most extreme version of this. After healing a lame man in the city of Lystra, the local crowd was so amazed they tried to worship him as a god. But moments later, agitators arrived from other towns and, with persuasive lies, turned the adoring crowd into a murderous mob. The verse tells us plainly what happened next: \"they stoned Paul and dragged him out of the city, thinking he was dead\" (Acts 14:19).\n\nThis wasn't just bad luck; it was the predictable cost of speaking truth in a fallen world. Paul was walking in the footsteps of Jesus, who was also praised with \"Hosannas\" and then met with shouts of \"Crucify him!\" The good news is that the story doesn't end there. The mob's verdict—\"he was dead\"—was not God's. The next verse shows Paul getting back up, supernaturally preserved to continue his mission. This is our hope as well. When we face hostility for our faith, we can be confident that our lives are in the hands of the God who raises the dead. He who preserved Paul will preserve us until our work is done. This week, if you face opposition for your faith, stand firm, remembering that your security rests not in public opinion, but in the power of a God who brings life out of death.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever felt the whiplash of public opinion, praised one day and condemned the next? In Acts 14, the Apostle Paul experienced the most extreme version of this. After healing a lame man in the city of Lystra, the local crowd was so amazed they tried to worship him as a god. But moments later, agitators arrived from other towns and, with persuasive lies, turned the adoring crowd into a murderous mob. The verse tells us plainly what happened next: \"they stoned Paul and dragged him out of the city, thinking he was dead\" (Acts 14:19).</p>\n<p>This wasn't just bad luck; it was the predictable cost of speaking truth in a fallen world. Paul was walking in the footsteps of Jesus, who was also praised with \"Hosannas\" and then met with shouts of \"Crucify him!\" The good news is that the story doesn't end there. The mob's verdict—\"he was dead\"—was not God's. The next verse shows Paul getting back up, supernaturally preserved to continue his mission. This is our hope as well. When we face hostility for our faith, we can be confident that our lives are in the hands of the God who raises the dead. He who preserved Paul will preserve us until our work is done. This week, if you face opposition for your faith, stand firm, remembering that your security rests not in public opinion, but in the power of a God who brings life out of death.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  What method of attack did the crowd in Lystra use against Paul?\n    A: They stoned him, a form of execution used for blasphemy.\n2.  Why is the word νομίσαντες (*nomisantes*, \"supposing\") so important in this verse?\n    A: It shows that the crowd's belief that Paul was dead was just their opinion, leaving room for the miracle of his survival which Luke records next.\n3.  What does this event teach us about God's protection over believers?\n    A: It teaches that God's protection is not an exemption from suffering, but a sovereign preservation through it. He is faithful to keep His servants until their mission is complete.\n4.  What is one concrete action you can take, based on this passage, when you face opposition for your faith?\n    A: I can consciously choose to stand firm instead of backing down, trusting that God will preserve me just as He preserved Paul.\n",
