from the Tanakh, framing Paul as a successor to the persecuted prophets. All streams converge on the historical reality of a violent clash of worldviews.</li>\n<li><strong>Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification:</strong> This passage points to Christ by <strong>contrast and conformity</strong>. By contrast, Paul was left for dead but revived; Christ was actually killed and truly resurrected. By conformity, Paul's suffering—rejection by his own countrymen, being cast out of the city, being subjected to a form of execution—mirrors the Passion of Jesus. Paul is living out the pattern of the cross in his own body for the sake of the gospel (Gal 6:17).</li>\n</ul>",
