      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:8-20 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\nκυκλωσάντων δὲ τῶν μαθητῶν αὐτὸν ἀναστὰς εἰσῆλθεν εἰς τὴν πόλιν, καὶ τῇ ἐπαύριον ἐξῆλθεν σὺν τῷ Βαρναβᾷ εἰς Δέρβην.\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 12 rows = 84 cells.*\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | κυκλωσάντων | kyklōsantōn | G2944 | κυκλόω | V-AAP-GPM | when...had encircled / gathered around |\n| 2 | δὲ | de | G1161 | δέ | Conj | but / and |\n| 3 | τῶν | tōn | G3588 | ὁ | T-GPM | the |\n| 4 | μαθητῶν | mathētōn | G3101 | μαθητής | N-GPM | disciples |\n| 5 | αὐτὸν | auton | G846 | αὐτός | P-ASM | him |\n| 6 | ἀναστὰς | anastas | G450 | ἀνίστημι | V-AAP-NSM | having risen up |\n| 7 | εἰσῆλθεν | eisēlthen | G1525 | εἰσέρχομαι | V-AAI-3S | he entered |\n| 8 | εἰς | eis | G1519 | εἰς | Prep | into |\n| 9 | τὴν | tēn | G3588 | ὁ | T-ASF | the |\n| 10 | πόλιν | polin | G4172 | πόλις | N-ASF | city |\n| 11 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 12 | τῇ ἐπαύριον | tē epaurion | G1887 | ἐπαύριον | Adv | on the next day |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation**\nBut when the disciples had encircled him, having risen up, he entered into the city; and on the next day, he went out with Barnabas to Derbe.\n\n**Standalone English Translation**\nBut when the disciples gathered around him, he got up and went back into the city. The next day he and Barnabas left for Derbe.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation**\nBut just when he was presumed dead, the disciples gathered around him [in a protective, prayerful circle], and he rose up [a living echo of the resurrection] and entered back into the very city that had just stoned him. Then, on the very next day, he departed with Barnabas to continue the mission, on to Derbe.\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:8-20 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Script (NA28)</strong>\nκυκλωσάντων δὲ τῶν μαθητῶν αὐτὸν ἀναστὰς εἰσῆλθεν εἰς τὴν πόλιν, καὶ τῇ ἐπαύριον ἐξῆλθεν σὺν τῷ Βαρναβᾷ εἰς Δέρβην.</p>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 12 rows = 84 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>κυκλωσάντων</td>\n<td>kyklōsantōn</td>\n<td>G2944</td>\n<td>κυκλόω</td>\n<td>V-AAP-GPM</td>\n<td>when...had encircled / gathered around</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>δὲ</td>\n<td>de</td>\n<td>G1161</td>\n<td>δέ</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>but / and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>τῶν</td>\n<td>tōn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-GPM</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>μαθητῶν</td>\n<td>mathētōn</td>\n<td>G3101</td>\n<td>μαθητής</td>\n<td>N-GPM</td>\n<td>disciples</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>αὐτὸν</td>\n<td>auton</td>\n<td>G846</td>\n<td>αὐτός</td>\n<td>P-ASM</td>\n<td>him</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>ἀναστὰς</td>\n<td>anastas</td>\n<td>G450</td>\n<td>ἀνίστημι</td>\n<td>V-AAP-NSM</td>\n<td>having risen up</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>εἰσῆλθεν</td>\n<td>eisēlthen</td>\n<td>G1525</td>\n<td>εἰσέρχομαι</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3S</td>\n<td>he entered</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>eis</td>\n<td>G1519</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>into</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>τὴν</td>\n<td>tēn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-ASF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>πόλιν</td>\n<td>polin</td>\n<td>G4172</td>\n<td>πόλις</td>\n<td>N-ASF</td>\n<td>city</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>τῇ ἐπαύριον</td>\n<td>tē epaurion</td>\n<td>G1887</td>\n<td>ἐπαύριον</td>\n<td>Adv</td>\n<td>on the next day</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation</strong>\nBut when the disciples had encircled him, having risen up, he entered into the city; and on the next day, he went out with Barnabas to Derbe.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation</strong>\nBut when the disciples gathered around him, he got up and went back into the city. The next day he and Barnabas left for Derbe.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation</strong>\nBut just when he was presumed dead, the disciples gathered around him [in a protective, prayerful circle], and he rose up [a living echo of the resurrection] and entered back into the very city that had just stoned him. Then, on the very next day, he departed with Barnabas to continue the mission, on to Derbe.</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\")**: God's power is most profoundly displayed not in preventing suffering, but in raising His people up through it to continue their kingdom assignment with supernatural courage and resolve.\n\n*   **Fallen Condition Focus (FCF)**: This passage addresses the human tendency to equate apparent defeat with actual defeat. It confronts our fear of suffering, which tempts us to retreat from our mission, and our despair when opposition seems to have won the day.\n    *   *Individual*: The temptation to quit when ministry is painful or fruitless.\n    *   *Corporate*: The temptation for a church to become timid and inward-focused when facing external hostility.\n\n*   **Shared Particulars**: Like the disciples at Lystra, we are called to stand with and support those who are suffering for the faith. Like Paul, we are called to get back up after being knocked down, not in our own strength, but in the power that raised Jesus from the dead.\n\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding)**: Before you are told to be courageous, remember that the same power that raised Christ from the dead and stood Paul up from the dust of Lystra now lives in you (Eph 1:19-20). Your endurance is not a product of your willpower but a fruit of His indwelling life.\n\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace)**:\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\"*: When you are knocked down by opposition, disappointment, or failure in your walk with God, get back up. Re-engage with your mission, even if it means going back into the \"city\" that hurt you.\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\"*: Cultivate a theology of the cross that expects suffering as a normal part of the Christian life and sees it as a platform for God to display His power (2 Cor 4:7).\n    *   *Relational*: When a brother or sister in your church is \"stoned\" by life—through persecution, grief, or trial—don't run away. Encircle them with your presence, prayers, and practical support. Be the faithful community that creates the context for their rising.\n    *   *Public / Vocational*: Do not be intimidated into silence by a hostile culture. The gospel's advance has always been marked by opposition. Your courageous, non-retaliatory presence in your workplace or community is a witness to the resurrection.\n\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\")**:\n    *   **Attribute(s) of God surfaced**: The faithfulness of God to His servants and the resurrection power of God that triumphs over violence and death.\n    *   **One-sentence doxology**: O Lord, you are the God who raises the dead, who stands your servants on their feet when the world has left them for dust, and whose mission cannot be stopped by the stones of men.\n    *   **Liturgical / hymnological resonance**: This passage resonates with the victory-in-suffering cadence of hymns that celebrate the power of the cross and the endurance of the saints.\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\")</strong>: God's power is most profoundly displayed not in preventing suffering, but in raising His people up through it to continue their kingdom assignment with supernatural courage and resolve.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Fallen Condition Focus (FCF)</strong>: This passage addresses the human tendency to equate apparent defeat with actual defeat. It confronts our fear of suffering, which tempts us to retreat from our mission, and our despair when opposition seems to have won the day.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Individual</em>: The temptation to quit when ministry is painful or fruitless.</li>\n<li><em>Corporate</em>: The temptation for a church to become timid and inward-focused when facing external hostility.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Shared Particulars</strong>: Like the disciples at Lystra, we are called to stand with and support those who are suffering for the faith. Like Paul, we are called to get back up after being knocked down, not in our own strength, but in the power that raised Jesus from the dead.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding)</strong>: Before you are told to be courageous, remember that the same power that raised Christ from the dead and stood Paul up from the dust of Lystra now lives in you (Eph 1:19-20). Your endurance is not a product of your willpower but a fruit of His indwelling life.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace)</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\"</em>: When you are knocked down by opposition, disappointment, or failure in your walk with God, get back up. Re-engage with your mission, even if it means going back into the \"city\" that hurt you.</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\"</em>: Cultivate a theology of the cross that expects suffering as a normal part of the Christian life and sees it as a platform for God to display His power (2 Cor 4:7).</li>\n<li><em>Relational</em>: When a brother or sister in your church is \"stoned\" by life—through persecution, grief, or trial—don't run away. Encircle them with your presence, prayers, and practical support. Be the faithful community that creates the context for their rising.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational</em>: Do not be intimidated into silence by a hostile culture. The gospel's advance has always been marked by opposition. Your courageous, non-retaliatory presence in your workplace or community is a witness to the resurrection.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\")</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Attribute(s) of God surfaced</strong>: The faithfulness of God to His servants and the resurrection power of God that triumphs over violence and death.</li>\n<li><strong>One-sentence doxology</strong>: O Lord, you are the God who raises the dead, who stands your servants on their feet when the world has left them for dust, and whose mission cannot be stopped by the stones of men.</li>\n<li><strong>Liturgical / hymnological resonance</strong>: This passage resonates with the victory-in-suffering cadence of hymns that celebrate the power of the cross and the endurance of the saints.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:20 — \"having risen up, he entered into the city\"\nKEY TERM:     ἀναστάς (anastas, \"having risen up\" — an echo of resurrection)\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: A lethal attack becomes a platform for God's resurrection power.\nIMAGE:        A lone man rising from the dust, surrounded by a faithful few.\nAPPLICATION:  For the church: when a believer falls, encircle them in faith.\nDOXOLOGY:     Praise to You, the God who raises us from the dust of our defeat.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:20 — &quot;having risen up, he entered into the city&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>ἀναστάς (anastas, &quot;having risen up&quot; — an echo of resurrection)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>A lethal attack becomes a platform for God&#x27;s resurrection power.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>A lone man rising from the dust, surrounded by a faithful few.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>For the church: when a believer falls, encircle them in faith.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Praise to You, the God who raises us from the dust of our defeat.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever felt knocked down, left for dead by circumstances or opposition? The Apostle Paul certainly was. On his first missionary journey in the city of Lystra, after a powerful ministry, a hostile mob stoned him, dragged him outside the city, and left him for dead. This could have been the end of the story. But it wasn't.\n\nAs a small group of faithful disciples gathered around his broken body, something incredible happened. Paul stood up. The word Luke uses for \"rose up\" is ἀναστάς (*anastas*), a deliberate echo of Jesus' own resurrection. Powered by God, Paul didn't just escape; he walked right back into the city that had tried to kill him. This wasn't about human grit; it was a living demonstration of God's resurrection power. It proved that no amount of human violence can stop God's divine mission. For us, this is a powerful picture. The same power that raised Jesus from the tomb and stood Paul up in the dust of Lystra is at work in us (Eph 1:19-20). When you feel defeated, remember that your story isn't over. Through Christ, you can rise again and continue the work He has called you to do.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever felt knocked down, left for dead by circumstances or opposition? The Apostle Paul certainly was. On his first missionary journey in the city of Lystra, after a powerful ministry, a hostile mob stoned him, dragged him outside the city, and left him for dead. This could have been the end of the story. But it wasn't.</p>\n<p>As a small group of faithful disciples gathered around his broken body, something incredible happened. Paul stood up. The word Luke uses for \"rose up\" is ἀναστάς (<em>anastas</em>), a deliberate echo of Jesus' own resurrection. Powered by God, Paul didn't just escape; he walked right back into the city that had tried to kill him. This wasn't about human grit; it was a living demonstration of God's resurrection power. It proved that no amount of human violence can stop God's divine mission. For us, this is a powerful picture. The same power that raised Jesus from the tomb and stood Paul up in the dust of Lystra is at work in us (Eph 1:19-20). When you feel defeated, remember that your story isn't over. Through Christ, you can rise again and continue the work He has called you to do.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  What specific word in the Greek text of Acts 14:20 echoes the theme of resurrection?\n    A: The participle ἀναστάς (*anastas*, \"having risen up\"), which shares the same root as the Greek word for resurrection, ἀνάστασις (*anastasis*).\n\n2.  What two courageous actions did Paul take immediately after being miraculously revived?\n    A: He first re-entered the very city that had stoned him, and then the next day, he continued his missionary journey to Derbe.\n\n3.  What does this event teach us about God's power in the midst of suffering?\n    A: It teaches that God's power is perfected in our weakness. He doesn't always prevent suffering, but He demonstrates His ultimate victory by raising us up through it to continue His mission.\n\n4.  How does this passage instruct the church to respond when a fellow believer is \"stoned\" by life's trials?\n    A: The church is called to gather around the suffering member with faithful presence and prayer, creating a context of support for God to work and raise them up.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>What specific word in the Greek text of Acts 14:20 echoes the theme of resurrection?\n    A: The participle ἀναστάς (<em>anastas</em>, \"having risen up\"), which shares the same root as the Greek word for resurrection, ἀνάστασις (<em>anastasis</em>).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>What two courageous actions did Paul take immediately after being miraculously revived?\n    A: He first re-entered the very city that had stoned him, and then the next day, he continued his missionary journey to Derbe.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>What does this event teach us about God's power in the midst of suffering?\n    A: It teaches that God's power is perfected in our weakness. He doesn't always prevent suffering, but He demonstrates His ultimate victory by raising us up through it to continue His mission.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>How does this passage instruct the church to respond when a fellow believer is \"stoned\" by life's trials?\n    A: The church is called to gather around the suffering member with faithful presence and prayer, creating a context of support for God to work and raise them up.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>",
