in His: \"By the power that raised the Son.\"\nGate 21: PASS — AABB rhyme scheme is declared and strictly followed with exact rhymes.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is a single fenced `text` code block.\nGate 23: PASS — All lines counted and confirmed to be between 6 and 8 syllables.\nGate 24: PASS — Title \"Risen in the Dust\" is a 4-syllable, concrete, memorable image.\n\n```text\nTitle: Risen in the Dust\nStyle: Folk rock, raw analog capture, upright piano, gritty acoustic guitar, floor tom, male vocals, Large room acoustics, live room bleed, thick mid-range, wooden resonance, environmental air, no noise reduction, tape saturation\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\n(A) The rocks flew hard from hateful hands\n(A) Left on the dry and dusty lands\n(B) They dragged him out beyond the gate\n(B) To seal the gospel's final fate\n\n[Chorus]\n(A) But in the dust the apostle rose\n(A) To face the worst of all his foes\n(B) He stood and walked back through the stone\n(B) To show God's power is alone\n\n[Verse 2]\n(A) The faithful few who gathered round\n(A) Saw life spring from the barren ground\n(B) They formed a wall of whispered prayer\n(B) And found a living Savior there\n\n[Chorus]\n(A) But in the dust the apostle rose\n(A) To face the worst of all his foes\n(B) He stood and walked back through the stone\n(B) To show God's power is alone\n\n[Bridge]\n(A) O Lord, we run this very race\n(A) And find in suffering Your grace\n(B) By the power that raised the Son\n(B) We rise again till work is done\n\n[Outro]\nThe next day's sun began to climb\nHe left the hate, he left the crime\nHe walked the road, his mission clear\nNo room for doubt, no time for fear\nOn to Derbe\nOn to Derbe\n\n[End]\n```\n",
