      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\")**: The miraculous recovery and immediate courageous action of the Apostle Paul after being stoned and left for dead by a hostile mob in Lystra.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\")**: God's resurrection power is so profoundly at work in His servants that even a lethal assault cannot stop the advance of the gospel, but instead becomes a platform to display divine preservation and apostolic resolve.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\")**: Apparent defeat for the gospel messenger is merely the prelude to a display of God's resurrection power that vindicates the messenger and propels the mission forward.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\")</strong>: The miraculous recovery and immediate courageous action of the Apostle Paul after being stoned and left for dead by a hostile mob in Lystra.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\")</strong>: God's resurrection power is so profoundly at work in His servants that even a lethal assault cannot stop the advance of the gospel, but instead becomes a platform to display divine preservation and apostolic resolve.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\")</strong>: Apparent defeat for the gospel messenger is merely the prelude to a display of God's resurrection power that vindicates the messenger and propels the mission forward.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role**: The thesis of Acts is the Holy Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, in fulfillment of Christ's commission (Acts 1:8). This verse is a dramatic case study of that thesis in action, demonstrating that the expansion is unstoppable precisely because it is supernaturally powered. It showcases the cost of apostleship and the divine resilience that overcomes it.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc**: This verse is the stunning climax and resolution of the Lystra episode (Acts 14:8-20) within the broader narrative of Paul’s First Missionary Journey (Acts 13-14). The arc moves from a miraculous healing (14:8-10), to mistaken identity as pagan gods (14:11-18), to violent rejection fueled by agitators from Antioch and Iconium (14:19). This verse provides the turn: from Paul lying \"dead\" outside the city to Paul standing, re-entering the city, and continuing his mission.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic**: The genre is Historical Narrative. The governing hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this event not as a prescription for how all persecution will end, but as a description of a foundational event that reveals a pattern: God's power is perfected in weakness (2 Cor 12:9), and the life of the apostle mirrors the suffering-and-glory pattern of Christ Himself.\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational)**: This event occurs squarely in the Church Age (Dispensation of Grace), under the New Covenant. It is a key moment in the initial Gentile mission, demonstrating the fulfillment of God's plan to bring salvation to the nations (Isa 49:6; Acts 13:47) and the intense opposition it would provoke.\n*   **Author & Attribution**: The author is Luke the physician, a companion of Paul, writing to Theophilus. The account is that of a careful historian and theologian, likely composed in the early AD 60s.\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors**: The verse is pulled into sharp relief by what immediately precedes it: Paul being dragged out of the city and left for dead (14:19). The tension is at its peak. What follows is the calm continuation of the mission to Derbe (14:20b-21), making this verse the hinge upon which the entire narrative turns from crisis to progress.\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels**: This event is the specific fulfillment of Paul's later testimony, \"Once I was stoned\" (2 Cor 11:25). It is the supreme example of the principle he articulates in 2 Corinthians 4:8-11, \"always carrying in the body the death of Jesus, so that the life of Jesus may also be manifested in our bodies.\" It also embodies Jesus' own warnings and promises regarding persecution (John 15:20; Matt 10:22-23).\n",
      "phase_c_big_picture_html": "<h3>Big Picture: Where this passage fits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Whole-Book Thesis &amp; Passage's Role</strong>: The thesis of Acts is the Holy Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, in fulfillment of Christ's commission (Acts 1:8). This verse is a dramatic case study of that thesis in action, demonstrating that the expansion is unstoppable precisely because it is supernaturally powered. It showcases the cost of apostleship and the divine resilience that overcomes it.</li>\n<li><strong>Discourse / Section Arc</strong>: This verse is the stunning climax and resolution of the Lystra episode (Acts 14:8-20) within the broader narrative of Paul’s First Missionary Journey (Acts 13-14). The arc moves from a miraculous healing (14:8-10), to mistaken identity as pagan gods (14:11-18), to violent rejection fueled by agitators from Antioch and Iconium (14:19). This verse provides the turn: from Paul lying \"dead\" outside the city to Paul standing, re-entering the city, and continuing his mission.</li>\n<li><strong>Genre &amp; Hermeneutic</strong>: The genre is Historical Narrative. The governing hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this event not as a prescription for how all persecution will end, but as a description of a foundational event that reveals a pattern: God's power is perfected in weakness (2 Cor 12:9), and the life of the apostle mirrors the suffering-and-glory pattern of Christ Himself.</li>\n<li><strong>Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational)</strong>: This event occurs squarely in the Church Age (Dispensation of Grace), under the New Covenant. It is a key moment in the initial Gentile mission, demonstrating the fulfillment of God's plan to bring salvation to the nations (Isa 49:6; Acts 13:47) and the intense opposition it would provoke.</li>\n<li><strong>Author &amp; Attribution</strong>: The author is Luke the physician, a companion of Paul, writing to Theophilus. The account is that of a careful historian and theologian, likely composed in the early AD 60s.</li>\n<li><strong>Gravitational Neighbors</strong>: The verse is pulled into sharp relief by what immediately precedes it: Paul being dragged out of the city and left for dead (14:19). The tension is at its peak. What follows is the calm continuation of the mission to Derbe (14:20b-21), making this verse the hinge upon which the entire narrative turns from crisis to progress.</li>\n<li><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels</strong>: This event is the specific fulfillment of Paul's later testimony, \"Once I was stoned\" (2 Cor 11:25). It is the supreme example of the principle he articulates in 2 Corinthians 4:8-11, \"always carrying in the body the death of Jesus, so that the life of Jesus may also be manifested in our bodies.\" It also embodies Jesus' own warnings and promises regarding persecution (John 15:20; Matt 10:22-23).</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology**: This event takes place during Paul's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars like Hoehner to approximately AD 47-48. This is early in the church's expansion into Gentile territory, a period of intense spiritual conflict and discovery.\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography**: Lystra was a city in the Roman province of Galatia, in the district of Lycaonia (modern-day south-central Turkey). It was a Roman colony, which gave it a certain civic status, but it was culturally more of a backwater compared to Antioch or Iconium. The stoning would have occurred just outside the city gates, a place of refuse and public execution.\n*   **Original Audience Identification**: Luke writes to Theophilus and, through him, to the broader Greco-Roman church. This story would serve as a powerful encouragement to believers facing their own persecution, assuring them that God's power is sufficient and that the mission's success does not depend on the physical safety of its messengers.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text)**: Luke, as a historian and theologian, is carefully curating these events to build a specific case. He wants to show that the Pauline mission is divinely ordained and supernaturally protected. The brevity and matter-of-fact tone of the account underscore the miraculous nature of the event—it is presented without fanfare, as a simple fact of apostolic life.\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology</strong>: This event takes place during Paul's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars like Hoehner to approximately AD 47-48. This is early in the church's expansion into Gentile territory, a period of intense spiritual conflict and discovery.</li>\n<li><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography</strong>: Lystra was a city in the Roman province of Galatia, in the district of Lycaonia (modern-day south-central Turkey). It was a Roman colony, which gave it a certain civic status, but it was culturally more of a backwater compared to Antioch or Iconium. The stoning would have occurred just outside the city gates, a place of refuse and public execution.</li>\n<li><strong>Original Audience Identification</strong>: Luke writes to Theophilus and, through him, to the broader Greco-Roman church. This story would serve as a powerful encouragement to believers facing their own persecution, assuring them that God's power is sufficient and that the mission's success does not depend on the physical safety of its messengers.</li>\n<li><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text)</strong>: Luke, as a historian and theologian, is carefully curating these events to build a specific case. He wants to show that the Pauline mission is divinely ordained and supernaturally protected. The brevity and matter-of-fact tone of the account underscore the miraculous nature of the event—it is presented without fanfare, as a simple fact of apostolic life.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\nThis single verse contains a complete narrative arc of reversal and resolve.\n\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax**: The verse is built around a series of participles leading to main verbs, a common feature of Lucan style. The genitive absolute κυκλωσάντων...τῶν μαθητῶν (\"when the disciples had encircled\") sets the scene. The key action is carried by the aorist participle ἀναστάς (*anastas*, \"having risen up\"), which has temporal priority to the main verb εἰσῆλθεν (*eisēlthen*, \"he entered\"). This structure emphasizes the rising as the pivotal act that enables the subsequent entry and departure.\n\n*   **Wordplay**: The most profound theological point is embedded in a word choice that functions as wordplay. The verb for \"he rose up\" is ἀναστάς (*anastas*), from the root ἀνίστημι (*anistēmi*). This is the same root as the noun for resurrection, ἀνάστασις (*anastasis*). Luke is deliberately painting a picture of a mini-resurrection. Paul, left for dead, \"resurrects\" and continues his work. He is living out the pattern of his Lord.\n\n*   **Imagery & Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?)**:\n    *   **The Circle of Disciples**: κυκλωσάντων (*kyklōsantōn*, \"having encircled\"). This is not a passive crowd; it's an intentional gathering. The image is one of protection, prayer, and faithful presence. They don't flee; they surround their fallen leader, expecting God to act. Their faith forms the context for the miracle.\n    *   **Re-entering the City**: This is an act of supreme spiritual defiance and courage. He returns to the very place of his \"execution.\" Why? To demonstrate to the new believers that the gospel cannot be killed by stones, to show the persecutors their violence is futile against God's plan, and to retrieve his belongings for the next leg of the journey. He does not flee as a victim; he walks back in as a victor in Christ.\n\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment**: This event is a [TYPE] of the believer's own journey. We are called to share in Christ's sufferings so that we may also share in His resurrection power (Phil 3:10; Rom 8:17). Paul's physical experience here becomes a living parable of the spiritual reality for every Christian who endures hardship for the gospel.\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<p>This single verse contains a complete narrative arc of reversal and resolve.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Linguistic Mechanics &amp; Syntax</strong>: The verse is built around a series of participles leading to main verbs, a common feature of Lucan style. The genitive absolute κυκλωσάντων...τῶν μαθητῶν (\"when the disciples had encircled\") sets the scene. The key action is carried by the aorist participle ἀναστάς (<em>anastas</em>, \"having risen up\"), which has temporal priority to the main verb εἰσῆλθεν (<em>eisēlthen</em>, \"he entered\"). This structure emphasizes the rising as the pivotal act that enables the subsequent entry and departure.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Wordplay</strong>: The most profound theological point is embedded in a word choice that functions as wordplay. The verb for \"he rose up\" is ἀναστάς (<em>anastas</em>), from the root ἀνίστημι (<em>anistēmi</em>). This is the same root as the noun for resurrection, ἀνάστασις (<em>anastasis</em>). Luke is deliberately painting a picture of a mini-resurrection. Paul, left for dead, \"resurrects\" and continues his work. He is living out the pattern of his Lord.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Imagery &amp; Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?)</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Circle of Disciples</strong>: κυκλωσάντων (<em>kyklōsantōn</em>, \"having encircled\"). This is not a passive crowd; it's an intentional gathering. The image is one of protection, prayer, and faithful presence. They don't flee; they surround their fallen leader, expecting God to act. Their faith forms the context for the miracle.</li>\n<li><strong>Re-entering the City</strong>: This is an act of supreme spiritual defiance and courage. He returns to the very place of his \"execution.\" Why? To demonstrate to the new believers that the gospel cannot be killed by stones, to show the persecutors their violence is futile against God's plan, and to retrieve his belongings for the next leg of the journey. He does not flee as a victim; he walks back in as a victor in Christ.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Foreshadowing &amp; Fulfillment</strong>: This event is a [TYPE] of the believer's own journey. We are called to share in Christ's sufferings so that we may also share in His resurrection power (Phil 3:10; Rom 8:17). Paul's physical experience here becomes a living parable of the spiritual reality for every Christian who endures hardship for the gospel.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic)**: This verse is a key station in the biblical motif of \"death and resurrection\" as the pattern of God's redemptive work. The trajectory runs from Joseph being left for dead in a pit before rising to power (Gen 37, 41), to Daniel in the lion's den (Dan 6), culminating in the **hinge-of-hinges**: the death and resurrection of Jesus Christ. Paul at Lystra is a post-ascension embodiment of that same pattern. The trajectory's **Christo-telic terminus** (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the final resurrection of the saints, of which this is a foretaste (1 Cor 15:20-23). The terminus verse is arguably 2 Timothy 2:11: \"If we have died with him, we will also live with him.\"\n\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag**:\n    *   **Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\")**: Demonstrates that the power of the gospel is not just for initial conversion but for ongoing preservation and empowerment through trials.\n    *   **Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\")**: The unseen actor here is the Holy Spirit, who provides the power for Paul's recovery and courage, fulfilling the promise of Acts 1:8.\n    *   **Christology (\"the doctrine of the person and work of Christ\")**: Paul’s experience is a living commentary on the death and resurrection of Christ; the servant is not greater than the master, and his life follows the master's pattern (John 15:20).\n    *   **Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\")**: Shows the proper response of the church to a suffering leader: not to scatter in fear, but to gather in faith.\n\n*   **Tripartite Synthesis**: Conservative Christian commentators universally see this as a miracle of divine preservation and a powerful illustration of the resurrection pattern in ministry. While not a text in the Hebrew Bible, the principle of God sustaining His persecuted prophets (like Jeremiah in the cistern, Jer 38) provides a clear Tanakh precedent for God's faithfulness to His messengers. Paul stands in the line of the persecuted prophets of Israel, now empowered by the Spirit of the resurrected Messiah.\n\n*   **Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification**: This passage points to Christ by demonstrating His resurrection life at work in His apostle. Paul is not the hero of the story; Christ's power working through Paul is the hero. The event makes no sense apart from the prior, greater resurrection of Jesus, which it echoes and confirms.\n",
      "phase_f_canonical_html": "<h3>Canonical Connection</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic)</strong>: This verse is a key station in the biblical motif of \"death and resurrection\" as the pattern of God's redemptive work. The trajectory runs from Joseph being left for dead in a pit before rising to power (Gen 37, 41), to Daniel in the lion's den (Dan 6), culminating in the <strong>hinge-of-hinges</strong>: the death and resurrection of Jesus Christ. Paul at Lystra is a post-ascension embodiment of that same pattern. The trajectory's <strong>Christo-telic terminus</strong> (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the final resurrection of the saints, of which this is a foretaste (1 Cor 15:20-23). The terminus verse is arguably 2 Timothy 2:11: \"If we have died with him, we will also live with him.\"</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Systematic-Theology Loci Tag</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\")</strong>: Demonstrates that the power of the gospel is not just for initial conversion but for ongoing preservation and empowerment through trials.</li>\n<li><strong>Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\")</strong>: The unseen actor here is the Holy Spirit, who provides the power for Paul's recovery and courage, fulfilling the promise of Acts 1:8.</li>\n<li><strong>Christology (\"the doctrine of the person and work of Christ\")</strong>: Paul’s experience is a living commentary on the death and resurrection of Christ; the servant is not greater than the master, and his life follows the master's pattern (John 15:20).</li>\n<li><strong>Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\")</strong>: Shows the proper response of the church to a suffering leader: not to scatter in fear, but to gather in faith.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Tripartite Synthesis</strong>: Conservative Christian commentators universally see this as a miracle of divine preservation and a powerful illustration of the resurrection pattern in ministry. While not a text in the Hebrew Bible, the principle of God sustaining His persecuted prophets (like Jeremiah in the cistern, Jer 38) provides a clear Tanakh precedent for God's faithfulness to His messengers. Paul stands in the line of the persecuted prophets of Israel, now empowered by the Spirit of the resurrected Messiah.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification</strong>: This passage points to Christ by demonstrating His resurrection life at work in His apostle. Paul is not the hero of the story; Christ's power working through Paul is the hero. The event makes no sense apart from the prior, greater resurrection of Jesus, which it echoes and confirms.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
