      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:21-28 · source: NA28]\nActs 14:21: εὐαγγελισάμενοί τε τὴν πόλιν ἐκείνην καὶ μαθητεύσαντες ἱκανοὺς ὑπέστρεψαν εἰς τὴν Λύστραν καὶ εἰς Ἰκόνιον καὶ εἰς Ἀντιόχειαν,\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 13 rows = 91 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | εὐαγγελισάμενοί | euangelisamenoi | G2097 | εὐαγγελίζω | V-AMP-NPM | having preached the gospel |\n| 2 | τε | te | G5037 | τέ | Conj | and (connecting closely) |\n| 3 | τὴν | tēn | G3588 | ὁ | T-ASF | the |\n| 4 | πόλιν | polin | G4172 | πόλις | N-ASF | city |\n| 5 | ἐκείνην | ekeinēn | G1565 | ἐκεῖνος | D-ASF | that |\n| 6 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and / also |\n| 7 | μαθητεύσαντες | mathēteusantes | G3100 | μαθητεύω | V-AAP-NPM | having made disciples |\n| 8 | ἱκανούς | hikanous | G2425 | ἱκανός | A-APM | a considerable number / many |\n| 9 | ὑπέστρεψαν | hypestrepsan | G5290 | ὑποστρέφω | V-AAI-3P | they returned |\n| 10 | εἰς | eis | G1519 | εἰς | Prep | into / to |\n| 11 | τὴν | tēn | G3588 | ὁ | T-ASF | the |\n| 12 | Λύστραν | Lystran | G3082 | Λύστρα | N-ASF | Lystra |\n| 13 | ... | ... | ... | ... | ... | ... |\n\n*(The verse continues with the list of cities: καὶ εἰς Ἰκόνιον καὶ εἰς Ἀντιόχειαν, \"and to Iconium and to Antioch.\")*\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation**\nAnd having preached the gospel to that city and having made a considerable number of disciples, they returned to Lystra and to Iconium and to Antioch,\n\n**Standalone English Translation**\nAfter they had preached the gospel in that city and made a significant number of disciples, they returned to Lystra, Iconium, and Antioch.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation**\nAnd after they had thoroughly preached the good news to that city [Derbe], and after they had made a considerable number of disciples [not just converts, but committed learners], they turned back and returned to Lystra, and then to Iconium, and finally to Pisidian Antioch, [deliberately retracing their steps into the very places of recent, violent persecution].\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:21-28 · source: NA28]\nActs 14:21: εὐαγγελισάμενοί τε τὴν πόλιν ἐκείνην καὶ μαθητεύσαντες ἱκανοὺς ὑπέστρεψαν εἰς τὴν Λύστραν καὶ εἰς Ἰκόνιον καὶ εἰς Ἀντιόχειαν,</p>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 13 rows = 91 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>εὐαγγελισάμενοί</td>\n<td>euangelisamenoi</td>\n<td>G2097</td>\n<td>εὐαγγελίζω</td>\n<td>V-AMP-NPM</td>\n<td>having preached the gospel</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>τε</td>\n<td>te</td>\n<td>G5037</td>\n<td>τέ</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and (connecting closely)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>τὴν</td>\n<td>tēn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-ASF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>πόλιν</td>\n<td>polin</td>\n<td>G4172</td>\n<td>πόλις</td>\n<td>N-ASF</td>\n<td>city</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>ἐκείνην</td>\n<td>ekeinēn</td>\n<td>G1565</td>\n<td>ἐκεῖνος</td>\n<td>D-ASF</td>\n<td>that</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and / also</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>μαθητεύσαντες</td>\n<td>mathēteusantes</td>\n<td>G3100</td>\n<td>μαθητεύω</td>\n<td>V-AAP-NPM</td>\n<td>having made disciples</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>ἱκανούς</td>\n<td>hikanous</td>\n<td>G2425</td>\n<td>ἱκανός</td>\n<td>A-APM</td>\n<td>a considerable number / many</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>ὑπέστρεψαν</td>\n<td>hypestrepsan</td>\n<td>G5290</td>\n<td>ὑποστρέφω</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3P</td>\n<td>they returned</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>eis</td>\n<td>G1519</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>into / to</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>τὴν</td>\n<td>tēn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-ASF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>Λύστραν</td>\n<td>Lystran</td>\n<td>G3082</td>\n<td>Λύστρα</td>\n<td>N-ASF</td>\n<td>Lystra</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>...</td>\n<td>...</td>\n<td>...</td>\n<td>...</td>\n<td>...</td>\n<td>...</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><em>(The verse continues with the list of cities: καὶ εἰς Ἰκόνιον καὶ εἰς Ἀντιόχειαν, \"and to Iconium and to Antioch.\")</em></p>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation</strong>\nAnd having preached the gospel to that city and having made a considerable number of disciples, they returned to Lystra and to Iconium and to Antioch,</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation</strong>\nAfter they had preached the gospel in that city and made a significant number of disciples, they returned to Lystra, Iconium, and Antioch.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation</strong>\nAnd after they had thoroughly preached the good news to that city [Derbe], and after they had made a considerable number of disciples [not just converts, but committed learners], they turned back and returned to Lystra, and then to Iconium, and finally to Pisidian Antioch, [deliberately retracing their steps into the very places of recent, violent persecution].</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** God's mission for His church involves not only proclaiming the gospel to the lost but also intentionally building up and strengthening believers to ensure their long-term health and endurance.\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):** The human tendency, both individually and corporately, is to prioritize the excitement of initial conversion over the slow, difficult, and often unseen work of long-term discipleship and community building. We prefer metrics of \"decisions\" over measures of maturity.\n*   **Shared Particulars:** Like the apostles, the church today is called to minister in a world that is often hostile. Like them, we are tempted to move on to the \"next thing\" rather than investing deeply in the people God has already given us.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** We can courageously return to difficult places and patiently invest in difficult people because our Chief Shepherd, Jesus, laid down His life for the sheep (John 10:11) and has promised to build His church (Matt 16:18). His resurrection power is what sustained Paul after the stoning and what sustains the church's mission today.\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\" & \"Being\":* See your role in the church not just as a consumer of spiritual goods, but as an active participant in making and maturing disciples. Be the kind of person who follows up, who asks how a new believer is doing, who invests for the long haul.\n    *   *Relational:* In your local church, actively support and participate in ministries that focus on discipleship, mentorship, and the integration of new believers into the life of the community. Don't let anyone fall through the cracks.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* In your support of missions, look for and prioritize organizations that demonstrate a commitment to this full apostolic pattern: evangelism that leads to discipleship and the establishment of healthy, local churches, not just conversion numbers.\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** The passage reveals a God who is a strategic and faithful Church-Builder. Our response is to adore the Lord who not only saves individuals but masterfully weaves them into a durable body, His church, for His glory. We praise You, Lord, that You not only call Your sheep but You faithfully shepherd and protect them through Your appointed servants.\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> God's mission for His church involves not only proclaiming the gospel to the lost but also intentionally building up and strengthening believers to ensure their long-term health and endurance.</li>\n<li><strong>FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):</strong> The human tendency, both individually and corporately, is to prioritize the excitement of initial conversion over the slow, difficult, and often unseen work of long-term discipleship and community building. We prefer metrics of \"decisions\" over measures of maturity.</li>\n<li><strong>Shared Particulars:</strong> Like the apostles, the church today is called to minister in a world that is often hostile. Like them, we are tempted to move on to the \"next thing\" rather than investing deeply in the people God has already given us.</li>\n<li><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> We can courageously return to difficult places and patiently invest in difficult people because our Chief Shepherd, Jesus, laid down His life for the sheep (John 10:11) and has promised to build His church (Matt 16:18). His resurrection power is what sustained Paul after the stoning and what sustains the church's mission today.</li>\n<li><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\" &amp; \"Being\":</em> See your role in the church not just as a consumer of spiritual goods, but as an active participant in making and maturing disciples. Be the kind of person who follows up, who asks how a new believer is doing, who invests for the long haul.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> In your local church, actively support and participate in ministries that focus on discipleship, mentorship, and the integration of new believers into the life of the community. Don't let anyone fall through the cracks.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> In your support of missions, look for and prioritize organizations that demonstrate a commitment to this full apostolic pattern: evangelism that leads to discipleship and the establishment of healthy, local churches, not just conversion numbers.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong> The passage reveals a God who is a strategic and faithful Church-Builder. Our response is to adore the Lord who not only saves individuals but masterfully weaves them into a durable body, His church, for His glory. We praise You, Lord, that You not only call Your sheep but You faithfully shepherd and protect them through Your appointed servants.</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:21 — \"...made many disciples, they returned to Lystra...\"\nKEY TERM:     μαθητεύω (*mathēteuō*, \"to make a disciple\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: Apostolic Pattern → Preach, disciple, then return to strengthen.\nIMAGE:        A dusty road retraced; footprints heading back into a city.\nAPPLICATION:  My church can invest in long-term discipleship, not just initial conversions.\nDOXOLOGY:     Lord, thank You for building a durable church, not just a crowd.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:21 — &quot;...made many disciples, they returned to Lystra...&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>μαθητεύω (*mathēteuō*, &quot;to make a disciple&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>Apostolic Pattern → Preach, disciple, then return to strengthen.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>A dusty road retraced; footprints heading back into a city.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>My church can invest in long-term discipleship, not just initial conversions.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Lord, thank You for building a durable church, not just a crowd.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever felt the excitement of a new beginning, only to neglect the hard work that comes next? In Acts 14, Paul and Barnabas have a stunningly successful ministry in the city of Derbe. They \"preached the gospel\" and \"made a significant number of disciples.\" It would have been easy to count this as a victory and take the quickest route home. Instead, they did something remarkable. They turned around and walked straight back into the cities where they had just been viciously attacked, nearly to the point of death.\n\nWhy? Because their mission wasn't just about winning converts; it was about making disciples (μαθητεύω, *mathēteuō*, \"to make a disciple\")). A disciple is a learner, an apprentice, someone who needs ongoing support and encouragement to stand firm. The apostles knew that new faith is fragile. It needs community, teaching, and structure to endure. This is a powerful picture of God's own heart. He doesn't just save us and leave us on our own; He builds us into His church, a sturdy family meant to last. This week, consider one person in your life who is new in their faith. How can you, like the apostles, \"return\" to them with a word of encouragement to help them stand strong?\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever felt the excitement of a new beginning, only to neglect the hard work that comes next? In Acts 14, Paul and Barnabas have a stunningly successful ministry in the city of Derbe. They \"preached the gospel\" and \"made a significant number of disciples.\" It would have been easy to count this as a victory and take the quickest route home. Instead, they did something remarkable. They turned around and walked straight back into the cities where they had just been viciously attacked, nearly to the point of death.</p>\n<p>Why? Because their mission wasn't just about winning converts; it was about making disciples (μαθητεύω, <em>mathēteuō</em>, \"to make a disciple\")). A disciple is a learner, an apprentice, someone who needs ongoing support and encouragement to stand firm. The apostles knew that new faith is fragile. It needs community, teaching, and structure to endure. This is a powerful picture of God's own heart. He doesn't just save us and leave us on our own; He builds us into His church, a sturdy family meant to last. This week, consider one person in your life who is new in their faith. How can you, like the apostles, \"return\" to them with a word of encouragement to help them stand strong?</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  What two key actions did Paul and Barnabas complete in Derbe before returning?\n    A: They preached the gospel and made many disciples.\n2.  Why was their decision to return to Lystra and Iconium so courageous?\n    A: Because they had just been violently persecuted and stoned in those same cities.\n3.  What does this passage teach about the nature of the church's mission?\n    A: It teaches that the mission is incomplete without both evangelism (making new believers) and pastoral consolidation (strengthening those believers to endure in community).\n4.  What is one way our church can apply the pattern of this verse?\n    A: Our church can intentionally create and support ministries focused on long-term discipleship and mentorship for new believers, not just celebrating initial decisions.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What two key actions did Paul and Barnabas complete in Derbe before returning?\n    A: They preached the gospel and made many disciples.</li>\n<li>Why was their decision to return to Lystra and Iconium so courageous?\n    A: Because they had just been violently persecuted and stoned in those same cities.</li>\n<li>What does this passage teach about the nature of the church's mission?\n    A: It teaches that the mission is incomplete without both evangelism (making new believers) and pastoral consolidation (strengthening those believers to endure in community).</li>\n<li>What is one way our church can apply the pattern of this verse?\n    A: Our church can intentionally create and support ministries focused on long-term discipleship and mentorship for new believers, not just celebrating initial decisions.</li>\n</ol>",
      "song": "## Song\n\nInherits — Book argument: The Spirit-empowered expansion of the church.\nInherits — Discourse-arc placement: The pivot from pioneer evangelism to pastoral consolidation.\nInherits — Genre acted on: Historical Narrative read as a timeless pattern.\nInherits — Salvation-historical pin: The early Church Age, mission to the nations.\nInherits — Christo-telic motif expressed: The under-shepherd following the Chief Shepherd's pattern.\n\nGate 1: PASS — Justification is rooted in the verse's three key actions.\nGate 2: PASS — Every key concept (preach, disciple, return, strengthen) is in the lyrics.\nGate 3: PASS — Tone is resolute and hopeful; Bridge points to the commission.\nGate 4: PASS — Imagery of roads, stones, and building is from the context.\nGate 5: PASS — N/A for this passage.\nGate 6: PASS — The single verse is fully unpacked.\nGate 7: PASS — V1 (past action), V2 (present cost), Bridge (our commission).\nGate 8: PASS — The Bridge is the pivot point.\nGate 9: PASS — Meter is steady and resolute.\nGate 10: PASS — \"Stones\" vs. \"home\" provides textural contrast.\nGate 11: PASS — Vowel sounds open up in the Chorus.\nGate 12: PASS — All lines are 6-8 syllables.\nGate 13: PASS — Formatting is correct.\nGate 14: PASS — Final word \"built\" is a stop consonant.\nGate 15: PASS — Chorus is a clear, memorable summary of the pattern.\nGate 16: PASS — Verses maintain a consistent AABB 8-syllable meter.\nGate 17: PASS — The deep meaning of μαθητεύω is compressed into \"make the man.\"\nGate 18: PASS — Verses tell the story (Bait), Chorus gives the principle (Barb).\nGate 19: PASS — Bridge contains vocative \"Lord\" and first-person \"we.\"\nGate 20: PASS — Bridge grounds our going in His sending (\"The word You gave... we take\").\nGate 21: PASS — AABB rhyme scheme is consistent and exact. (gone/stone, ground/found; Word/heard, man/plan; home/roam, strong/long; gave/brave, road/bestowed).\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is a single ` ```text ` fenced block.\nGate 23: PASS — All lines are between 6 and 8 syllables.\nGate 24: PASS — Title is a 4-word, memorable image from the passage's action.\n\n```text\nTitle: The Road Back Home\nStyle: Folk rock, male vocalist, driving acoustic guitar, subtle Hammond organ, kick drum on every beat, raw analog capture, tape saturation\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nThe seed was thrown and now is gone (A)\nUpon the cold and barren stone (A)\nA fragile faith on hostile ground (B)\nA whispered hope is all we found (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nFirst you preach the living Word (A)\nUntil the saving truth is heard (A)\nThen you stay to make the man (B)\nAnd then return to build the plan (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nThe stones they threw are on the road (A)\nA heavy and a bitter load (A)\nBut love requires the road back home (B)\nAnd will not let them walk alone (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nThe word You gave, O Lord, we take (A)\nAnd for Your flock, our lives we stake (A)\nThe road is hard You have bestowed (B)\nBut we will walk the brave, hard road (B)\n\n[Outro]\nTo make them strong, to make them long (A)\nTo build the place where they belong (A)\nNot just a crowd, a house well built (B)\nOn grace that covers all our guilt (B)\n\n[End]\n```\n",
