e <code>```text</code> fenced block.\nGate 23: PASS — All lines are between 6 and 8 syllables.\nGate 24: PASS — Title is a 4-word, memorable image from the passage's action.</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-text\">Title: The Road Back Home\nStyle: Folk rock, male vocalist, driving acoustic guitar, subtle Hammond organ, kick drum on every beat, raw analog capture, tape saturation\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nThe seed was thrown and now is gone (A)\nUpon the cold and barren stone (A)\nA fragile faith on hostile ground (B)\nA whispered hope is all we found (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nFirst you preach the living Word (A)\nUntil the saving truth is heard (A)\nThen you stay to make the man (B)\nAnd then return to build the plan (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nThe stones they threw are on the road (A)\nA heavy and a bitter load (A)\nBut love requires the road back home (B)\nAnd will not let them walk alone (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nThe word You gave, O Lord, we take (A)\nAnd for Your flock, our lives we stake (A)\nThe road is hard You have bestowed (B)\nBut we will walk the brave, hard road (B)\n\n[Outro]\nTo make them strong, to make them long (A)\nTo build the place where they belong (A)\nNot just a crowd, a house well built (B)\nOn grace that covers all our guilt (B)\n\n[End]\n</code></pre>",
      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The apostolic pattern for completing a church-planting initiative.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** It consists of two primary actions—gospel proclamation and intentional disciple-making—followed by a strategic return to consolidate and strengthen the new believers.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** Faithful ministry establishes new believers through evangelism and discipleship, and then ensures their endurance by deliberately returning to strengthen them.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):</strong> The apostolic pattern for completing a church-planting initiative.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):</strong> It consists of two primary actions—gospel proclamation and intentional disciple-making—followed by a strategic return to consolidate and strengthen the new believers.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):</strong> Faithful ministry establishes new believers through evangelism and discipleship, and then ensures their endurance by deliberately returning to strengthen them.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the church from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, fulfilling the commission of Acts 1:8. This verse marks a crucial pivot in the first missionary journey (Acts 13-14), shifting from the outward advance of the gospel to the pastoral consolidation of the churches planted. It demonstrates the *method* of that expansion: not just winning converts, but building durable communities of faith.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This verse concludes the outward leg of Paul and Barnabas's first missionary journey, which began in Pisidian Antioch (13:14), moved to Iconium (14:1), Lystra (14:8), and finally Derbe (14:20). Acts 14:21 initiates the return journey, where the focus shifts from pioneer evangelism to pastoral edification (14:22-23). This verse is the hinge between the two phases.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic:** The genre is Historical Narrative. The primary hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this passage as descriptive of the apostolic pattern, which becomes prescriptive in principle for the church's mission (cf. Matt 28:19-20; Titus 1:5). We distinguish what is recorded from what is universally commanded, but here the pattern aligns perfectly with the didactic teaching of the epistles.\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** The passage is set firmly in the Church Age, under the New Covenant. The events occur in the dispensation of Grace, where the gospel is going forth to Gentiles (\"the nations\") without the prerequisite of adherence to the Mosaic Law, a central theme of Paul's ministry and the later Jerusalem Council (Acts 15).\n*   **Author & Attribution:** The author is Luke the physician, a companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), writing the second volume of his two-part work, Luke-Acts. The work is dated conservatively to the early AD 60s, likely composed in Rome during Paul's first imprisonment.\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors:** The verse is immediately preceded by Paul's miraculous recovery from being stoned and left for dead in Lystra (14:19-20). This context makes the decision to *return* to Lystra an act of profound courage and pastoral love. It is immediately followed by the content of their ministry on the return journey: \"strengthening the souls of the disciples, encouraging them to continue in the faith\" (14:22).\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** This pattern is the fulfillment of the Great Commission: \"Go therefore and make disciples (μαθητεύσατε, *mathēteusate*) of all nations\" (Matt 28:19 [Pericope: Matt 28:16-20 · source: NA28]). The action of returning to appoint elders is explicitly commanded to Titus: \"This is why I left you in Crete, so that you might put what remained into order, and appoint elders in every town as I directed you\" (Titus 1:5 [Pericope: Titus 1:5-9 · source: NA28]).\n",
      "phase_c_big_picture_html": "<h3>Big Picture: Where this passage fits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Whole-Book Thesis &amp; Passage's Role:</strong> The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the church from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, fulfilling the commission of Acts 1:8. This verse marks a crucial pivot in the first missionary journey (Acts 13-14), shifting from the outward advance of the gospel to the pastoral consolidation of the churches planted. It demonstrates the <em>method</em> of that expansion: not just winning converts, but building durable communities of faith.</li>\n<li><strong>Discourse / Section Arc:</strong> This verse concludes the outward leg of Paul and Barnabas's first missionary journey, which began in Pisidian Antioch (13:14), moved to Iconium (14:1), Lystra (14:8), and finally Derbe (14:20). Acts 14:21 initiates the return journey, where the focus shifts from pioneer evangelism to pastoral edification (14:22-23). This verse is the hinge between the two phases.</li>\n<li><strong>Genre &amp; Hermeneutic:</strong> The genre is Historical Narrative. The primary hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this passage as descriptive of the apostolic pattern, which becomes prescriptive in principle for the church's mission (cf. Matt 28:19-20; Titus 1:5). We distinguish what is recorded from what is universally commanded, but here the pattern aligns perfectly with the didactic teaching of the epistles.</li>\n<li><strong>Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):</strong> The passage is set firmly in the Church Age, under the New Covenant. The events occur in the dispensation of Grace, where the gospel is going forth to Gentiles (\"the nations\") without the prerequisite of adherence to the Mosaic Law, a central theme of Paul's ministry and the later Jerusalem Council (Acts 15).</li>\n<li><strong>Author &amp; Attribution:</strong> The author is Luke the physician, a companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), writing the second volume of his two-part work, Luke-Acts. The work is dated conservatively to the early AD 60s, likely composed in Rome during Paul's first imprisonment.</li>\n<li><strong>Gravitational Neighbors:</strong> The verse is immediately preceded by Paul's miraculous recovery from being stoned and left for dead in Lystra (14:19-20). This context makes the decision to <em>return</em> to Lystra an act of profound courage and pastoral love. It is immediately followed by the content of their ministry on the return journey: \"strengthening the souls of the disciples, encouraging them to continue in the faith\" (14:22).</li>\n<li><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels:</strong> This pattern is the fulfillment of the Great Commission: \"Go therefore and make disciples (μαθητεύσατε, <em>mathēteusate</em>) of all nations\" (Matt 28:19 [Pericope: Matt 28:16-20 · source: NA28]). The action of returning to appoint elders is explicitly commanded to Titus: \"This is why I left you in Crete, so that you might put what remained into order, and appoint elders in every town as I directed you\" (Titus 1:5 [Pericope: Titus 1:5-9 · source: NA28]).</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** The first missionary journey is dated by conservative scholars (Hoehner, Bruce) to approximately AD 46-48. This verse describes events at the end of that period. The political entity is the Roman province of Galatia.\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:**\n    *   **Derbe:** An ancient city in Lycaonia, southern Galatia (modern Turkey). Its precise location is debated, but likely near the mound of Kerti Hüyük.\n    *   **Lystra:** About 100 km (60 miles) northwest of Derbe. Site of the stoning of Paul (Acts 14:19).\n    *   **Iconium:** About 30 km (18 miles) north of Lystra (modern Konya). A major city on the trade route where Paul and Barnabas faced a plot to stone them (Acts 14:5).\n    *   **Pisidian Antioch:** A major Roman colony, northwest of Iconium. The starting point of the Galatian ministry (Acts 13:14).\n    The decision to retrace their steps on foot through this hostile territory, rather than taking an easier route home, is a deliberate, costly, and strategic choice.\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** Luke writes to Theophilus (Luke 1:3; Acts 1:1), a likely high-ranking Roman official, and to a wider Greco-Roman and Christian audience. His purpose is to provide an orderly and historically reliable account of the origins and expansion of the Christian faith, demonstrating its divine power and its political harmlessness to the Roman order.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke is a careful historian, compiling eyewitness accounts (Luke 1:2) to create a definitive narrative. His emphasis on the sequence—preaching, making disciples, returning to strengthen—is not accidental but a core part of his theology of how the church is built and sustained by the Holy Spirit.\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology:</strong> The first missionary journey is dated by conservative scholars (Hoehner, Bruce) to approximately AD 46-48. This verse describes events at the end of that period. The political entity is the Roman province of Galatia.</li>\n<li><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography:</strong><ul>\n<li><strong>Derbe:</strong> An ancient city in Lycaonia, southern Galatia (modern Turkey). Its precise location is debated, but likely near the mound of Kerti Hüyük.</li>\n<li><strong>Lystra:</strong> About 100 km (60 miles) northwest of Derbe. Site of the stoning of Paul (Acts 14:19).</li>\n<li><strong>Iconium:</strong> About 30 km (18 miles) north of Lystra (modern Konya). A major city on the trade route where Paul and Barnabas faced a plot to stone them (Acts 14:5).</li>\n<li><strong>Pisidian Antioch:</strong> A major Roman colony, northwest of Iconium. The starting point of the Galatian ministry (Acts 13:14).\nThe decision to retrace their steps on foot through this hostile territory, rather than taking an easier route home, is a deliberate, costly, and strategic choice.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Original Audience Identification:</strong> Luke writes to Theophilus (Luke 1:3; Acts 1:1), a likely high-ranking Roman official, and to a wider Greco-Roman and Christian audience. His purpose is to provide an orderly and historically reliable account of the origins and expansion of the Christian faith, demonstrating its divine power and its political harmlessness to the Roman order.</li>\n<li><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):</strong> Luke is a careful historian, compiling eyewitness accounts (Luke 1:2) to create a definitive narrative. His emphasis on the sequence—preaching, making disciples, returning to strengthen—is not accidental but a core part of his theology of how the church is built and sustained by the Holy Spirit.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax:** The verse is structured around two aorist active participles, εὐαγγελισάμενοί (*euangelisamenoi*, \"having preached the gospel\") and μαθητεύσαντες (*mathēteusantes*, \"having made disciples\"), which describe the actions completed *before* the main verb, ὑπέστρεψαν (*hypestrepsan*, \"they returned\"). This grammatical structure emphasizes that the return journey is predicated on the successful completion of the evangelistic and discipling work in Derbe. The sequence is theologically significant: proclamation leads to discipleship, which then requires consolidation.\n*   **Wordplay:** There is no overt wordplay, but there is a powerful conceptual link between μαθητεύσαντες (*mathēteusantes*, \"having made disciples\") and the \"disciples\" (τοὺς μαθητάς, *tous mathētas*) they return to strengthen in the next verse (14:22). Luke shows the full lifecycle of discipleship: from inception to edification.\n*   **Key Terms:**\n    *   εὐαγγελίζω (*euangelizō*, \"to preach the gospel\"): This is not just any speech, but the specific proclamation of the good news about Jesus Christ's death and resurrection for salvation.\n    *   μαθητεύω (*mathēteuō*, \"to make a disciple\"): This verb goes beyond simple conversion. It implies bringing someone into the position of a learner, a follower, an apprentice of Jesus. It is the core command of the Great Commission.\n    *   ἱκανός (*hikanos*, \"a considerable number/sufficient\"): Luke uses this word to indicate a successful mission, not just one or two converts, but a viable group large enough to form the nucleus of a church.\n    *   ὑποστρέφω (*hypostrephō*, \"to return\"): This word signifies a deliberate turning back over a previous route, highlighting the intentionality of their pastoral follow-up.\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Linguistic Mechanics &amp; Syntax:</strong> The verse is structured around two aorist active participles, εὐαγγελισάμενοί (<em>euangelisamenoi</em>, \"having preached the gospel\") and μαθητεύσαντες (<em>mathēteusantes</em>, \"having made disciples\"), which describe the actions completed <em>before</em> the main verb, ὑπέστρεψαν (<em>hypestrepsan</em>, \"they returned\"). This grammatical structure emphasizes that the return journey is predicated on the successful completion of the evangelistic and discipling work in Derbe. The sequence is theologically significant: proclamation leads to discipleship, which then requires consolidation.</li>\n<li><strong>Wordplay:</strong> There is no overt wordplay, but there is a powerful conceptual link between μαθητεύσαντες (<em>mathēteusantes</em>, \"having made disciples\") and the \"disciples\" (τοὺς μαθητάς, <em>tous mathētas</em>) they return to strengthen in the next verse (14:22). Luke shows the full lifecycle of discipleship: from inception to edification.</li>\n<li><strong>Key Terms:</strong><ul>\n<li>εὐαγγελίζω (<em>euangelizō</em>, \"to preach the gospel\"): This is not just any speech, but the specific proclamation of the good news about Jesus Christ's death and resurrection for salvation.</li>\n<li>μαθητεύω (<em>mathēteuō</em>, \"to make a disciple\"): This verb goes beyond simple conversion. It implies bringing someone into the position of a learner, a follower, an apprentice of Jesus. It is the core command of the Great Commission.</li>\n<li>ἱκανός (<em>hikanos</em>, \"a considerable number/sufficient\"): Luke uses this word to indicate a successful mission, not just one or two converts, but a viable group large enough to form the nucleus of a church.</li>\n<li>ὑποστρέφω (<em>hypostrephō</em>, \"to return\"): This word signifies a deliberate turning back over a previous route, highlighting the intentionality of their pastoral follow-up.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment:** This passage is the fulfillment of Christ's commission in Acts 1:8, demonstrating the gospel moving into \"Judea and Samaria, and to the end of the earth.\" It also fulfills the pattern of the Great Commission [PROPHECY] (Matt 28:19-20). The courage to return to places of persecution is a living embodiment of Jesus's warnings and promises about suffering for the gospel (John 15:20; 16:33).\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** This verse is a key hinge in the biblical motif of **shepherding God's flock**. This motif begins with figures like Jacob and David, is articulated as God's own work in Ezekiel 34 (\"I myself will be the shepherd of my sheep\"), and finds its *hinge-of-hinges* in Jesus, the Good Shepherd who lays down His life (John 10:11). The apostles, as under-shepherds, now enact this pattern. The *Christo-telic terminus* (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the charge given by the resurrected Christ (Matt 28:19) and the accountability of under-shepherds to the Chief Shepherd at His appearing (1 Pet 5:4).\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:**\n    *   Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"): This verse provides a foundational pattern for church planting and pastoral care: evangelism, discipleship, and leadership development (which follows in v.23).\n    *   Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"): Salvation is initiated through the preaching of the gospel (εὐαγγελίζω) and results in a new identity as a disciple (μαθητής).\n    *   Missiology (a sub-discipline of Ecclesiology): It establishes the principle that missions is not complete until churches are not just planted but established and strengthened.\n",
      "phase_f_canonical_html": "<h3>Canonical Connection</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Foreshadowing &amp; Fulfillment:</strong> This passage is the fulfillment of Christ's commission in Acts 1:8, demonstrating the gospel moving into \"Judea and Samaria, and to the end of the earth.\" It also fulfills the pattern of the Great Commission [PROPHECY] (Matt 28:19-20). The courage to return to places of persecution is a living embodiment of Jesus's warnings and promises about suffering for the gospel (John 15:20; 16:33).</li>\n<li><strong>Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):</strong> This verse is a key hinge in the biblical motif of <strong>shepherding God's flock</strong>. This motif begins with figures like Jacob and David, is articulated as God's own work in Ezekiel 34 (\"I myself will be the shepherd of my sheep\"), and finds its <em>hinge-of-hinges</em> in Jesus, the Good Shepherd who lays down His life (John 10:11). The apostles, as under-shepherds, now enact this pattern. The <em>Christo-telic terminus</em> (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the charge given by the resurrected Christ (Matt 28:19) and the accountability of under-shepherds to the Chief Shepherd at His appearing (1 Pet 5:4).</li>\n<li><strong>Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:</strong><ul>\n<li>Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"): This verse provides a foundational pattern for church planting and pastoral care: evangelism, discipleship, and leadership development (which follows in v.23).</li>\n<li>Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"): Salvation is initiated through the preaching of the gospel (εὐαγγελίζω) and results in a new identity as a disciple (μαθητής).</li>\n<li>Missiology (a sub-discipline of Ecclesiology): It establishes the principle that missions is not complete until churches are not just planted but established and strengthened.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
