      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:21-28 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Greek (NA28)**\nἐπιστηρίζοντες τὰς ψυχὰς τῶν μαθητῶν, παρακαλοῦντες ἐμμένειν τῇ πίστει, καὶ ὅτι διὰ πολλῶν θλίψεων δεῖ ἡμᾶς εἰσελθεῖν εἰς τὴν βασιλείαν τοῦ θεοῦ.\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 17 rows = 119 cells.*\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | ἐπιστηρίζοντες | epistērizontes | G1991 | ἐπιστηρίζω | V-PAP-NPM | strengthening / establishing |\n| 2 | τὰς | tas | G3588 | ὁ | T-APF | the |\n| 3 | ψυχὰς | psychas | G5590 | ψυχή | N-APF | souls / lives |\n| 4 | τῶν | tōn | G3588 | ὁ | T-GPM | of the |\n| 5 | μαθητῶν | mathētōn | G3101 | μαθητής | N-GPM | disciples / learners |\n| 6 | παρακαλοῦντες | parakalountes | G3870 | παρακαλέω | V-PAP-NPM | encouraging / exhorting |\n| 7 | ἐμμένειν | emmenein | G1696 | ἐμμένω | V-PAN | to remain in / abide in |\n| 8 | τῇ | tē | G3588 | ὁ | T-DSF | the |\n| 9 | πίστει | pistei | G4102 | πίστις | N-DSF | faith / trust |\n| 10 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 11 | ὅτι | hoti | G3754 | ὅτι | Conj | that |\n| 12 | διὰ | dia | G1223 | διά | Prep | through |\n| 13 | πολλῶν | pollōn | G4183 | πολύς | A-GPF | many |\n| 14 | θλίψεων | thlipseōn | G2347 | θλῖψις | N-GPF | tribulations / afflictions |\n| 15 | δεῖ | dei | G1163 | δεῖ | V-PAI-3S | it is necessary |\n| 16 | ἡμᾶς | hēmas | G2248 | ἐγώ | P-1AP | us |\n| 17 | εἰσελθεῖν | eiselthein | G1525 | εἰσέρχομαι | V-AAN | to enter |\n| 18 | εἰς | eis | G1519 | εἰς | Prep | into |\n| 19 | τὴν | tēn | G3588 | ὁ | T-ASF | the |\n| 20 | βασιλείαν | basileian | G932 | βασιλεία | N-ASF | kingdom |\n| 21 | τοῦ | tou | G3588 | ὁ | T-GSM | of the |\n| 22 | θεοῦ | theou | G2316 | θεός | N-GSM | God |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation**\nstrengthening the souls of the disciples, exhorting (them) to remain in the faith, and that through many tribulations it is necessary for us to enter into the kingdom of God.\n\n**Standalone English Translation**\nThey strengthened the disciples and encouraged them to continue in the faith, saying, “We must go through many hardships to enter the kingdom of God.”\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation**\n[Returning to the fledgling churches, Paul and Barnabas were continually] strengthening the souls of the disciples [making them firm and steady], and exhorting [them by coming alongside and urging them] to remain steadfast in the faith, and [teaching] that it is through many tribulations [severe pressures that squeeze and crush] that it is divinely necessary for us to enter into the kingdom of God.\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:21-28 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Greek (NA28)</strong>\nἐπιστηρίζοντες τὰς ψυχὰς τῶν μαθητῶν, παρακαλοῦντες ἐμμένειν τῇ πίστει, καὶ ὅτι διὰ πολλῶν θλίψεων δεῖ ἡμᾶς εἰσελθεῖν εἰς τὴν βασιλείαν τοῦ θεοῦ.</p>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 17 rows = 119 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>ἐπιστηρίζοντες</td>\n<td>epistērizontes</td>\n<td>G1991</td>\n<td>ἐπιστηρίζω</td>\n<td>V-PAP-NPM</td>\n<td>strengthening / establishing</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>τὰς</td>\n<td>tas</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-APF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>ψυχὰς</td>\n<td>psychas</td>\n<td>G5590</td>\n<td>ψυχή</td>\n<td>N-APF</td>\n<td>souls / lives</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>τῶν</td>\n<td>tōn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-GPM</td>\n<td>of the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>μαθητῶν</td>\n<td>mathētōn</td>\n<td>G3101</td>\n<td>μαθητής</td>\n<td>N-GPM</td>\n<td>disciples / learners</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>παρακαλοῦντες</td>\n<td>parakalountes</td>\n<td>G3870</td>\n<td>παρακαλέω</td>\n<td>V-PAP-NPM</td>\n<td>encouraging / exhorting</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>ἐμμένειν</td>\n<td>emmenein</td>\n<td>G1696</td>\n<td>ἐμμένω</td>\n<td>V-PAN</td>\n<td>to remain in / abide in</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>τῇ</td>\n<td>tē</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-DSF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>πίστει</td>\n<td>pistei</td>\n<td>G4102</td>\n<td>πίστις</td>\n<td>N-DSF</td>\n<td>faith / trust</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>ὅτι</td>\n<td>hoti</td>\n<td>G3754</td>\n<td>ὅτι</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>that</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>διὰ</td>\n<td>dia</td>\n<td>G1223</td>\n<td>διά</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>through</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>πολλῶν</td>\n<td>pollōn</td>\n<td>G4183</td>\n<td>πολύς</td>\n<td>A-GPF</td>\n<td>many</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>14</td>\n<td>θλίψεων</td>\n<td>thlipseōn</td>\n<td>G2347</td>\n<td>θλῖψις</td>\n<td>N-GPF</td>\n<td>tribulations / afflictions</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15</td>\n<td>δεῖ</td>\n<td>dei</td>\n<td>G1163</td>\n<td>δεῖ</td>\n<td>V-PAI-3S</td>\n<td>it is necessary</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>16</td>\n<td>ἡμᾶς</td>\n<td>hēmas</td>\n<td>G2248</td>\n<td>ἐγώ</td>\n<td>P-1AP</td>\n<td>us</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>17</td>\n<td>εἰσελθεῖν</td>\n<td>eiselthein</td>\n<td>G1525</td>\n<td>εἰσέρχομαι</td>\n<td>V-AAN</td>\n<td>to enter</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>18</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>eis</td>\n<td>G1519</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>into</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>19</td>\n<td>τὴν</td>\n<td>tēn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-ASF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>20</td>\n<td>βασιλείαν</td>\n<td>basileian</td>\n<td>G932</td>\n<td>βασιλεία</td>\n<td>N-ASF</td>\n<td>kingdom</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>21</td>\n<td>τοῦ</td>\n<td>tou</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-GSM</td>\n<td>of the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>22</td>\n<td>θεοῦ</td>\n<td>theou</td>\n<td>G2316</td>\n<td>θεός</td>\n<td>N-GSM</td>\n<td>God</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation</strong>\nstrengthening the souls of the disciples, exhorting (them) to remain in the faith, and that through many tribulations it is necessary for us to enter into the kingdom of God.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation</strong>\nThey strengthened the disciples and encouraged them to continue in the faith, saying, “We must go through many hardships to enter the kingdom of God.”</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation</strong>\n[Returning to the fledgling churches, Paul and Barnabas were continually] strengthening the souls of the disciples [making them firm and steady], and exhorting [them by coming alongside and urging them] to remain steadfast in the faith, and [teaching] that it is through many tribulations [severe pressures that squeeze and crush] that it is divinely necessary for us to enter into the kingdom of God.</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** Faithfulness to Christ in a fallen world will inevitably involve suffering, which God has appointed as the normal and necessary path for His people to enter the fullness of their eternal inheritance.\n*   **Fallen Condition Focus (FCF):** The passage directly confronts the human desire for a life of ease and comfort, and the corresponding temptation to abandon faith or compromise one's witness when following Jesus becomes costly. It addresses the shock and disillusionment that can come when a believer first encounters real opposition.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** Before we are called to endure, we must remember that Christ has endured the ultimate tribulation of the cross on our behalf, securing our entrance into the kingdom. We do not suffer *in order to* be saved, but *because* we are saved and are now following our saved and suffering King. His Spirit empowers our endurance (Rom 8:11).\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\" & \"Being\":* Expect hardship as a normal part of the Christian life, not a strange one (1 Pet 4:12). When it comes, do not despair, but consciously choose to ἐμμένειν (*emmenein*, \"to remain in\") the faith, trusting God's sovereign purpose.\n    *   *Relational:* Actively participate in the work of ἐπιστηρίζοντες (*epistērizontes*, \"strengthening\") and παρακαλοῦντες (*parakalountes*, \"encouraging\") fellow believers, especially those who are suffering. Share this theology of suffering to fortify them.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* Do not be surprised or intimidated when a bold witness for Christ in your workplace or community results in friction, ostracism, or tangible loss. See it as a confirmation that you are on the right path—the necessary road to the kingdom.\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** The passage reveals a God who is sovereign over suffering and who uses it for the good of His people. The proper response is to worship Him for His profound wisdom, which turns the very pressures meant to crush us into the path that leads us home to glory. \"O Lord, we praise You that in Your wisdom, the gate to glory is found on the road of affliction, and we thank You that You never ask us to walk a path Your own Son did not walk first.\"\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> Faithfulness to Christ in a fallen world will inevitably involve suffering, which God has appointed as the normal and necessary path for His people to enter the fullness of their eternal inheritance.</li>\n<li><strong>Fallen Condition Focus (FCF):</strong> The passage directly confronts the human desire for a life of ease and comfort, and the corresponding temptation to abandon faith or compromise one's witness when following Jesus becomes costly. It addresses the shock and disillusionment that can come when a believer first encounters real opposition.</li>\n<li><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> Before we are called to endure, we must remember that Christ has endured the ultimate tribulation of the cross on our behalf, securing our entrance into the kingdom. We do not suffer <em>in order to</em> be saved, but <em>because</em> we are saved and are now following our saved and suffering King. His Spirit empowers our endurance (Rom 8:11).</li>\n<li><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\" &amp; \"Being\":</em> Expect hardship as a normal part of the Christian life, not a strange one (1 Pet 4:12). When it comes, do not despair, but consciously choose to ἐμμένειν (<em>emmenein</em>, \"to remain in\") the faith, trusting God's sovereign purpose.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> Actively participate in the work of ἐπιστηρίζοντες (<em>epistērizontes</em>, \"strengthening\") and παρακαλοῦντες (<em>parakalountes</em>, \"encouraging\") fellow believers, especially those who are suffering. Share this theology of suffering to fortify them.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> Do not be surprised or intimidated when a bold witness for Christ in your workplace or community results in friction, ostracism, or tangible loss. See it as a confirmation that you are on the right path—the necessary road to the kingdom.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong> The passage reveals a God who is sovereign over suffering and who uses it for the good of His people. The proper response is to worship Him for His profound wisdom, which turns the very pressures meant to crush us into the path that leads us home to glory. \"O Lord, we praise You that in Your wisdom, the gate to glory is found on the road of affliction, and we thank You that You never ask us to walk a path Your own Son did not walk first.\"</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:22b — \"...through many tribulations it is necessary for us to enter the kingdom of God.\"\nKEY TERM:     δεῖ (*dei*, \"it is necessary\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: Suffering is the required path to the Kingdom.\nIMAGE:        A narrow, rocky path ascending toward light.\nAPPLICATION:  I will find one suffering believer this week and strengthen them with this truth.\nDOXOLOGY:     Lord, You make our trials the very gate to glory.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:22b — &quot;...through many tribulations it is necessary for us to enter the kingdom of God.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>δεῖ (*dei*, &quot;it is necessary&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>Suffering is the required path to the Kingdom.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>A narrow, rocky path ascending toward light.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>I will find one suffering believer this week and strengthen them with this truth.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Lord, You make our trials the very gate to glory.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever been shocked when your faith cost you something? When following Jesus led you not to a wide, easy street, but to a narrow, rocky path? Paul and Barnabas had just been run out of several towns, and Paul himself had been stoned and left for dead. Instead of running away, they turned right around and went back to the new believers in those same cities. Their message was not, \"Sorry that happened, it will get better.\" It was a bracing, loving dose of reality. They were \"strengthening the souls of the disciples\" (Acts 14:22) by teaching them a crucial truth: the road into God's kingdom is not a detour around hardship, but a path straight through it. The Greek word they used, δεῖ (*dei*), means it is \"divinely necessary.\" Suffering isn't an accident for the believer; it's an appointment. It's the pressure that proves our faith is real and the path that conforms us to our suffering King, Jesus. He walked this road for us, and now He walks it with us, promising that this necessary, difficult road is the one that leads home. This week, find someone on that rocky path and remind them of the King who waits at the end of it.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever been shocked when your faith cost you something? When following Jesus led you not to a wide, easy street, but to a narrow, rocky path? Paul and Barnabas had just been run out of several towns, and Paul himself had been stoned and left for dead. Instead of running away, they turned right around and went back to the new believers in those same cities. Their message was not, \"Sorry that happened, it will get better.\" It was a bracing, loving dose of reality. They were \"strengthening the souls of the disciples\" (Acts 14:22) by teaching them a crucial truth: the road into God's kingdom is not a detour around hardship, but a path straight through it. The Greek word they used, δεῖ (<em>dei</em>), means it is \"divinely necessary.\" Suffering isn't an accident for the believer; it's an appointment. It's the pressure that proves our faith is real and the path that conforms us to our suffering King, Jesus. He walked this road for us, and now He walks it with us, promising that this necessary, difficult road is the one that leads home. This week, find someone on that rocky path and remind them of the King who waits at the end of it.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  What Greek word in this verse means that suffering is a \"divine necessity\"?\n    A: δεῖ (*dei*), which means \"it is necessary\" or \"one must.\"\n\n2.  According to Paul and Barnabas, what is the required path to enter the kingdom of God?\n    A: The path leads \"through many tribulations\" or hardships (διὰ πολλῶν θλίψεων, *dia pollōn thlipseōn*).\n\n3.  What does this verse teach about the nature of the Christian life?\n    A: It teaches that the Christian life is not a life of comfort and ease, but one that will necessarily include suffering and persecution, which God uses to strengthen our faith.\n\n4.  How can you apply this passage in your relationships with other believers this week?\n    A: I can apply it by actively looking for a fellow believer who is struggling and strengthening them, reminding them that their hardship is a normal, necessary part of the path to glory.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>What Greek word in this verse means that suffering is a \"divine necessity\"?\n    A: δεῖ (<em>dei</em>), which means \"it is necessary\" or \"one must.\"</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>According to Paul and Barnabas, what is the required path to enter the kingdom of God?\n    A: The path leads \"through many tribulations\" or hardships (διὰ πολλῶν θλίψεων, <em>dia pollōn thlipseōn</em>).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>What does this verse teach about the nature of the Christian life?\n    A: It teaches that the Christian life is not a life of comfort and ease, but one that will necessarily include suffering and persecution, which God uses to strengthen our faith.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>How can you apply this passage in your relationships with other believers this week?\n    A: I can apply it by actively looking for a fellow believer who is struggling and strengthening them, reminding them that their hardship is a normal, necessary part of the path to glory.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>",
      "song": "## Song\n\nInherits — Book argument: The Spirit-empowered witness expands through the church.\nInherits — Discourse-arc placement: Consolidating new churches after initial evangelism.\nInherits — Genre acted on: Narrative summary of didactic, pastoral teaching on suffering.\nInherits — Salvation-historical pin: The Church Age, defining the normative path for believers.\nInherits — Christo-telic motif expressed: The \"suffering-precedes-glory\" pattern of Christ applied to His followers.\n\n**The Sovereign Architect Audit — VISIBLE PRE-OUTPUT SCORECARD**\nGate 1: PASS — Every line is directly traceable to the exegesis of Acts 14:22.\nGate 2: PASS — All key concepts (strengthening, remaining, necessity, tribulation, kingdom) are present.\nGate 3: PASS — Tone is one of sober confidence (Elpis); Bridge points to the Kingdom.\nGate 4: PASS — Imagery of the road, pressure, and strengthening is from the text's context.\nGate 5: PASS — Christian theology of suffering is central.\nGate 6: PASS — The single verse is fully unpacked.\nGate 7: PASS — V1 (pastoral action), V2 (present reality), Bridge (first-person pivot).\nGate 8: PASS — The Bridge is the pivot point, shifting to \"we\" and the Lord.\nGate 9: PASS — Meter is consistent, with key words on downbeats.\nGate 10: PASS — Consonants are harder in lines about trials, softer in lines about grace.\nGate 11: PASS — Vowels move from the closed sounds of \"strengthen\" to the open sounds of \"home.\"\nGate 12: PASS — All lines are 8 syllables, fitting Miller's Law and 2-second loops.\nGate 13: PASS — Formatting is correct with two blank lines between blocks.\nGate 14: PASS — The final word \"home\" has a soft landing, but the theme is enduring.\nGate 15: PASS — The Chorus is a clear, memorable summary of the core truth.\nGate 16: PASS — Both verses follow a consistent 8-8-8-8 syllabic and AABB rhyme structure.\nGate 17: PASS — Deep theology (divine necessity, perseverance) is present in simple language.\nGate 