      "h1_title_html": "<p>Acts 14:23 — Establishing Church Leadership Through Apostolic Appointment</p>",
      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:21–28 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Greek (NA28)**\nχειροτονήσαντες δὲ αὐτοῖς κατ’ ἐκκλησίαν πρεσβυτέρους προσευξάμενοι μετὰ νηστειῶν παρέθεντο αὐτοὺς τῷ κυρίῳ εἰς ὃν πεπιστεύκεισαν.\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 11 rows = 77 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | χειροτονήσαντες | cheirotonēsantes | G5500 | χειροτονέω | V-AAP-NPM | having appointed / selected |\n| 2 | δὲ | de | G1161 | δέ | Conj | and / but |\n| 3 | αὐτοῖς | autois | G846 | αὐτός | P-DPM | for them |\n| 4 | κατ’ | kat' | G2596 | κατά | Prep | in each / according to |\n| 5 | ἐκκλησίαν | ekklēsian | G1577 | ἐκκλησία | N-ASF | church / assembly |\n| 6 | πρεσβυτέρους | presbyterous | G4245 | πρεσβύτερος | A-APM | elders (older men) |\n| 7 | προσευξάμενοι | proseuxamenoi | G4336 | προσεύχομαι | V-AMP-NPM | having prayed |\n| 8 | μετὰ | meta | G3326 | μετά | Prep | with |\n| 9 | νηστειῶν | nēsteiōn | G3521 | νηστεία | N-GPF | fastings |\n| 10 | παρέθεντο | parenthento | G3908 | παρατίθημι | V-AMI-3P | they committed / entrusted |\n| 11 | τῷ κυρίῳ | tō kyriō | G2962 | κύριος | N-DSM | to the Lord |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\nAnd having appointed for them elders in each church, having prayed with fastings, they committed them to the Lord in whom they had believed.\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\nAnd when they had appointed elders for them in every church, with prayer and fasting they committed them to the Lord in whom they had believed.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\nThen, having deliberately selected and appointed elders [as spiritual overseers] for them in each and every church, and having prayed with accompanying fastings [demonstrating their utter dependence on God for this solemn act], they entrusted them completely to the care of the Lord in whom they had placed their settled faith and trust.\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:21–28 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Greek (NA28)</strong>\nχειροτονήσαντες δὲ αὐτοῖς κατ’ ἐκκλησίαν πρεσβυτέρους προσευξάμενοι μετὰ νηστειῶν παρέθεντο αὐτοὺς τῷ κυρίῳ εἰς ὃν πεπιστεύκεισαν.</p>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 11 rows = 77 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>χειροτονήσαντες</td>\n<td>cheirotonēsantes</td>\n<td>G5500</td>\n<td>χειροτονέω</td>\n<td>V-AAP-NPM</td>\n<td>having appointed / selected</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>δὲ</td>\n<td>de</td>\n<td>G1161</td>\n<td>δέ</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and / but</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>αὐτοῖς</td>\n<td>autois</td>\n<td>G846</td>\n<td>αὐτός</td>\n<td>P-DPM</td>\n<td>for them</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>κατ’</td>\n<td>kat'</td>\n<td>G2596</td>\n<td>κατά</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>in each / according to</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>ἐκκλησίαν</td>\n<td>ekklēsian</td>\n<td>G1577</td>\n<td>ἐκκλησία</td>\n<td>N-ASF</td>\n<td>church / assembly</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>πρεσβυτέρους</td>\n<td>presbyterous</td>\n<td>G4245</td>\n<td>πρεσβύτερος</td>\n<td>A-APM</td>\n<td>elders (older men)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>προσευξάμενοι</td>\n<td>proseuxamenoi</td>\n<td>G4336</td>\n<td>προσεύχομαι</td>\n<td>V-AMP-NPM</td>\n<td>having prayed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>μετὰ</td>\n<td>meta</td>\n<td>G3326</td>\n<td>μετά</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>with</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>νηστειῶν</td>\n<td>nēsteiōn</td>\n<td>G3521</td>\n<td>νηστεία</td>\n<td>N-GPF</td>\n<td>fastings</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>παρέθεντο</td>\n<td>parenthento</td>\n<td>G3908</td>\n<td>παρατίθημι</td>\n<td>V-AMI-3P</td>\n<td>they committed / entrusted</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>τῷ κυρίῳ</td>\n<td>tō kyriō</td>\n<td>G2962</td>\n<td>κύριος</td>\n<td>N-DSM</td>\n<td>to the Lord</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)</strong>\nAnd having appointed for them elders in each church, having prayed with fastings, they committed them to the Lord in whom they had believed.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)</strong>\nAnd when they had appointed elders for them in every church, with prayer and fasting they committed them to the Lord in whom they had believed.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)</strong>\nThen, having deliberately selected and appointed elders [as spiritual overseers] for them in each and every church, and having prayed with accompanying fastings [demonstrating their utter dependence on God for this solemn act], they entrusted them completely to the care of the Lord in whom they had placed their settled faith and trust.</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** God's design for the health and endurance of His church includes a structure of qualified, spiritually-appointed leaders who are entrusted to His sovereign care.\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):**\n    *   *Individual:* The tendency to resist authority and accountability, preferring a self-directed spirituality that is untethered from the local church body.\n    *   *Corporate:* The tendency for churches to drift into chaos, heresy, or inactivity without godly leadership, or conversely, to place their trust in a single charismatic human leader rather than a plurality of qualified elders and the Lord Himself.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** Because Jesus is the Good Shepherd who laid down His life for the sheep (John 10:11) and the Chief Shepherd who now watches over His flock from heaven (1 Pet 5:4), we can have confidence that He provides for the church's needs. He has not left us as orphans but has given the gift of leadership (Eph 4:11-12) to build up the body. Our trust is not ultimately in the elders, but in the Lord who appointed them and to whom they are committed.\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* Actively pray for your church's elders by name. If your church lacks elders, pray for the Lord to raise up qualified men.\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Cultivate a heart of humble submission to your spiritual leaders, recognizing their God-given role to watch over your soul (Heb 13:17).\n    *   *Relational:* Encourage your elders. The work is spiritually demanding and often thankless. Let them know you are praying for them and are grateful for their service.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* In your own sphere of leadership (at work, in the community), model the principles of servant-leadership and dependence on God seen here.\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** This passage reveals God as the faithful **Guardian of His Church**. We praise You, Lord, that You are the one who ultimately keeps and sustains Your people. You are the Chief Shepherd, and we worship You for providing for Your flock by entrusting us to the care of those You have called.\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> God's design for the health and endurance of His church includes a structure of qualified, spiritually-appointed leaders who are entrusted to His sovereign care.</li>\n<li><strong>FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Individual:</em> The tendency to resist authority and accountability, preferring a self-directed spirituality that is untethered from the local church body.</li>\n<li><em>Corporate:</em> The tendency for churches to drift into chaos, heresy, or inactivity without godly leadership, or conversely, to place their trust in a single charismatic human leader rather than a plurality of qualified elders and the Lord Himself.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> Because Jesus is the Good Shepherd who laid down His life for the sheep (John 10:11) and the Chief Shepherd who now watches over His flock from heaven (1 Pet 5:4), we can have confidence that He provides for the church's needs. He has not left us as orphans but has given the gift of leadership (Eph 4:11-12) to build up the body. Our trust is not ultimately in the elders, but in the Lord who appointed them and to whom they are committed.</li>\n<li><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\":</em> Actively pray for your church's elders by name. If your church lacks elders, pray for the Lord to raise up qualified men.</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\":</em> Cultivate a heart of humble submission to your spiritual leaders, recognizing their God-given role to watch over your soul (Heb 13:17).</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> Encourage your elders. The work is spiritually demanding and often thankless. Let them know you are praying for them and are grateful for their service.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> In your own sphere of leadership (at work, in the community), model the principles of servant-leadership and dependence on God seen here.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong> This passage reveals God as the faithful <strong>Guardian of His Church</strong>. We praise You, Lord, that You are the one who ultimately keeps and sustains Your people. You are the Chief Shepherd, and we worship You for providing for Your flock by entrusting us to the care of those You have called.</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:23 — \"...they committed them to the Lord in whom they had believed.\"\nKEY TERM:     πρεσβυτέρους (*presbyterous*, \"elders\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: Apostolic appointment entrusts the church to the Lord's care.\nIMAGE:        Hands of appointment committing a flock to the Chief Shepherd.\nAPPLICATION:  This week, I will pray by name for the elders of my church.\nDOXOLOGY:     Lord, we praise You as the faithful Guardian of Your Church.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:23 — &quot;...they committed them to the Lord in whom they had believed.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>πρεσβυτέρους (*presbyterous*, &quot;elders&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>Apostolic appointment entrusts the church to the Lord&#x27;s care.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>Hands of appointment committing a flock to the Chief Shepherd.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>This week, I will pray by name for the elders of my church.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Lord, we praise You as the faithful Guardian of Your Church.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\n\nHave you ever wondered how a brand-new church, planted in a hostile city, could possibly survive after its founders leave? Acts 14 gives us a powerful snapshot of God's plan. After preaching the gospel in southern Galatia and facing intense persecution—including Paul being stoned and left for dead—Paul and Barnabas did something remarkable. They went back to those same fragile communities. Their goal wasn't just to encourage, but to establish a foundation for the future.\n\nThe Bible says they \"appointed πρεσβυτέρους (*presbyterous*, \"elders\") for them in every church\" (Acts 14:23). This wasn't just an administrative task; it was a deeply spiritual act. With prayer and fasting, they showed their complete dependence on God. Then, they did the most important thing: they \"committed them to the Lord.\" They entrusted these new leaders and the precious flock into the hands of the only one who could truly protect them. This reminds us that the Church's survival never depends on human programs or personalities, but on the watchful care of Jesus, our Chief Shepherd (1 Peter 5:4). He is the one who builds His church, and He provides leaders to shepherd us along the way. This week, take a moment to pray for your own church leaders, thanking God for His provision and asking for His strength to sustain them.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever wondered how a brand-new church, planted in a hostile city, could possibly survive after its founders leave? Acts 14 gives us a powerful snapshot of God's plan. After preaching the gospel in southern Galatia and facing intense persecution—including Paul being stoned and left for dead—Paul and Barnabas did something remarkable. They went back to those same fragile communities. Their goal wasn't just to encourage, but to establish a foundation for the future.</p>\n<p>The Bible says they \"appointed πρεσβυτέρους (<em>presbyterous</em>, \"elders\") for them in every church\" (Acts 14:23). This wasn't just an administrative task; it was a deeply spiritual act. With prayer and fasting, they showed their complete dependence on God. Then, they did the most important thing: they \"committed them to the Lord.\" They entrusted these new leaders and the precious flock into the hands of the only one who could truly protect them. This reminds us that the Church's survival never depends on human programs or personalities, but on the watchful care of Jesus, our Chief Shepherd (1 Peter 5:4). He is the one who builds His church, and He provides leaders to shepherd us along the way. This week, take a moment to pray for your own church leaders, thanking God for His provision and asking for His strength to sustain them.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n\n1.  What two spiritual disciplines accompanied the appointment of elders in Acts 14:23?\n    A: Prayer and fasting.\n2.  What does the Greek word χειροτονήσαντες (*cheirotonēsantes*) mean in this context?\n    A: It means \"having appointed\" or \"selected,\" referring to the apostles' action of establishing leaders.\n3.  What does this passage teach us about Christ's role in the church after leaders are appointed?\n    A: It teaches that Christ remains the ultimate guardian. The leaders and the church are \"committed to the Lord,\" showing He is the Chief Shepherd who sustains His flock.\n4.  What is one specific action you can take this week based on this verse?\n    A: I can pray specifically, by name, for the elders and leaders of my church, asking the Lord to sustain and guide them.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What two spiritual disciplines accompanied the appointment of elders in Acts 14:23?\n    A: Prayer and fasting.</li>\n<li>What does the Greek word χειροτονήσαντες (<em>cheirotonēsantes</em>) mean in this context?\n    A: It means \"having appointed\" or \"selected,\" referring to the apostles' action of establishing leaders.</li>\n<li>What does this passage teach us about Christ's role in the church after leaders are appointed?\n    A: It teaches that Christ remains the ultimate guardian. The leaders and the church are \"committed to the Lord,\" showing He is the Chief Shepherd who sustains His flock.</li>\n<li>What is one specific action you can take this week based on this verse?\n    A: I can pray specifically, by name, for the elders and leaders of my church, asking the Lord to sustain and guide them.</li>\n</ol>",
      "song": "## Song\n\nInherits — Book argument: The consolidation and structuring of the Church.\nInherits — Discourse-arc placement: The pastoral climax of the first missionary journey.\nInherits — Genre acted on: Narrative precedent for church governance.\nInherits — Salvation-historical pin: The early Church Age.\nInherits — Christo-telic motif expressed: Christ the Chief Shepherd providing under-shepherds.\n\n**The Sovereign Architect Audit — Visible Pre-Output Scorecard**\nGate 1: PASS — Nuance of \"appoint\" and \"commit\" is grounded in the Greek.\nGate 2: PASS — Every key concept from the verse is mapped.\nGate 3: PASS — Tone is confident trust in God's provision. Bridge points to the Chief Shepherd.\nGate 4: PASS — Imagery of shepherds, flocks, and hands is primary.\nGate 5: PASS — Christian, Jewish (elder model), and apostolic teaching synthesized.\nGate 6: PASS — The single verse is fully unpacked.\nGate 7: PASS — V1 (past action), V2 (present need), Bridge (Christ's eternal role).\nGate 8: PASS — The Bridge is the theological and emotional reveal.\nGate 9: PASS — Meter is steady; key words land on downbeats.\nGate 10: PASS — \"Stoned\" and \"hostile\" have harder consonants; \"commit\" and \"Lord\" are softer.\nGate 11: PASS — Vowels move toward the open sounds of \"Lord\" and \"hope\" in the Chorus/Bridge.\nGate 12: PASS — All lines are 7-9 syllables.\nGate 13: PASS — Formatting is correct.\nGate 14: PASS — The song has a timeless, foundational feel. Ends on \"Lord.\"\nGate 15: PASS — The Chorus is a clear, memorable summary of the verse.\nGate 16: PASS — Verses maintain a consistent AABB rhythm.\nGate 17: PASS — Deep ecclesiology is compressed into simple, singable lines.\nGate 18: PASS — Verses tell the story (Bait); Chorus gives the principle (Barb).\nGate 19: PASS — Bridge addresses the \"Chief Shepherd\" (vocative) and uses \"our\" (enrolment).\nGate 20: PASS — \"He is the Shepherd, strong and true / So we raise up shepherds, too.\"\nGate 21: PASS — Rhyme is AABB and exact throughout.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is in a single fenced `text` code block.\nGate 23: PASS — Syllable counts verified per line (all are 7-9).\nGate 24: PASS — Title is a concrete image-pair, memorable and non-abstract.\n\n```text\nTitle: The Shepherd's Hands\nStyle: Folk rock, male vocalist, baritone, determined, steady rhythm, acoustic guitar, subtle upright bass, spacious kick drum, Large room acoustics, live room bleed, thick mid-range, wooden resonance, environmental air, no noise reduction, raw analog capture, tape saturation\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\n(A) The hostile ground, the seed was sown\n(A) The threat of chains, the hurled stone\n(B) They traced their steps back through the fire\n(B) To build and raise the structure higher\n\n[Chorus]\n(A) Appointed elders for the flock\n(A) The church is built upon the Rock\n(B) With prayer and fasting, hands were laid\n(B) A trust in God was displayed\n\n[Verse 2]\n(A) The pattern set, the charge is clear\n(A) To lead in faith and not in fear\n(B) A plurality of watchful eyes\n(B) To guard the flock with truth and prize\n\n[Chorus]\n(A) Appointed elders for the flock\n(A) The church is built upon the Rock\n(B) With prayer and fasting, hands were laid\n(B) A trust in God was displayed\n\n[Bridge]\n(A) We trust them to the Lord of all\n(A) Who hears His faithful servants' call\n(B) O Chief Shepherd, strong and true\n(B) Our hope is only found in You\n\n[Outro]\nCommitted to the Lord alone\nWho guards the church He calls His own\nCommitted to the Lord alone\nHe will not abandon His own\nTo the Lord\n\n[End]\n```\n",
