      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:21-28 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Greek (NA28)**\nκαὶ διελθόντες τὴν Πισιδίαν ἦλθον εἰς τὴν Παμφυλίαν,\n\n***\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 6 rows = 42 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and / also / even |\n| 2 | διελθόντες | dielthontes | G1330 | διέρχομαι | V-AAP-NPM | having passed through / having traversed |\n| 3 | τὴν | tēn | G3588 | ὁ | T-ASF | the |\n| 4 | Πισιδίαν | Pisidian | G4099 | Πισιδία | N-ASF | Pisidia |\n| 5 | ἦλθον | ēlthon | G2064 | ἔρχομαι | V-AAI-3P | they came / they went |\n| 6 | εἰς | eis | G1519 | εἰς | Prep | into / to |\n| 7 | τὴν | tēn | G3588 | ὁ | T-ASF | the |\n| 8 | Παμφυλίαν | Pamphylian | G3828 | Παμφυλία | N-ASF | Pamphylia |\n\n***\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\nAnd having passed through the Pisidia, they came into the Pamphylia.\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\nAfter passing through Pisidia, they came to Pamphylia.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\nAnd so, continuing their return journey, having deliberately traversed the entire region of Pisidia [where they had previously ministered], they arrived in the coastal province of Pamphylia.\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:21-28 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Greek (NA28)</strong>\nκαὶ διελθόντες τὴν Πισιδίαν ἦλθον εἰς τὴν Παμφυλίαν,</p>\n<hr>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 6 rows = 42 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and / also / even</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>διελθόντες</td>\n<td>dielthontes</td>\n<td>G1330</td>\n<td>διέρχομαι</td>\n<td>V-AAP-NPM</td>\n<td>having passed through / having traversed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>τὴν</td>\n<td>tēn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-ASF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Πισιδίαν</td>\n<td>Pisidian</td>\n<td>G4099</td>\n<td>Πισιδία</td>\n<td>N-ASF</td>\n<td>Pisidia</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>ἦλθον</td>\n<td>ēlthon</td>\n<td>G2064</td>\n<td>ἔρχομαι</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3P</td>\n<td>they came / they went</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>eis</td>\n<td>G1519</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>into / to</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>τὴν</td>\n<td>tēn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-ASF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>Παμφυλίαν</td>\n<td>Pamphylian</td>\n<td>G3828</td>\n<td>Παμφυλία</td>\n<td>N-ASF</td>\n<td>Pamphylia</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)</strong>\nAnd having passed through the Pisidia, they came into the Pamphylia.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)</strong>\nAfter passing through Pisidia, they came to Pamphylia.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)</strong>\nAnd so, continuing their return journey, having deliberately traversed the entire region of Pisidia [where they had previously ministered], they arrived in the coastal province of Pamphylia.</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** True spiritual leadership is marked not just by visionary pioneering but by the patient, often difficult, follow-up work required to ensure the long-term health and stability of God's people.\n\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):** The human tendency, both individually and corporately, is to chase the excitement of the new (the \"next big thing,\" the new initiative, the pioneer project) while neglecting the less glamorous, often harder, work of maintenance, discipleship, and strengthening what has already begun.\n\n*   **Shared Particulars:** Believers today are also called to a \"journey\" of faith. Like the missionaries, our path is not always the easiest one. It often requires us to \"retrace our steps\"—revisiting foundational truths, checking in on those we have discipled, and doing the hard work of building relationships and institutions that last.\n\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** We are empowered for this patient work because our Chief Shepherd, Jesus Christ, did not abandon His flock. After His resurrection, He returned to His disciples to strengthen and commission them (John 20-21; Acts 1:1-8). He is the one who builds and sustains His Church (Matt 16:18). Because He is faithful to finish His work, we can be faithful in our small part of it.\n\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\" & \"Being\":* Resist the urge to measure your spiritual life only by new starts. Intentionally invest in the relationships and commitments you already have. Be the person who follows up, who checks in, who finishes the task.\n    *   *Relational:* In your local church, honor and support the ministries of discipleship, teaching, and pastoral care as much as the ministries of evangelism and outreach. If you have led someone to faith or mentored them, make a plan to \"retrace your steps\" and see how they are doing (cf. Acts 15:36).\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* In your work, cultivate a reputation for reliability and follow-through, not just for innovative ideas. See the completion and strengthening of projects as an act of faithful stewardship that honors a God of order.\n\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** The passage reveals a God who inspires and empowers pastoral persistence. We worship the Chief Shepherd who never tires of caring for His flock. \"To You, O Lord, the great Shepherd of the sheep, who seeks the lost and strengthens the weak, be all glory for Your relentless, pursuing care.\"\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> True spiritual leadership is marked not just by visionary pioneering but by the patient, often difficult, follow-up work required to ensure the long-term health and stability of God's people.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):</strong> The human tendency, both individually and corporately, is to chase the excitement of the new (the \"next big thing,\" the new initiative, the pioneer project) while neglecting the less glamorous, often harder, work of maintenance, discipleship, and strengthening what has already begun.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Shared Particulars:</strong> Believers today are also called to a \"journey\" of faith. Like the missionaries, our path is not always the easiest one. It often requires us to \"retrace our steps\"—revisiting foundational truths, checking in on those we have discipled, and doing the hard work of building relationships and institutions that last.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> We are empowered for this patient work because our Chief Shepherd, Jesus Christ, did not abandon His flock. After His resurrection, He returned to His disciples to strengthen and commission them (John 20-21; Acts 1:1-8). He is the one who builds and sustains His Church (Matt 16:18). Because He is faithful to finish His work, we can be faithful in our small part of it.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\" &amp; \"Being\":</em> Resist the urge to measure your spiritual life only by new starts. Intentionally invest in the relationships and commitments you already have. Be the person who follows up, who checks in, who finishes the task.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> In your local church, honor and support the ministries of discipleship, teaching, and pastoral care as much as the ministries of evangelism and outreach. If you have led someone to faith or mentored them, make a plan to \"retrace your steps\" and see how they are doing (cf. Acts 15:36).</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> In your work, cultivate a reputation for reliability and follow-through, not just for innovative ideas. See the completion and strengthening of projects as an act of faithful stewardship that honors a God of order.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong> The passage reveals a God who inspires and empowers pastoral persistence. We worship the Chief Shepherd who never tires of caring for His flock. \"To You, O Lord, the great Shepherd of the sheep, who seeks the lost and strengthens the weak, be all glory for Your relentless, pursuing care.\"</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:24 — \"After passing through Pisidia, they came to Pamphylia.\"\nKEY TERM:     διελθόντες (*dielthontes*, \"having passed through/traversed\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: A hard journey chosen for the sake of the flock.\nIMAGE:        Two men walking a dusty, mountain road back toward the sea.\nAPPLICATION:  This week, I will intentionally follow up with one person I am discipling or have encouraged.\nDOXOLOGY:     Praise to the Shepherd who retraces His steps to care for His own.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:24 — &quot;After passing through Pisidia, they came to Pamphylia.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>διελθόντες (*dielthontes*, &quot;having passed through/traversed&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>A hard journey chosen for the sake of the flock.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>Two men walking a dusty, mountain road back toward the sea.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>This week, I will intentionally follow up with one person I am discipling or have encouraged.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Praise to the Shepherd who retraces His steps to care for His own.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\n\nHave you ever been tempted to take a shortcut? After a long and difficult project, it's natural to want the quickest way home. In Acts 14, the apostles Paul and Barnabas had just completed a grueling, dangerous, but fruitful mission trip. They had planted churches deep in modern-day Turkey. Now, it was time to go home. The easy route would have been to head south to the nearest port and sail away. Instead, as Acts 14:24 tells us, \"After passing through Pisidia, they came to Pamphylia.\"\n\nThis short sentence hides a profound truth. They chose the hard way back—an arduous overland journey through rugged mountains—for one reason: to retrace their steps. The verses just before this tell us they were \"strengthening the souls of the disciples\" and \"appointing elders in every church.\" Their journey wasn't just about geography; it was about pastoral care. They valued the health of these new believers more than their own comfort. This is a beautiful picture of our God. He is the Good Shepherd who doesn't just find His sheep, but who faithfully nurtures and protects them for the long haul (John 10:11-14). Because He is so faithful to us, we can find the strength to do the slow, steady, and sometimes difficult work of caring for the people He has placed in our lives. Who is one person you can intentionally check in on and encourage this week?\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever been tempted to take a shortcut? After a long and difficult project, it's natural to want the quickest way home. In Acts 14, the apostles Paul and Barnabas had just completed a grueling, dangerous, but fruitful mission trip. They had planted churches deep in modern-day Turkey. Now, it was time to go home. The easy route would have been to head south to the nearest port and sail away. Instead, as Acts 14:24 tells us, \"After passing through Pisidia, they came to Pamphylia.\"</p>\n<p>This short sentence hides a profound truth. They chose the hard way back—an arduous overland journey through rugged mountains—for one reason: to retrace their steps. The verses just before this tell us they were \"strengthening the souls of the disciples\" and \"appointing elders in every church.\" Their journey wasn't just about geography; it was about pastoral care. They valued the health of these new believers more than their own comfort. This is a beautiful picture of our God. He is the Good Shepherd who doesn't just find His sheep, but who faithfully nurtures and protects them for the long haul (John 10:11-14). Because He is so faithful to us, we can find the strength to do the slow, steady, and sometimes difficult work of caring for the people He has placed in our lives. Who is one person you can intentionally check in on and encourage this week?</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n\n1.  What two Roman provinces did Paul and Barnabas travel through in this verse?\n    A: They passed through Pisidia and then came into Pamphylia.\n2.  Why was the specific route they chose significant?\n    A: It was the harder, overland route, showing their pastoral commitment to revisiting and strengthening the churches they had just planted.\n3.  What does this passage teach us about the nature of Christian ministry?\n    A: It teaches that ministry involves both pioneering evangelism and the equally important, patient work of discipleship and strengthening believers in their faith.\n4.  What is one practical way you can apply the principle of this verse this week?\n    A: I can intentionally follow up with someone I have mentored, encouraged, or shared the gospel with, choosing relationship over convenience.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What two Roman provinces did Paul and Barnabas travel through in this verse?\n    A: They passed through Pisidia and then came into Pamphylia.</li>\n<li>Why was the specific route they chose significant?\n    A: It was the harder, overland route, showing their pastoral commitment to revisiting and strengthening the churches they had just planted.</li>\n<li>What does this passage teach us about the nature of Christian ministry?\n    A: It teaches that ministry involves both pioneering evangelism and the equally important, patient work of discipleship and strengthening believers in their faith.</li>\n<li>What is one practical way you can apply the principle of this verse this week?\n    A: I can intentionally follow up with someone I have mentored, encouraged, or shared the gospel with, choosing relationship over convenience.</li>\n</ol>",
