      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The westward overland journey of Paul and Barnabas, retracing their steps through the Roman province of Pisidia to reach the coastal region of Pamphylia.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** This deliberate and difficult journey, rather than a faster sea route, demonstrates their pastoral commitment to strengthening the newly planted churches before returning to their sending base.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** Faithful apostolic ministry involves not only pioneering new gospel territory but also the arduous work of retracing steps to establish and confirm new believers in the faith.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):</strong> The westward overland journey of Paul and Barnabas, retracing their steps through the Roman province of Pisidia to reach the coastal region of Pamphylia.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):</strong> This deliberate and difficult journey, rather than a faster sea route, demonstrates their pastoral commitment to strengthening the newly planted churches before returning to their sending base.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):</strong> Faithful apostolic ministry involves not only pioneering new gospel territory but also the arduous work of retracing steps to establish and confirm new believers in the faith.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, according to Christ's commission in Acts 1:8. This verse is a crucial logistical link in the return leg of the First Missionary Journey (Acts 13:1–14:28), demonstrating the practical execution of that mission. It shows the gospel not just advancing but also taking root.\n\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This verse sits within the conclusion of the First Missionary Journey (Acts 14:21-28). Having reached their easternmost point in Derbe, Paul and Barnabas turn back west. This pericope (\"the literary unit — the natural sense-unit of the passage\") details their methodology on the return: strengthening disciples (v. 22), appointing elders (v. 23), and reporting back to their sending church (vv. 26-27). Verse 24 is the geographical pivot that makes this pastoral work possible.\n\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic:** The genre is historical narrative, specifically a form of ancient travelogue. The governing *hermeneutic* (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is the *Sensus Literalis* (\"the plain literal-historical-grammatical meaning of a text in its own context\"). We read this as a factual account of movement, asking *why* the author, Luke, included this specific detail. The narrative is selective; every geographical note serves his larger theological purpose of showing the strategic and pastoral nature of the mission.\n\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** This event occurs squarely in the Church Age (Dispensation of Grace), following the inauguration of the New Covenant at the Cross and Pentecost. The gospel is now going to both Jew and Gentile, forming local churches as the primary expression of God's people on earth.\n\n*   **Author & Attribution:** The author is Luke the physician, a companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), writing to his patron Theophilus (Acts 1:1). The work is dated conservatively to the early AD 60s, likely composed in Rome during Paul's first imprisonment.\n\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors:** The verse is preceded by the missionaries' intensive ministry in Lystra and Derbe, where they strengthened disciples and appointed elders (Acts 14:21-23). It is followed by their preaching in Perga (in Pamphylia) and their journey down to the port of Attalia to sail for home (Acts 14:25). This verse connects the inland ministry to the coastal departure.\n\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** This brief travel notice is characteristic of Luke's style throughout Acts, marking transitions between major ministry episodes (e.g., Acts 16:6-8 [Pericope: Acts 16:6-10 · source: NA28]; Acts 20:1-3 [Pericope: Acts 20:1-6 · source: NA28]). It echoes the pattern of Paul's subsequent journeys, which also included both breaking new ground and revisiting established churches (Acts 18:23 [Pericope: Acts 18:23-28 · source: NA28]).\n",
      "phase_c_big_picture_html": "<h3>Big Picture: Where this passage fits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Whole-Book Thesis &amp; Passage's Role:</strong> The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, according to Christ's commission in Acts 1:8. This verse is a crucial logistical link in the return leg of the First Missionary Journey (Acts 13:1–14:28), demonstrating the practical execution of that mission. It shows the gospel not just advancing but also taking root.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Discourse / Section Arc:</strong> This verse sits within the conclusion of the First Missionary Journey (Acts 14:21-28). Having reached their easternmost point in Derbe, Paul and Barnabas turn back west. This pericope (\"the literary unit — the natural sense-unit of the passage\") details their methodology on the return: strengthening disciples (v. 22), appointing elders (v. 23), and reporting back to their sending church (vv. 26-27). Verse 24 is the geographical pivot that makes this pastoral work possible.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Genre &amp; Hermeneutic:</strong> The genre is historical narrative, specifically a form of ancient travelogue. The governing <em>hermeneutic</em> (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is the <em>Sensus Literalis</em> (\"the plain literal-historical-grammatical meaning of a text in its own context\"). We read this as a factual account of movement, asking <em>why</em> the author, Luke, included this specific detail. The narrative is selective; every geographical note serves his larger theological purpose of showing the strategic and pastoral nature of the mission.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):</strong> This event occurs squarely in the Church Age (Dispensation of Grace), following the inauguration of the New Covenant at the Cross and Pentecost. The gospel is now going to both Jew and Gentile, forming local churches as the primary expression of God's people on earth.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Author &amp; Attribution:</strong> The author is Luke the physician, a companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), writing to his patron Theophilus (Acts 1:1). The work is dated conservatively to the early AD 60s, likely composed in Rome during Paul's first imprisonment.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Gravitational Neighbors:</strong> The verse is preceded by the missionaries' intensive ministry in Lystra and Derbe, where they strengthened disciples and appointed elders (Acts 14:21-23). It is followed by their preaching in Perga (in Pamphylia) and their journey down to the port of Attalia to sail for home (Acts 14:25). This verse connects the inland ministry to the coastal departure.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels:</strong> This brief travel notice is characteristic of Luke's style throughout Acts, marking transitions between major ministry episodes (e.g., Acts 16:6-8 [Pericope: Acts 16:6-10 · source: NA28]; Acts 20:1-3 [Pericope: Acts 20:1-6 · source: NA28]). It echoes the pattern of Paul's subsequent journeys, which also included both breaking new ground and revisiting established churches (Acts 18:23 [Pericope: Acts 18:23-28 · source: NA28]).</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** This event takes place during the First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars like Hoehner to c. AD 47-48, during the reign of Emperor Claudius.\n\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:**\n    *   **Pisidia (Πισιδία, *Pisidia*):** A rugged, mountainous region in southern Anatolia (modern Turkey). Its main city was Pisidian Antioch (Acts 13:14), located on a plateau at an altitude of ~1,200m (3,900 ft). Travel through this area was notoriously difficult and dangerous due to harsh terrain and the threat of robbers (cf. 2 Cor 11:26, \"dangers from rivers, dangers from robbers\").\n    *   **Pamphylia (Παμφυλία, *Pamphylia*):** The fertile coastal plain south of the Taurus Mountains and Pisidia. Its main port was Attalia, and its key city was Perga. The journey from the Pisidian highlands down to the Pamphylian coast involved a significant descent.\n    *   **The Route's Significance:** By choosing to travel overland westward through Pisidia, Paul and Barnabas were deliberately retracing their initial path (cf. Acts 13:13-14). This was a much harder route than simply sailing home from a closer port. This choice underscores the pastoral priority of the mission described in the preceding verses.\n\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** The primary recipient is Theophilus (Acts 1:1), a likely high-ranking Gentile believer. The wider audience is the burgeoning Christian church, composed of both Jews and Gentiles, who needed a definitive, Spirit-inspired account of their own origins and the apostolic pattern for mission.\n\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke is writing as a careful historian (*diegesis*, \"narrative,\" Luke 1:1) and theologian to provide certainty about the gospel's spread. He includes this seemingly minor travel detail to reinforce a major theme: the apostolic mission was not a hit-and-run affair but a deep commitment to the long-term health of the churches they planted.\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology:</strong> This event takes place during the First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars like Hoehner to c. AD 47-48, during the reign of Emperor Claudius.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Pisidia (Πισιδία, <em>Pisidia</em>):</strong> A rugged, mountainous region in southern Anatolia (modern Turkey). Its main city was Pisidian Antioch (Acts 13:14), located on a plateau at an altitude of ~1,200m (3,900 ft). Travel through this area was notoriously difficult and dangerous due to harsh terrain and the threat of robbers (cf. 2 Cor 11:26, \"dangers from rivers, dangers from robbers\").</li>\n<li><strong>Pamphylia (Παμφυλία, <em>Pamphylia</em>):</strong> The fertile coastal plain south of the Taurus Mountains and Pisidia. Its main port was Attalia, and its key city was Perga. The journey from the Pisidian highlands down to the Pamphylian coast involved a significant descent.</li>\n<li><strong>The Route's Significance:</strong> By choosing to travel overland westward through Pisidia, Paul and Barnabas were deliberately retracing their initial path (cf. Acts 13:13-14). This was a much harder route than simply sailing home from a closer port. This choice underscores the pastoral priority of the mission described in the preceding verses.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Original Audience Identification:</strong> The primary recipient is Theophilus (Acts 1:1), a likely high-ranking Gentile believer. The wider audience is the burgeoning Christian church, composed of both Jews and Gentiles, who needed a definitive, Spirit-inspired account of their own origins and the apostolic pattern for mission.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):</strong> Luke is writing as a careful historian (<em>diegesis</em>, \"narrative,\" Luke 1:1) and theologian to provide certainty about the gospel's spread. He includes this seemingly minor travel detail to reinforce a major theme: the apostolic mission was not a hit-and-run affair but a deep commitment to the long-term health of the churches they planted.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\n\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax:** The structure is simple and efficient. It is a single clause led by the conjunction καί (*kai*, \"and\"), linking it to the preceding actions.\n    *   The key action is described by an aorist active participle, διελθόντες (*dielthontes*, \"having passed through\"). This participle of attendant circumstance describes the action that precedes the main verb. It implies a completed traversal of the region, not just a quick pass. The root verb διέρχομαι (*dierchomai*) often means to travel throughout an area for the purpose of ministry (cf. Acts 8:40; 20:25).\n    *   The main verb is ἦλθον (*ēlthon*, \"they came\"), a simple aorist indicative. It states the historical fact of their arrival in the next region. The grammar emphasizes the journey *through* Pisidia as the necessary prelude to their arrival *in* Pamphylia.\n\n*   **The Why Imperative (Why this detail?):** Luke includes this verse to answer the unspoken question: \"How did they get from the inland cities of Derbe and Lystra back to the sea?\" His answer highlights their pastoral strategy. They did not take the easiest route home. They took the route that allowed them to revisit the churches in Iconium and Pisidian Antioch, fulfilling the mission described in verse 22 (\"strengthening the souls of the disciples, encouraging them to continue in the faith\"). The geographical movement serves a theological and pastoral purpose.\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Linguistic Mechanics &amp; Syntax:</strong> The structure is simple and efficient. It is a single clause led by the conjunction καί (<em>kai</em>, \"and\"), linking it to the preceding actions.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The key action is described by an aorist active participle, διελθόντες (<em>dielthontes</em>, \"having passed through\"). This participle of attendant circumstance describes the action that precedes the main verb. It implies a completed traversal of the region, not just a quick pass. The root verb διέρχομαι (<em>dierchomai</em>) often means to travel throughout an area for the purpose of ministry (cf. Acts 8:40; 20:25).</li>\n<li>The main verb is ἦλθον (<em>ēlthon</em>, \"they came\"), a simple aorist indicative. It states the historical fact of their arrival in the next region. The grammar emphasizes the journey <em>through</em> Pisidia as the necessary prelude to their arrival <em>in</em> Pamphylia.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>The Why Imperative (Why this detail?):</strong> Luke includes this verse to answer the unspoken question: \"How did they get from the inland cities of Derbe and Lystra back to the sea?\" His answer highlights their pastoral strategy. They did not take the easiest route home. They took the route that allowed them to revisit the churches in Iconium and Pisidian Antioch, fulfilling the mission described in verse 22 (\"strengthening the souls of the disciples, encouraging them to continue in the faith\"). The geographical movement serves a theological and pastoral purpose.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** This verse is a small part of the great Acts 1:8 trajectory: the gospel moving from Jerusalem, to Judea and Samaria, and to the \"end of the earth.\" This journey into Gentile territory is a direct fulfillment of that commission. The *Christo-telic terminus* (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the building of Christ's body, the Church, for which He died and rose again (Eph 5:25-27). The missionaries are acting as agents of the ascended Christ, who builds His church through His Spirit-filled people (Matt 16:18).\n\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:**\n    *   **Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"):** This passage, in its context, provides a foundational pattern for church planting and pastoral care. It demonstrates that the apostolic mission included both evangelism (founding churches) and edification (strengthening them).\n    *   **Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\"):** The entire missionary journey is empowered and directed by the Holy Spirit (Acts 13:2, 4). This travel is one component of that Spirit-led work.\n\n*   **Tripartite Synthesis:** While Christian commentators focus on the pastoral strategy, it's worth noting the Jewish context of travel. Journeys were often dangerous and undertaken with purpose. A rabbi traveling would be expected to teach along the way. Paul and Barnabas, operating as Jewish apostles, embody this principle: their travel is never \"empty\" but is always an occasion for ministry, fulfilling their mandate to be a \"light to the Gentiles\" (Acts 13:47, quoting Isa 49:6).\n",
      "phase_f_canonical_html": "<h3>Canonical Connection</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):</strong> This verse is a small part of the great Acts 1:8 trajectory: the gospel moving from Jerusalem, to Judea and Samaria, and to the \"end of the earth.\" This journey into Gentile territory is a direct fulfillment of that commission. The <em>Christo-telic terminus</em> (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the building of Christ's body, the Church, for which He died and rose again (Eph 5:25-27). The missionaries are acting as agents of the ascended Christ, who builds His church through His Spirit-filled people (Matt 16:18).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"):</strong> This passage, in its context, provides a foundational pattern for church planting and pastoral care. It demonstrates that the apostolic mission included both evangelism (founding churches) and edification (strengthening them).</li>\n<li><strong>Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\"):</strong> The entire missionary journey is empowered and directed by the Holy Spirit (Acts 13:2, 4). This travel is one component of that Spirit-led work.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Tripartite Synthesis:</strong> While Christian commentators focus on the pastoral strategy, it's worth noting the Jewish context of travel. Journeys were often dangerous and undertaken with purpose. A rabbi traveling would be expected to teach along the way. Paul and Barnabas, operating as Jewish apostles, embody this principle: their travel is never \"empty\" but is always an occasion for ministry, fulfilling their mandate to be a \"light to the Gentiles\" (Acts 13:47, quoting Isa 49:6).</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
