      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:21-28 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\nκαὶ λαλήσαντες ἐν Περγῇ τὸν λόγον κατέβησαν εἰς Ἀττάλειαν\n\n***\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 7 rows = 49 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and / also / even |\n| 2 | λαλήσαντες | lalēsantes | G2980 | λαλέω | V-AAP-NPM | having spoken / after speaking |\n| 3 | ἐν | en | G1722 | ἐν | Prep | in / at / among |\n| 4 | Περγῇ | Pergē | G4011 | Πέργη | N-DSF | Perga |\n| 5 | τὸν | ton | G3588 | ὁ | T-ASM | the |\n| 6 | λόγον | logon | G3056 | λόγος | N-ASM | word / message / account |\n| 7 | κατέβησαν | katebēsan | G2597 | καταβαίνω | V-AAI-3P | they went down / descended |\n| 8 | εἰς | eis | G1519 | εἰς | Prep | into / to |\n| 9 | Ἀττάλειαν | Attaleian | G825 | Ἀττάλεια | N-ASF | Attalia |\n\n***\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\nAnd having spoken in Perga the word, they went down into Attalia.\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\nAfter they had preached the word in Perga, they went down to Attalia.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\nAnd after they had faithfully spoken the word [of the gospel] in the city of Perga, they descended [in elevation] to the port city of Attalia.\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:21-28 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Script (NA28)</strong>\nκαὶ λαλήσαντες ἐν Περγῇ τὸν λόγον κατέβησαν εἰς Ἀττάλειαν</p>\n<hr>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 7 rows = 49 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and / also / even</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>λαλήσαντες</td>\n<td>lalēsantes</td>\n<td>G2980</td>\n<td>λαλέω</td>\n<td>V-AAP-NPM</td>\n<td>having spoken / after speaking</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>ἐν</td>\n<td>en</td>\n<td>G1722</td>\n<td>ἐν</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>in / at / among</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Περγῇ</td>\n<td>Pergē</td>\n<td>G4011</td>\n<td>Πέργη</td>\n<td>N-DSF</td>\n<td>Perga</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>τὸν</td>\n<td>ton</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-ASM</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>λόγον</td>\n<td>logon</td>\n<td>G3056</td>\n<td>λόγος</td>\n<td>N-ASM</td>\n<td>word / message / account</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>κατέβησαν</td>\n<td>katebēsan</td>\n<td>G2597</td>\n<td>καταβαίνω</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3P</td>\n<td>they went down / descended</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>eis</td>\n<td>G1519</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>into / to</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>Ἀττάλειαν</td>\n<td>Attaleian</td>\n<td>G825</td>\n<td>Ἀττάλεια</td>\n<td>N-ASF</td>\n<td>Attalia</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)</strong>\nAnd having spoken in Perga the word, they went down into Attalia.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)</strong>\nAfter they had preached the word in Perga, they went down to Attalia.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)</strong>\nAnd after they had faithfully spoken the word [of the gospel] in the city of Perga, they descended [in elevation] to the port city of Attalia.</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** God honors faithful completion and strategic movement in His service; the proclamation of His word is the non-negotiable priority that must precede every new step.\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):** The human tendency is to either quit before a task is done (like John Mark earlier in Perga) or to wander aimlessly without a clear sense of purpose or completion. This verse addresses the need for faithful perseverance and strategic direction.\n*   **Shared Particulars:** Believers today are also called to be witnesses in their own \"Pergas\" (places of work, community, even difficulty) and need wisdom to know when a season of ministry is complete and it is time to move to the next \"Attalia\" (the next task or phase).\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** Because Christ finished His work on the cross with the cry \"It is finished!\" (John 19:30), believers are freed and empowered by His Spirit to finish the work He has given them. Our perseverance is a fruit of His.\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* Identify one task God has given you. Before moving on to something new, ask what it looks like to \"speak the word\" there one last time, bringing it to a faithful conclusion.\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Cultivate the character of a finisher. Resist the urge to abandon projects, relationships, or commitments prematurely. Trust God for the grace to be steadfast.\n    *   *Relational:* In your church or small group, celebrate the completion of ministry seasons. Honor those who have served faithfully and commission them as they move on to the next stage, just as Antioch sent and received the apostles.\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** The passage reveals a God who directs His servants with strategic purpose. We worship Him as the Lord of the mission, the One who charts the course and empowers the journey. \"Lord, you are the Master Strategist, who guides your servants' feet and ensures your word is proclaimed in every place you intend.\"\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> God honors faithful completion and strategic movement in His service; the proclamation of His word is the non-negotiable priority that must precede every new step.</li>\n<li><strong>FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):</strong> The human tendency is to either quit before a task is done (like John Mark earlier in Perga) or to wander aimlessly without a clear sense of purpose or completion. This verse addresses the need for faithful perseverance and strategic direction.</li>\n<li><strong>Shared Particulars:</strong> Believers today are also called to be witnesses in their own \"Pergas\" (places of work, community, even difficulty) and need wisdom to know when a season of ministry is complete and it is time to move to the next \"Attalia\" (the next task or phase).</li>\n<li><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> Because Christ finished His work on the cross with the cry \"It is finished!\" (John 19:30), believers are freed and empowered by His Spirit to finish the work He has given them. Our perseverance is a fruit of His.</li>\n<li><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\":</em> Identify one task God has given you. Before moving on to something new, ask what it looks like to \"speak the word\" there one last time, bringing it to a faithful conclusion.</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\":</em> Cultivate the character of a finisher. Resist the urge to abandon projects, relationships, or commitments prematurely. Trust God for the grace to be steadfast.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> In your church or small group, celebrate the completion of ministry seasons. Honor those who have served faithfully and commission them as they move on to the next stage, just as Antioch sent and received the apostles.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong> The passage reveals a God who directs His servants with strategic purpose. We worship Him as the Lord of the mission, the One who charts the course and empowers the journey. \"Lord, you are the Master Strategist, who guides your servants' feet and ensures your word is proclaimed in every place you intend.\"</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:25 — \"having spoken in Perga the word, they went down\"\nKEY TERM:     λόγος (*logos*, \"the word/message\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: Faithful preaching precedes strategic movement to the next mission phase.\nIMAGE:        A dusty road descending from an inland city to a sunlit seaport.\nAPPLICATION:  For the church: faithfully conclude one ministry task before starting the next.\nDOXOLOGY:     Praise to the God who directs our steps and completes His mission.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:25 — &quot;having spoken in Perga the word, they went down&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>λόγος (*logos*, &quot;the word/message&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>Faithful preaching precedes strategic movement to the next mission phase.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>A dusty road descending from an inland city to a sunlit seaport.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>For the church: faithfully conclude one ministry task before starting the next.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Praise to the God who directs our steps and completes His mission.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\n\nHave you ever been tempted to leave a difficult task unfinished? On their first missionary journey, Paul and Barnabas returned to the city of Perga, a place where their young assistant, John Mark, had previously deserted them. It could have been an awkward, painful stop. But they didn't skip it. Luke tells us simply that after they had \"spoken the word in Perga, they went down to Attalia\" (Acts 14:25).\n\nTheir priority was clear: faithfully deliver God's message, the λόγος (*logos*, \"word\"), one more time. Only after completing that ministry task did they make the strategic move down to the seaport of Attalia to catch a ship for home. Their journey wasn't aimless; it was a deliberate sequence of preaching, strengthening, and moving on. Because Jesus declared His own work \"finished\" on the cross (John 19:30), we are empowered by His Spirit to see our own assignments through. This week, consider one area where you're called to be faithful. Ask God for the grace to \"speak the word\" there, completing your task with integrity before you look to the next horizon.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever been tempted to leave a difficult task unfinished? On their first missionary journey, Paul and Barnabas returned to the city of Perga, a place where their young assistant, John Mark, had previously deserted them. It could have been an awkward, painful stop. But they didn't skip it. Luke tells us simply that after they had \"spoken the word in Perga, they went down to Attalia\" (Acts 14:25).</p>\n<p>Their priority was clear: faithfully deliver God's message, the λόγος (<em>logos</em>, \"word\"), one more time. Only after completing that ministry task did they make the strategic move down to the seaport of Attalia to catch a ship for home. Their journey wasn't aimless; it was a deliberate sequence of preaching, strengthening, and moving on. Because Jesus declared His own work \"finished\" on the cross (John 19:30), we are empowered by His Spirit to see our own assignments through. This week, consider one area where you're called to be faithful. Ask God for the grace to \"speak the word\" there, completing your task with integrity before you look to the next horizon.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n\n1.  What two cities are mentioned in Acts 14:25?\n    A: Perga (the inland city) and Attalia (the coastal port).\n2.  What did Paul and Barnabas do in Perga before they left?\n    A: They spoke \"the word,\" meaning they preached the gospel message.\n3.  What does this verse teach about the pattern of apostolic ministry?\n    A: It shows that ministry is strategic and methodical. The proclamation of the gospel is the priority that must be completed before moving to the next phase of the mission.\n4.  How can a believer or a church apply the principle from this verse?\n    A: The church can apply this by seeking to faithfully conclude one ministry task or season with integrity before launching into the next one, ensuring priorities are in order.\n\n***\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What two cities are mentioned in Acts 14:25?\n    A: Perga (the inland city) and Attalia (the coastal port).</li>\n<li>What did Paul and Barnabas do in Perga before they left?\n    A: They spoke \"the word,\" meaning they preached the gospel message.</li>\n<li>What does this verse teach about the pattern of apostolic ministry?\n    A: It shows that ministry is strategic and methodical. The proclamation of the gospel is the priority that must be completed before moving to the next phase of the mission.</li>\n<li>How can a believer or a church apply the principle from this verse?\n    A: The church can apply this by seeking to faithfully conclude one ministry task or season with integrity before launching into the next one, ensuring priorities are in order.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>",
