rama depicting the fulfillment of the Great Commission. Before a radiant, unseen throne, a vast, diverse multitude from every nation, tribe, and tongue (Revelation 7:9) stands in worship. Their faces are lifted in joy. The image is not of a single person, but of the corporate, global fruit of the mission that began in verses like Acts 14:26. Volumetric light, cinematic.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n\n## Slide Deck Sidecar\n```markdown\n---\nbook: \"Acts\"\nchapter: \"14\"\nsection: \"26\"\nvisual_palette: warm amber, low-key key-light, gold-hour skin tones\n---\n\n# Acts 14:26 — The Missionary Report: Grace Entrusted, Grace Fulfilled\nThis single verse encapsulates the entire theology of Christian mission: a divine entrustment to God's grace, requiring faithful completion and accountable reporting back to the sending church.\n\n*Slide deck: 7 sections, 7 total sub-slides, ≤5 bullets per slide.*\n\n## The Text\nThe verse marks the physical and theological completion of the first missionary journey, bringing the narrative full circle back to its starting point in Antioch.\n\n- κἀκεῖθεν (*kakeithen*) — \"and from there\" (Attalia)\n- ἀπέπλευσαν (*apepleusan*) — \"they sailed away\" (return voyage)\n- ἦσαν παραδεδομένοι (*ēsan paradedomenoi*) — \"they had been entrusted\" (divine passive)\n- τῇ χάριτι (*tē chariti*) — \"to the grace\" (the sphere of empowerment)\n- ὃ ἐπλήρωσαν (*ho eplērōsan*) — \"which they fulfilled\" (a completed task)\n\n### Detail\nThe Greek text of Acts 14:26 is a masterclass in theological compression. The journey concludes with a sail from Attalia back to Antioch, the very city ὅθεν (*hothen*, \"from where\") the mission began (Acts 13:1-3). The key phrase, ἦσαν παραδεδομένοι τῇ χάριτι τοῦ θεοῦ (*ēsan paradedomenoi tē chariti tou theou*, \"they had been entrusted to the grace of God\"), uses a periphrastic perfect/pluperfect construction. This highlights a past action with ongoing results: they were handed over to God's grace at the start, and they remained in that state of entrustment. The passive voice points to God as the primary actor. Grace, χάρις (*charis*), is not just a divine attitude but God's active enablement for the ἔργον (*ergon*, \"work\") they were given. The final verb, ἐπλήρωσαν (*eplērōsan*, \"they fulfilled\"), is a conclusive aorist, declaring the mission a successfully completed whole.\n\n## The Thesis\nThe core truth is that God's grace is the beginning, middle, and end of all true ministry. He commissions, He empowers, and to Him belongs the glory for the completed work.\n\n- Subject — The return of Paul and Barnabas to their sending church\n- Complement — They faithfully completed the work God's grace entrusted to them\n- Big Idea — God's grace is the sole resource for the mission He assigns\n- Image — A ship returning to its home harbor\n- Principle — Ministry requires sending, empowering, and reporting\n\n### Detail\nThe Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\") is the missionaries' return. The Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\") is the successful, grace-powered completion of their task. This yields the Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"): all Christian mission is a closed loop of grace. It begins with an entrustment from God, operates within the sphere of His grace, and concludes with a report of what He has accomplished. The Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\") is that God's work must be done God's way—by His power and for His glory, with accountability to His people. This stands against all human self-reliance or freelance ministry that lacks a sending and reporting structure.\n\n## Big Picture\nThis verse is the formal conclusion of the first great wave of Gentile missions, setting the stage for the book's central theological debate at the Jerusalem Council.\n\n- Book Thesis — The Spirit-empowered spread of the gospel (Acts 1:8)\n- Section Arc — Concludes the First Missionary Journey (Acts 13-14)\n- Genre — Historical Narrative establishing a normative pattern\n- Salvation History — Church Age, gospel expanding to the Gentiles\n- Context — Immediately precedes the report to the church (14:27)\n\n### Detail\nIn the arc of Acts, this verse is a crucial hinge. It closes the narrative of the first missionary journey, which proved that God was powerfully saving Gentiles apart from the Mosaic Law. This success is the data that will be brought to the Jerusalem Council in Acts 15. The pericope (\"the literary unit\") of Acts 14:21-28 shows the consolidation of the work before the return. This verse places the entire endeavor within its proper theological frame: it was God's work, done by God's grace. This occurs in the dispensation of Grace, demonstrating the New Covenant's power among the nations, fulfilling the promise to Abraham (Gen 12:3) that his seed would be a blessing to the world.\n\n## Setting\nThe scene shifts from the mission field of Galatia back to the home base: Antioch, the vibrant, multicultural hub of early Gentile Christianity.\n\n- Location — Antioch on the Orontes (modern Antakya, Turkey)\n- Date — c. AD 48-49\n- Significance — The first Gentile-majority church; the first missionary-sending hub\n- Audience — Theophilus and the wider Greco-Roman world\n- Author's Purpose — To provide a reliable, theological account of Christian origins\n\n### Detail\nAntioch was the third city of the Roman Empire, a strategic center for commerce and ideas. It was here that followers of Jesus were first called Χριστιανούς (*Christianous*, \"Christians,\" Acts 11:26). Its significance as the sending church cannot be overstated; it represents the new, non-Judean center of the faith's expansion. By returning here, Paul and Barnabas affirm the authority and role of the local church in God's global mission. Luke's purpose in recording this is to assure his reader, Theophilus, that the Gentile mission was not a rogue movement but a divinely commissioned, orderly, and accountable expansion of the one true faith, empowered by God's grace.\n\n## Verse-Level Craft\nThe grammar of the verse carries its theology: a divine passive, a dative of sphere, and a conclusive aorist tense tell the whole story of grace.\n\n- Key Verb — ἦσαν παραδεδομένοι (*ēsan paradedomenoi*, \"they had been entrusted\")\n- Key Noun — τῇ χάριτι (*tē chariti*, \"to the grace\")\n- Voice — Passive voice points to God as the entrusting agent\n- Tense — Aorist ἐπλήρωσαν (*eplērōsan*) signifies a completed work\n- Structure — The verse forms an inclusio with the sending in Acts 13:1-3\n\n### Detail\nThe linguistic genius of this verse lies in its perfect fusion of grammar and theology. The periphrastic perfect/pluperfect passive (ἦσαν παραδεδομένοι, *ēsan paradedomenoi*) shows that the missionaries were the objects of God's action, not the subjects of their own ambition. They were \"handed over\" into a state of trust. The object of this trust was τῇ χάριτι (*tē chariti*, \"the grace\") of God—the dative case marking grace as the divine atmosphere in which they lived and worked. The entire journey is then summarized as the ἔργον (*ergon*, \"work\") which they fulfilled (ἐπλήρωσαν, *eplērōsan*). The aorist tense of this final verb presents the arduous, multi-year journey as a single, successfully finished task. The structure creates a perfect bookend: sent from Antioch in grace (Acts 13:3), returned to Antioch having completed the work in grace (Acts 14:26).\n\n## Canonical Connection\nThe pattern of being sent, empowered, and reporting back fits a mission motif that runs from Genesis to Revelation, culminating in Christ's own mission.\n\n- Motif — The Divine Commission (Sending of Abram, Moses, Christ, the Church)\n- Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\") — Establishes the pattern of a sending, supporting local church\n- Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\") — Grace is the power for both salvation and service\n- Christo-telic Terminus — The final report at the Bema Seat of Christ (2 Cor 5:10)\n- Apostolic Pattern — Accountability is integral to mission\n\n### Detail\nThis verse exemplifies the canonical motif of the divine commission. God is a sending God. He sent Abram (Gen 12:1), Moses (Ex 3:10), and ultimately His Son (John 3:17). Christ, the ultimate Sent One, now sends His church (John 20:21). Acts 14:26 is this principle in action. This has profound implications for Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"), establishing the local church as the proper agent for sending and receiving missionaries. It also impacts Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"), showing that grace is not static but dynamic—the power that saves is the power that sends. The entire pattern points toward the Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\"): the final accountability every believer will give for their \"work\" at the judgment seat of Christ (2 Cor 5:10; Rom 14:12).\n\n## Life Applications\nThe verse calls us to see all our work as an entrustment of grace that requires faithful execution and joyful accountability.\n\n- FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus\") — Our tendency to rely on our own strength for God's work\n- Redemptive Indicative — Christ perfectly fulfilled His work, securing our grace\n- Personal — View your life and tasks as a stewardship of grace\n- Relational — Actively support and pray for your church's missionaries\n- Doxological Response — Worship God as the one who entrusts and enables by grace\n\n### Detail\nThe Fallen Condition Focus (\"the broken human condition the passage addresses\") is our default mode of self-reliance. We act as owners, not stewards. The Redemptive Indicative is the gospel cure: Jesus, the ultimate steward, perfectly fulfilled His mission, and now provides His grace as our sole resource (2 Cor 12:9). This leads to the imperative. Personally, we must reframe our tasks—parenting, our job, our church service—as an ἔργον (*ergon*, \"work\") entrusted to us by God, to be fulfilled in His power. Relationally, we must embody the Antioch church's role by actively sending, supporting, and receiving reports from those on the mission field. The proper Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis\") is to praise God not for our work, but for His grace that works through us (1 Cor 15:10).\n```",
