td>N-GSM</td>\n<td>God</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>eis</td>\n<td>G1519</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>for / unto</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>τὸ</td>\n<td>to</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>Art-ASN</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>14</td>\n<td>ἔργον</td>\n<td>ergon</td>\n<td>G2041</td>\n<td>ἔργον</td>\n<td>N-ASN</td>\n<td>work / task</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15</td>\n<td>ὃ</td>\n<td>ho</td>\n<td>G3739</td>\n<td>ὅς</td>\n<td>Pro-Rel-ASN</td>\n<td>which</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>16</td>\n<td>ἐπλήρωσαν</td>\n<td>eplērōsan</td>\n<td>G4137</td>\n<td>πληρόω</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3P</td>\n<td>they fulfilled / completed</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation (Formal Equivalence)</strong></p>\n<p>And from there they sailed away to Antioch, from where they had been entrusted to the grace of God for the work which they fulfilled.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation (Optimal Equivalence)</strong></p>\n<p>From there they sailed back to Antioch, where they had been commended to the grace of God for the work they had now completed.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation (Meaning-Based Expansion)</strong></p>\n<p>And from that port [of Attalia], they sailed away, returning to Antioch [in Syria], the very place from which they had been previously entrusted to the unearned favor and divine enablement of God for the specific mission [He had assigned them], a work which they had now brought to its complete fulfillment.</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\")**: All effective Christian ministry is a work entrusted by God, empowered by His grace, and accountable to His people.\n\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\")**: The passage addresses the human tendency toward self-reliance and pride in ministry (the individual FCF) and the corresponding tendency for churches to neglect their role in formally commissioning, supporting, and holding accountable those they send out (the corporate FCF).\n\n*   **Shared Particulars**: Like Paul and Barnabas, believers today are called to specific \"works\" by God. Like the church at Antioch, local churches today are called to be sending bases. We share the same resource for the task: the grace of God.\n\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding)**: Before we are ever sent to do a work for God, the Son was sent to do a work for us. Jesus Christ was the ultimate one \"entrusted\" with a mission—to live, die, and rise again for our salvation. He perfectly \"fulfilled\" that work, declaring \"It is finished!\" (John 19:30). Because His work is complete, we are now given His grace not only for our salvation but for our service.\n\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace)**:\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\"*: Identify the specific \"work\" God has entrusted to you—in your family, vocation, or church—and consciously rely on His grace, not your own strength, to fulfill it.\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\"*: Cultivate a deep sense of being an \"entrusted\" person. Your life and ministry are not your own; they are a stewardship from God.\n    *   *Relational*: Actively participate in the missionary life of your local church. Pray for, give to, and communicate with the missionaries your church has \"entrusted to the grace of God.\" Insist on hearing their reports when they return.\n    *   *Public / Vocational*: View your secular work as a divine entrustment. Fulfill your professional duties with excellence as a way of completing the \"work\" God has given you in that sphere.\n\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\")**: The passage reveals God as the great **Entruster and Enabler**. We adore Him because He does not send us out on our own but commits us entirely to the care and power of His own grace. \"To You, O God, be the glory for the work you commission and the grace by which it is fulfilled.\"\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\")</strong>: All effective Christian ministry is a work entrusted by God, empowered by His grace, and accountable to His people.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\")</strong>: The passage addresses the human tendency toward self-reliance and pride in ministry (the individual FCF) and the corresponding tendency for churches to neglect their role in formally commissioning, supporting, and holding accountable those they send out (the corporate FCF).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Shared Particulars</strong>: Like Paul and Barnabas, believers today are called to specific \"works\" by God. Like the church at Antioch, local churches today are called to be sending bases. We share the same resource for the task: the grace of God.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding)</strong>: Before we are ever sent to do a work for God, the Son was sent to do a work for us. Jesus Christ was the ultimate one \"entrusted\" with a mission—to live, die, and rise again for our salvation. He perfectly \"fulfilled\" that work, declaring \"It is finished!\" (John 19:30). Because His work is complete, we are now given His grace not only for our salvation but for our service.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace)</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\"</em>: Identify the specific \"work\" God has entrusted to you—in your family, vocation, or church—and consciously rely on His grace, not your own strength, to fulfill it.</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\"</em>: Cultivate a deep sense of being an \"entrusted\" person. Your life and ministry are not your own; they are a stewardship from God.</li>\n<li><em>Relational</em>: Actively participate in the missionary life of your local church. Pray for, give to, and communicate with the missionaries your church has \"entrusted to the grace of God.\" Insist on hearing their reports when they return.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational</em>: View your secular work as a divine entrustment. Fulfill your professional duties with excellence as a way of completing the \"work\" God has given you in that sphere.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\")</strong>: The passage reveals God as the great <strong>Entruster and Enabler</strong>. We adore Him because He does not send us out on our own but commits us entirely to the care and power of His own grace. \"To You, O God, be the glory for the work you commission and the grace by which it is fulfilled.\"</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:26b — \"...entrusted to the grace of God for the work they had now completed.\"\nKEY TERM:     παραδεδομένοι (*paradedomenoi*, \"having been entrusted\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: God's grace commissions and completes the work He gives His people.\nIMAGE:        A ship returning safely to its home harbor after a long voyage.\nAPPLICATION:  Pray by name for a missionary your church has sent out.\nDOXOLOGY:     Praise to the God who entrusts us to His all-sufficient grace.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:26b — &quot;...entrusted to the grace of God for the work they had now completed.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>παραδεδομένοι (*paradedomenoi*, &quot;having been entrusted&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>God&#x27;s grace commissions and completes the work He gives His people.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>A ship returning safely to its home harbor after a long voyage.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>Pray by name for a missionary your church has sent out.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Praise to the God who entrusts us to His all-sufficient grace.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever felt the relief and joy of coming home after a long, difficult journey? That’s the scene in Acts 14:26. The apostles Paul and Barnabas are sailing back to their home church in Antioch after their first-ever missionary trip—a journey filled with riots, stonings, and incredible fruit. Luke, the author, summarizes the whole enterprise in one powerful sentence: they were returning to the place where they had been \"entrusted to the grace of God for the work they had now completed.\"\n\nThink about that phrase: \"entrusted to the grace of God.\" Their mission wasn't powered by their own courage, eloquence, or strategy. From the moment they left, they were handed over to God's active, enabling power. His grace was their provision, their protection, and their power source. And now, returning home, they could report that the work was done. The same grace that sent them out brought them home and made the work fruitful.\n\nThis gives us a powerful model for our own lives. The ultimate \"Sent One,\" Jesus, perfectly completed the work the Father gave Him on the cross (John 19:30). Because of His finished work, that same grace is now available to us for whatever task He has entrusted to us. Whether in our homes, our jobs, or our specific church ministries, we are not left to our own resources. We too have been entrusted to the all-sufficient grace of God. This week, could you pray for a missionary your church has sent out, asking God to make His grace their tangible resource, just as it was for Paul and Barnabas?\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever felt the relief and joy of coming home after a long, difficult journey? That’s the scene in Acts 14:26. The apostles Paul and Barnabas are sailing back to their home church in Antioch after their first-ever missionary trip—a journey filled with riots, stonings, and incredible fruit. Luke, the author, summarizes the whole enterprise in one powerful sentence: they were returning to the place where they had been \"entrusted to the grace of God for the work they had now completed.\"</p>\n<p>Think about that phrase: \"entrusted to the grace of God.\" Their mission wasn't powered by their own courage, eloquence, or strategy. From the moment they left, they were handed over to God's active, enabling power. His grace was their provision, their protection, and their power source. And now, returning home, they could report that the work was done. The same grace that sent them out brought them home and made the work fruitful.</p>\n<p>This gives us a powerful model for our own lives. The ultimate \"Sent One,\" Jesus, perfectly completed the work the Father gave Him on the cross (John 19:30). Because of His finished work, that same grace is now available to us for whatever task He has entrusted to us. Whether in our homes, our jobs, or our specific church ministries, we are not left to our own resources. We too have been entrusted to the all-sufficient grace of God. This week, could you pray for a missionary your church has sent out, asking God to make His grace their tangible resource, just as it was for Paul and Barnabas?</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  To which city did Paul and Barnabas return to report on their mission?\n    A: Antioch in Syria, their sending church.\n2.  What does the key phrase \"entrusted to the grace of God\" tell us about their mission?\n    A: It shows their mission was not based on their own strength but was commissioned by and empowered by God's divine enablement from start to finish.\n3.  What does this verse teach us about God's role in Christian ministry?\n    A: It teaches that God is the sovereign initiator who entrusts His people with specific work, and He is the faithful enabler who provides the grace necessary to complete it.\n4.  What is one concrete way you can apply the pattern of this verse this week?\n    A: I can pray for a specific missionary sent out by my church, asking God to sustain them by His grace as they fulfill their work.\n",
