ng imperative).\nGate 21: PASS — All stanzas are strict AABB, with sonorous, exact rhymes.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is a single fenced code block with the <code>text</code> tag.\nGate 23: PASS — All lines counted and confirmed to be between 7 and 8 syllables.\nGate 24: PASS — Title is a 4-word concrete image, memorable and drawn from the core metaphor.</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-text\">Title: The Harbor of Grace\nStyle: Folk, Male vocals, acoustic guitar, upright bass, gentle fiddle, natural reverb, Large room acoustics, live room bleed, thick mid-range, wooden resonance, environmental air, no noise reduction, raw analog capture, tape saturation\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nFrom Antioch we sailed away (A)\nTo bring the light of day (A)\nThrough bitter pain and stoning strife (B)\nWe offered endless life (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nEntrusted to the grace of God (A)\nThe path the Spirit trod (A)\nThe work He gave is now complete (B)\nA victory so sweet (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nWe have a mission of our own (A)\nNot by our strength alone (A)\nBut by Your grace, O Lord, we stand (B)\nHeld in Your mighty hand (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nOne day we'll reach the final shore (A)\nAnd stand before the door (A)\nWe'll give account for all we've done (B)\nBefore the Risen Son (B)\n\n[Outro]\nWe sailed back to the shore (A)\nAnd trusted Him once more (A)\nThe work is done, the journey ends (B)\nOn His great grace depends (B)\n\n[End]\n</code></pre>",
      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\")**: The return of Paul and Barnabas to their sending church in Antioch at the conclusion of their first missionary journey.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\")**: Their return marked the faithful completion of the specific work to which they had been divinely entrusted by the grace of God.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\")**: God's grace is both the authority for and the enablement of the mission He entrusts to His church, which requires faithful completion and accountable reporting.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\")</strong>: The return of Paul and Barnabas to their sending church in Antioch at the conclusion of their first missionary journey.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\")</strong>: Their return marked the faithful completion of the specific work to which they had been divinely entrusted by the grace of God.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\")</strong>: God's grace is both the authority for and the enablement of the mission He entrusts to His church, which requires faithful completion and accountable reporting.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role**: The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, fulfilling Christ's commission (Acts 1:8). This verse serves as the formal conclusion to the first major missionary journey (Acts 13:1–14:28), a pivotal section that demonstrates the gospel's successful leap into the Gentile world. It is a moment of resolution and accountability, showing a completed cycle of sending, working, and returning.\n\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc**: This single verse is the capstone of the entire First Missionary Journey narrative. It follows the missionaries as they retrace their steps, strengthening the disciples and appointing elders in the newly planted churches (Acts 14:21-25). It immediately precedes their formal report to the church (Acts 14:27), setting the stage for the crucial Jerusalem Council in Acts 15, which would theologically ratify the Gentile mission they had just completed.\n\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic**: The genre is **Historical Narrative**. The governing hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to distinguish description from prescription. This verse *describes* the pattern of missionary work: being sent out from a local church, operating under God's grace, and reporting back upon completion. While not a direct command, it establishes a powerful and normative apostolic pattern for church-based missions and accountability (cf. Heb 13:17).\n\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational)**: This event occurs firmly within the **Church Age** (Dispensation of Grace), under the New Covenant. It represents a key moment in the \"times of the Gentiles\" (Luke 21:24; Rom 11:25), where the gospel's focus expands dramatically beyond its Jewish origins, fulfilling God's promise to Abraham that in him all the families of the earth would be blessed (Gen 12:3).\n\n*   **Author & Attribution**: The author is Luke the physician, the companion of Paul, as part of his two-volume work Luke-Acts. This is the uniform testimony of the early church (e.g., Irenaeus, Muratorian Canon). The work is dated conservatively to the early AD 60s, likely composed in Rome during Paul's first imprisonment.\n\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors**: The verse is pulled forward by the preceding account of church planting and elder appointment (14:21-25), showing the fruit of the journey. It is pulled backward by the subsequent verse (14:27), which details the content of their report: \"all that God had done with them, and how he had opened a door of faith to the Gentiles.\"\n\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels**: This verse forms a pattern with the conclusions of Paul's other missionary journeys (Acts 18:22; Acts 21:7-17), where returning to a home base for reporting and fellowship is standard practice. The central theme of grace as the power for ministry is a constant refrain in Paul's own writings (1 Cor 15:10; 2 Cor 12:9; Eph 3:7-8).\n",
      "phase_c_big_picture_html": "<h3>Big Picture: Where this passage fits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Whole-Book Thesis &amp; Passage's Role</strong>: The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth, fulfilling Christ's commission (Acts 1:8). This verse serves as the formal conclusion to the first major missionary journey (Acts 13:1–14:28), a pivotal section that demonstrates the gospel's successful leap into the Gentile world. It is a moment of resolution and accountability, showing a completed cycle of sending, working, and returning.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Discourse / Section Arc</strong>: This single verse is the capstone of the entire First Missionary Journey narrative. It follows the missionaries as they retrace their steps, strengthening the disciples and appointing elders in the newly planted churches (Acts 14:21-25). It immediately precedes their formal report to the church (Acts 14:27), setting the stage for the crucial Jerusalem Council in Acts 15, which would theologically ratify the Gentile mission they had just completed.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Genre &amp; Hermeneutic</strong>: The genre is <strong>Historical Narrative</strong>. The governing hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to distinguish description from prescription. This verse <em>describes</em> the pattern of missionary work: being sent out from a local church, operating under God's grace, and reporting back upon completion. While not a direct command, it establishes a powerful and normative apostolic pattern for church-based missions and accountability (cf. Heb 13:17).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational)</strong>: This event occurs firmly within the <strong>Church Age</strong> (Dispensation of Grace), under the New Covenant. It represents a key moment in the \"times of the Gentiles\" (Luke 21:24; Rom 11:25), where the gospel's focus expands dramatically beyond its Jewish origins, fulfilling God's promise to Abraham that in him all the families of the earth would be blessed (Gen 12:3).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Author &amp; Attribution</strong>: The author is Luke the physician, the companion of Paul, as part of his two-volume work Luke-Acts. This is the uniform testimony of the early church (e.g., Irenaeus, Muratorian Canon). The work is dated conservatively to the early AD 60s, likely composed in Rome during Paul's first imprisonment.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Gravitational Neighbors</strong>: The verse is pulled forward by the preceding account of church planting and elder appointment (14:21-25), showing the fruit of the journey. It is pulled backward by the subsequent verse (14:27), which details the content of their report: \"all that God had done with them, and how he had opened a door of faith to the Gentiles.\"</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels</strong>: This verse forms a pattern with the conclusions of Paul's other missionary journeys (Acts 18:22; Acts 21:7-17), where returning to a home base for reporting and fellowship is standard practice. The central theme of grace as the power for ministry is a constant refrain in Paul's own writings (1 Cor 15:10; 2 Cor 12:9; Eph 3:7-8).</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology**: The conclusion of the first missionary journey is dated by conservative scholars (Hoehner, Bruce) to approximately AD 48-49. This places the event during the reign of Emperor Claudius in Rome.\n\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography**: The journey concludes with a sea voyage from Attalia (modern Antalya, Turkey), the main port of Pamphylia, back to Antioch on the Orontes (modern Antakya, Turkey, near the Syrian border). Antioch was a major metropolis, the third-largest city in the Roman Empire, and critically, the location of the first major Gentile-background church and the missionary-sending headquarters (Acts 11:19-26; 13:1-3).\n\n*   **Original Audience Identification**: Luke's primary audience is Theophilus (Acts 1:1), a likely high-ranking Roman official, and through him, the broader Greco-Roman world. He writes to provide an orderly and historically reliable account of the origins of the Christian faith, demonstrating its divine power, historical reality, and orderly expansion.\n\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text)**: Luke is writing as a careful historian and theologian, documenting the fulfillment of Christ's promises. His purpose is to assure his readers of the certainty of the things they have been taught (Luke 1:4), showing that the Gentile mission was not an accident or an innovation, but the direct, Spirit-led outworking of God's redemptive plan.\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology</strong>: The conclusion of the first missionary journey is dated by conservative scholars (Hoehner, Bruce) to approximately AD 48-49. This places the event during the reign of Emperor Claudius in Rome.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography</strong>: The journey concludes with a sea voyage from Attalia (modern Antalya, Turkey), the main port of Pamphylia, back to Antioch on the Orontes (modern Antakya, Turkey, near the Syrian border). Antioch was a major metropolis, the third-largest city in the Roman Empire, and critically, the location of the first major Gentile-background church and the missionary-sending headquarters (Acts 11:19-26; 13:1-3).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Original Audience Identification</strong>: Luke's primary audience is Theophilus (Acts 1:1), a likely high-ranking Roman official, and through him, the broader Greco-Roman world. He writes to provide an orderly and historically reliable account of the origins of the Christian faith, demonstrating its divine power, historical reality, and orderly expansion.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text)</strong>: Luke is writing as a careful historian and theologian, documenting the fulfillment of Christ's promises. His purpose is to assure his readers of the certainty of the things they have been taught (Luke 1:4), showing that the Gentile mission was not an accident or an innovation, but the direct, Spirit-led outworking of God's redemptive plan.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\n\nThis single verse is a masterpiece of theological compression, bookending the entire missionary journey with the theme of God's sovereign grace. The journey began in Antioch when Paul and Barnabas were set apart by the Holy Spirit and sent off by the church (Acts 13:1-3). This verse marks their return to that same point of origin, creating a perfect narrative inclusio (\"framing repetition that opens and closes a unit\").\n\nThe crucial phrase is ἦσαν παραδεδομένοι τῇ χάριτι τοῦ θεοῦ (*ēsan paradedomenoi tē chariti tou theou*, \"they had been entrusted to the grace of God\"). The verb form is a periphrastic perfect or pluperfect, built from the verb \"to be\" (ἦσαν, *ēsan*) and a perfect passive participle (παραδεδομένοι, *paradedomenoi*). This grammatical structure emphasizes a state of being that resulted from a past action. They *had been* handed over, and they *remained* in that state of entrustment throughout their journey. The passive voice is a divine passive: God (through the Holy Spirit and the church) was the one doing the entrusting. They were not self-appointed freelancers; they were commissioned agents.\n\nTheir commission was specifically \"to the grace of God.\" The dative case of τῇ χάριτι (*tē chariti*, \"to the grace\") indicates the sphere or element in which their mission was to be carried out. χάρις (*charis*, \"grace/unearned favor\") is not merely God's attitude but His active, divine enablement. They were sent out not with human resources, but having been committed into the care and power of God's own grace to accomplish the work.\n\nThe final clause, εἰς τὸ ἔργον ὃ ἐπλήρωσαν (*eis to ergon ho eplērōsan*, \"for the work which they fulfilled\"), defines the purpose of the entrustment and declares its successful completion. The ἔργον (*ergon*, \"work\") was the specific task given by the Spirit in Acts 13:2. The verb ἐπλήρωσαν (*eplērōsan*, \"they fulfilled/completed\") is in the aorist tense, viewing the entire, arduous journey as a single, completed whole. They did what they were sent to do. The verse thus forms a tight theological loop: The grace that commissioned the work was the same grace that empowered its completion.\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<p>This single verse is a masterpiece of theological compression, bookending the entire missionary journey with the theme of God's sovereign grace. The journey began in Antioch when Paul and Barnabas were set apart by the Holy Spirit and sent off by the church (Acts 13:1-3). This verse marks their return to that same point of origin, creating a perfect narrative inclusio (\"framing repetition that opens and closes a unit\").</p>\n<p>The crucial phrase is ἦσαν παραδεδομένοι τῇ χάριτι τοῦ θεοῦ (<em>ēsan paradedomenoi tē chariti tou theou</em>, \"they had been entrusted to the grace of God\"). The verb form is a periphrastic perfect or pluperfect, built from the verb \"to be\" (ἦσαν, <em>ēsan</em>) and a perfect passive participle (παραδεδομένοι, <em>paradedomenoi</em>). This grammatical structure emphasizes a state of being that resulted from a past action. They <em>had been</em> handed over, and they <em>remained</em> in that state of entrustment throughout their journey. The passive voice is a divine passive: God (through the Holy Spirit and the church) was the one doing the entrusting. They were not self-appointed freelancers; they were commissioned agents.</p>\n<p>Their commission was specifically \"to the grace of God.\" The dative case of τῇ χάριτι (<em>tē chariti</em>, \"to the grace\") indicates the sphere or element in which their mission was to be carried out. χάρις (<em>charis</em>, \"grace/unearned favor\") is not merely God's attitude but His active, divine enablement. They were sent out not with human resources, but having been committed into the care and power of God's own grace to accomplish the work.</p>\n<p>The final clause, εἰς τὸ ἔργον ὃ ἐπλήρωσαν (<em>eis to ergon ho eplērōsan</em>, \"for the work which they fulfilled\"), defines the purpose of the entrustment and declares its successful completion. The ἔργον (<em>ergon</em>, \"work\") was the specific task given by the Spirit in Acts 13:2. The verb ἐπλήρωσαν (<em>eplērōsan</em>, \"they fulfilled/completed\") is in the aorist tense, viewing the entire, arduous journey as a single, completed whole. They did what they were sent to do. The verse thus forms a tight theological loop: The grace that commissioned the work was the same grace that empowered its completion.</p>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic)**: This verse is a key station in the biblical motif of the *divine commission*. The pattern begins with God sending Abram from his country (Gen 12:1), sending Moses to Pharaoh (Ex 3:10), and sending His prophets to Israel (Jer 7:25). This trajectory finds its ultimate expression in the Father sending the Son into the world (John 3:17; Gal 4:4). The Son, in turn, sends His disciples as He was sent (John 20:21). Acts 14:26 shows this pattern now fully operational in the church: the Triune God, through a local body of believers, sends out agents who operate in His grace, fulfill His work, and return to give an account. The Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the final accounting at the Bema Seat of Christ (2 Cor 5:10), where all work done in His name will be evaluated.\n\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag**:\n    *   **Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\")**: Establishes the normative pattern of the local church as a missionary-sending base, with a structure of commissioning and accountability.\n    *   **Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\")**: Highlights that the very grace which saves is the grace that empowers for service; mission is a grace-based enterprise from start to finish.\n    *   **Theology Proper (\"the doctrine of God Himself\")**: Portrays God as the sovereign initiator and sustainer of mission, who entrusts tasks to His people.\n    *   **Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\")**: While not explicit in this verse, it's the direct fulfillment of the Spirit's command in Acts 13:2, showing the Spirit's work brought to completion.\n\n*   **Tripartite Synthesis**: Conservative Christian commentators universally see this verse as a paradigm for missions, emphasizing the themes of grace, accountability, and the local church's role (Stott, Bock, Bruce). The concept of being a \"sent one\" resonates deeply with the Jewish concept of the שָׁלִיחַ (*šālîaḥ*, \"agent/emissary\"), who acts with the full authority of the sender. This verse Christianizes that legal and relational concept: the missionaries are agents of God, operating with His authority and enabled by His grace.\n\n*   **Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification**: The \"work\" they fulfilled is Christ's work, the Great Commission (Matt 28:18-20). The \"grace\" they were entrusted to is the grace of the Lord Jesus Christ (2 Cor 8:9). They function as ambassadors *for Christ* (2 Cor 5:20), and their report is ultimately an account of what *God* had done through them (Acts 14:27), magnifying the true agent of salvation.\n",
      "phase_f_canonical_html": "<h3>Canonical Connection</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic)</strong>: This verse is a key station in the biblical motif of the <em>divine commission</em>. The pattern begins with God sending Abram from his country (Gen 12:1), sending Moses to Pharaoh (Ex 3:10), and sending His prophets to Israel (Jer 7:25). This trajectory finds its ultimate expression in the Father sending the Son into the world (John 3:17; Gal 4:4). The Son, in turn, sends His disciples as He was sent (John 20:21). Acts 14:26 shows this pattern now fully operational in the church: the Triune God, through a local body of believers, sends out agents who operate in His grace, fulfill His work, and return to give an account. The Christo-telic terminus (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the final accounting at the Bema Seat of Christ (2 Cor 5:10), where all work done in His name will be evaluated.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Systematic-Theology Loci Tag</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\")</strong>: Establishes the normative pattern of the local church as a missionary-sending base, with a structure of commissioning and accountability.</li>\n<li><strong>Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\")</strong>: Highlights that the very grace which saves is the grace that empowers for service; mission is a grace-based enterprise from start to finish.</li>\n<li><strong>Theology Proper (\"the doctrine of God Himself\")</strong>: Portrays God as the sovereign initiator and sustainer of mission, who entrusts tasks to His people.</li>\n<li><strong>Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\")</strong>: While not explicit in this verse, it's the direct fulfillment of the Spirit's command in Acts 13:2, showing the Spirit's work brought to completion.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Tripartite Synthesis</strong>: Conservative Christian commentators universally see this verse as a paradigm for missions, emphasizing the themes of grace, accountability, and the local church's role (Stott, Bock, Bruce). The concept of being a \"sent one\" resonates deeply with the Jewish concept of the שָׁלִיחַ (<em>šālîaḥ</em>, \"agent/emissary\"), who acts with the full authority of the sender. This verse Christianizes that legal and relational concept: the missionaries are agents of God, operating with His authority and enabled by His grace.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification</strong>: The \"work\" they fulfilled is Christ's work, the Great Commission (Matt 28:18-20). The \"grace\" they were entrusted to is the grace of the Lord Jesus Christ (2 Cor 8:9). They function as ambassadors <em>for Christ</em> (2 Cor 5:20), and their report is ultimately an account of what <em>God</em> had done through them (Acts 14:27), magnifying the true agent of salvation.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
