      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:21-28 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Greek (NA28)**\n\nΠαραγενόμενοι δὲ καὶ συναγαγόντες τὴν ἐκκλησίαν, ἀνήγγελλον ὅσα ἐποίησεν ὁ θεὸς μετ’ αὐτῶν καὶ ὅτι ἤνοιξεν τοῖς ἔθνεσιν θύραν πίστεως.\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 15 rows = 105 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Παραγενόμενοι | Paragenomenoi | G3854 | παραγίνομαι | V-AMP-NPM | Having arrived |\n| 2 | δὲ | de | G1161 | δέ | Conj | and / but |\n| 3 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and / also |\n| 4 | συναγαγόντες | synagagontes | G4863 | συνάγω | V-AAP-NPM | having gathered together |\n| 5 | τὴν | tēn | G3588 | ὁ | T-ASF | the |\n| 6 | ἐκκλησίαν | ekklēsian | G1577 | ἐκκλησία | N-ASF | church / assembly |\n| 7 | ἀνήγγελλον | anēngellon | G312 | ἀναγγέλλω | V-IAI-3P | they were reporting / began to report |\n| 8 | ὅσα | hosa | G3745 | ὅσος | A-APN | all that / as much as |\n| 9 | ἐποίησεν | epoiēsen | G4160 | ποιέω | V-AAI-3S | he did |\n| 10 | ὁ | ho | G3588 | ὁ | T-NSM | the |\n| 11 | θεὸς | theos | G2316 | θεός | N-NSM | God |\n| 12 | μετ’ | met’ | G3326 | μετά | Prep | with |\n| 13 | αὐτῶν | autōn | G846 | αὐτός | P-GPM | them |\n| 14 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 15 | ὅτι | hoti | G3754 | ὅτι | Conj | that / how |\n| 16 | ἤνοιξεν | ēnoixen | G455 | ἀνοίγω | V-AAI-3S | he opened |\n| 17 | τοῖς | tois | G3588 | ὁ | T-DPN | to the |\n| 18 | ἔθνεσιν | ethnesin | G1484 | ἔθνος | N-DPN | Gentiles / nations |\n| 19 | θύραν | thyran | G2374 | θύρα | N-ASF | a door |\n| 20 | πίστεως | pisteōs | G4102 | πίστις | N-GSF | of faith |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation**\n\nAnd having arrived and having gathered together the church, they were reporting all that God did with them and that He opened to the Gentiles a door of faith.\n\n**Standalone English Translation**\n\nWhen they arrived and gathered the church together, they reported all that God had done with them and how he had opened a door of faith to the Gentiles.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation**\n\nAnd upon their arrival back in Antioch, they called the whole church together and began to report, in detail, everything that God Himself had accomplished in partnership with them, and specifically [the history-altering news] that He had decisively opened a door of faith to the non-Jewish nations.\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:21-28 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Greek (NA28)</strong></p>\n<p>Παραγενόμενοι δὲ καὶ συναγαγόντες τὴν ἐκκλησίαν, ἀνήγγελλον ὅσα ἐποίησεν ὁ θεὸς μετ’ αὐτῶν καὶ ὅτι ἤνοιξεν τοῖς ἔθνεσιν θύραν πίστεως.</p>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 15 rows = 105 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>Παραγενόμενοι</td>\n<td>Paragenomenoi</td>\n<td>G3854</td>\n<td>παραγίνομαι</td>\n<td>V-AMP-NPM</td>\n<td>Having arrived</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>δὲ</td>\n<td>de</td>\n<td>G1161</td>\n<td>δέ</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and / but</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and / also</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>συναγαγόντες</td>\n<td>synagagontes</td>\n<td>G4863</td>\n<td>συνάγω</td>\n<td>V-AAP-NPM</td>\n<td>having gathered together</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>τὴν</td>\n<td>tēn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-ASF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>ἐκκλησίαν</td>\n<td>ekklēsian</td>\n<td>G1577</td>\n<td>ἐκκλησία</td>\n<td>N-ASF</td>\n<td>church / assembly</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>ἀνήγγελλον</td>\n<td>anēngellon</td>\n<td>G312</td>\n<td>ἀναγγέλλω</td>\n<td>V-IAI-3P</td>\n<td>they were reporting / began to report</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>ὅσα</td>\n<td>hosa</td>\n<td>G3745</td>\n<td>ὅσος</td>\n<td>A-APN</td>\n<td>all that / as much as</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>ἐποίησεν</td>\n<td>epoiēsen</td>\n<td>G4160</td>\n<td>ποιέω</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3S</td>\n<td>he did</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>ho</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-NSM</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>θεὸς</td>\n<td>theos</td>\n<td>G2316</td>\n<td>θεός</td>\n<td>N-NSM</td>\n<td>God</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>μετ’</td>\n<td>met’</td>\n<td>G3326</td>\n<td>μετά</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>with</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>αὐτῶν</td>\n<td>autōn</td>\n<td>G846</td>\n<td>αὐτός</td>\n<td>P-GPM</td>\n<td>them</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>14</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15</td>\n<td>ὅτι</td>\n<td>hoti</td>\n<td>G3754</td>\n<td>ὅτι</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>that / how</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>16</td>\n<td>ἤνοιξεν</td>\n<td>ēnoixen</td>\n<td>G455</td>\n<td>ἀνοίγω</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3S</td>\n<td>he opened</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>17</td>\n<td>τοῖς</td>\n<td>tois</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-DPN</td>\n<td>to the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>18</td>\n<td>ἔθνεσιν</td>\n<td>ethnesin</td>\n<td>G1484</td>\n<td>ἔθνος</td>\n<td>N-DPN</td>\n<td>Gentiles / nations</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>19</td>\n<td>θύραν</td>\n<td>thyran</td>\n<td>G2374</td>\n<td>θύρα</td>\n<td>N-ASF</td>\n<td>a door</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>20</td>\n<td>πίστεως</td>\n<td>pisteōs</td>\n<td>G4102</td>\n<td>πίστις</td>\n<td>N-GSF</td>\n<td>of faith</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation</strong></p>\n<p>And having arrived and having gathered together the church, they were reporting all that God did with them and that He opened to the Gentiles a door of faith.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation</strong></p>\n<p>When they arrived and gathered the church together, they reported all that God had done with them and how he had opened a door of faith to the Gentiles.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation</strong></p>\n<p>And upon their arrival back in Antioch, they called the whole church together and began to report, in detail, everything that God Himself had accomplished in partnership with them, and specifically [the history-altering news] that He had decisively opened a door of faith to the non-Jewish nations.</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** God is sovereignly at work in the world to save people from every nation, and He opens doors of opportunity for the gospel through the faithful partnership of His sent people.\n\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):**\n    *   *Individual:* The tendency to take credit for spiritual success or to despair in the face of spiritual opposition, forgetting that God is the one who opens doors.\n    *   *Corporate:* The temptation for a church to become inwardly focused and forget its primary calling to send and support the mission to the nations, or to erect human barriers (like legalism or cultural prejudice) that God has torn down.\n\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** Before we are called to *do* anything, we are reminded of what God *has done*. He has, through the cross of Christ, already thrown open the door of faith. Our access to God is not something we must build or earn; it is a gift we receive through an already-opened door. Our missionary work is not about trying to pry open a locked door but about inviting people to walk through the one Christ has already opened.\n\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\" & \"Being\":* Cultivate a posture of dependent prayer, asking God to open doors for the gospel in your own life and around the world (Col 4:3). When you see spiritual fruit, be quick to give God the glory, recognizing His agency.\n    *   *Relational:* Actively support and encourage those your church has \"sent out,\" whether to a foreign field or a local ministry. Be part of the \"sending church\" that prays, gives, and eagerly listens to the reports of what God is doing.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* See your own workplace or neighborhood as a potential \"open door.\" Pray for opportunities to speak of Christ, and trust that God is the one who prepares hearts and provides the opening.\n\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** This verse calls us to adore God as the Great Doorkeeper and the Lord of the Harvest. We praise Him for His sovereign grace that makes a way for salvation where there was no way, and for His faithfulness in using His people to carry this good news to the ends of the earth. \"To You, O Lord, be the glory for every open door and every soul brought from darkness into Your marvelous light!\"\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> God is sovereignly at work in the world to save people from every nation, and He opens doors of opportunity for the gospel through the faithful partnership of His sent people.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Individual:</em> The tendency to take credit for spiritual success or to despair in the face of spiritual opposition, forgetting that God is the one who opens doors.</li>\n<li><em>Corporate:</em> The temptation for a church to become inwardly focused and forget its primary calling to send and support the mission to the nations, or to erect human barriers (like legalism or cultural prejudice) that God has torn down.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> Before we are called to <em>do</em> anything, we are reminded of what God <em>has done</em>. He has, through the cross of Christ, already thrown open the door of faith. Our access to God is not something we must build or earn; it is a gift we receive through an already-opened door. Our missionary work is not about trying to pry open a locked door but about inviting people to walk through the one Christ has already opened.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\" &amp; \"Being\":</em> Cultivate a posture of dependent prayer, asking God to open doors for the gospel in your own life and around the world (Col 4:3). When you see spiritual fruit, be quick to give God the glory, recognizing His agency.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> Actively support and encourage those your church has \"sent out,\" whether to a foreign field or a local ministry. Be part of the \"sending church\" that prays, gives, and eagerly listens to the reports of what God is doing.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> See your own workplace or neighborhood as a potential \"open door.\" Pray for opportunities to speak of Christ, and trust that God is the one who prepares hearts and provides the opening.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong> This verse calls us to adore God as the Great Doorkeeper and the Lord of the Harvest. We praise Him for His sovereign grace that makes a way for salvation where there was no way, and for His faithfulness in using His people to carry this good news to the ends of the earth. \"To You, O Lord, be the glory for every open door and every soul brought from darkness into Your marvelous light!\"</p>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:27 — \"...how He had opened a door of faith to the Gentiles.\"\nKEY TERM:     θύραν πίστεως (*thyran pisteōs*, \"a door of faith\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: God's sovereign work in missions opens the way for salvation by faith alone.\nIMAGE:        A wide-open door, with light streaming out to all nations.\nAPPLICATION:  Our church can pray for and celebrate the reports of what God is doing globally.\nDOXOLOGY:     Praise to You, Lord, the One who opens doors no one can shut.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:27 — &quot;...how He had opened a door of faith to the Gentiles.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>θύραν πίστεως (*thyran pisteōs*, &quot;a door of faith&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>God&#x27;s sovereign work in missions opens the way for salvation by faith alone.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>A wide-open door, with light streaming out to all nations.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>Our church can pray for and celebrate the reports of what God is doing globally.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Praise to You, Lord, the One who opens doors no one can shut.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever felt like you were banging your head against a locked door, trying to make something good happen? In our spiritual lives, it's easy to feel that way—that success depends entirely on our own effort. The missionaries Paul and Barnabas had just returned from a grueling journey filled with riots, stonings, and immense hardship. But when they gathered their home church to give a report, their message wasn't about their own heroic efforts. Their headline was simple: \"Look at what God has done!\" (Acts 14:27).\n\nSpecifically, they celebrated how God Himself had thrown open a θύραν πίστεως (*thyran pisteōs*, \"a door of faith\") to the non-Jewish world. For centuries, the way to God seemed to have many barriers. But now, the missionaries declared, God has made the entrance stunningly simple: it is a door made of faith. This wasn't their achievement; it was God's sovereign and gracious act. This is great news for us. It means the pressure is off. Our job is not to force open doors but to faithfully walk through the ones God opens, inviting others to come in with us. This week, we can pray with confidence, asking God to open a door for the gospel in our own lives, and trust that He is the one who holds the key.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever felt like you were banging your head against a locked door, trying to make something good happen? In our spiritual lives, it's easy to feel that way—that success depends entirely on our own effort. The missionaries Paul and Barnabas had just returned from a grueling journey filled with riots, stonings, and immense hardship. But when they gathered their home church to give a report, their message wasn't about their own heroic efforts. Their headline was simple: \"Look at what God has done!\" (Acts 14:27).</p>\n<p>Specifically, they celebrated how God Himself had thrown open a θύραν πίστεως (<em>thyran pisteōs</em>, \"a door of faith\") to the non-Jewish world. For centuries, the way to God seemed to have many barriers. But now, the missionaries declared, God has made the entrance stunningly simple: it is a door made of faith. This wasn't their achievement; it was God's sovereign and gracious act. This is great news for us. It means the pressure is off. Our job is not to force open doors but to faithfully walk through the ones God opens, inviting others to come in with us. This week, we can pray with confidence, asking God to open a door for the gospel in our own lives, and trust that He is the one who holds the key.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  What was the key metaphor Paul and Barnabas used to describe Gentile salvation?\n    A: They said God had opened a \"door of faith\" to the Gentiles.\n\n2.  According to the report, who was the primary agent responsible for the mission's success?\n    A: God Himself. They reported \"all that God had done with them.\"\n\n3.  What does this verse teach us about God's role and our role in mission?\n    A: God is the sovereign actor who decisively opens the door for salvation. Our role is to go in partnership with Him, and then give Him the glory for the results.\n\n4.  How can our church apply the principle of this verse this month?\n    A: Our church can dedicate time in a service or prayer meeting to hear a report from a missionary we support and celebrate what God is doing through them.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>What was the key metaphor Paul and Barnabas used to describe Gentile salvation?\n    A: They said God had opened a \"door of faith\" to the Gentiles.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>According to the report, who was the primary agent responsible for the mission's success?\n    A: God Himself. They reported \"all that God had done with them.\"</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>What does this verse teach us about God's role and our role in mission?\n    A: God is the sovereign actor who decisively opens the door for salvation. Our role is to go in partnership with Him, and then give Him the glory for the results.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>How can our church apply the principle of this verse this month?\n    A: Our church can dedicate time in a service or prayer meeting to hear a report from a missionary we support and celebrate what God is doing through them.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>",
