      "h1_title_html": "<p>Acts 14:28 — The Consolidation of the Church Through Apostolic Presence</p>",
      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:24–28 · source: NA28]\n**Acts 14:28** ἦσαν δὲ διατρίβοντες χρόνον οὐκ ὀλίγον σὺν τοῖς μαθηταῖς.\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 8 rows = 56 cells.*\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | ἦσαν | ēsan | G2258 | εἰμί | V-IAI-3P | they were |\n| 2 | δὲ | de | G1161 | δέ | Conj | and / but |\n| 3 | διατρίβοντες | diatribontes | G1304 | διατρίβω | V-PAP-NPM | spending time / remaining |\n| 4 | χρόνον | chronon | G5550 | χρόνος | N-ASM | time |\n| 5 | οὐκ | ouk | G3756 | οὐ | Adv | not |\n| 6 | ὀλίγον | oligon | G3641 | ὀλίγος | A-ASM | a little |\n| 7 | σὺν | syn | G4862 | σύν | Prep | with |\n| 8 | τοῖς | tois | G3588 | ὁ | T-DPM | the |\n| 9 | μαθηταῖς | mathētais | G3101 | μαθητής | N-DPM | disciples / learners |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\nAnd they were remaining for a time not little with the disciples.\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\nAnd they stayed there with the disciples for a considerable time.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\nAnd so they remained [settling in after their arduous journey], spending no small amount of time [in a deliberate season of consolidation and teaching] together with the disciples [in the sending church of Antioch].\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:24–28 · source: NA28]\n<strong>Acts 14:28</strong> ἦσαν δὲ διατρίβοντες χρόνον οὐκ ὀλίγον σὺν τοῖς μαθηταῖς.</p>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 8 rows = 56 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>ἦσαν</td>\n<td>ēsan</td>\n<td>G2258</td>\n<td>εἰμί</td>\n<td>V-IAI-3P</td>\n<td>they were</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>δὲ</td>\n<td>de</td>\n<td>G1161</td>\n<td>δέ</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and / but</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>διατρίβοντες</td>\n<td>diatribontes</td>\n<td>G1304</td>\n<td>διατρίβω</td>\n<td>V-PAP-NPM</td>\n<td>spending time / remaining</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>χρόνον</td>\n<td>chronon</td>\n<td>G5550</td>\n<td>χρόνος</td>\n<td>N-ASM</td>\n<td>time</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>οὐκ</td>\n<td>ouk</td>\n<td>G3756</td>\n<td>οὐ</td>\n<td>Adv</td>\n<td>not</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>ὀλίγον</td>\n<td>oligon</td>\n<td>G3641</td>\n<td>ὀλίγος</td>\n<td>A-ASM</td>\n<td>a little</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>σὺν</td>\n<td>syn</td>\n<td>G4862</td>\n<td>σύν</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>with</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>τοῖς</td>\n<td>tois</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>T-DPM</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>μαθηταῖς</td>\n<td>mathētais</td>\n<td>G3101</td>\n<td>μαθητής</td>\n<td>N-DPM</td>\n<td>disciples / learners</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)</strong>\nAnd they were remaining for a time not little with the disciples.</p>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)</strong>\nAnd they stayed there with the disciples for a considerable time.</p>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)</strong>\nAnd so they remained [settling in after their arduous journey], spending no small amount of time [in a deliberate season of consolidation and teaching] together with the disciples [in the sending church of Antioch].</p>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\")**: Healthy spiritual growth, both for individuals and for the Church, requires intentional seasons of stability, deep teaching, and fellowship, which are just as vital as seasons of outreach and activity.\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\")**: The passage addresses the human tendency toward restlessness and the glorification of constant activity over quiet faithfulness. Individually, we can devalue seasons of quiet growth. Corporately, churches can prize numerical expansion and new programs over the deep, slow work of discipleship.\n*   **Shared Particulars**: Like the church in Antioch, modern believers and churches exist in a cycle of sending and staying, of outreach and in-house strengthening. We face the same temptation to prioritize the \"exciting\" work of evangelism over the \"ordinary\" work of being discipled and discipling others in our local context.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding)**: Because Christ, our Apostle and High Priest, has finished His earthly journey and is now seated at the right hand of the Father (Heb 8:1), He provides the ultimate stability for His Church. Our seasons of rest and growth are grounded in His finished work and secured presence. We do not have to be in constant, anxious motion because our security is in Him.\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace)**:\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\"*: Intentionally commit to a season of \"staying\" in your local church. Prioritize consistent attendance, deep study of the Word, and fellowship over church-hopping or constant activity.\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\"*: Cultivate a heart that values being a disciple—a learner (μαθητής, *mathētēs*)—as much as being a witness. Embrace the quiet, unseen work of spiritual formation.\n    *   *Relational*: Invest \"no little time\" in discipling relationships within your church. Pour into others and allow others to pour into you, building the deep bonds of fellowship seen here.\n    *   *Public / Vocational*: Recognize that your workplace or community needs your steady, long-term presence as much as it needs your initial gospel proclamation. Be a faithful, long-haul witness.\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\")**: This passage reveals God as the Lord of both the journey and the dwelling place. We worship Him for His wisdom in designing the Church to grow not just by going, but by staying. \"Lord, You are the God of the road and the God of the room. We praise You for the wisdom that builds Your Church through both dynamic mission and deep, abiding fellowship.\"\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\")</strong>: Healthy spiritual growth, both for individuals and for the Church, requires intentional seasons of stability, deep teaching, and fellowship, which are just as vital as seasons of outreach and activity.</li>\n<li><strong>FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\")</strong>: The passage addresses the human tendency toward restlessness and the glorification of constant activity over quiet faithfulness. Individually, we can devalue seasons of quiet growth. Corporately, churches can prize numerical expansion and new programs over the deep, slow work of discipleship.</li>\n<li><strong>Shared Particulars</strong>: Like the church in Antioch, modern believers and churches exist in a cycle of sending and staying, of outreach and in-house strengthening. We face the same temptation to prioritize the \"exciting\" work of evangelism over the \"ordinary\" work of being discipled and discipling others in our local context.</li>\n<li><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding)</strong>: Because Christ, our Apostle and High Priest, has finished His earthly journey and is now seated at the right hand of the Father (Heb 8:1), He provides the ultimate stability for His Church. Our seasons of rest and growth are grounded in His finished work and secured presence. We do not have to be in constant, anxious motion because our security is in Him.</li>\n<li><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace)</strong>:<ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\"</em>: Intentionally commit to a season of \"staying\" in your local church. Prioritize consistent attendance, deep study of the Word, and fellowship over church-hopping or constant activity.</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\"</em>: Cultivate a heart that values being a disciple—a learner (μαθητής, <em>mathētēs</em>)—as much as being a witness. Embrace the quiet, unseen work of spiritual formation.</li>\n<li><em>Relational</em>: Invest \"no little time\" in discipling relationships within your church. Pour into others and allow others to pour into you, building the deep bonds of fellowship seen here.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational</em>: Recognize that your workplace or community needs your steady, long-term presence as much as it needs your initial gospel proclamation. Be a faithful, long-haul witness.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\")</strong>: This passage reveals God as the Lord of both the journey and the dwelling place. We worship Him for His wisdom in designing the Church to grow not just by going, but by staying. \"Lord, You are the God of the road and the God of the room. We praise You for the wisdom that builds Your Church through both dynamic mission and deep, abiding fellowship.\"</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:28 — \"remained no little time with the disciples.\"\nKEY TERM:     οὐκ ὀλίγον (ouk oligon, \"not a little\" — a long time)\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: Apostolic presence is vital for consolidating the church.\nIMAGE:        Weary travelers finding rest and purpose in their home base.\nAPPLICATION:  Invest deeply in your local church through faithful, long-term presence.\nDOXOLOGY:     Lord, thank You for the gift of staying and growing together.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:28 — &quot;remained no little time with the disciples.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>οὐκ ὀλίγον (ouk oligon, &quot;not a little&quot; — a long time)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>Apostolic presence is vital for consolidating the church.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>Weary travelers finding rest and purpose in their home base.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>Invest deeply in your local church through faithful, long-term presence.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Lord, thank You for the gift of staying and growing together.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nAfter a grueling and dangerous missionary journey, you might expect the apostles Paul and Barnabas to take a quick break and head right back out. But Acts 14:28 tells us something profound: \"they stayed there with the disciples for a considerable time.\" The original Greek uses a deliberate understatement, χρόνον οὐκ ὀλίγον (*chronon ouk oligon*, \"a not little time\"), to emphasize just how significant this season was. This wasn't just a vacation; it was a strategic part of their ministry. They poured themselves into teaching and strengthening the believers in their home church of Antioch.\n\nThis verse paints a beautiful picture of the rhythm of Christian life and ministry. There are times for going and times for staying. There are seasons for planting the gospel in new soil and seasons for tending the garden at home. Our culture often celebrates constant motion and visible results, but God builds His church just as much through the quiet, faithful, long-term presence of believers who are committed to one another. Our security in the finished work of Christ (Hebrews 10:12-14) frees us from anxious activity. This week, consider how you can invest \"no little time\" right where you are, strengthening the disciples around you through your steady presence.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>After a grueling and dangerous missionary journey, you might expect the apostles Paul and Barnabas to take a quick break and head right back out. But Acts 14:28 tells us something profound: \"they stayed there with the disciples for a considerable time.\" The original Greek uses a deliberate understatement, χρόνον οὐκ ὀλίγον (<em>chronon ouk oligon</em>, \"a not little time\"), to emphasize just how significant this season was. This wasn't just a vacation; it was a strategic part of their ministry. They poured themselves into teaching and strengthening the believers in their home church of Antioch.</p>\n<p>This verse paints a beautiful picture of the rhythm of Christian life and ministry. There are times for going and times for staying. There are seasons for planting the gospel in new soil and seasons for tending the garden at home. Our culture often celebrates constant motion and visible results, but God builds His church just as much through the quiet, faithful, long-term presence of believers who are committed to one another. Our security in the finished work of Christ (Hebrews 10:12-14) frees us from anxious activity. This week, consider how you can invest \"no little time\" right where you are, strengthening the disciples around you through your steady presence.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  What literary device does Luke use to describe the length of the apostles' stay?\n    A: Litotes (understatement), saying it was \"not a little time\" to mean it was a very long time.\n2.  What does this verse teach about the missionary cycle?\n    A: It teaches that the cycle is incomplete without a phase of returning, reporting, and consolidating the home base through teaching and fellowship.\n3.  What doctrine of the church (Ecclesiology) does this verse model?\n    A: It models the importance of the local church for discipleship, spiritual formation, and as a stable base for mission. Our growth is tied to being rooted in a specific community of believers.\n4.  What is one concrete way you can apply the principle of \"staying\" this week?\n    A: I can invest deeply in my local church by prioritizing consistent fellowship and service, choosing stability over restlessness.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What literary device does Luke use to describe the length of the apostles' stay?\n    A: Litotes (understatement), saying it was \"not a little time\" to mean it was a very long time.</li>\n<li>What does this verse teach about the missionary cycle?\n    A: It teaches that the cycle is incomplete without a phase of returning, reporting, and consolidating the home base through teaching and fellowship.</li>\n<li>What doctrine of the church (Ecclesiology) does this verse model?\n    A: It models the importance of the local church for discipleship, spiritual formation, and as a stable base for mission. Our growth is tied to being rooted in a specific community of believers.</li>\n<li>What is one concrete way you can apply the principle of \"staying\" this week?\n    A: I can invest deeply in my local church by prioritizing consistent fellowship and service, choosing stability over restlessness.</li>\n</ol>",
