      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\")**: The extended period of time Paul and Barnabas spent with the disciples in Antioch after their first missionary journey.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\")**: This deliberate season of remaining and teaching was an essential, non-negotiable phase of missionary work, equal in importance to the outward expansion.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\")**: God's work of building the Church requires not only the outward planting of the gospel but also the inward strengthening of believers through extended, faithful presence and teaching.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\")</strong>: The extended period of time Paul and Barnabas spent with the disciples in Antioch after their first missionary journey.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\")</strong>: This deliberate season of remaining and teaching was an essential, non-negotiable phase of missionary work, equal in importance to the outward expansion.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\")</strong>: God's work of building the Church requires not only the outward planting of the gospel but also the inward strengthening of believers through extended, faithful presence and teaching.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role**: The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel \"to the end of the earth\" (Acts 1:8). This verse concludes the narrative of the first major Gentile mission, acting as a \"rest note\" that demonstrates a crucial part of the expansion cycle: consolidation. It shows that the apostolic mission was not merely about evangelistic \"blitzes\" but about establishing deep, lasting communities of faith.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc**: Acts 14:28 serves as the capstone to the entire first missionary journey (Acts 13:1–14:28). After a whirlwind of travel, preaching, persecution, and church planting, this verse brings the apostles home to their sending church in Antioch. It provides the quiet conclusion before the next major theological conflict erupts in Acts 15:1, making this period of peace and teaching profoundly significant.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic**: The genre is historical narrative. The governing *hermeneutic* (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this as a factual report of events. The description of this \"staying\" is prescriptive in principle; it models a vital rhythm for all subsequent ministry and mission.\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational)**: This event occurs firmly within the Church Age (the Dispensation of Grace). The New Covenant is active, and the Church, composed of both Jews and Gentiles, is being established as God's primary instrument in the world. This verse shows the maturation of a local expression of that Church.\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors**: The verse is preceded by the triumphant report to the Antioch church, where the apostles \"declared all that God had done with them, and how he had opened a door of faith to the Gentiles\" (Acts 14:27). It is immediately followed by the arrival of Judaizers from Judea (Acts 15:1), whose false teaching will precipitate the Jerusalem Council. This verse, therefore, describes a precious and strategic season of peace and doctrinal consolidation just before a major theological battle.\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels**: This pattern of extended apostolic stays for the purpose of teaching and strengthening is a hallmark of Paul's ministry. Other examples include his 18 months in Corinth (Acts 18:11), three years in Ephesus (Acts 20:31), and two years under house arrest in Rome, where he was \"teaching...with all boldness\" (Acts 28:30-31).\n",
      "phase_c_big_picture_html": "<h3>Big Picture: Where this passage fits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Whole-Book Thesis &amp; Passage's Role</strong>: The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the gospel \"to the end of the earth\" (Acts 1:8). This verse concludes the narrative of the first major Gentile mission, acting as a \"rest note\" that demonstrates a crucial part of the expansion cycle: consolidation. It shows that the apostolic mission was not merely about evangelistic \"blitzes\" but about establishing deep, lasting communities of faith.</li>\n<li><strong>Discourse / Section Arc</strong>: Acts 14:28 serves as the capstone to the entire first missionary journey (Acts 13:1–14:28). After a whirlwind of travel, preaching, persecution, and church planting, this verse brings the apostles home to their sending church in Antioch. It provides the quiet conclusion before the next major theological conflict erupts in Acts 15:1, making this period of peace and teaching profoundly significant.</li>\n<li><strong>Genre &amp; Hermeneutic</strong>: The genre is historical narrative. The governing <em>hermeneutic</em> (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this as a factual report of events. The description of this \"staying\" is prescriptive in principle; it models a vital rhythm for all subsequent ministry and mission.</li>\n<li><strong>Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational)</strong>: This event occurs firmly within the Church Age (the Dispensation of Grace). The New Covenant is active, and the Church, composed of both Jews and Gentiles, is being established as God's primary instrument in the world. This verse shows the maturation of a local expression of that Church.</li>\n<li><strong>Gravitational Neighbors</strong>: The verse is preceded by the triumphant report to the Antioch church, where the apostles \"declared all that God had done with them, and how he had opened a door of faith to the Gentiles\" (Acts 14:27). It is immediately followed by the arrival of Judaizers from Judea (Acts 15:1), whose false teaching will precipitate the Jerusalem Council. This verse, therefore, describes a precious and strategic season of peace and doctrinal consolidation just before a major theological battle.</li>\n<li><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels</strong>: This pattern of extended apostolic stays for the purpose of teaching and strengthening is a hallmark of Paul's ministry. Other examples include his 18 months in Corinth (Acts 18:11), three years in Ephesus (Acts 20:31), and two years under house arrest in Rome, where he was \"teaching...with all boldness\" (Acts 28:30-31).</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology**: Following conservative Christian chronology (Hoehner), the first missionary journey concludes around AD 48. This \"long time\" in Antioch likely spans from late AD 48 through AD 49, leading up to the Jerusalem Council (c. AD 49/50).\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography**: The setting is Antioch on the Orontes in Syria (modern-day Antakya, Turkey; 36.2023° N, 36.1609° E). As the third-largest city in the Roman Empire, it was a strategic, cosmopolitan hub and the base of operations for the Gentile mission. It was the place where believers were first called \"Christians\" (Acts 11:26).\n*   **Original Audience Identification**: Luke writes to Theophilus (Acts 1:1) and the broader, second-generation church. For them, this simple verse would reinforce the importance of pastoral stability and deep teaching, countering any notion that ministry is only about constant, dramatic expansion.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text)**: Luke, the careful historian (Luke 1:1-4), includes this summary statement to provide a complete picture of the missionary cycle. It's not just about the journey out; it's about the return, the report, and the reinvestment in the home base. He emphasizes that the foundation of the church in Antioch was strong enough to both send out and receive back the church's foremost missionaries.\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology</strong>: Following conservative Christian chronology (Hoehner), the first missionary journey concludes around AD 48. This \"long time\" in Antioch likely spans from late AD 48 through AD 49, leading up to the Jerusalem Council (c. AD 49/50).</li>\n<li><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography</strong>: The setting is Antioch on the Orontes in Syria (modern-day Antakya, Turkey; 36.2023° N, 36.1609° E). As the third-largest city in the Roman Empire, it was a strategic, cosmopolitan hub and the base of operations for the Gentile mission. It was the place where believers were first called \"Christians\" (Acts 11:26).</li>\n<li><strong>Original Audience Identification</strong>: Luke writes to Theophilus (Acts 1:1) and the broader, second-generation church. For them, this simple verse would reinforce the importance of pastoral stability and deep teaching, countering any notion that ministry is only about constant, dramatic expansion.</li>\n<li><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text)</strong>: Luke, the careful historian (Luke 1:1-4), includes this summary statement to provide a complete picture of the missionary cycle. It's not just about the journey out; it's about the return, the report, and the reinvestment in the home base. He emphasizes that the foundation of the church in Antioch was strong enough to both send out and receive back the church's foremost missionaries.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\n*   **Literal-Primary Filter**: The verse is a straightforward summary statement. Paul and Barnabas stayed in Antioch for a significant duration.\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax**: The Greek uses a periphrastic construction: ἦσαν...διατρίβοντες (*ēsan...diatribontes*, literally \"they were spending time\"). This imperfect-tense construction emphasizes the continuous, ongoing nature of their stay. It wasn't a brief stopover; it was a settled season of life and ministry.\n*   **Literary Devices**: The key device is **litotes**, a form of ironic understatement where an affirmative is expressed by negating its opposite. The phrase χρόνον οὐκ ὀλίγον (*chronon ouk oligon*, \"a not little time\") is a deliberate understatement for \"a very long time\" or \"a considerable time.\" This rhetorical choice adds a sense of gravity and significance to the period, suggesting it was substantial and important.\n*   **Wordplay**: The verb διατρίβω (*diatribō*, \"to spend time/remain\") carries the sense of rubbing or wearing away, implying a deep, involved presence, not a superficial visit. They were \"wearing in\" the gospel with the disciples. The word for disciples, μαθηταῖς (*mathētais*), comes from the root for \"to learn.\" Thus, the apostles remained for a long time with the \"learners,\" implying a season of intensive teaching and discipleship.\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Literal-Primary Filter</strong>: The verse is a straightforward summary statement. Paul and Barnabas stayed in Antioch for a significant duration.</li>\n<li><strong>Linguistic Mechanics &amp; Syntax</strong>: The Greek uses a periphrastic construction: ἦσαν...διατρίβοντες (<em>ēsan...diatribontes</em>, literally \"they were spending time\"). This imperfect-tense construction emphasizes the continuous, ongoing nature of their stay. It wasn't a brief stopover; it was a settled season of life and ministry.</li>\n<li><strong>Literary Devices</strong>: The key device is <strong>litotes</strong>, a form of ironic understatement where an affirmative is expressed by negating its opposite. The phrase χρόνον οὐκ ὀλίγον (<em>chronon ouk oligon</em>, \"a not little time\") is a deliberate understatement for \"a very long time\" or \"a considerable time.\" This rhetorical choice adds a sense of gravity and significance to the period, suggesting it was substantial and important.</li>\n<li><strong>Wordplay</strong>: The verb διατρίβω (<em>diatribō</em>, \"to spend time/remain\") carries the sense of rubbing or wearing away, implying a deep, involved presence, not a superficial visit. They were \"wearing in\" the gospel with the disciples. The word for disciples, μαθηταῖς (<em>mathētais</em>), comes from the root for \"to learn.\" Thus, the apostles remained for a long time with the \"learners,\" implying a season of intensive teaching and discipleship.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment**: This verse is a fulfillment of the second half of the Great Commission: \"...teaching them to observe all that I have commanded you\" (Matt 28:20). Evangelism (the journey) is incomplete without discipleship (the stay). [TYPE]: This pattern of apostolic teaching establishes the model for the pastoral office, which is built on faithful, resident instruction (cf. 1 Tim 3:2, \"able to teach\"; Titus 1:9, \"he must hold firm to the trustworthy word as taught\").\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic)**: This verse contributes to the biblical motif of \"dwelling.\" God dwelled with His people in the Tabernacle (Exod 25:8), Christ \"dwelt among us\" (John 1:14, ἐσκήνωσεν, *eskēnōsen*, \"he tabernacled\"), and now His apostles dwell with the Church to build it up. The *Christo-telic terminus* (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the final, eternal dwelling of God with His people in the New Jerusalem, where \"the dwelling place of God is with man\" (Rev 21:3). This verse is a small picture of that settled, secure fellowship.\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag**:\n    *   **Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\")**: This is the primary locus. The verse demonstrates the importance of the local church as both a sending base and a place for spiritual formation and consolidation. It models the rhythm of mission and discipleship.\n    *   **Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\")**: The disciples with whom they stayed are the fruit of the salvation proclaimed on the journey. Their growth is part of the outworking of that salvation.\n",
      "phase_f_canonical_html": "<h3>Canonical Connection</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Foreshadowing &amp; Fulfillment</strong>: This verse is a fulfillment of the second half of the Great Commission: \"...teaching them to observe all that I have commanded you\" (Matt 28:20). Evangelism (the journey) is incomplete without discipleship (the stay). [TYPE]: This pattern of apostolic teaching establishes the model for the pastoral office, which is built on faithful, resident instruction (cf. 1 Tim 3:2, \"able to teach\"; Titus 1:9, \"he must hold firm to the trustworthy word as taught\").</li>\n<li><strong>Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic)</strong>: This verse contributes to the biblical motif of \"dwelling.\" God dwelled with His people in the Tabernacle (Exod 25:8), Christ \"dwelt among us\" (John 1:14, ἐσκήνωσεν, <em>eskēnōsen</em>, \"he tabernacled\"), and now His apostles dwell with the Church to build it up. The <em>Christo-telic terminus</em> (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the final, eternal dwelling of God with His people in the New Jerusalem, where \"the dwelling place of God is with man\" (Rev 21:3). This verse is a small picture of that settled, secure fellowship.</li>\n<li><strong>Systematic-Theology Loci Tag</strong>:<ul>\n<li><strong>Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\")</strong>: This is the primary locus. The verse demonstrates the importance of the local church as both a sending base and a place for spiritual formation and consolidation. It models the rhythm of mission and discipleship.</li>\n<li><strong>Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\")</strong>: The disciples with whom they stayed are the fruit of the salvation proclaimed on the journey. Their growth is part of the outworking of that salvation.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
